<SLUG> BC-MACAU-CHINA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SHADOW OF HONG KONG, CHINA GAINS A SEEDIER PIECE
</HEADLINE>
 (CHANGES reference to Cultural Revolution in 2nd graf; ALTERS
description in 3rd graf) 
 (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By MARK LANDLER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MACAU _ Five hundred years of European colonialism in Asia
sputters to a close here this weekend on a desolate, rain-swept
waterfront dredged out of Macau's once-beguiling harbor. At the
stroke of midnight on Sunday, China will reclaim this tiny enclave
from Portugal, raising its red flag over another patch of Chinese
soil and setting the stage for what it hopes will be eventual
reunification with Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Britain's hand-over of nearby Hong Kong two years ago,
which was heralded by years of Chinese anticipation and British
angst, this is not the reluctant surrender of a prized possession.
Portugal tried to give back this enclave of 430,000 people once
before, after the revolution that ended decades of dictatorship in
Portugal in 1974, but China's leaders, fearful of losing a trading
channel to the outside world, demurred.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the Portuguese administration has presided over
Macau's steady deterioration into a disreputable, vaguely sinister
gambling destination for weekend wagerers from Hong Kong. As feuds
between rival Chinese gangs have terrorized the colony over the
last few years, the economy has withered and Macau has become ever
more hooked on the casinos, which generate more than half of its
tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a local, I'd have to say the Portuguese haven't done a good
job,'' said Eric T.M. Yeung, a prominent Macau businessman who
makes toys. ``But in fairness, they had their own problems and
couldn't pay attention to a little spot of land on the other side
of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior Chinese official in the future local government, who
asked not to be identified to avoid offending the Portuguese, said:
``Hong Kong is so successful that Hong Kong people always think
they are superior to the Chinese. We are happy in Macau, but I
don't think anyone is proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Portuguese officials are keenly aware of their checkered legacy.
They were the first Europeans to colonize in Asia, driven by a lust
for adventure and discovery, and a desire to spread the
Christianity that had helped free Portugal of Moorish, Muslim rule.
But for all the centuries they have lingered here, the Portuguese
have left behind no lasting political culture.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few weeks, they have worked diligently to promote
the artifacts, old and new, of 442 years of colonial rule:
meticulously restored buildings in Portuguese pastels, a
state-of-the-art airport and gleaming causeways that connect Macau
with its outer islands.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal's president, Jorge Sampaio, said that in the last
decade Macau had taken on many of the hallmarks of a liberal
Western state, including the rule of law, freedom of religion and a
free press. ``Well, it could have been done 300 years ago,'' he
said in an interview on the eve of the hand-over, ``but that was
not the habit of time.''
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday's ceremony, the departing colonial masters from a
small nation on the other side of the world have produced the
trappings of a momentous occasion. Last week, workers frantically
hammered the last planks on an $8 million pavilion where President
Jiang Zemin of China will take control of the 8-square-mile
territory from Sampaio. Officials say the translucent building is
meant to resemble a Chinese lantern. In truth, it looks more like a
giant, softly lighted bathtub.
</P>
<P>
   The Portuguese have also sought to account for the dark side of
their rule: a stunted political system, with few local Chinese
trained to take over the government, shaky courts, a corrupt police
force, and a democracy movement that can be summed up by the fact
that it has exactly one elected legislator.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can build an airport in five years; we can build a bridge
in two,'' said Jorge Alberto Rangel, the secretary for public
administration, who is coordinating the hand-over ceremony. ``But
forming people takes time. We really did what we thought was best
for Macau.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangel's sense of conflict is deeply felt. A native Macanese _
part Portuguese, part Chinese _ he comes from one of the colony's
oldest families.
</P>
<P>
   But he also served in the Portuguese Army as an infantry
commander in Guinea-Bissau, in West Africa. There, Rangel witnessed
Portugal's chaotic departure from its African colonies after the
1974 revolution. With no leadership and no capacity to govern
themselves, formerly Portuguese Mozambique and Angola fell into
bloody strife, which in Angola continues today.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened in Africa was disaster,'' Rangel said. ``We made
no preparations, like we have here. I believe Macau deserved to
have it done differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Portugal's sudden renunciation of empire was not just a tragedy
in Africa. Its retreat from East Timor 25 years ago opened the door
for Indonesia to invade and turn the colony into an unwilling
province. Guerrilla rebels fought the Indonesian army until this
year, when Jakarta unexpectedly agreed to allow the East Timorese
to decide their own future. The Indonesian army left, but not
before reducing much of the territory to cinders and attacking the
Roman Catholic Church, whose strength in East Timor is arguably
Portugal's most lasting legacy there.
</P>
<P>
   Macau was spared such predations, mainly because China
effectively gave Portugal squatter's rights after its seafarers
landed here in 1557. Satisfied as long as the Portuguese paid
tribute, the Chinese allowed them to build a bustling trading post
in the 17th and 18th centuries. Along with the traders came the
Jesuit priests, who used Macau as a base to launch missions into
China. The richly detailed facade of Sao Paulo, the surviving
fragment of a church that burned down in 1831, attests to the
church's deep roots here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing that a European power could remain on Chinese
soil for all this time,'' said Fok Kai Cheong, a professor of
history at the University of Macau. ``They survived every kind of
Chinese government: dynastic, xenophobic, nationalistic,
Communist.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Macau kept the peace with China, it could do little
about the thrusting British colony 38 miles across the Pearl River
delta. Hong Kong, which was ceded to Britain in 1842 after the
Opium War, rapidly supplanted Macau as the preferred trading hub in
the region. By the early 20th century, Macau was a backwater known
mostly as a refuge for families fleeing from China's war with
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Macau's next shock came in 1966, when Chinese laborers caught up
in the fever of the Cultural Revolution rose up against the
Portuguese. The unrest was quelled, but it shook Macau's
administrators and soured Lisbon's appetite for its vestigial
foothold in Asia. As the Portuguese retreated, local Chinese _
mostly bankers and traders _ emerged as the de facto powers in the
colony.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Among those shadow leaders was Ho Yin, a banker who is revered
by many here for mediating between the Chinese and the Portuguese.
His son, Edmund Ho, was chosen to be the first postcolonial chief
executive of Macau by a Beijing-appointed committee last May.
</P>
<P>
   Like his counterpart in Hong Kong, Tung Chee-hwa, Ho is a
conservative businessman who is not likely to ruffle the feathers
of the Chinese leaders. He even looks a bit like Tung, with
razor-cut hair that would pass muster in boot camp. But unlike the
courtly Tung, he can be blunt.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview here on the eve of taking control, Ho, 44, came
across like a big-city mayor who wanted to let people know who was
boss. His target was the Chinese gangs, or triads, which have waged
an ugly war for control of Macau's casinos since the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``My basic policy on the triads is that they have to learn how
to behave,'' he said. ``I don't think we'll have to go house to
house, arresting people and putting them in concentration camps.
But they must know how to behave. If you are in the underworld,
learn to keep it under.''
</P>
<P>
   Ho also welcomed Beijing's decision to deploy army troops in
Macau after the hand-over. Portugal had protested the move, noting
that it had withdrawn its troops in 1974. Sampaio even briefly
threatened to boycott the ceremony Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Although Ho said the troops would not be used for police work,
he clearly relished having a garrison at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``One major advantage is that I will have psychological support
for making drastic changes in the police,'' he said. ``Because if
they say, `We're not happy, we don't want reforms, we don't want to
do our jobs,' I'll say, `You can just step aside and I'll put in
the soldiers.'''
</P>
<P>
   Remarks like that would cause a tempest in Hong Kong, where
pro-democracy leaders are on the lookout for any authoritarian
tendencies in the government. Among Macau's overwhelmingly Chinese
population, however, they are seen as an overdue return to law and
order.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Most local people don't object to the Chinese army coming to
Macau,'' said Ng Kuok Cheong, the lone pro-democracy member in the
territory's legislature. ``They believe that mainland China can
control crime, but that the Portuguese government can't.''
</P>
<P>
   China is happy that most Macanese see it that way. For Beijing,
the ceremony Sunday is another step in its push to reunify all of
China, including Taiwan, the seat of the Chinese Nationalist
government whose 22 million people seem unlikely to accept any move
that would place them under Communist rule.
</P>
<P>
   Ng, a soft-spoken former loan officer at the Bank of China who
lost his job because of his politics, said that democracy had
little future in Macau. But he blames that less on China than on
Portugal. ``The British established a pro-Western capitalist elite
in Hong Kong,'' Ng said. ``The Portuguese never did that. Their
primary concern was preserving Portuguese culture.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A magnificent salmon-pink edifice housing the public security
department here attests both to that Portuguese concern and to the
accompanying failure to curb the gang wars that have killed
government officials, scared off tourists and brought gun battles
and car bombings to otherwise tranquil streets.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Macau sentenced its most flamboyant triad leader,
Wan Kuok-koi, to 15 years in prison. It was a victory for the
authorities, who had seethed as Wan strutted around town with an
aura of invincibility. Yet Wan, who goes by the nickname Broken
Tooth, got in some telling last words. As he was being led away, he
screamed at the police: ``You're corrupt. You've taken dirty
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Few people here believe Wan's demise will end the mayhem. But
they note approvingly that China has arrested hundreds of suspected
triad members in neighboring Guangdong Province. Now, they say, the
new government must figure out how to clean up Macau's casinos,
which have contributed to the crime wave by allowing gangs to take
control of VIP rooms that cater to high rollers.
</P>
<P>
   Cramped, dark and crawling with prostitutes, Macau's casinos are
worlds away from the theme-park ambience of Las Vegas. The gambling
industry is controlled by Stanley Ho, a Hong Kong billionaire who
has held an exclusive government license since 1961. That license
expires in 2001, and Edmund Ho, who is not related to Stanley, has
not revealed whether it will be renewed.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For now, Macau's next leader is busy building a government
``from ground zero,'' Edmund Ho notes in a swipe at the decamping
colonials. He is also putting out the word that Macau intends to
remain a distinct enclave, with its own laws and customs. Even he
acknowledges, however, that it will live mostly in memory _
Europe's last foothold in Asia, soon to be lost in the enormity of
modern China.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone here would like the world to remember that there's a
Macau somewhere in this region,'' Ho said a bit wistfully. ``But we
have to be realistic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
