<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-HOUSTON-GEORGETOWN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Houston's late-game lapse bails out Georgetown
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JERRY WIZIG &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WASHINGTON _ Kenny Younger's 3-point shot with 3 minutes, 44
seconds to play lifted the Houston Cougars into a tie with
Georgetown.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cougars never scored again and, taking advantage of
game-turning offensive rebounds and two critical UH turnovers, the
Hoyas sealed an up-and-down 83-75 victory Saturday that was a far
cry from the teams' 1984 NCAA championship matchup.
</P>
<P>
   That game, won by the Hoyas 84-75 at Seattle, was eons ago in
terms of where both programs are today, with Georgetown, coming off
a 15-16 record, now 6-3 and the 5-5 Cougars, in coach Clyde
Drexler's words, ``making progress back to respectability.''
</P>
<P>
   John Thompson, who retired as Hoyas coach Jan. 8, 1999, was
among the sparse MCI Center crowd of 7,198. President Clinton, a
Georgetown alumnus, attended the Washington Wizards game Thursday
night but passed on this one.
</P>
<P>
   Georgetown, aggressive as ever on the boards if not as skilled
in other areas, hammered the Cougars 29-15 on the glass in the
second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seemed like it was five times as much,'' Drexler said of the
near 2-to-1 margin.
</P>
<P>
   After Younger's shot, only his second field goal of the day,
Georgetown rebounded two consecutive Hoyas misses to set up guard
Kevin Braswell's 3-pointer. The game's 17th lead change restored
the lead for good to the Hoyas with 2:44 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   UH failed to score on its ensuing trip down the court, and Rhese
Gibson fired in his only basket of the game from the right corner
after another offensive rebound by Georgetown, which claimed 21 of
its 46 at the offensive end.
</P>
<P>
   Younger then missed another 3-pointer, and Gee Gervin had his
3-pointer blocked by 6-11 center Ruben Boumtje Boumtje. After
Braswell charged, George Williams, UH's 6-8 freshman, saw his
baseline shot go in and out, and the Cougars were done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were letting them get rebounds until they made a shot,''
Drexler said of the second half, when the foul-plagued Cougars were
forced to play about six minutes with four reserves and Williams on
the floor. ``For the second game in a row, Gee and Kenny got in
foul trouble, and it's tough on us when they are on the bench. We
had guys come off the bench and play enormous roles, and that's
what we are going to have to have.''
</P>
<P>
   UH's Torrence Botts, a 6-1 sophomore walk-on, contributed nine
points, a team-high six rebounds, five assists and a steal. Tega
Moceanu, a 6-8 junior walk-on, added nine points, including a pair
of treys, but he picked up a flagrant foul and an ensuing technical
for two personals late in the first half. Both Younger and Gervin
went to the bench for a long stretch with their fourth personals
with 11 minutes to go, Gervin's occurring in a loose-ball scramble
when he was kicked in the nose and an official changed the foul
call to Gervin from Larry Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Gervin scored 16 of his game-high 24 in the first half as the
Cougars led most of the way. Younger, who was 2-for-10 shooting
after a 3-of-13 effort in the one-point loss at Louisiana-Monroe on
Wednesday, added 12 points and Chad Hendrick had 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenny was (Conference USA) Player of the Week last week,''
Drexler said. ``Since then, we haven't seen him.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington scout Wil Robinson, one of a platoon of NBA talent
evaluators watching, said of Gervin, ``He'll be playing in the
league.''
</P>
<P>
   But first, Gervin and the Cougars need to do something about
their costly lapses at the end of close games.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get rebounds at the end and come down and score, I feel
like it would have been our game,'' Gervin said. ``But we gave them
too many chances to score after they missed shots and those late
turnovers were killers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hoyas' 23 turnovers helped the Cougars, who shot only 27.6
percent in the second half and 37.9 for the game. Georgetown
blocked nine shots, including five by 6-11 Jameel Watkins, who also
had nine rebounds. Victor Samnick, a 6-8 freshman, helped hold UH's
Williams without a first-half field goal and also scored 17 points.
Braswell (18), 6-3 guard Anthony Perry (15 points with nine
rebounds) and Boumtje Boumtje (10) helped give the Hoyas four
double-figure scorers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt if we will play a team this year that changes as often
and plays as many kinds of zone defenses as Houston,'' Georgetown
coach Craig Esherick said. ``Until the end of the game, we couldn't
get an offensive flow going.''
</P>
<P>
   But that flow came just in time to swing the game to the Hoyas.
</P>
</TEXT>
