<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA GIVES DEPAUL FROSH-BITE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Searching for answers and desperate for victory,
UCLA coach Steve Lavin got his wish Saturday against No. 19 DePaul:
gifted big men Dan Gadzuric and Jerome Moiso played together for
the first time this season. They did not disappoint, combining for
32 points, 20 rebounds and five blocks.
</P>
<P>
   But the story of UCLA's return from its Gonzaga grave was not
the hulking front-liners with their thunder dunks and intimidating
swats. It was a black headband worn by unassuming freshman forward
Jason Kapono.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I wasn't playing well, and I needed to do
something to change things up,'' Kapono said. ``I put the headband
on, and I came out loose. The next thing I know, we're out there
playing well and winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Kapono scored a team-high 20 points and drained three 3-point
baskets early in the second half to propel UCLA to a 76-58 victory
before 10,024 at Pauley Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   His first strike, from the top of the key, gave UCLA a 31-30
lead it would never relinquish. A minute later, he struck from the
right corner for a 36-30 lead. Three possessions later, his swish
from the right wing gave the Bruins a 42-30 margin and forced the
Blue Demons to call timeout.
</P>
<P>
   When the surge ended _ it was, by far, UCLA's best offensive
stretch of the season _ the Bruins had outscored DePaul 23-5 and
were cruising to victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first four games, I wasn't scared, I was just hesitant,''
Kapono said. ``I told coach Lavin that I was just trying to find my
niche.''
</P>
<P>
   He has _ as the vortex of UCLA's offense.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 18 Bruins (4-1) spent all week correcting the flaws in
their zone offense _ flaws exposed last season in the NCAA
Tournament and last week against Gonzaga. The coaches emphasized
passing and discouraged dribbling, and they stationed Kapono, their
smartest player, in the middle of the court _ the optimum spot for
him to direct the offense and distribute the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Time and again, he'd catch a pass with his back to the basket,
spin, and hit open teammates on the wings or in the corners. The
crisp ball movement spread DePaul's zone defense and enabled the
Bruins to shoot 54.5 percent in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach told us to pass instead of dribble and keep the ball
moving like a hot potato,'' Bruins guard Ryan Bailey said. ``We had
to make the defense honor each person.''
</P>
<P>
   DePaul, which shot 30 percent against UCLA's long-limbed zone
defense, made Kapono's job easier by sending four players to the
offensive boards. The strategy generated 25 offensive rebounds, and
it ruined the Blue Demons' floor balance and enabled UCLA's dormant
fast break to shift into high gear. Each of Kapono's 3-pointers
came in transition, as did most of its baskets during the 23-5
surge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very bad offensively,'' said DePaul coach Pat Kennedy,
who was without injured point guard Rashon Bruno. ``We didn't get
any good looks, and UCLA's defense was all over.''
</P>
<P>
   If Kapono was the Bruins' vortex, Bailey was their initiator.
Healthy for the first time in weeks _ he had tendinitis in his foot
_ Bailey totaled seven rebounds, five assists and three steals in
26 crafty minutes at point guard. His presence enabled Earl Watson
(1 of 9 from the field) to slide to wing guard, his natural
position. That subtle change sparked UCLA's best ball movement
since it dismantled Syracuse in February.
</P>
<P>
   Expect to see Watson on the wing more often, with the ball in
Bailey's _ or Kapono's _ hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ryan gave us a great lift,'' Lavin said. ``He and Kapono can
kick it ahead to Earl.''
</P>
<P>
   Note: The question is when, not if, ineligible forward Matt
Barnes will be reinstated. Barnes said he has passed three of the
four classes needed to lift his academic suspension.
</P>
<P>
   ``The grade I don't know is from an English class, and I had an
A going into the final, so I know I'm OK,'' Barnes said. ``Now, I'm
going to sit in my dorm and wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the grade is posted _ Barnes hopes it's today or Monday _
he'll hop a plane and join the Bruins in Hawaii.
</P>
</TEXT>
