<HEADER>
A3267 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     12-19 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA REBOUNDS IN STYLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ I !ital!read!off! about UCLA's embarrassing loss
to Gonzaga last weekend at Pauley Pavilion. The 17 second-half
points, the 26-percent shooting, the sullen postgame quotes (``We
rolled over'').
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't there, though. And now I don't believe it really
happened. I'm not sure there's even a university called Gonzaga.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe last Sunday's newspaper was somebody's idea of a prank.
</P>
<P>
   A team couldn't play as badly as UCLA supposedly did against
Gonzaga, and turn around and destroy 19th-ranked DePaul 76-58 the
way the Bruins did Saturday in front of 10,024 fans at Pauley.
</P>
<P>
   The guys from DePaul _ you want to talk about sullen? _ must
have thought the same thing I did.
</P>
<P>
   These weren't the Bruins they read about. These weren't the
Bruins they watched on videotape.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gonzaga tape, I told our kids, was going to be
misleading,'' DePaul coach Pat Kennedy said. ``Gonzaga is a very
good, experienced team that executes that flex offense very well.
If Gonzaga could shoot the 3 like that all the time, they could
beat anybody. Now UCLA had its back to the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told our kids that other than Duke, this is the most
talented team we'll play all year.''
</P>
<P>
   The result for those talented Bruins, a 27-7 run after they
trailed at halftime, had DePaul sounding like UCLA the Saturday
before.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Demons, like the Bruins before them, noted the absence
of a key player (injured point guard Rashon Burno).
</P>
<P>
   They pointed to a critical, second-half offensive lapse.
</P>
<P>
   They concluded, as tomahawk-jamming guard Paul McPherson put it,
``We have a long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Demons did have an excuse worth listening to. Their
flight west Friday was five hours late getting off the ground in
Chicago because O'Hare Airport had to be closed for a couple of
hours after a jet skidded off a frozen runway. They thought they
might have to cancel the game, and got to Los Angeles too late to
practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids were all screwed up,'' Kennedy said. ``I don't know
(if it's an excuse), I'm just saying it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday, DePaul was grounded by a UCLA team that responded
to a bad loss the way coach Steve Lavin's teams have done
repeatedly the past three seasons, the way they did after losing to
Tulsa, to Kansas (by 13), at Stanford (by 48), to North Carolina
(by 41) in Alaska, and at Duke (by 36).
</P>
<P>
   They played as if they had something to prove _ as a team and
not only to the seven NBA clubs that were represented Saturday.
(The Lakers' Jerry West and the Clippers' Elgin Baylor were in the
crowd.)
</P>
<P>
   Another loss would have slotted the Bruins below the nation's
ranked teams for now and cost them rungs in the NCAA Tournament
seedings in March. Another loss would have put Lavin under fire
from more than the talk-radio jocks.
</P>
<P>
   The guys on the radio pregame show, by the way, were predicting
a defeat for 18th-ranked UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   The victory inserts UCLA into sentences with 15th-ranked Texas
and 11th-ranked Duke, which handed DePaul its only losses in nine
earlier games.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're good, they're athletic,'' McPherson said after the
game.
</P>
<P>
   He compared UCLA more to Texas, with its physical center, than
Duke, with its emphasis on the perimeter game.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Forward-center Jerome) Moiso makes things happen inside, and
(center Dan) Gadzuric gets everything around the basket,''
McPherson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're definitely a good team,'' said Quentin Richardson, the
game's top scorer with 22 points.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, as much as anybody, was affected by UCLA's strength,
its defense. DePaul's leader got only eight shots in the first half
and finished 8 for 23; the Blue Demons shot 30.1 percent in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They switched into and out of their zone really well, and we
didn't adjust to it well enough,'' Richardson said of the Bruins.
``They stayed packed in the whole game, and with Moiso and Gadzuric
in there, I had a pretty hard time getting to the basket.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' defense resulted in a fast break like none the Blue
Demons have seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where they clearly beat us was in the offensive transition,''
Kennedy said, ``and nobody had done that to us this year. They kept
getting behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   That made the Bruins (4-1) look pretty good as they go to Hawaii
for a three-game tournament and look ahead to their next big test
against No.24 Purdue Dec. 30 at Pauley.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's best not to get too excited just because they
dominated a ranked team. One game does not a season make, as we
were reminded after the loss to Gonzaga, the game that might not
really have taken place after all. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-19-99 0021EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
