<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-19 00:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3268 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-LA-HOSTAGE-RESOLUTION     12-19 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-HOSTAGE-RESOLUTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOSTAGE STANDOFF ENDS AT LOUISIANA JAIL
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
(No byline)    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. MARTINVILLE, La. _ The end of the siege at the St. Martin
Parish jail in this small southern Louisiana town came suddenly
late Saturday night as six detainees released their seven hostages
in a whirl of colored lights as ambulances rushed to the jail. As
suddenly as it started, it was over. Dozens of members of Swat
teams ran from the building cheering and high-fiving, stripping off
their riot gear and throwing it in the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's over,'' they yelled to reporters standing nearby.
``Everyone is OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Stretchers were brought down with two hostages who had been held
the longest, the jail's warden, Todd Louviere, 35, and deputy Jolie
Sonnier, 20. Louviere had grown a beard over the six days he was
held hostage by a group of six detainees who were protesting their
long imprisonment. Five of the detainees were Cubans and one was
from the Bahamas. Five women inmates had also been held.
</P>
<P>
   Family members of the hostages rushed to the scene, weeping and
seeking information in the confusion. ``Thank god they're OK,''
sobbed a woman who identified herself as Ms. Sonnier's mother.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, FBI special agent in charge Charles
Mathews III announced that the hostage crisis had ended at 10 p.m.
``It's all over,'' he said. ``Everybody is fine.''
</P>
<P>
   The St. Martin Parish sheriff, Charles S. Fuselier, said, ``I
don't think we could have asked for a better Christmas present than
this.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The authorities said the release was negotiated by federal and
state officials along with a local spanish-speaking television
producer and the mother of one of the hostage-takers.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Placer, a television producer in Lafayette, La., said the
authorities asked for her help on Friday as the detainees were
demanding that the media be involved. The hostage-taker's mother,
Mercedes Villar, said Saturday that she had been promised that the
detainees would be returned to Cuba. Asked repeatedly to confirm or
deny this, Mathews would say only ``No comment.''
</P>
<P>
   The standoff began in the jail in this town of 8,000 on Monday
when five inmates, armed with a knife and a screwdriver, overcame
Louviere, Ms. Sonnier and another guard, Brandon Boudreaux. Three
other prisoners later joined the ringleaders, the police said. The
rebel inmates had demanded safe passage from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, two Cubans involved in the uprising surrendered,
and Boudreaux, 20, was released along with three female inmates.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Saturday, the authorities at the jail had cleared the
remaining 54 prisoners from the jail.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The police said the 54 inmates, the last of 172 who were in St.
Martin Parish jail, 110 miles west of New Orleans, when the siege
began, left through a hole cut in an interior wall so the
hostage-takers could not see them. The inmates, who were taken to
other jails, were not involved in the uprising and had asked to be
moved, said Mathews.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most of the hostage-takers are immigrants who have completed
sentences for crimes committed in the United States but have
remained in custody because they cannot be deported home, the
Immigration and Naturalization Service said. One has been held for
nearly seven years.
</P>
<P>
   The immigration agency has said that the Cubans came ashore in
the Mariel boatlift in 1980, during which Fidel Castro sent
hundreds of criminals to the United States. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Officials declined to explain any of the releases, but the
flurry of activity occurred a few hours after Louviere and Ms.
Sonnier used the jail public address system to speak out in support
of their captors' cause.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They criticized United States policy on Cuban detainees and
urged that a helicopter be brought in to take the detainees to
freedom.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
