<HEADER>
A3284 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-JOKES-T     12-19 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-JOKES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS' LOSING WAYS HAVE MADE THEM THE RUNNING JOKE OF
PROFESSIONAL SPORTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ /This guy goes into a 7-Eleven and leaves two Mavericks
tickets on the dashboard of his unlocked car. When he comes back he
finds six tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   Poor Mavericks. They just can't win for, well, losing.
</P>
<P>
   The losingest pro sports franchise of the decade has become a
running joke. Turn on ``SportsCenter.'' Pick up the newspaper. Tune
in to sports-talk radio. Everyone is making fun of the Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, rightfully so,'' Mavericks guard Hubert Davis said.
``Until we start winning, jokes are going to be made about us.''
</P>
<P>
   Bad coaching, bad drafts, bad trades and bad free-agency
signings have doomed the franchise to a laughingstock. The
Mavericks have had seven head coaches and 94 players on their
roster this decade alone.
</P>
<P>
   Things have gotten so bad for the Mavericks that comedians no
longer regularly take their name in shame. Four Day Weekend Comedy
Troup in Fort Worth has not done a spoof on the Mavericks in two
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're so pathetic that no one even comments about them
anymore,'' said David Ahearn, a partner in the comedy club.
``That's how bad it's gotten. The Mavericks are almost a parody of
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   /Did you hear that the Mavericks played a scrimmage against
themselves _ and tied.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks' record is laughable. They are 612-938 (.395) in
their 20-year history, and in a league that has more than half of
the 29 teams in the playoffs each year, the Mavericks have gone
nine seasons without a postseason berth.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks can't even console themselves with a claim of ``at
least we're not the Clippers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clips may have a worse reputation, but the Mavericks have a
worse record. The Lakers' NBA stepsisters were 282-506 (.358) from
the 1989-90 to the 1998-99 season; the Mavericks were an NBA-worst
246-542 (.312).
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Mavericks (8-16) lost at home to Vancouver, a
team that had a 30-game road losing streak. And after Phoenix lost
a recent game in Dallas, Danny Ainge quit as the Suns' coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mavs are like Kmart,'' said Aaron Richard, 25, of
Lewisville. ``They're never going to be taken seriously until they
either change their name or move.''
</P>
<P>
   It has not been all the Mavericks' fault. They have had bad
luck, too. The Mavericks lost a team-record 363 player games to
injury in 1997-98. Last season, guard Robert Pack missed 25 of 50
games, and forward Cedric Ceballos was out for 37 as the team
finished 19-31.
</P>
<P>
   This season, the Mavericks have had 10 players miss a total of
128 games, including 22 by Gary Trent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget the Bambino Curse,'' Mavericks guard Erick Strickland
said. ``What about the Maverick Curse?''
</P>
<P>
   It was not always this way. The Mavericks once were good.
</P>
<P>
   Remember when they lost to the Los Angeles Lakers in the seventh
game of the Western Conference finals in 1988? Second-year
Mavericks forward Dirk Nowitzki doesn't. He was 9 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great,'' said Brad Davis, 43, who played with the
Mavericks from 1980-92 and now is the team's radio analyst. ``It
was a lot like what the Stars are going through now. We were
selling out season tickets, and you know, every time we went out on
the court, we thought we were going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, every time the Mavericks go out on the court, everyone
expects them to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Kissell, 26, of Crowley is a sports fan. He is not a
Mavericks fan. Asked if he owns any Mavericks apparel, Kissell
said, ``You mean other than a paper bag I can put over my head?''
</P>
<P>
   Tough crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``A bumper sticker seen on a police car: ``Go Cowboys ... and
take the Mavericks with you!''''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the NBA lockout and the Mavericks' history, the team
still averaged 14,513 at Reunion Arena last season. This season the
Mavericks' slogan is: ``One Fan At A Time.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim White, 29, isn't buying it _ or tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would really like the Mavs to stop sending me things in the
mail,'' said White of Keller. ``I do not want season tickets to see
a semi-professional team play. Save your stamp.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Hamilton, 45, recently moved from Omaha, Neb., to McKinney.
He attended his first Mavericks game this season but hasn't decided
if it will be his last.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to figure out if I'm going to become a Mavs' fan or
not,'' Hamilton said. ``I haven't quite figured it out. That tells
you something, right?''
</P>
<P>
   Even longtime Mavericks fans _ no, that's not a misnomer _ have
a sense of humor about their team.
</P>
<P>
   Lance Luna, 27, grew up with the Mavericks. His family has had
two season tickets since the team's debut in 1980-81. Every year he
keeps believing the Mavericks will be better. Every year he's
disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' Luna said, laughing, ``they are my team. I'm going to
give them one more chance. Just one more year. I know they don't
deserve it. I'm just a diehard fan. Stupid, I know.''
</P>
<P>
   /Did you hear about the new McDonald's value meal? For a $1.99
you get a cheeseburger, fries, a drink and two Mavericks tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks have two banners hanging in the rafters of Reunion
Arena. One honors the retired jersey No. 15 of Davis. The other
remembers the 1986-87 NBA Midwest Division Champions.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars, who have called Reunion home only since the 1993-94
season, have 10 banners, including one for winning the Stanley Cup
championship last season. The Stars began this season with only 13
fewer victories than the Mavericks in four fewer seasons this
decade.
</P>
<P>
   In a city where playoff berths are expected and championships
are celebrated, the Mavericks are in a no-win situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should the fans have faith in us?'' guard Steve Nash said.
``We haven't won in 10 years. It's been a perpetual cycle of
inadequacy. We're just the latest inheritors of the situation.
We're trying to fight out of it. There are not a lot of ways to get
better. There's free agency, and there's youth. We're going with
youth. It's going to take some time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks have almost the same roster as last season.
Strapped by the salary cap, coach/general manager Don Nelson could
not afford to keep forward Samaki Walker from leaving for San
Antonio. They were only able to add bit players like Randell
Jackson and Damon Jones.
</P>
<P>
   If the Mavericks and their fans didn't laugh, they might cry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize the Mavs are the Mavs,'' said Reed Williams, 22, of
Dallas. ``But one day, the Mavs are going to shine again.''
</P>
<P>
   Until then, the Mavericks will play the part of punchline. Their
best hope is to have the last laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just laugh at the things people say,'' Strickland said. ``I
laugh at it. I think it's funny. I think the team wants to work
that much harder to prove them wrong.''
\Nsubheds:Decade of defeat The teams with the worst winning
percentages in each of the four major leagues this decade, through
Saturday: Team League W-L-T Pct. Mavericks NBA 254-558 .313
Cincinnati Bengals NFL 52-106 .329 Ottawa Senators NHL 176-327-73
.350 Detroit Tigers MLB 702-852 .452
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
