<HEADER>
A3285 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-STARS-INJURIES-TE     12-19 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-INJURIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS RESPOND WITHOUT HATCHER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia _ Captain Derian Hatcher has, at
times, been a lone steadying influence n this tumultuous Stars'
season, marked by injuries and struggles.
</P>
<P>
   He began this season a lot as he ended last, a defensive
stalwart. When losing streaks and scoring droughts swooped in, he
took responsibility for returning the Stars to Stanley Cup-winning
form.
</P>
<P>
   His teammates took his cue and followed his lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at Hatch and he's a big guy, and you look at him and
go `You know what? He's a machine,''' Stars defenseman Brad
Lukowich said. ``And so you don't think anything is going to happen
to a guy like that, and then to see him in that state, like he was
after the game, it was a shocker. I was blown away. I was like,
`Wow, this is for real.' ''
</P>
<P>
   A glance at Hatcher, hobbling around on crutches with a
six-to-eight-week recovery prognosis, redefined reality for a Stars
bunch that finally appeared be improving. Now, the Stars have to
find another steadying influence to hold together a fragile
confidence that Hatcher had helped build.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Derian, along with our goalie, are the two players who
have outperformed the norms and kept our team floating lots of
nights,'' Stars general manager Bob Gainey said. ``There comes a
time when we either need an upgrade across the board from a group
of players who are underperforming, or different players to grab
that challenge or responsibility and help to diminish what we're
going to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Gainey said the answer has to come from within because neither a
trade nor a free-agent signing is imminent. He already had been
shopping around and found little help available.
</P>
<P>
   So, it's sink or swim time without the best defensive defenseman
in the NHL serving as a life vest.
</P>
<P>
   Day 1 of Life Without Hatcher began last night with a 4-2
victory against the Vancouver Canucks at General Motors Place.
</P>
<P>
   While Hatcher returned to Dallas on Saturday after sustaining a
laceration on his lower calf that punctured his muscle midway
through Friday's game against Edmonton, news on forward Joe
Nieuwendyk proved to be better. Nieuwendyk also exited Friday's
game after a cross check caused cartilage damage around his ribs.
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said Nieuwendyk felt better and might
be ready to return as soon as Tuesday's game against Calgary.
</P>
<P>
   Stars players had been preparing to be without both players.is
enough].
</P>
<P>
   ``I think any time you lose a guy like Derian, it's an immediate
impact,'' said defenseman Richard Matvichuk, Hatcher's defensive
partner for four-plus seasons. ``What Derian brings to this team is
like what nobody brings to any other team. He's our captain, our
leader, and don't forget, he's doing it for 35 minutes a night.''
</P>
<P>
   So, who replaces Hatcher?
</P>
<P>
   The answer isn't one person. Everybody said it has to be a team
effort, forwards included.
</P>
<P>
   Said Matvichuk: ``Playing without him is going to be weird. ...
Myself, Darryl \RSydor\S and Zubie \R]Sergei Zubov\S are going to
have to take the blunt end of things.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have been without Hatcher before, including the first
five games of the playoffs last season. Times, however, were
different. The Stars had a certain swagger about them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to lose a player, a good player, when
everything was functioning well,'' Gainey said. ``You could sort of
plaster over that crack more easily. But when it's not ...''
</P>
<P>
   The way Hitchcock sees it, the Stars can use Hatcher's injury as
a way to become a better team if they start fixing the cracks
instead of relying on Hatcher and goalie Ed Belfour, to cover them.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, our team is not going to be the same,'' Hitchcock said.
``What I mean by not the same is this is either going to make us
better or worse. But we have a real chance for it to make us better
because it's going to force people to really come together.
</P>
<P>
   The team will go on, but the person who is reeling a bit is
Hatcher. He had been mounting what possibly was a Norris
Trophy-like season. He was averaging 30-plus minutes a game and had
solidified his reputation as the best defensive defenseman in the
NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just shrugs,'' Hitchcock said, ``but he's a very emotional
person. He's very disappointed, and he recognized that the team was
starting to play well ...''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
