<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-19 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3288 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-SPELLMAN-     12-19 1310
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-SPELLMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPELLMAN FINDS SELF, REVIVES NFL CAREER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ In one unforgettable day during the summer,
Cowboys defensive tackle Alonzo Spellman's life completely changed
while he lounged inside his first-story master bedroom at his
Chicago home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lord came to me, and it was like a cool breeze over my
body, then all of a sudden I couldn't keep my eyes dry,'' Spellman
said. ``I had been praying every day for 5 1/2 months.''
</P>
<P>
   Two months later, Cowboys owner Jerry Jones worked a deal with
agent Leigh Steinberg to bring Spellman into a team environment
that prides itself on a strong support system _ namely former
Cowboys running back Calvin Hill and his staff, which has been set
up to counsel players in a myriad of off-field matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' Spellman said, ``God comes right on time.''
</P>
<P>
   Spellman was shown a picture of himself from the 1992 Chicago
Bears media guide and was asked to talk about that person.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh man! That guy right there? He was extremely motivated,''
Spellman said. ``Wow! That guy ... well, he thought he knew
everything. He thought he was going to be the next great defensive
end of the Chicago Bears. Nothing was going to stop him. Fast cars.
Fast money. Fast women.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a 20-year-old's dream. But he wasn't a bad guy. He
didn't drink. He didn't smoke. But in every other area, he was
always going 100 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``So when Jesus Christ came back into my life, I knew I wanted
to start fresh because the Lord had taken away that old spirit.
With my renewed spirit, I didn't want to be reminded of that old
person that I used to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I used to put a premium on clothes and shoes, so I gave
away probably $30,000 to $50,000 worth of shoes and maybe $100,000
worth of clothes to family members. It was good for them. It was
even better for me.''
</P>
<P>
   To appreciate Alonzo Spellman is to measure how far he has come
in five months with the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Or in seven months since renewing his faith in God.
</P>
<P>
   Or in 20 months since he went spiritually bankrupt and
behaviorally helter-skelter during a SWAT-team standoff in April
1998.
</P>
<P>
   That's the image we have of the old Alonzo Spellman,
unexplainably barricading himself inside the suburban Chicago home
of his publicist for eight hours during a tense standoff with
police that ended only when former Chicago Bears teammate and Hall
of Famer Mike Singletary stepped forward and talked Spellman down
from his emotional ledge.
</P>
<P>
   That same bizarre day, amid the standoff, linebacker Derrick
Thomas of the Kansas City Chiefs tried to convey to Spellman by
telephone that not all was lost, and that Thomas was ready to go to
the wall for him to get the Chiefs to trade for his talents.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of a quick happy-ending, the next day Spellman _
shirtless and shoeless _ broke through a hospital door and escaped
what everyone around him felt he needed: medical evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   Two months later, the Bears, who had drafted him as a
20-year-old junior and first-round pick from Ohio State to become
the next Richard Dent, now gave him his unconditional release.
</P>
<P>
   Except for some short-lived interest shown by the Jacksonville
Jaguars in August 1998, Spellman remained on the NFL unemployment
line until the Cowboys signed him for the $400,000 veteran's
minimum July 29.
</P>
<P>
   No other NFL team even bid for his services.
</P>
<P>
   It was about this same time that Spellman was given a diagnosis
of] bipolar disorder, or clinical depression. Spellman since has
debunked the diagnosis, although he stops short of explaining what
he means.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Spellman is a Pro Bowl-type player, a model citizen, a
walking-talking testimonial for Jesus Christ, and one of the most
genuine and engaging personalities on the team.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said, ``Alonzo has inspired me in a way that I haven't
been inspired in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Spellman's words get stuck in his throat whenever he is asked
about an Aug. 2, 1998 Chicago ``Sun-Times'' report that claimed he
``told \Rhis publicist\S he wanted to kill himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Spellman won't go there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not ready to get into what was going through my head \Rin
April 1998\S. But it was a lot ... a lot,'' said Spellman, his
words at first partially choked with emotion, then merely conserved
for another time perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know one day I will be able to have a true testimony to
young saints walking into the Christian way of life,'' Spellman
said. ``I know the Lord will put me in that place, and I can talk
to a group of young Christians about the marathon of faith that you
have to run.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he had an emotional problem before joining the
Cowboys, Spellman shook his head. And when asked if he has taken
any medication for depression, he shook his head again.
</P>
<P>
   ``My medication was my Bible,'' Spellman said. ``It was only my
Bible, because I would never have been able to come back \Rto the
NFL\S with anything else. Never.''
</P>
<P>
   Spellman is content for the rest of us to be left in the dark a
little bit about his darkest hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the \RImmaculate Reception\S catch that Franco
Harris made,'' said Spellman with a belly laugh. ``It's not on the
tape.''
</P>
<P>
   While he was careful to say that he doesn't take his unwanted
past lightly, he admitted there is no pain or shame or fear in
recalling these events.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because,'' he explained, ``I'm completely delivered from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-eight years ago this month, Spellman was baptized in the
Methodist church. He was 3 months old. He was raised in a rough New
Jersey neighborhood by his mother, who worked two jobs, and no
matter if young Alonzo was asleep when he came home, she would wake
him up and have him recite The Lord's Prayer before going back to
bed.
</P>
<P>
   Spellman experienced peer pressure to join a gang when he 10. By
the sixth grade, he was smoking cigarettes. But he dropped that
habit _ cold turkey _ in the eighth grade because his state
championship basketball team had a chance to participate in the
Junior Olympics in Iowa City, Iowa. His team took home the bronze.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could begin to see then how much money you could really make
playing sports. That's why I quit smoking cigarettes,'' recalled
Spellman.
</P>
<P>
   Spellman's mother kept after him to find a ``church home'' when
he arrived at Ohio State, but he never did, and that's when he
began to drift.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he hit the NFL after his junior year, Alonzo's
drifting had turned into serious running in the fast lane. At that
speed, it was inevitable, somebody was going to get hurt when the
wheels fell off.
</P>
<P>
   And that somebody was him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may sound strange,'' Spellman said, ``but going through
what I went through is good in one sense. No one can ever say that
it wasn't God who touched my life and who changed me. Only God
could have done that.
</P>
<P>
   ``No human could have done that, it's just not possible.''
</P>
<P>
   His troubled past is a kaleidoscope of wrongdoings and wrong
turns.
</P>
<P>
   He had a confrontation with a Detroit hotel security guard in
which the 6-foot-4, 292-pound Spellman had to be subdued by pepper
spray. Another time, he was found asleep in his car, parked along a
freeway, with an open container of alcohol and no driver's license.
Michigan police once termed him ``a real threat to society.''
</P>
<P>
   And all this happened as recently as 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The life that I was living was unreal ... something you
normally see only in the movies,'' Spellman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I wouldn't have accepted Jesus Christ back into my life, I
wouldn't have been productive in anything every again. Forget about
football ... I wouldn't have been productive in anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Does he ever think about back-sliding?
</P>
<P>
   Spellman gave an incredulous look, then laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even fathom it,'' he said.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
