<HEADLINE>
AINGE CALLS THE RIGHT PLAY: FAMILY FIRST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Danny Ainge should be commended for retiring from coaching so he
can spend more time with his family.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches must remember their lot in life doesn't mean they should
``fit'' their family in whenever they can. On the contrary. It's
family first, then the job.
</P>
<P>
   That Ainge passed up guaranteed millions to continue coaching
the Phoenix Suns is a testament to his admirable commitment to his
family. Why anyone would believe that no one in this day and age
would dare put their family ahead of work is incredible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the biggest downfall of our whole society is that
families are being destroyed,'' Ainge said. ``I think fathers need
to take more responsibility and be better fathers, but that's not
my motivation here at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always hoped and prayed we'd have better families in our
whole society. A lot of people miss their children and what's going
on in their families. A lot of families have to have both parents
at work just to survive; it's not easy. But I do have the ability
to spend more time with my children and to make this choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Some observers say Suns assistant coach Scott Skiles, who has
replaced Ainge, orchestrated an ``ousting'' of Ainge to enhance his
own career. If that's true, then Skiles should know that what goes
around comes around.
</P>
<P>
   Ainge has a wife and five children. With the demanding NBA
schedule, that's a lot of birthdays, PTA meetings, dinners, movies,
outings at the park, and soccer, basketball and football games,
etc., that he missed.
</P>
<P>
   Any precious moment missed with his family can never, ever be
recaptured. Never! Ever!
</P>
<P>
   Those who have children, and really care about their well-being
and moral upbringing, can relate to Ainge. He simply chose his
family over his career, and that's a novelty in a world where
people are too often judged by how much money they make, the size
of their house, the car they drive, and how much power they wield.
</P>
<P>
   ``The family unit is probably a little stronger in my \RMormon\S
faith, and my family is obviously very important to me,'' Ainge
said. ``It's been very difficult for me to enjoy seven-game winning
streaks, when the people that are the closest to me, I feel like
I'm not living up to my responsibilities as a father and a husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult when you have somebody who devotes 21 years of
their life to you. My teen-age children, my wife and their lives
have completely revolved around mine for my entire career. I want
my life to revolve around theirs at this time in my life. It's that
simple.''
</P>
<P>
   It is that simple. It's also true that the world would be a
better place if there were more people who conducted their lives
like Danny Ainge.
\Nsubheds:AROUND THE EAST New York Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy has
some thoughts on trying to balance his affection for 37-year-old
center Patrick Ewing, and doing what's best for the Knicks. ``I've
learned one thing: Coaching a player on the same team, as he ages,
is the most difficult coaching there is,'' Van Gundy said. ``It
ends ugly far too often.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami Heat coach Pat Riley refers to Charles Barkley as ``one of
the great talents the NBA has seen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were playing in the Miami Arena a year ago or two
years ago, he went after a loose ball, and he landed in my wife's
lap,'' Riley said. ``And he looked at her and said, `You tell your
husband he can't guard me or stop me.'''
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey forward Keith Van Horn shot 50 percent or better from
the field once in his first 17 games. He followed up with four
consecutive games of shooting 50 percent or better (33-of-61),
before going 6-for-15 against Cleveland. During that five-game
stretch, the Nets were 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   During his past 11 games, Chicago's Elton Brand has been the
league's most productive rookie, averaging 18.5 points and 10.2
rebounds per game. In that same period, Houston's Steve Francis was
averaging 19 points and 5.2 assists, while Lamar Odom of the Los
Angeles Clippers was averaging 15.5 points and 6.1 rebounds.
\Nsubheds:AROUND THE WEST The Los Angeles Clippers set an NBA
record for fewest points in a half since the advent of the
24-second shot clock in 1954, when they scored 19 Tuesday against
the Los Angeles Lakers. ``Hey, I almost outscored them by myself,''
said Lakers guard Kobe Bryant, who had 16 points by halftime.
</P>
<P>
   In a loss to Portland this past week, Sacramento rookie Jason
Williams was ejected for the first time in his career, and cursed
himself afterward. ``I wasn't shooting well,'' Williams said, ``and
I was frustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Golden State coach P.J. Carlesimo was all but fired after his
team's 2-16 start. Then he was given a reprieve after the Warriors
beat Atlanta, Minnesota and Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle guard Vernon Maxwell averaged 18.7 points during his
first 12 games off the bench, but is only averaging 7.1 points
while shooting 24.1 percent from the field in his past seven games.
``I can go into a funk at least once a year,'' Maxwell said. ``I
just hope this is it _ an early one.''
Douglas C. Pizac Jazz center Greg Ostertag, called for a foul on
this play against Mavericks center Sean Rooks, has been part of a
block party this season.
\Nsubheds:SPOTLIGHT Jazz's middle men lead defensive renaissance
Don't look now, but those old guys up in Salt Lake City have
apparently taken their Geritol and are slowly climbing the Western
Conference ladder.
</P>
<P>
   And the Utah Jazz can thank its center-by-committee tandem of
Olden Polynice and Duncanville native Greg Ostertag for the
resurrection.
</P>
<P>
   Before losing Friday night at Indiana, the Jazz had won seven
consecutive games with a defensive surge led by Polynice and
Ostertag. The Jazz limited opponents to 84.8 points and .403
shooting from the field.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz also averaged 7.4 blocked shots and 9.3 steals per game
in that seven-game span.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, in its previous 15 games, Utah allowed 92.6 points
and .460 shooting, and could muster just 4.6 blocks and 7.1 steals
per game. Jazz coach Jerry Sloan knows who gets the kudos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ostertag and Polynice are playing better,'' Sloan said.
``Those guys have been blocking shots and making people aware that
we have somebody in the middle. That's critical to us.''
</P>
<P>
   A 13-year veteran, Polynice signed a free-agent contract with
the Jazz during the offseason. Polynice admittedly was tentative
early in the season while learning his new defensive assignments.
</P>
<P>
   But recently, Polynice has tried to be more aggressive early in
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early in the season when I was not sure about things, teams
were just driving in, and I blame myself because I have a lot of
pride in that,'' Polynice said. ``Lately, it hasn't happened as
frequently because psychologically, I've been going into the games
with that mindset that nobody's coming in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Sloan, himself a defensive stalwart during his playing days with
the Chicago Bulls, appreciates what Polynice and Ostertag are
giving his team in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel better about our team,'' Sloan said. ``We're trying to
do the right thing, trying to execute, trying to find the right
person.''
nn
</P>
