<HEADLINE>
GRETZKY UNDERRATED IN ESPN CENTURY LIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What in the heck was ESPN thinking? Better yet, were they
thinking?
</P>
<P>
   The idea that Wayne Gretzky is only the fifth-best athlete on
their Top 50 list of the century's greatest athletes has to be a
joke. The not-so-funny punch line is that ESPN thinks there are
four athletes who dominated their sport more thoroughly, did more
to promote the game they played or did more to change the sporting
landscape than Gretzky.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, there is only one.
</P>
<P>
   Numbers 1-4 have been surmised to be Babe Ruth, Michael Jordan,
Muhammad Ali and Jim Brown. Gretzky stands second to only Ali.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Jordan was good. But did he dominate basketball as
thoroughly as Gretzky dominated hockey? No.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Brown was good. But did his ability change football from a
Canadian game to all the rage in cities like Phoenix and San Jose
and Dallas? No.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Babe Ruth was larger than life. But did his off-the-field
persona rival Gretzky's image as a consummate gentleman and
ambassador of the game? No.
</P>
<P>
   He has the numbers to hang with Jordan, Brown and Ruth. Gretzky
scored 894 goals and assisted on 1,963 more, including his amazing
92-goal season. Gretzky has the championships, too, leading his
team to four Stanley Cups.
</P>
<P>
   Only Ali with his dominance and grace on so many levels did more
for sport and society.
</P>
<P>
   My guess is the folks at ESPN used the same line of thinking
that goes into how they do their highlights. You can see every slam
dunk and chest bump from the NBA and every tackle and touchdown
from the NFL and every strikeout and double play from MLB, but the
NHL is often relegated to scores only.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is that hockey isn't as big as basketball, football or
baseball, so therefore Gretzky can't be as big as Jordan, Brown or
Ruth. They're right. He's bigger and should have his rightful spot
behind Ali because of it.
Yzerman a throwback, but one that's admired What does an NFL
touchdown minus a dance, Don Nelson admitting he's wrong and the 17
years that Steve Yzerman has spent with the Detroit Red Wings have
in common?
</P>
<P>
   They're all about as rare as a Cowboys victory away from Texas
Stadium this season.
</P>
<P>
   Yzerman has spent all 17 of his seasons as a Detroit Red Wing,
growing up with a franchise and a city. In the age of free agency
and trades, it's a feat about as common as the aforementioned
Nelson apology.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is definitely meaningful to me, absolutely; particularly in
the fact that we have been able to win the Stanley Cup here,''
Yzerman said. ``But the most important, from my perspective, the
biggest reason I am in a good situation, because I play on a good
team with a lot of good players, I don't feel the burden of having
to carry a team or anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he has been able to float through what has been a
couple of milestone-filled months for him.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 17, he recorded his 900th assist making him the 10th
player in NHL history to reach that plateau. With an assist on Nov.
20 vs. Edmonton, he became the seventh player in NHL history to
record 1,500 points in a career. Then on Nov. 24, he played in his
1,200th NHL regular-season game, following that up two nights later
on the 26th _ also against Edmonton _ when he became the 11th
player in league history to score 600 goals. Let's just say, it's
been a busy 17 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it has gone by fairly quickly actually,'' Yzerman said.
``I feel like I have played on four different teams, with four
different groups of guys. ... I have kind of gone through different
groups of players so it felt like different teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Yzerman has seen a lot in 17 seasons. The first couple of years
were spent rebuilding. The next couple were spent getting better.
The next couple falling back. The last few have been spent reaping
the rewards.
</P>
<P>
   The Detroit Red Wings won the Stanley Cup in 1997 and 1998. But,
Yzerman says he appreciates the not-so-good times, too, especially
now that it is getting close to ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found it a difficult time, you know, early in the '90s. Our
team suffered some disappointing playoff losses in the first round.
One to Toronto, one to San Jose, and it was getting very difficult
to play because there was so many questions, you know, was our team
good enough, was our leadership strong enough,'' Yzerman said. ``So
it became difficult, and then to find out we were able to win a
couple of Stanley Cups and now it is kind of _ I guess it is almost
like _ it makes it a lot easier to play right now because we have
answered a lot of questions. So it is a lot of fun to be playing
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   And, after 17 seasons, does Yzerman look to the future?
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get going in the hockey season, you get so caught up
in the present and how you are playing now and how your team is
doing and what is happening right now, you don't think too far
ahead,'' Yzerman said. ``But, again, I hope to play 20 years, you
know, that would take me three more after this. Whether I play 19
or 20 or 21 or 22, I am not sure, but I tried to set a goal of
20.''
</P>
<P>
   You can almost guarantee they'll be spent in Detroit.
 &LR; subheds:Around the East  &LR; agatea:What's that your mother used to
say? It's all fun and games until somebody gets hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Well, that's exactly what the NHL SuperSkills competition used
to be until Florida Panthers goalie Trevor Kidd dislocated his
right shoulder during the Rapid Fire competition. The Panthers'
best player so far this season will be out for at least two months.
</P>
<P>
   Yikes. And all for a couple of drills meant to be fun and
gather] participants for the SuperSkills competition at the NHL's
All-Star game in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   If the on-the-verge-of-moving Ottawa Senators think that every
pro sports-hungry U.S. city is going to embrace hockey, thereby
pumping money into owners' wallets the way Dallas did, had better
take a look at the Carolina Hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   Less than four seasons in North Carolina, their first in their
new arena, and they're already having trouble selling out the
place. Meanwhile, another tenant at the recently finished
Entertainment and Sports Arena in Raleigh, the North Carolina State
Wolfpack men's basketball team, doesn't have enough seats to fill
the demand.
</P>
<P>
   The Pack has already sold out all of its Atlantic Coast
Conference games. The Hurricanes, meanwhile, are averaging 12,660
fans a game, a number that looks only to decrease when ACC play
begins in January.  &LR; subheds:Around the West  &LR; agatea:OK, so Clark
Griswold has nothing on the media covering the Edmonton Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   After the charter plane scheduled to take the Oilers and the
accompanying media from New York to Detroit on Tuesday night was
grounded, the team and media were left scrounging for hotel rooms.
There weren't that many available at 12:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   They finally found a place at around 1:30 a.m., but there wasn't
enough room. Guess who was the first to go? Yep, the media. They
were taken by shuttle bus to a nearby motel that, as Oilers beat
writer Robin Brownlee put it, ``was, let's say, not listed in the
NHL media directory.''
</P>
<P>
   They were charged $120 for the night, the transaction taking
place by sliding credit cards to the night clerk hidden behind
bullet-proof glass. The reporters were greeted by, well let's just
say females willing to offer companionship in the lobby, and rooms
that might have been part of a crime scene at one point.
</P>
<P>
   Forget Colorado. Forget Phoenix. Forget San Jose. If the Stars
are going to get back to the Stanley Cup Finals, the Western
Conference road looks to once again go through Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings have won five consecutive games, seven of their
past eight and nine of their past 11. They have the league's best
home record at 15-3-1. They have 46 points through 32 games, the
most they have had at this point in a season since 1995-96, when
they had 48 and finished with an NHL-record 131.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
