<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALL-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTRACTS, NOT TALENT, DICTATE TRADING HABITS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When he was general manager of the San Diego Padres, ``Trader''
Jack McKeon once made a deal while waiting in line to check out of
his hotel during the winter meetings. He tells an amusing story
about plying a fellow GM with drink until he agreed to another
trade.
</P>
<P>
   McKeon, now the Reds' manager, would not enjoy being a GM today.
This year's winter meetings concluded with only a couple of trades
of significance, not because the modern-day GMs don't have McKeon's
appetite for dealing, but because they are constrained by
economics.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much fun as I had, I was in a different era,'' McKeon said.
``You made trades the old fashioned way. You traded player for
player. You didn't have to worry about contracts, you didn't have
to go to management and see if you had the finances.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, finances and free agency dictate everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time you mention a guy, the first thing they look at
is the contract instead of the statistics,'' Astros manager Larry
Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, a handful of GMs deserve credit for making _ or trying
to make _ trades this off-season despite the contract.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers traded for Juan Gonzalez even though he can became a
free agent at the end of next season. It cost them a solid starting
pitcher in Justin Thompson, a talented young outfielder in Gabe
Kapler and a future closer type in Francisco Cordero for a player
who might walk after one season.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies gave up a couple of former No. 1 draft choices for
Andy Ashby, another player who can become a free agent after the
2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox surrendered a top prospect in Adam Everett for
Astros outfielder Carl Everett, knowing they might only have him
for one season.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets were willing to send their closer, Armando Benitez,
plus talented youngsters Octavio Dotel and Roger Cedeno, to the
Mariners for Ken Griffey Jr., knowing full well he too can be a
free agent this time next year. Griffey vetoed the deal.
</P>
<P>
   But for the most part, clubs aren't willing to take that gamble.
Mike Hampton, Alex Rodriguez, Manny Ramirez and Mike Mussina, four
more high-profile members of next year's free-agent class, could be
had for the right price but received scant attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``In most cases, I think you're going to find those players back
with the same team,'' Dierker said. ``I don't think anyone can
justify giving up a number of players and a vast amount of money.
The Mariners have not won their division year after year with
Griffey, so there's no guarantee you're going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why the Braves never were a serious entry in the Griffey
sweepstakes. It widely was assumed they would be the front-runners
when the superstar outfielder went on the block, but when
preliminary conversations with the Mariners included names such as
Andruw Jones and Kevin Millwood, the Braves dropped out.
</P>
<P>
   Why should they pay a high price in young talent when they can
shower him with Ted Turner's millions next year?
</P>
<P>
   ``We are interested, but if you're talking about some of the
players I've heard, the price is pretty steep,'' Braves manager
Bobby Cox said. ``Especially if you can bid on him next year
without giving up players.''
</P>
<P>
   In a different era, it's a chance Trader Jack willing would
take. Now, the cost is simply too high. Good deal The Astros went
to the winter meetings with a glut of outfielders and hoped to deal
one for help elsewhere, but were finding no takers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of teams have extra outfielders, and almost everyone
needs pitching depth,'' Larry Dierker said. ``It's hard to offer a
team an outfielder when they're trying to give you an outfielder.''
</P>
<P>
   After the meetings, though, they made a good trade by swapping
Adam Everett for Carl Everett, a deal that helps both teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros lost their shortstop when Ricky Gutierrez became a
free agent. Adam Everett played at the Double-A level last year and
probably needs more minor-league seasoning, but eventually he
should be an upgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Everett gives the Red Sox a major upgrade in center field
over Damon Buford and Darren Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   The trade also means that Moises Alou, who missed all of last
season while injured but had an MVP-caliber year in '98, isn't
likely to be traded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd be best taking him to spring training and playing him,''
Dierker said. ``He's clearly one of our best three outfielders.''
Hot-stove embers Cubs manager Don Baylor expects new second baseman
Eric Young's defense to improve once he's reunited with Gene Glynn,
who coached him in Colorado. ``I saw the improvement from working
with Gene,'' Baylor said. ``Everyone in the infield I assigned Gene
Glynn to got better. I wanted to let EY know that program was going
to start again. I told EY he could be a good second baseman.''
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox talked before the winter meetings about making an
offer for Mariners shortstop Alex Rodriguez but didn't send GM Ron
Schueler to Anaheim, Calif. Was a Rodriguez pursuit just wishful
thinking? ``That was prayerful thinking,'' manager Jerry Manuel
said.
</P>
<P>
   Jack McKeon wasn't upset that GM Jim Bowden wasn't able to trade
for Ken Griffey Jr. ``I don't think there's any club in baseball
that wouldn't like to have him,'' Bowden said. ``But I like the
guys I have, too. They played hard for me last year.''
</P>
<P>
   McKeon sees NL rookie of the year Scott Williamson as one of the
most dominating closers in baseball in the near future. ``I
envision him being a Trevor Hoffman in another year or two,''
McKeon said. However, the Reds will consider making him a starter
if they have a hole in the rotation next season.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
