<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-19 02:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3294 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-CELTICS-ROCKETS-B     12-19 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-ROCKETS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELTICS DROPS 9TH STRAIGHT ON ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ No relief here. What looked to be the Celtics' best
hope for a win on the road this week ended up like all the others
in the past seven days. Geez, can Paul Pierce be this valuable?
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night the Celtics followed the same suicidal pattern
that has plagued them all week _ poor defense, falling behind,
inopportune breakdowns, late rotations, rushed shots, and, needless
to say, another loss. This one was a 100-94 setback to the Rockets,
who themselves are struggling and rebuilding and, as is their wont,
came close to blowing a 17-point lead in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But they didn't, and now we have to deal with the math. It isn't
good. The Celtics have dropped five in a row to fall to 10-13. They
have lost nine straight on the road since their win in Toronto on
Opening Night. They are falling like a stone with no relief on the
horizon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no time to get down,'' said Kenny Anderson, who had 23
points. ``I've been through this before. You have to stay
professional, stay together, and continue to play hard. (If you
don't), the roof will cave in.''
</P>
<P>
   Some might suggest it already is falling. Coach Rick Pitino
watched in equal parts exasperation and disbelief as his team again
unraveled. The Celtics led early but fell behind in the second
half, the greatest deficit 17 with 9:04 left. They trailed by 13
with 4:18 left. They did get to within 4 but no closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like the collapse was in again,'' Houston coach Rudy
Tomjanovich said. His team had lost five straight and only
Wednesday had blown a fourth-quarter lead in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   But the Celtics were forced to foul, and Houston made its free
throws _ 15 of 21 in the quarter. That made up for horrible
shooting (27 percent) from the floor in the fourth quarter _ the
Rockets made one field goal in the final 9:04 and still won the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to finally get a win,'' said Kelvin Cato, who had a
career-high 27 points and 12 rebounds. ``It ain't the championship.
But it's better than losing.''
</P>
<P>
   Down the hallway, Antoine Walker, who had a dreadful first half
(1 of 7, 0 rebounds) and a terrific second half (20 points), was
making what has now become a daily request: Please let us get us a
win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to fight our way through it,'' he said. ``Obviously,
we're disappointed. But we have got to find a way to win. We can't
wait for Paul or Danny (Fortson) to come back. We have to do it
soon.''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics did have Vitaly Potapenko back after a three-game
absence due to a calf strain. He had 8 points and 6 rebounds in 30
minutes. But the Celtics were again beaten up inside, as Houston
had a 48-38 rebounding advantage and shot 40 free throws to
Boston's 24. The Celtics also didn't rotate well when they
double-teamed Cuttino Mobley (21 points) or Steve Francis (15
points.) Cato (11 of 13) got a lot of dunks, his specialty.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he is getting annoyed by all this, Pitino said, ``I
made up my mind this year I'm not going to get upset at anything.
Even this type of basketball at the beginning is not going to break
me.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a close game into the third, when the Rockets made their
first breakaway move. A 9-0 ran capped by a Cato 3-point play (and
a Rudy T fist pump) made Houston's lead 59-50, up to then the
largest of the game. Houston got it to 12 and led, 76-66, entering
the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets appeared to settle things with a 10-3 run to open
the final quarter, capped by, of all things, an unchecked stroll
across the lane from Bryce Drew for his only hoop of the game. That
made it 84-67. Boston, however, awoke and went on an 11-0 run to
get to within 6 before a quick, 7-0 Houston counter (capped by a
Mobley trey) made it 93-80 with 4:18 left.
</P>
<P>
   But as bad as the Celtics have been in digging holes, they've
been just as resilient in trying to dig their way out. They got to
within 4 (94-90) on a Walker trey with 1:27 left. But instead of
fouling Cato (a 59 percent free-throw shooter) or Kenny Thomas (a
59 percenter), they went after Mobley, who shoots 85 percent from
the line, or Francis, a 75 percenter.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end, when you have a chance to win, you foul the wrong
people. You can't do that,'' Pitino said. ``You've got to be
intelligent.''
</P>
<P>
   But they weren't. That's how you end a rally and lose a game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-19-99 0217EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
