<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FISET IS A FLOP IN RETURN AS STARTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There seemed to be at least a morsel of good in
the previous two blowouts. Sure, the Kings were thumped and goalie
Jamie Storr failed to play beyond the first period in losses to New
Jersey and the New York Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   But the other side of it was Stephane Fiset got to shake off the
rust of five weeks of inactivity with 80 minutes of hockey.
</P>
<P>
   That surely would prove crucial since it was later discovered
Storr was suffering effects of post-concussion syndrome. He was
placed on injured reserve, but with Fiset proving his injured right
hand was again healthy, it cushioned the blow of losing Storr.
</P>
<P>
   Then Fiset was bombarded in the first period by the Chicago
Blackhawks on Saturday. The Blackhawks scored on three of their
first four shots, and knocked Fiset out less than 28 minutes into
his first start since Nov. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Fiset, who missed 14 games with a right hand contusion, allowed
six goals on 21 shots before being yanked in favor of Marcel
Cousineau.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like the puck was the size of a pea,'' Fiset said. ``I
couldn't stop it. I was fighting everything. I was probably too
nervous at the beginning and probably putting too much pressure on
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Fiset was injured, he was one of the best goalies in the
league and perhaps the biggest reason the Kings were consistently
among the top few teams. He was 7-4-3 with a 2.45 goals against.
</P>
<P>
   But he suffered the contusion to his right hand just five days
after inking a three-year contract extension with the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goaltending isn't at the level we need to have it,'' Kings
coach Andy Murray said in summarizing how Storr and Fiset played
lately.
</P>
<P>
   It brings up an interesting scenario as the Kings enter a
difficult three game spell against San Jose, Phoenix and Colorado.
Will Cousineau will remain on the bench, or get a shot if Storr
doesn't return and Fiset doesn't return to early-season form?
</P>
<P>
   Smokin' Smolinski: Bryan Smolinski's first-period goal extended
the center's point-scoring streak to seven games. His value to the
Kings goes beyond his goals and assists, but the scoring doesn't
hurt, either.
</P>
<P>
   Smolinski entered the night leading the Kings with 24 assists
(third in the league) and 31 points. He also had 14 assists in his
past 12 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the guys who kept us afloat here,'' Murray said.
``He's been strong down the middle, has been a guy that I feel I
can depend on, and as coaches, we can depend on him.''
</P>
<P>
   From the point: For the third time in less than a week the Kings
faced a former coach. Chicago coach Bob Pulford coached the Kings
from 1972-1977 and still hold the franchise mark with 178 wins. New
Jersey head coach Robbie Ftorek and Devils assistant Larry Robinson
are both former Kings coaches. . . . The Kings' next win will be
the 1,000th in franchise history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
