<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALENDARS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    There's a dazzling array to keep track of the day
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Stumped about what to give the friends and
relatives remaining on your holiday shopping list?
</P>
<P>
   What better year to give a calendar than 2000? (OK, so some of
you will argue for 2001.)
</P>
<P>
   With an average price of $10 to $16, a wall or desk calendar is
an affordable, easy-to-wrap _ even mail _ last-minute gift that
recipients of all ages will find useful.
</P>
<P>
   Today's calendars not only help keep track of our busy lives,
but entertain and educate as well.
</P>
<P>
   A calendar can be a personal gift: Just match the recipient's
hobby or special interest.
</P>
<P>
   And the choices are amazing. Today's mega-bookstores stock as
many as 400 calendar titles with categories ranging from Irish and
Religious to Girlfriends and Golden Retrievers.
</P>
<P>
   Those who love beautiful photography can spend their days gazing
at colorful cardinals or sun-drenched village streets of Provence.
Sports enthusiasts can pick up tips on fly fishing, golf or tennis.
Bridge players can spend 366 days perfecting their game.
</P>
<P>
   You can begin each day with a horoscope, inspirational verse,
quips from your favorite humorist or a gourmet recipe.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget the kids. Calendars help the little ones understand
the concept of time, and those aimed at older children provide
interesting information on subjects ranging from the Civil War to
baseball. Educators say a calendar, with its bite-sized bits of
information, motivates children to read.
</P>
<P>
   Some calendars include coupons, and a calendar purchase can
benefit your favorite charity. ``The Millennium of Hope'' calendar,
with colorful artwork done by children affected by AIDS, benefits
pediatric AIDS research. Call (877) 687-5437 or e-mail
hope(at)vtechkids.com.
</P>
<P>
   Visit a local museum store for art and nature calendars.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most appreciated calendars is the one you create
yourself. Print shops, such as Kinko's Copies, can help you turn
favorite family photos into a yearlong keepsake.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of 2000's interesting calendar possibilities:
</P>
<P>
   _ In ``Look-Alikes'' (Workman, $9.95) nothing is what it seems.
Award-winning artist Joan Steiner has created a clever
three-dimensional world using commonplace objects that look like
something else. The whole family will find this one intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Mom's Plan-et'' (Avalanche, $12.99) is a 16-month organizer
that includes 198 stickers (everything from ``haircut'' to
``vet''), extra-large grids, a storage pocket and magnetic hanger
for the fridge.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cynthia Hart's ``Family Scrapbook Calendar'' (Workman, $11.95)
is intended to become a scrapbook when the year has ended. It comes
with plastic templates and suggestions for cropping photos. The
calendar and stickers are printed on acid-free paper with acid-free
inks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Workman's new Page-A-Day Stickies are clever. You can tear off
the pages and stick them anywhere _ on the fridge, a computer
screen, bathroom mirror.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Popular Mechanics'' calendar includes 365 helpful tips
for maintaining your home and car ($10.95).
</P>
<P>
   _ What's neat about the daily spin calendars from Avalanche
($11.99) is their shape. The pages are swirled and they sit on a
removable plastic easel.
</P>
<P>
   _ Top-selling calendars for the kids this year, according to
Border's Books, Music and Cafe: Make Your Own Calendar, American
Girls, Winnie-the-Pooh, Curious George, Wizard of Oz and Stickers
and Scribbles.
</P>
<P>
   _ The best-selling calendar in the United States for the past 14
years? ``The Far Side Off-The-Wall 1999 Calendar'' sold 2.8 million
copies. Its publisher, Andrews McMeel, publishes 100 titles each
year. According to Ann Binkley of Border's, the ``Far Side
Millennium Boxed Calendar'' is one of this year's top sellers along
with: Pokemon, artist Thomas Kinkade, the Dilbert box calendar,
Backstreet Boys, Ansel Adams, Mary Engelbreit and the Sierra Club.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
