<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-NOTES19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fund-raising looms larger in GOP race
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The kind words and warm smiles that marked
relations between the top Republican candidates disappeared in the
chill of an Iowa evening last week as the campaign for the GOP
presidential nomination entered a more combative phase.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.) tangled
over campaign finance reform and, to a lesser extent, taxes at
Monday's debate in Des Moines.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as the week unfolded, the Bush and McCain campaigns traded
criticisms over each other's stands on campaign finance reform.
``Bush stands as guardian of special interest control of political
process,'' one McCain news release began.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign Web site headlined the candidate's opposition to
McCain's proposal to ban the unregulated, unlimited contributions
to political parties known as soft money. The McCain proposal ``has
a huge loophole that benefits Democrats and would hurt the
Republican Party and our conservative principles,'' Bush said in a
statement. Bush wants to block the mostly-Democrat labor unions
from designating a portion of members' dues for political activity.
</P>
<P>
   These exchanges were a far cry from the stout praise each man
had offered the other in recent weeks. They reflect one major
point: To the extent that Bush has a serious challenge on his
hands, McCain is the only Republican candidate who appears capable
of upsetting his carefully laid plans.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has drawn even with Bush or pulled ahead in various polls
in New Hampshire, which holds the nation's first primary Feb. 1.
McCain's independent streak and call for reform play well in that
state.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush is counting on attracting traditional Republican voters
and social conservatives by portraying campaign reform as a
detriment to the GOP. Those voters play a more important role in
such states as South Carolina, another early test Feb. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Dollars providing Bush organizational advantage
</P>
<P>
   McCain's campaign operates on a much smaller budget than Bush's.
And while the senator has tried to use his more nimble organization
as a symbol in his underdog campaign, last week provided two
glimpses of Bush's massive advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Bush announced comprehensive organizations in Michigan and
Florida. Michigan's Feb. 22 primary is potentially significant, if
McCain wins in New Hampshire or South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   McCain laid out a modest package of health care reforms Tuesday
in South Carolina. But for the second straight week, campaign aides
scrambled after the fact to provide an estimate of how much the
proposals would cost. A speech on defense policy a week earlier
also lacked price tags.
</P>
<P>
   California justices sink proposal on redistricting
</P>
<P>
   The California Supreme Court last week blocked a proposed voter
initiative that would have stripped the state Legislature of its
power to draw congressional and other electoral districts and
handed it to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling was a victory for Democrats, who control both houses
in the Legislature as well as the Governor's Mansion. Legislatures
around the nation will draw new district lines in 2001, following
release of the results of the 2000 census.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, fearing huge losses in the largest state, sought to
limit the Democrats' influence on the process.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans already had poured $1 million into
building support for the issue. But the strategy they settled on
was, in the end, their undoing.
</P>
<P>
   Reasoning that most voters would be indifferent, at best, to a
mundane ballot question about redistricting, the measure's backers
combined it with a provision to reduce the salaries of state
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   The court decided that putting the two issues together violates
the state constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley: Campaign gifts are at root of problems
</P>
<P>
   As McCain and former Democratic Sen. Bill Bradley held their
unusual joint meeting on campaign finance reform Thursday, Bradley
began airing a new ad on the topic in Iowa and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Using a town hall setting, Bradley tells the audience that
eliminating soft money is important ``to virtually everything
else'' he would try to do as president.
</P>
<P>
   ``National health insurance: Give me a world with campaign
finance reform, (and) it's gonna be a lot easier,'' Bradley says.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, most presidential candidates will spend the early
part of the week in Iowa, New Hampshire or South Carolina, then
retire from the campaign trail until after the new year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
