<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR MONDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Monday, Dec. 20:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ELECT (Moscow) _ Centrist parties made major gains Sunday
in Russian parliamentary elections in an apparent breakthrough for
pro-reform groups, according to an exit poll. (Summary from wires.)
By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-VOTERS (St. Petersburg, Russia) _ Her husband walked
through mushy snow, still in his thick brown knit sleeping shirt,
to vote early in Russia s parliamentary elections Sunday, but Maria
Chashena, 78 and stiff, was in no shape to get out. So Sunday
afternoon a delegation of election officials trudged to her
minuscule second-story walkup and stood sardined in the kitchen as
she sat beneath a yellowed poster of Russian czars, committing
democracy. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (MozdoK, Russia) _ Mikhail A. Kashpurin is a
frail old man with years of valorous service in the Soviet army, an
unblemished labor record and a story to tell. It boils down to
this. He was in the wrong place at the wrong time. The place was
Grozny and the time was Russia's ongoing military campaign. By
Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   MACAU-CHINA (Macau) _ With the solemn lowering of one flag and
the triumphant raising of another, China claimed sovereignty over
Macau, ending 442 years of Portuguese rule and shaking off the last
vestiges of European colonial involvement in Asia. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-SYRIA (Jerusalem) _ Prime Minister Ehud Barak met with
his cabinet on Sunday and said that he wants to pursue a ``core''
agreement with Syria. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   KUWAIT-WOMEN-VOTE (Kuwait City) _ Kuwaiti society is divided
over the issue of political rights for women. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-EXECUTIONS (Tokyo) _ Japan executed two convicted felons
last week in a manner so quiet that the government did not even
reveal their names, a common practice that has raised howls from
human rights advocates. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-POPE (Jerusalem) _ The Israeli government announces dates
and an itinerary for a visit from the pope early next year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TERROR-RDP (Washington) _ Developments in the case of a man
identified as Ahmed Ressam, who is suspected of having terrorist
connections. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   TERROR-BORDERS _ Customs has tightened security at 301 ports of
entry. By Robert D. McFadden.
</P>
<P>
   GUN-DATABASE _ In a long sought move that will help law
enforcement agencies identify guns used in crimes when only their
shell casings are left at a crime scene, the Clinton administration
disclosed Sunday that it is tripling the budget to develop a
unified national data base of shell casings and bullets. By Fox
Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-REFORM-JEWS _ A Reform Jewish group votes on a resolution
demanding that its members support gun control. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-CLAWSON _ Ken W. Clawson, one of President Richard M.
Nixon's staunch defenders as director of White House communications
during the Watergate era, died on Friday at a hospital in New
Orleans. He was 63. By David Stout.
</P>
<P>
   NBC-INTERNET _ NBC, along with several affiliated companies, has
agreed to back a new nationwide service that will offer high-speed
Internet access over telephone lines. By Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   NY-WELFARE-FOSTERCARE _ In Suffolk County, the first children go
into foster care as a direct result of state regulations that
require shelters to eject parents who fail to meet all welfare
rules, including work, job search and eligibility requirements. By
Nina Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   NJ-EMISSIONS-SWAP _ New Jersey has signed a deal with the
Netherlands that makes it the first state to swap emission credits
with another country. By Steve Strunsky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-DEBATE (Washington) _ In their latest debate, Al Gore and
Bill Bradley appeared on NBC's ``Meet the Press'' television show.
By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-DEBATE-NOTEBOOK _ A television critic reviews the
performance of the candidates. By Caryn James.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CUBANS-PRISON-DEAL (Washington) _ U.S. officials secured the
release of seven hostages at a Louisiana prison on Sunday by
promising their captors safe passage to Cuba, sources close to the
negotiations said. (Summary from wires.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SAFIRE-COLUMN _ Details to come. By William Safire.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
