   EDS: OUTLOOK 2000 will replace the regular Monday Business
section this week. A separate OUTLOOK 2000 budget moved Saturday
and will be repeated Sunday in categories ``f'' and ``v.''
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE
</P>
<P>
   (Coded e)
</P>
<P>
   GATSBY-OPERA-1920S (New York) _ The technique of evoking
vernacular music has a long heritage in opera, and John Harbison
conceived ``The Great Gatsby'' as an extension of the tradition.
The iconic F. Scott Fitzgerald novel, on which the opera is based,
is set in the Jazz Age, the early 1920s. So the narrative is filled
with popular songs, dance music and show tunes from the period. The
work receives its world premiere Monday at the Metropolitan Opera.
By Anthony Tommasini.
</P>
<P>
   GATSBY-OPERA-LYRICIST (New York) _ Murray Horwitz has been a
clown and worked for the New York State Assembly (not at the same
time). He has acted on ``Kojak,'' staged performances at the White
House and for the last 10 years run cultural programming for
National Public Radio. So when the composer John Harbison was
looking for an enterprising lyricist to give an authentic 1920s
flavor to pop songs in his new opera ``The Great Gatsby,'' he
turned to the eclectic Horwitz. By Ralph Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   WRITERS-ON-WRITING (Undated) _ Whenever I face an audience with
at least minimal familiarity with my work, there are two questions
always asked: ``Why do you write both fiction and poetry?''
``What's the difference between writing poetry and fiction?'' Marge
Piercy contributes the latest installment in the Writers on Writing
series.
</P>
<P>
   WIS-ORCHESTRA-CUBA (Havana, Cuba) _ Mighty America gives Cuba a
lesson in can-do efficiency? Think again. The Milwaukee Symphony's
weekend adventures on this embargoed island became a drama with
several happy endings, but the opening acts were tortured indeed.
By Bernard Holland.
</P>
<P>
   HAMLET-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ In Andrei Serban's gaudy,
frantic staging of Shakespeare's ``Hamlet,'' which opens Sunday
night at the Public Theater with Liev Schreiber as the vacillating
prince, the title character isn't the only one to put an antic
disposition on. By Ben Brantley. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WIESEL-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ In the first volume of his
memoirs, ``All Rivers Run to the Sea,'' the novelist and Holocaust
survivor Elie Wiesel described the first four decades of his life,
from his birth in 1928 up to his marriage in 1969. In his new
volume, ``And the Sea Is Never Full'' he turns outward. By
Christopher Lehmann-Haupt.
</P>
<P>
   TV-LECORSAIRE-REVIEW (Undated) _ There is exciting dancing to be
seen Monday night in the American Ballet Theater production of ``Le
Corsaire,'' on PBS. But the dancing is accompanied _ and almost
sunk _ by what may well be the most witless and tedious running
commentary ever to be foisted on a televised work of art. By
Jennifer Dunning.
</P>
</TEXT>
