<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-19 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3361 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-OUTLOOK-NEWSPAPERS-2T     12-19 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTLOOK-NEWSPAPERS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS DATA ABOUT READERS GROWS, NEWSPAPERS ASK: NOW WHAT?
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., La., Ill., N.Y., Fla., Calif., Conn.)   (jw) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every day, around midafternoon, Jennifer Musser, an editor of
philly.com, finds out more about her audience than any print editor
has ever known. On Dec. 5, for instance, she knew that the Web
site's most-visited article was The Philadelphia Inquirer's account
of a 76ers' basketball game, with 4,097 hits, and that the average
visitor stayed three-and-a-half minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Inquirer's article on a crack addict who starved her
daughter to death got barely a third as many hits, but the average
visitor lingered almost five-and-a-half minutes over the wrenching
account. Another article, a review of a performance by the rock
singer Beck, had an unusual number of hits _ because, Ms. Musser
later discovered, a Web site for the artist's fans had set up a
link to it.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Musser's Web site, www.philly.com, is owned by Knight Ridder
and offers visitors every article in the company's two Philadelphia
papers, The Philadelphia Inquirer and its rival, The Philadelphia
Daily News. Then it makes available to the newspapers' editors the
core data accumulated on those visits.
</P>
<P>
   Such data _ similar to the feedback that Nielsen ratings have
given television programmers and far more detailed than gross
measurements like circulation or even readership _ is golden to
newspapers as they enter the year 2000. Challenged to recreate
themselves both online and in print, newspapers _ and their
advertisers _ have a greater appetite for information about their
appeal, their audiences and their competition than ever, according
to both those who gather and those who use the data.
</P>
<P>
   What they find and how they use that information is likely to
reshape the business of newspapering, online and off.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a proliferation of news and information
sources, so people's expectations have changed,'' said Greg
Martire, the managing partner of the research firm of Clark,
Martire &AMP; Bartolomeo. ``The traditional role of the newspaper has
been nibbled away from all sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``The free weekly is doing a better job reporting on soccer
leagues; CNN is doing a better job of providing instant worldwide
coverage,'' he added. ``Given that, the newspaper has held up
remarkably well.''
</P>
<P>
   But declining circulation figures over 15 years reflect the
erosion of the audience. And years of increasing data about
audience preferences offer tempting solutions. In addition, highly
advanced presses and increasingly computerized delivery systems now
provide more opportunities to adapt to reader preferences.
Newspaper Web sites offer even more flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   One core question is how willing publishers should be to marry
the data about audience preferences to the technologies that allow
them to accommodate those preferences.
</P>
<P>
   J. Walker Smith, the president of Yankelovich Partners, the
market research firm based in Norwalk, Conn., said studies by his
firm argue for more customization.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to customize things,'' he said. In a world of
incessantly expanding choices, ``it will be harder and harder for
media to intrude their way into people's attention spans,'' he
added. ``Instead, they are going to have to find a way to get an
invitation to be in front of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers, then, have an incentive to customize. But how?
Customizing for the mass market _ giving most prominence to the
articles that tend to attract the most readers _ may result in a
less attractive product.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started in the news business,'' said Tom Rosenstiel,
the director of the Project for Excellence in Journalism, a press
watchdog group based in Washington, ``my first editor said: Assume
that no more than 15 percent of the people want to read any of
these stories. So lay out your front page so that everyone who is a
potential reader wants to read at least one story.'' He added,
``The great risk of knowing how many people read every story, but
not knowing who the people are, is that you start producing only
those stories that will reach a large number of people, and in the
end, the result is you end up with even fewer people.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing how people behave (their true news tastes) may not, for
instance, be the same as knowing how they see themselves. For 12
years, the Pew Research Center in Washington has conducted surveys
on the most-followed news events. There is no easy way to correlate
these with Nielsen ratings, which come closer to measuring actual
behavior. But some of the most closely watched news events, like
the O.J. Simpson trial and the death of Diana, Princess of Wales,
do not even make the top 20 on the Pew list.
</P>
<P>
   The probable gap between what people say and what people do
reflects a basic problem in the customization effort, at least when
it comes to general news. It is unclear how audiences will react if
editors tailor products to what readers show they care about at the
expense of what they say they care about _ or the reverse.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the audience for newspapers is not necessarily the
same as the audience for news online. Ms. Musser at philly.com, for
one, says that the demographics of her online news audience are
different _ younger and more male _ from those of the average
newspaper audience.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Carol Perruso, president of latimes.com, the online site of The
Los Angeles Times, has found in recent surveys that online news
consumers themselves can be divided into two groups. ``People who
went to portal sites and television news sites such as MSNBC tended
to put a higher premium on breaking news and news summaries,'' she
said. ``And people who went to newspapers' sites favored in-depth
coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   So, while many newspapers are splitting into offline and online
versions of themselves, with slightly different audiences, they are
finding that both audiences value one of newspapers' traditional
strengths _ their depth.
</P>
<P>
   On the business side, too, there are similarities between
newspapers and their online offspring. For instance, they share the
need to keep the high-margin classified-ad franchise from being
taken over by online help-wanted sites like monster.com.
</P>
<P>
   But they have different business imperatives. It is not at all
clear that the print business model _ a combination of advertising
and circulation revenue _ will work online, for example.
</P>
<P>
   The search for a new business model is one reason Knight Ridder,
Tribune Company and The New York Times Company are exploring the
ways to have their digital properties _ Knightridder.com, Tribune
Interactive and The Times Company Digital _ issue securities that
will tap into the high value of Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting infusion of capital, the companies hope, could pay
for everything from acquisitions to technological experiments that
could reduce dependence on advertisers and create services or
information packages for which subscribers would pay a premium.
</P>
<P>
   The printed newspapers, more than half of which are part of
larger newspaper chains, are meanwhile rethinking everything from
their size to their delivery schedules.
</P>
<P>
   Many newspapers, like The Washington Post and The Miami Herald,
have cut costs by reducing the width of their pages by half an inch
to save paper.
</P>
<P>
   And The Arizona Republic is perfecting a computerized delivery
system that would break apart the six-day or Sunday or both
subscription schedule and allow subscribers to opt for, say, just
the Wednesday newspaper, with the grocery ads, and the Friday
paper, with its entertainment listings.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all that has changed in the newspaper business in the
last century, one thing has remained constant, the amount of time
people say they spend with their daily newspaper: 15 to 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   That is the average amount of time 4,000 Chicago businessmen
said they spent when they were surveyed in 1916, amid World War I.
It is the average 1,761 New York college students said they spent
in 1920. And it is the figure that emerged from focus groups
convened in recent years by Clark, Martire &AMP; Bartolomeo, the
research firm, in dozens of cities. Martire said the number did not
change even when the number of pages changed. ``The smaller paper
they just read more intensively,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Philly.com visitors stay, on average, 11.5 minutes, according to
the Web monitoring firm I/Pro. In the Internet Age, with the
nirvana of large broadband information pipes said to be just around
the technological corner, such persistent results are a reminder
that at the end of the bursting pipes is a human brain with an
appetite for general news that is limited.
</P>
<P>
   ``The supply has vastly expanded,'' said Rosenstiel, the media
critic. ``The natural human instinct for how much news you need,
how much time you spend absorbing the world around you, has not
changed.'' At least not in terms of reading habits.
</P>
<P>
   That, he said, casts doubt on the proposition that people will
eagerly take on the task of sorting through the new avalanche of
information themselves. ``If people aren't spending any more time''
reading news, in print or online, he said, the idea ``that everyone
will be their own editor doesn't work in real life; people do not
have time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
