<HEADLINE>
TELECOMMUTING, THE NEXT PHASE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Ill., N.Y.)   (jw) 
 By DAVID LEONHARDT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If ever there was a company likely to take to telecommuting, it
is AT&AMP;T. The huge corporation has thousands of employees around the
world. Many perform white-collar tasks that can be accomplished on
computers and sent over the Internet. Even the company's bottom
line can benefit when its workers dial into the company's network
or pick up the phone to call headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in 1999, five years after AT&AMP;T began a formal telecommuting
program, the percentage of managers who worked from home at least
once each week dropped to 24 percent, from 29 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is AT&AMP;T alone.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, thousands of people who tried working from
home part time during the 1990s have returned to the office full
time. Many felt disconnected from their colleagues, became
frustrated about slow computer hookups or simply grew tired of
trying to be a parent and an employee at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   It is enough to make one wonder whether the workplace of the
early 21st century will in fact resemble a traditional office much
more than was once thought.
</P>
<P>
   Do not be fooled, workplace experts say, contending that in
reality this is the lull before the telecommuting storm. Companies
and workers alike are working out early kinks and awaiting new
technology, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is going to transform the workplace,'' said John A.
Challenger, the chief executive of Challenger, Gray &AMP; Christmas, a
Chicago outplacement firm. Over the next few years, analysts say,
flexible work arrangements will force companies to reassess how
they use space and cause more people to take part-time jobs or
become independent contractors.
</P>
<P>
   As broadband Internet access begins to enter homes in the next
year _ the change AT&AMP;T says its telecommuters are waiting for _ the
office computer will no longer be so much faster than the home PC.
And as the cost of videoconferencing equipment continues to fall,
the technology will soon be affordable to many more people.
</P>
<P>
   Demographic forces are playing a role, as well. As the number of
baby boomers taking care of elderly parents grows, the ability to
stay home will become more attractive. The current tight labor
markets, meanwhile, are certainly vulnerable to economic cycles,
but they are also a product of population trends that will continue
through the first few years of the new decade, forcing employers to
look for highly skilled workers wherever they can find them.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-three percent of human resource executives recently polled
by Challenger, Gray &AMP; Christmas said that telecommuting would be
the most important workplace trend of the 21st century _ ranking it
higher than any other subject. And while statistics on the subject
are notoriously unreliable, most analysts agree that at least 10
million Americans now telecommute regularly, and that number is not
expected to fall.
</P>
<P>
   The hiccups of the last few years are not uncommon when new
technology is adopted. Such practices often go through three
stages, said John Chambers, the chief executive of Cisco Systems,
which builds much of the networking behind the Internet. First
comes an initial excitement; then skepticism that the trend will
truly take off, and, finally, widespread acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommuting is now moving out of the second of those stages,
many workplace experts say.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the 1990s, telecommuting captured workers'
imaginations as a way to hold on to their careers and salaries
while removing some of the strain of long weeks at the office.
</P>
<P>
   Managers, for their part, realized it could help them cut down
on real estate costs and potentially even improve productivity by
making workers happier. Often, however, both sides underestimated
the ensuing difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many companies rushed into telecommuting,'' said Rick
Wald, a principal at the human resource consulting firm William M.
Mercer, who advises companies on flexible benefits. ``It really
requires training for managers. They need to manage people
differently.''
</P>
<P>
   That is precisely the lesson that Merrill Lynch learned, and its
response offers a glimpse of what telecommuting could become. In
1994, it started a pilot program but quickly discovered that
neither telecommuters nor their bosses were ready for all the
questions that arose: How often should a worker check voice mail?
Is day care still necessary? Do telecommuters really work full
time?
</P>
<P>
   So two years later Merrill Lynch created an elaborate training
program for people who wanted to work at home sometimes, said
Janice Miholics, a vice president for alternative work arrangements
in the private-client technology group. Employees must write a
formal proposal to enter the program. Both they and their bosses
then sit through a two-hour training session. Finally, the
telecommuters spend their first two weeks in transition, dialing
into the office from an on-site laboratory, where they are given a
laptop, printer and other equipment to take home.
</P>
<P>
   In Mrs. Miholics' division, 350 of the 1,800 workers now
telecommute at least once a week. Only one employee has ever
stopped telecommuting for a reason other than a job change, she
said. ``It's allowed us to retain some critical people who
otherwise would have left,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
