<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-19 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3366 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-OUTLOOK-WORKPLACE-NYT     12-19 0373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTLOOK-WORKPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: she said. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Other companies are learning the same lessons. ``We're starting
to sift out a lot of the failed programs,'' said Christena
Nippert-Eng, a sociologist at the Illinois Institute of Technology,
who has studied telecommuting. ``The programs that exist now are
much better.''
</P>
<P>
   The next problem will be deciding what to do with the office
when it has fewer people in it, workplace experts said. One
solution, called hoteling, involves getting rid of permanent
offices and instead assigning full-time workers to a new office or
cubicle each day, depending on what is available.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the country's largest consulting firms, where employees
are often out of the office on assignment, have adopted hoteling
and cut down their real estate costs. But it has failed to catch on
elsewhere because employees often find it dehumanizing. ``When you
play with someone's space, you're playing with 8 to 10 to 12 hours
of their day,'' said Robin Szumyk, a principal in William M.
Mercer's human resources practice.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Lisa Hilbish, an account executive in Charlotte, N.C.,
for Ceridian Employer Services, which sells payroll software to
companies. She works from home about twice each week and said it
was a benefit that made her more likely to remain in her job. The
one complication, however, is that, when she decides to come into
the office on short notice, there are often no desks available, and
she must work in a room used for employee breaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of loud,'' Mrs. Hilbish said. ``You don't get as
much done.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, some companies are building space for specific
departments or teams so that workers can feel at home there, even
if they are sharing it with colleagues, said Susan L. Boyle, a
managing partner at HLW International, a New York workplace
consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   That, however, does not solve the problem of what to do when
everybody shows up on the same day. Such questions will loom over
the workplace in the next few years as telecommuting becomes more
widespread.
</P>
<P>
   ``The technology piece will get itself worked out. The security
piece will get itself worked out,'' Ms. Boyle said. ``But there's
an emotional piece, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
