<SLUG> BC-OUTLOOK-BANKS-REED-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ATM PROPHET IS A LATE CONVERT TO THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As a young Citicorp executive more than 20 years ago,
John S. Reed earned a reputation as a technology guru for his
stubborn insistence that automated teller machines _ faceless boxes
that spit out money _ would eventually make legions of human bank
tellers unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   After the bank initially lost millions of dollars on his ATM
bet, Reed was vindicated: the gizmos are now as common as corner
newsstands. And empty teller windows at many banks attest to the
fate of the machines' human counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Reed is now co-chief executive of Citigroup, the country's
largest financial services concern and the creation of last year's
merger of Citicorp and Travelers Group. But for all his interest in
technology, Reed admits that the impact and importance of the
Internet escaped his attention until recently.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet has now snared the attention of everyone in the
banking industry. Companies are rushing to create Internet banking
capabilities, either as part of the bank, as in Citigroup's case,
or as an entirely separate entity. While no clear leaders have
emerged among the banks, Wells Fargo and Bank One have been
particularly aggressive competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Reed said that tackling the challenges of the Internet was now a
high-priority at Citigroup. Indeed, a job reshuffling in July put
Reed in charge of Citigroup's Internet strategy, while Citigroup's
other co-chief executive, Sanford I. Weill, retains most of the
other operational duties at the company.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview at his Midtown Manhattan office, Reed shared his
thoughts about the Internet, online financial services and the
future of banking.
</P>
<P>
   Following are excerpts from that conversation:
</P>
<P>
   Reed: First of all, this is a revolution. I believe we are
living through a sea change. In the next few years, a lot of
customers are going to be dealing with their finances over the
Internet. Today, about 25 percent of the U.S. population is on the
Internet; 75 percent is not. It is growing rapidly. Around the
world the numbers are different, but, still, the growth is
significant.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What regions around the world are growing fastest in Internet
usage?
</P>
<P>
   A: Japan, Brazil, Singapore are hot spots. The problem right now
is, No. 1, the terrestrial competition is pretty good. Sitting down
and paying bills with a check, having a checking account and cash
machines is pretty easy. So in order to have the Internet be
attractive, it has to be better than things that are already pretty
effective and efficient.
</P>
<P>
   One of the things that will make a significant difference over
time is pricing. Pricing on the Internet will be significantly
cheaper. You pay more for terrestrial banking services because of
the cost of operating a branch network. The Internet world won't
have those costs and, therefore, should be priced more
attractively. We need to be able to translate those cost savings to
the customer.
</P>
<P>
   Also, there is a difference between being ``on the net'' and
``of the net.'' ``On the net'' means someone comes on, they find
us, and they find what they're looking for. ``Of the net'' means
we're embedded in someone else's offering.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why has online stock trading taken off so much more rapidly
than online banking?
</P>
<P>
   A: If you're happy writing checks and dealing with your bank in
the normal way, there is not tremendous motivation to get you onto
the Internet. I think one thing that is causing banks to be slow
compared to brokers is that banking is a much more complex
relationship. In Japan, 20 percent of our customers are coming to
us through the Internet or by phone. When they sign up, we send
them the forms and they sign. They never see a branch; they never
deal with us physically.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason they deal with us is they are looking for the
products we offer that are not available from their local Japanese
banks. For whatever reason, they are electronically comfortable,
and they come in and deal with us. It is an important part of our
growth. I think here in the States it will come in time, but it
will come when there is a clear price advantage.
</P>
<P>
   We should be able to pay people a lot more for their money. I
think we are going to develop a set of people who deal with us
differently. They are going to deal with us over the Internet and
with cash machines and they will never see a branch. They won't
care about a branch. Then the question will be, why did they choose
us, and it's going to have to be some sense of ``OK-ness'' with who
we are and some degree of the quality of service of the
interaction.
</P>
<P>
   I believe that this notion of community is very important in the
electronic world. I think the bank will have to establish some kind
of community feel. The customer has to enjoy interacting with us,
feel good about interacting with us. We are going to have to do a
lot of experimenting as to what constitutes that kind of community.
Advice is going to turn out to be one of the key issues. I think to
a much greater degree than we recognize, people come into the
branches of banks because they want to talk to people. That
dialogue gives them a sense of how they should manage their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you think that is broken up demographically _ that younger
people may be willing to find their advice in a medium like the Net
rather than rely on an adviser in a branch?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think that is true. I just don't have the data to support
it. I have a feeling most of us are quite ignorant about finance.
It's amazing to me _ I have friends who are professors at famous
universities who are absolutely naive with regard to money. That's
because there isn't any part of the normal education process that
teaches you, unless you're raised in a family where your parents
talked to you about these things. It's just not a subject you run
into.
</P>
<P>
   So I would guess that half of the people who run into
difficulties with a credit card never learned the fundamental
disciplines of a budget. And it doesn't make any difference how
much money you have, whether it's a lot of money or a little money.
Actually people with a little money tend to learn a lot more
quickly because they get forced by the world to learn how to manage
their resources. The good news is I have a feeling that, 30 to 45
years from now, we will have a much better-educated public.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are these things getting increasingly commodified as the
consumer is getting more educated?
</P>
<P>
   A: If somebody arrived from Mars and you put a Ford and Chevy in
front of them, I think they would have a hard time deciding what
the difference is. The point is, a car is a car is a car, and big
differences are really quite subtle. So from the perspective of a
Martian, let's face it, most banks aren't all that different.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will the differences matter in the future?
</P>
<P>
   A: It will matter, but we need to form these communities, and we
are going to have to be warm and fuzzy and meaningful. Yes, there
will be subtle differences with presentation and style and so
forth. I was talking to Bob Pitman from America Online. He
estimates that 80 percent of the people on the Net are looking for
convenience and 20 percent are looking for price. So a feeling of
convenience is going to be important. Someone has to know who you
are, who they are taking money from and so forth. It isn't as
though you can just go in and buy a share of stock with anyone _
you have to set up a relationship. And once you set up the
relationship, the likelihood is you'll stick with it. But it is all
open space right now.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you worry about Quicken or AOL getting between you and
your customers?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. I do believe that it will be a revolution. Like all
revolutions it will be very easy to get lost. We have not figured
it out. You can see the P/Es of these Internet companies, and you
say to yourself, ``You know what? What the market is saying to you
is, `If you can get your business into the Internet space, it is
more valuable.'''
</P>
<P>
   Why is it more valuable? Because your cost of acquiring
customers is very small compared to terrestrial stuff. Your cost in
serving a customer is almost negligible. If you do want to play,
you have to confront the question of ``OK, how do I operate in this
space? How do I get from here to there?''
</P>
<P>
   I just spent an extended period meeting with Internet companies.
I was probing to see what sort of inner contradictions there were
that might bring this all to a screeching halt. I was trying to
figure out if this thing is really going anywhere. And I believe it
is. Maybe 20 percent of the G.N.P. is highly susceptible to
disintermediation by the Internet. That's a lot of money. This will
be profound.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who do you worry about the most?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't worry about anybody. The challenge is ours. I admire
_ and that's a little different from worry _ AOL. AOL is clearly
predominant. I have been in business for a very long time, and
there are very few instances where people start from zero and end
up with 20 million customers. And they have done precisely that. We
did that with our credit cards. Maybe _ and I don't know the facts
here _ our friends at Fidelity did that with mutual funds. This
idea of being able to gain customers at that speed is more
noteworthy than people think.
</P>
<P>
   I am a revolutionary, as you may know, and anytime you give me a
fork in the road where the choice is a slow change or a revolution,
I will always take the revolution. I am a great believer that that
is how changes take place. The Internet is real. It is fundamental.
And it is also a young person's game.
</P>
<P>
   Q: As a manager of this, what are the questions you are not
seeing answered that you would like to see answered, or issues
explored that are not being explored?
</P>
<P>
   A: From my point of view, we have to figure out fundamental
economics. We have to worry a lot about privacy, how to treat
customers. And we have to get working on some of these expert
systems and selling and so forth and so on. We bring some specific
knowledge of how our business works, and we are going to have to
let people who know a little bit more about the Internet worry
about how to do the software.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think this is going to be fun and games. It's going to
be quite a big change in the next 10 to 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
