<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-19 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3371 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-OUTLOOK-MUTFUND-ART-N     12-19 1264
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTLOOK-MUTFUND-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOES A SLOWING OF NEW CASH PORTEND PROBLEMS FOR THE FUND
INDUSTRY? 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Are the mutual fund industry's best days behind it?
</P>
<P>
   Sales gains are slowing. Fund company stocks are lagging. Some
fund investors have taken their big gains and cashed in. And
challenges from cheaper institutionalized money managers, online
brokerage firms and other new competitors have led some analysts to
predict that the tough times for the industry are only starting.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1997, the amount of new money flowing into stock mutual
funds has slowed: In the first 10 months of this year, cash flows
into equity funds totaled $142.9 billion, slightly ahead of $141
billion for the period last year but well below the record pace of
1997. That year investors poured in a net of $193.6 billion through
October and $227.3 billion for the full year. What is more, sales
growth for taxable bond funds has slowed considerably, as just
$14.4 billion flowed in this year through October, in contrast to
$50.7 billion for the 1998 period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prior fund flows were extraordinary because a good bit of it''
was from large companies creating 401(k) plans, said A. Michael
Lipper, the chairman of Lipper Inc., the fund research company in
Summit, N.J. ``That's a one-time impact.'' Lipper added that
household ownership of funds might be approaching a saturation
point as the growth in the percentage of people who own funds
begins to decelerate.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, most people in 401(k) plans have already shifted money
from bonds, money market funds and other conservative investments
to equity funds. That means future growth will come mostly from
additional contributions to retirement or brokerage firm accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Also contributing to the slowdown in fund inflows is lingering
investor trauma from late 1998, when the Russian economic crisis
and the near-collapse of Long-Term Capital Management L.P. sent
markets plunging. Another factor, no doubt, is the rise in
popularity of online stock trading. Given all these factors,
analysts and fund company executives say fund inflows could remain
tepid for some time, even if the stock market continues to rise.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is that many longtime fund investors are now
redeeming fund shares to enjoy some of their gains. Alan Greenspan,
the Federal Reserve Board chairman, for example, has suggested that
gains in the stock market and in home values have led to increased
consumer spending and helped sustain the strong economy.
</P>
<P>
   A first-ever joint survey conducted this year by the Securities
Industry Association and the Investment Company Institute lends
support to Greenspan's theory: Outside of employer-sponsored
retirement plans, only 57 percent of investors put all the proceeds
from their most recent mutual fund sales back into the market; the
other 43 percent spent at least part of the money elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The high stock market volatility of the last year has not helped
fund sales. And funds have been feasting off the stunning market
run-up of the last five years, adds John C. Bogle, founder and
senior chairman of the Vanguard Group, the nation's No. 2 mutual
fund company after Fidelity Investments. Without that wind at their
backs, he saidfunds are likely to be merged into other funds
or liquidated.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a market-dependent business,'' Bogle said. ``The
forecast for the future is basically what the markets are going to
do. If we're in for a more subdued market, that's going to put
pressure on cash flows. I would look for pressure on cash flows to
continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the industry's worries is that the new money that has
flowed into funds has gone mainly into the hottest funds, while
some weaker funds have suffered net redemptions. Consequently,
Bogle predicted that more than a quarter of today's funds could be
liquidated or merged out of existence over the next five years. ``I
don't expect these great markets to continue,'' Bogle said.
``Reversion to the mean will take its toll'' on many funds.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last five years, funds that mimic the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index have significantly outperformed most general equity
funds, and that, too, has dimmed the luster of actively managed
funds _ even though many funds managed to beat the S&AMP;P for part of
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Funds have for a long time underperformed the market,'' said
Harold Evensky, a financial adviser in Coral Gables, Fla. People
``perceive they can do better buying their own stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   That dissatisfaction with actively managed funds has led some
investors to forgo funds in favor of accounts at online brokerage
firms. Forrester Research has estimated that total assets in online
accounts will approach $400 billion this year, triple the total
three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But it is far from clear just how much money is being taken out
of funds to buy stocks: In the joint survey, only 6 percent of
investors said that the money for their most recent stock purchase
came from selling equity fund shares; in contrast, 8 percent said
the money for their most recent mutual fund purchase came from
selling shares of individual stocks.
</P>
<P>
   But other problems may loom for the industry. The 401(k) flows
that have become a bedrock source of new money _ one-third to
one-half of sales each year at some fund companies have been to
employer-sponsored retirement accounts _ are facing increased
competition from separate, or co-mingled, accounts, where money is
pooled and managed for less than a retail fund typically charges to
handle accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The shift of 401(k) money away from funds has been significant
among employer plans with more than 5,000 participants, said Ryan
Tagal, an analyst at Cerulli Associates, a Boston consulting firm.
Lower cost is the biggest reason, he said, with managers of
co-mingled accounts willing to handle money much more cheaply than
retail funds do. ``Mutual funds are probably too expensive for
these large plans,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A serious and prolonged market slump, were it to occur, could
devastate fund company profits and batter their already beaten-down
shares. When the S&AMP;P 500 index fell almost 20 percent in the fall
of 1998, shares of some of the largest publicly traded fund
companies fell more than twice that much.
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about the industry's future have taken a further toll
on those stocks this year, as shares of some big fund companies
have stayed flat for the year.
</P>
<P>
   But the poor recent returns mask the stunning prosperity that
many fund companies have enjoyed over the long term. Shares of two
of the largest publicly traded fund companies, Franklin Resources
and T. Rowe Price Associates, have given 19-fold and 35-fold
returns, respectively, over the last dozen years. That compares
with an eightfold total return for the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, many fund families still manage returns on equity of
more than 25 percent. And even with little money coming in, they
can count on their revenue base expanding by up to 10 percent or so
every year, assuming stocks revert to their historical average
annual returns. And many companies are branching into other areas.
</P>
<P>
   But many smaller funds and fund families, particularly those
that do not match the performance of their peers, can expect things
to get worse over the next five years, Bogle said. ``A lot of funds
are going to give up the ghost,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
