<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVIVING THE FOOD FEST 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Wondering how to enjoy holiday festivities and ward off
unwanted pounds? Here are a few strategies,'' begins an article in
Northwest Health, an HMO newsletter. Along with their suggestions,
I have inserted some of my observations.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Never go to a holiday event hungry.''
</P>
<P>
   That means I have to eat before I go, right? That's a great
start to a holiday diet plan. I won't even attempt to explain to my
wife when I walk out the front door gnawing on a chicken leg.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Don't sit or stand near the buffet table.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, I'll stand in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Allow yourself just two visits to the buffet table. Start
with cold foods and fill up on the fruits and vegetables. Then go
back for hot foods.''
</P>
<P>
   Wait a minute. I have spent a large part of my life learning how
and when to attack a buffet table. You begin with the expensive
stuff, like prawns, crab legs and smoked salmon. Apple slices and
celery sticks are ``foods of last resort'' and are to be considered
only if or when the fudge brownies run out.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``As you select foods, keep items within the inner circle of
your plate. For an added challenge, leave a half-inch to an inch of
space between each item of food.''
</P>
<P>
   With a battle plan like that, you don't need a plate, you need
something the size of a garbage can lid or manhole cover.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Burn off extra calories. Take the stairs instead of the
elevator. Park farther from stores and walk. Turn on music and
dance at home.''
</P>
<P>
   I challenge the author of that article to skip down the stairs
and dance down the street while clutching a 16-pound smoked turkey,
which is the kind of baggage most of us hope to acquire during the
holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is sure. Your neighbors will burn up a few calories
laughing when they see you tango past the living-room window.
</P>
<P>
   Gee, just thinking about all that exercise makes me hungry. How
about some:
</P>
<P>
   Rye Cocktail Snacks
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces sharp Cheddar cheese, grated
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup minced green onions
</P>
<P>
   1 4-ounce can chopped black olives
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   1 loaf party rye bread
</P>
<P>
   Moosh together first four ingredients and let stand an hour.
Spread on sliced party rye. Freeze on baking sheet until needed.
Bake at 375 degrees for 8 to 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Holiday Bean Dip
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cooking oil
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds cup minced onion
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, mashed
</P>
<P>
   1 and one-half teaspoons cumin powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon oregano
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon chili powder
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   One-eighth teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 8-ounce can tomato sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 16-ounce can refried beans
</P>
<P>
   Cook the onion in oil 4 minutes. Add garlic, cumin, oregano,
chili powder, salt and pepper and stir-cook another minute. Add the
tomato sauce and simmer another 3 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Remove pan from heat, let sauce cool for 5 minutes, then mix
with the refried beans. When well combined, serve at room
temperature with tortilla chips for dipping.
</P>
<P>
   Low-fat Chix Snacks
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 pounds boneless, skinless chicken breast
</P>
<P>
   1 and one-half cups soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 and one-half cups dry sherry
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon Chinese five-spice powder
</P>
<P>
   1 cinnamon stick
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon peanut or canola oil
</P>
<P>
   Whack the chicken into bite-size pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Dump all the other ingredients into a saucepan. Bring to a boil,
then add chicken and simmer 15 minutes. Remove pan from heat and
let sit, covered, 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer chicken to an airtight container and keep in the
refrigertor. Serve at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   You can refrigerate the sauce in a covered jar for your next
batch of chicken snacks.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon's Snack
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces blue cheese, crumbled
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, mashed
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons red-wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup chopped red onion
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup minced parsley
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle the cheese onto an 8-inch plate. Mix together garlicand olive oil and drizzle over cheese. Combine other ingredients
and pour over the cheese. Refrigerate one hour. Sprinkle with
pepper and serve with wheat crackers.
</P>
<P>
   I first tried this dynamite appetizer, prepared by niece Megan
McNamer, at a gathering in Montana. Meg said she found it in a book
written by one of my favorite Seattle cooking authorities, Sharon
Kramis. In turn, Kramis credited the recipe to an unnamed Mercer
Island cook, who submitted it to a weekly newspaper. I have no idea
where the Mercer Island cook found the original recipe, but I'm
pretty sure it did not originate in an HMO newsletter on holiday
dieting strategies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
