<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991219.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-19 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3381 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-OUTLOOK-INTEREST-RATE     12-19 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTLOOK-INTEREST-RATES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOWER INTEREST RATES ARE TIED TO AN ECONOMIC SLOWDOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Inflation is calm. The Federal Reserve is vigilant. And the
federal budget deficit has disappeared. So conditions should be
right for long-term interest rates finally to fall decisively below
5 percent, a level they have seen only briefly in the final third
of the century about to end.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. Other factors, like the strong stock market, work against
any slippage in rates, and many analysts say that only a
significant slowdown in economic growth will push rates down any
time soon. But just the fact that this decline can be contemplated
shows how much the financial and economic environment has changed
over the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   The overall Consumer Price Index was up a mild 2.6 percent over
the last 12 months through November. While that is above the 1.6
percent in 1998, much of this year's rise has come from the jump in
oil prices. The core rate, which excludes food and energy, is up
just 2.1 percent through November, down from the 2.4 percent core
rate for 1998. All of these are far below the 12.5 percent that the
overall Consumer Price Index rose in 1980 when long-term government
interest rates topped 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve, which now has 20 years of credible
inflation-fighting behind it, is trusted to pounce on any
inflationary threat. Even with inflation low this year, the Fed
raised its short-term interest rate target a quarter of a
percentage point three times to slow the economy and take upward
pressure off prices.
</P>
<P>
   And with the monetary side of policy secure, the fiscal side has
also improved. At least for the time being, the federal budget has
a surplus, which should take some pressure off the government's
$5.7 trillion debt.
</P>
<P>
   But even with all that, long-term government interest rates fell
below 5 percent only briefly in late 1998 _ and it was panic over
the global financial crisis that produced the fall. Money poured
into this country as investors sought safety. When foreign markets
stabilized, some of that money left, and bond yields in this
country rose again.
</P>
<P>
   Now, some forecasters say that even though the conditions for a
further rate decline are in place, it will still take a slowdown in
the pace of United States economic growth to get long-term interest
rates much below their current levels, 6.37 percent for Treasury
bonds and 7.59 percent for corporate bonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we are there yet,'' said Bruce Steinberg, chief
economist at Merrill Lynch, who is forecasting that the yield on
the 30-year Treasury bond will be around 6 percent in the fourth
quarter of next year. ``First, we need to see some significant
slowing in economic activity.''
</P>
<P>
   With a forecast of 3.6 percent growth from the fourth quarter of
this year to the fourth quarter of 2000, he does not expect that,
unless ``something unpleasant happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Such unpleasantness could come in two forms: a stock market
crash, which would dampen consumer spending enough to slow growth
significantly, or aggressive rate increases from the Federal
Reserve. Steinbergis is expecting one quarter-point increase in the
Fed's short-term interest rate target as early as February. But
three increases, he said, would surely convince investors that the
economy was going to slow a lot, bringing interest rates down.
</P>
<P>
   Two factors are combining to make a rate decline less likely,
despite the positive environment. One is that real interest rates,
which are adjusted for inflation, are high. The other is that
higher worker productivity has raised the Fed's speed limit for
economic growth. At least for now, the higher real rates and the
higher speed limit mean that the demand for capital to invest and
to feed a growing economy will keep rates higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology investment is driving this,'' said James E.
Glassman, senior U.S. economist at the Chase Manhattan Bank,
explaining the higher real interest rates. ``And the opening up of
global opportunities,'' he added, alluding to the chances for new
investment in China if Beijing is able to enter the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Glassman said real long-term rates are now around 4 percent, the
rate on the 30-year Treasury bond indexed to inflation.
</P>
<P>
   He is not worried, though, about the higher real interest rates,
maintaining that they are positive. ``The future looks better and
people want to invest,'' he said. ``Higher real rates are a
barometer for the outlook for the future.'' He noted that the
current level of real rates is about where they were during the
railroad boom in the mid-1800s and at the turn of this century.
</P>
<P>
   Chase is forecasting only a small decline in the rate of
economic growth next year, to 3 percent, from an estimated
3.8 &UR;  &LR; percent this year. Inflation is expected to remain about 2
percent. And long-term Treasury yields, it expects, will change
relatively little, perhaps falling below 6 percent by the end of
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg of Merrill Lynch said the rise in workers'
productivity in the 1990s had pushed the Fed's growth speed limit
up to a range of 3.5 percent to 4 percent. Fed officials have
acknowledged that the limit is higher, but not how much. So
analysts can only estimate how much it has been raised from what
was thought to be a ceiling of 2 percent to 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Glassman judges the speed limit to be slightly slower, around 3
percent to 3.5 percent. But any increase is important because it
raises the pace at which the Fed thinks the economy can grow
without generating worrisome inflationary pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The faster growth allowed with the higher speed limit means
there will be more credit demand to fuel this extra growth before
the Fed puts on the brakes, all of which suggests that interest
rates will have more trouble falling even if inflation remains low.
</P>
<P>
   Glassman said that inflation expectations were also making it
hard for interest rates to come down. Based on surveys of inflation
expectations and on the Treasury bonds indexed to inflation, he
said, consumers expect inflation to stay at the 2 percent level for
some time. Investors still have ``the 1970s inflation bug,'' he
said, noting that it takes just a few hints of stronger growth to
make people worry again.
</P>
<P>
   So a slowdown is the answer, right now, for lower interest
rates. And that means the stock market will probably determine
whether interest rates go lower or not.
</P>
<P>
   If stock prices keep rising, consumers are likely to continue
spending, as they feel wealthier every day. And that spending would
presumably prevent the economy from slowing enough to satisfy the
Federal Reserve. That could force a series of Fed rate increases
that could lead to a bigger slowdown, especially if the stock
market crumbled in the face of higher rates.
</P>
<P>
   And after that, interest rates could fall.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
