<SLUG> BC-OUTLOOK-REFLECTIONS-1150(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TIME OF ENERGY, ENTERPRISE AND E-EVERYTHING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By REED ABELSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When well-known executives were asked to sum up the most
important characteristics of the last 100 years in an epitaph for
the 20th century, they invariably talked about the powerful impact
of technology in all its myriad forms: the airplane, television,
computers and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before this century, science did not matter to the average
person,'' said Franklin Raines, the chairman and chief executive of
Fannie Mae, the world's largest nonbank financial services company.
``In this century, science is changing our lives fundamentally.''
</P>
<P>
   But as much as these business leaders, who hailed from
entertainment and financial services and industry, praised the huge
advances in technology over the last 100 years, they expressed
concern about how technology could be used and the double-edged
nature of change.
</P>
<P>
   The dark side of the passing century was hinted at by the comic
creator Stan Lee's rendition of Mongorr, a despot eager to
infiltrate our world to take advantage of the new technology. But,
in as epic terms as any battle waged between superheroes, Robert
Rubin, the former treasury secretary, also talked about the stark
contrasts of the last 100 years: the huge advances made and the
devastation wrought by the ability of people to hurt one another.
``Human nature has remained a constant,'' he concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the executives were also quick to note the substantial
divide that exists between those who have benefited from the
prosperity of the last 100 years and those who have not. ``The
haves and have-nots are getting further apart,'' said Lawrence
Bossidy, the chairman of Honeywell, the industrial giant created by
the recent merger of Honeywell, the maker of electronic controls,
and AlliedSignal, a diversified manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   As the chairman of Stan Lee Media, a publicly held company based
in Encino, Calif., Lee &UR;  &LR; is participating directly in the revolution
being created by the Internet. ``I've been in comics, radio,
television, animation, movies and now the Internet,'' said Lee, who
is one of the people responsible for such memorable superheroes as
Spider-Man and the Fantastic Four and plans to bring a new
generation of different superheroes and villains to the Internet in
short animated episodes.
</P>
<P>
   Television and the Internet, in particular, have achieved
enormous global reach, Lee says. People who once lived in isolation
are exposed as never before to what is going on in the rest of the
world. ``There are no hicks anymore,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Lee is genuinely worried about how this technology is used.
Like Mongorr, one of Lee's new characters, there are those who may
use the Internet to harness hatred. ``I'm hoping that the closer we
come together, the more that will fade away,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When Bossidy &UR;  &LR; of Honeywell thinks about the 20th century, he
ticks off the numerous advances in electronics: the cathode ray
tube in televisions, the microchip and the various iterations of
computers that allow work to be done rapidly, leading to huge
improvements in productivity.
</P>
<P>
   The advances in medicine _ the cure of diseases like scarlet
fever and new treatments for heart disease and cancer _ are also
striking, Bossidy said. ``People feel better. They don't just live
longer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the role of the corporation has also undergone significant
change, he argued, as companies have become much more efficient.
``Corporations used to be run exclusively by dictators,'' said
Bossidy, who spent more than three decades at General Electric
before joining AlliedSignal, where he became chief executive in
1991. ``Now you have to lead and be prepared to serve,'' he said,
and employees have the freedom to contribute.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, governments and other organizations will rely on a
corporate model to improve how they operate, according to Bossidy.
He also believes that companies will be asked more and more to
address social issues like education, not in privatizing them but
in marshaling resources.
</P>
<P>
   But Bossidy was wary of trying to guess what other innovations
the next century might bring. Just as few foresaw the Internet,
``most of the changes in the 21st century will not be predicted,''
he argued.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin, &UR;  &LR; who is as well known on Wall Street as he is in
Washington, takes an evenhanded approach in assessing the century.
Once a top official at Goldman Sachs, he is now the chairman of the
executive committee of the board for Citigroup, the nation's
largest financial services company. ``It has been a period of
tremendous advance,'' Rubin said, noting how much of the global
population has benefited from technology. But he is quick to point
out the last century's episodes of war and violence as well as the
use of technology for mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Globalization has also remarkably changed how we live, he noted.
``I think we are far more interdependent today than we were 100
years ago,'' economically, environmentally and geopolitically,
Rubin said. He, too, is concerned about the gulf between those who
are enjoying this century's tremendous prosperity and those who are
not but understand what they are missing.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge, he said, will be to see how the tension between
sovereignty and the growing global interdependence is handled, and
he believes the United States must decide what role it should play.
``There is a tremendous struggle between those who believe that the
U.S. should play a major leadership role and those who believe in
some fashion that we should turn inward and turn our back,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   David Komansky, the chairman and chief executive of Merrill
Lynch &AMP; Co., takes a strikingly more optimistic view. ``Be
bullish,'' he argued, not about financial markets but in viewing
the strides made in the past 100 years. Despite world wars, the
Great Depression and other economic turbulence, there have been
significant improvements in the standard of living, medicine and
technology, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are on the doorstep of a truly global lifestyle
that will benefit every person in every part of the world,''
Komansky said.
</P>
<P>
   The power of instant communication _ the ability to make a
telephone call anywhere in the world or tune into CNN to see
minute-by-minute broadcasts of war _ has created a world that is
linked almost in real time, Komansky said.
</P>
<P>
   Globalization, he argued, has transformed businesses like
Merrill Lynch, which two decades ago was primarily a domestic firm.
Today, more than a third of its business is conducted outside the
United States, and Merrill employs 65,000 people in 44 countries.
Managing the huge variety of people from different ethnic
backgrounds becomes more of a challenge, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the phenomenon of globalization is in its very early
days,'' Komansky predicted. But he said he was confident that
civilization would continue to make great progress. ``The future is
much brighter than the past,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
