<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Raines, the head of Fannie Mae, the country's largest provider
of home-mortgage financing, is keenly aware of how much more
accessible capital _ in the form of mortgages, credit cards and
loans _ is today than it was before a variety of government
programs were created in the aftermath of the Great Depression to
help homeowners, farmers and small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Then, ``the government was involved in pushing capital out into
the economy and making it much more available to the individual,''
Raines said.
</P>
<P>
   While the private sector has taken over much of that role _ and
Fannie Mae is now a publicly held company _ the continuing spread
of capital has helped create ``a huge wealth effect'' in the United
States, according to Raines.
</P>
<P>
   But Raines, the first black chief executive of one of the
nation's largest 100 corporations, also spoke of the ``century-long
effort'' to promote equality and ``integrate black America into
society.'' Corporate America has also taken part in that effort, he
said, and he pointed to the advancement of several black executives
within the last few years. ``Ten years ago, you couldn't think
about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Raines also talked about those who have been left behind in what
is known as the wealth gap. ``The democratization of wealth has not
been complete,'' he said, and he voiced concern that the nation
could lose its commitment to that goal during the next 100 years.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Eisner, &UR;  &LR; the chairman and chief executive of Walt Disney
Co., was reluctant to pontificate, but he, too, emphasized the
transforming power of technology. The 20th century ``has been a
triumph for human expression,'' he said. Communication has been
transformed, he said, from what was once largely face to face to
something that is now both instant and universal for people around
the globe. No matter how effective books and other printed forms of
expression were in creating change, the widespread adoption of
television and the Internet has fundamentally changed how we
express ourselves, he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the next century may see advances that make such
communication even more efficient and ubiquitous, it cannot make
communication faster, Eisner noted. ``You can't go faster than
instant,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner, who suggested that philosophers and psychiatrists were
more adept at thinking about the implications of this change, shied
away from predicting where this instant human expression, allowing
anyone to say anything to nearly anyone else, would lead. Either
global democracy or totalitarianism could result, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Stewart, the entrepreneur whose sense of style led to the
creation of her own media and merchandising empire, Martha Stewart
Living Omnimedia, worries that we are already witnessing the
drawbacks of the new speed at which we conduct our lives. While she
applauded the advances of the 20th century in technology, science
and medicine, ``advancement in the study of the humanities, in art
and in cultural endeavors, seems to have been less progressive,
especially in the second half of this century,'' she argued.
</P>
<P>
   The result of the widespread adoption of the telephone, faxes,
e-mail messages and computers has been the inability to think
creatively, Ms. Stewart said. Answering e-mail has taken the place
of writing a great novel. Her own life has been consumed by the
Internet, she said, and technology has allowed her to do any number
of jobs at once. ``It's insane,'' she laughed, but she said she was
also saddened by the widespread implications of this speed.
</P>
<P>
   She is also concerned about the social impact of the technology,
which she described as taking away physical contact, from seeing
someone directly or talking to them on the telephone. ``It is much
more introverted living,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   What she hopes is that the next century will provide more time
for people to reflect. As people get used to the technology, they
may learn to dominate it. And she hopes that we remain sensitive to
the challenge of making technology accessible to all, although she
is confident that will happen. ``Computers are going to be cheap,''
she said. ``Everyone is going to have them.''
</P>
<P>
   As the chairman and chief executive of America Online, one of
the best-known providers of access to the Web, Stephen Case enjoys
a key vantage point on the development of the Internet. The
proliferation of telephones and cars, the television, the computer
and the Internet created an increasingly mobile society, Case said.
Businesses were opened up, and people could be on the move without
losing all ties to family and friends. ``Suddenly, anything was
possible,'' Case said.
</P>
<P>
   The result, according to Case, has been the American century.
``It was a time of unprecedented opportunity,'' he argued, as
technology, coupled with the spread of democracy and the relative
prosperity and security of this period, allowed people to explore
new areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology was a real driver because it created not just whole
new industries, but it has also reshaped our lives,'' Case said.
</P>
<P>
   But he acknowledged that the challenge faced by society is in
making sure everyone has access. ``It is not about dropping
computers'' into places where people have difficulty taking
advantage of the technology, he said, but about developing an
integrated approach to making sure they have the tools and
wherewithal to use the computers.
</P>
<P>
   Case believes, however, that the Internet journey is only
beginning and that there is much to learn yet about how it will
affect this country and the world. ``I do think the next century is
going to be the Internet century,'' he said, and the next decade or
two will be defined by the changes wrought by the new medium. The
Internet has the ability to transform all aspects of what we do to
gather information, shop, communicate or be entertained.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very, very empowering,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
