<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-19 17:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3397 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-CABBAGE-PATCH20-COX     12-19 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CABBAGE-PATCH20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cabbage Patch Kids still a hot pick
 &HT;    By Clint Williams
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The frantic hordes are gone, the white-hot media
spotlight is focused elsewhere. But, like a balding pop star
playing Vegas, Cabbage Patch Kids are still making a very nice
living.
</P>
<P>
   Before Pokemon, before Tickle Me Elmo, before Mighty Morphin'
Power Rangers, there were Cabbage Patch Kids, the
so-ugly-they're-cute plush dolls that originated in Cleveland, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, Cabbage Patch Kids triggered a national mania, the
first of what has become a holiday tradition of stampeding to buy
the hot toy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cabbage Patch Kids fever,'' said Julia Jensen of Mattel, ``was
the granddaddy of the toy frenzies.''
</P>
<P>
   That frenzy is the one by which all others are measured. Toy
store tussles were commonplace as parents desperately tried to grab
Cabbage Patch Kids to put under the Christmas tree.
</P>
<P>
   The madness of people seeking the dolls became the stuff of
legends _ and a ``Newsweek'' cover story. A Kansas City, Mo.,
postman flew to London to buy a doll for his daughter. A Milwaukee
radio DJ convinced two dozen people to stand in Milwaukee County
Stadium, American Express cards raised to the sky, expecting
airborne delivery of 2,000 Cabbage Patch Kids.
</P>
<P>
   The dolls that struck such a universal chord were the offspring
of Xavier Roberts, an artist who traveled from his mountain home to
regional craft fairs selling hand-stitched dolls. The dolls weren't
(and still aren't) referred to as being sold, but ``adopted.''
</P>
<P>
   When demand for the kids increased, Roberts opened BabyLand
General Hospital in Cleveland. The remodeled house on a quiet side
street is staffed with ``nurses'' and ``doctors'' who care for the
hundreds of Cabbage Patch Kids up for adoption. Hand-stitched
infants lay in cribs, while posed toddlers sit in a classroom or
``scamper'' over playground equipment.
</P>
<P>
   A licensing agreement with Coleco brought to market copies of
the original Cabbage Patch Kids. Computer manufacturing allowed for
each of the dolls to be just a little different. Each left the
factory with a name and birth date. The doll's adoption certificate
allowed the owners to register them. The uniqueness was part of the
allure. Whatever the attraction, 3 million dolls weren't enough.
</P>
<P>
   Cabbage Patch fever brought the world to Cleveland, a town that
even now has just two traffic lights. People who couldn't find a
Cabbage Patch Kid in their cities called BabyLand General.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just calls back-to-back as fast as I could answer
them,'' recalled Becky Campbell, a nurse at BabyLand General.
</P>
<P>
   Some out-of-towners called local residents, offering to pay them
to buy a Cabbage Patch Kid at BabyLand General and ship it. Some
out-of-towners came to Cleveland themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Most came looking for the mass-produced version and many left
with a hand-made original, said Robin Davis, doctor at BabyLand
General.
</P>
<P>
   Cabbage Patch Kids were the No. 1 toy three years running.
Annual sales topped $300 million. But just as Elvis gave way to the
Beatles, other toys became what commentators soon were calling
``the next Cabbage Patch Kids.''
</P>
<P>
   But just as Elvis continues to sell millions of records, Cabbage
Patch Kids continue to sell in similar numbers. Since their
introduction, more than 90 million Cabbage Patch Kids have been
adopted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barbie goes on forever, and Cabbage Patch Kids may well go on
forever,'' said Wayne Wilste of Cleveland, who has adopted more
than 260 Cabbage Patch Kids.
</P>
<P>
   Cabbage Patch Kids ``is a very important product line for us,''
said Jensen of Mattel, which has been making the dolls and
accessories since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Sales were an estimated $63 million in 1998, according to the
NPD Group, a marketing firm that tracks the $15 billion toy
industry. BabyLand General still gets 300,000 visitors a year, many
of whom make the trip to adopt a hand-stitched kid for a fee of
$185 to $375.
</P>
<P>
   Cabbage Patch Kids have remained popular because they have all
the elements of a good toy, said Julie Creighton, director of the
Duracell Kid's Choice Toy Survey and Parenting magazine Toy Hall of
Fame Awards. The dolls are soft, cuddly and durable, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under all of that frenzy, there were a whole lot of little
kids hugging the little things,'' Creighton said.
</P>
<P>
   An interactive Cabbage Patch Kid that links with computers using
wireless technology will be introduced in February, Jensen said.
</P>
<P>
   But Cabbage Patch Kids have always been interactive, Creighton
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the trick of Cabbage Patch Kids. They come alive
because the children bring them to life.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
