<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-19 17:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3398 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-DEMS-MEETPRESS20-COX     12-19 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-MEETPRESS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore suggests biweekly debates with Bradley as alternative to TV
ads
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore challenged rival Bill
Bradley on Sunday to abandon expensive television advertising and
instead wage their campaign for president in a series of twice
weekly debates.
</P>
<P>
   Gore sprung his challenge during a joint appearance with Bradley
on NBC's ``Meet the Press.'' Bradley immediately dismissed the
challenge as a stunt, refusing to shake Gore's outstretched hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sounds to me like you are having trouble raising money,''
Bradley snapped. ``This is a ridiculous proposal. ... For 10 months
that I was running for president you ignored me. You pretended I
didn't exist. Suddenly, I started to do better, and you want to
debate every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore repeated his challenge to reporters after the event, and
said he would extend a similar one to the Republican nominee if he
wins the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Gore dismissed the suggestion that his campaign was facing money
problems, and campaign aides denied that his proposal was designed
to conserve money.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's exchange inside the beltway was Bradley and Gore's
third face-to-face encounter of the campaign, and the first to take
place without the tempering influence of a live audience or voters
posing questions.
</P>
<P>
   The difference in their demeanor was dramatic. The two former
Senate colleagues, calling each other ``Bill'' and ``Al,''
interrupted one another frequently and displayed an aggressiveness
that has erupted only briefly in their previous encounters.
</P>
<P>
   They disagreed sharply over which of them possessed the vision
to lead the country into the next century, and clashed repeatedly
over health care policy, education and campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   Gore sought repeatedly to sow doubts about Bradley's commitment
to protect Medicare, the health insurance program for the elderly,
by asserting that Bradley had only recently vowed not to raise the
eligibility age for Medicare as a way to extend viability of the
program.
</P>
<P>
   He dismissed Bradley's plan to enroll Medicaid recipients in the
same insurance program available to government workers as a ``$150
per month voucher'' that wouldn't purchase health insurance in the
real world, Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore portrayed himself as the only candidate with a
``revolutionary'' education platform, and accused Bradley of having
only a handful of ``nibble around the edges'' proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Gore would spend $115 billion to decrease class sizes, offer
bonuses for teachers and invest in new school construction. Bradley
would spend money to double the size of Head Start, increase day
care options and invest in community colleges.
</P>
<P>
   Both said they opposed publicly financed vouchers for poor
children to use in private schools. But Bradley, who voted for
pilot voucher programs when he was a senator, said policy makers
would have to look closely at vouchers if it was shown that they
improved the quality of public schools.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the two men debated the dilemma faced by poor,
urban parents in Washington who have no choice but to send their
children to bad schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to have a national commitment,'' Gore said. ``That
means getting 2 million new teachers over the next 10 years. That
means rigorous peer review of current teachers ... It means closing
down failing schools. It means reducing class size.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley cited his plan to entice more teachers into urban areas
with loan forgiveness programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The single most important thing that the national government
could do is to make sure there's a good teacher in every
classroom,'' Bradley said. ``The difference is Al proposes an
education program ... (that) comes from Washington ... as opposed
to helping people where they live their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley defended himself far more aggressively than he had done
in previous encounters with Gore. He accused Gore of
misrepresenting his health care plan, or not ``telling the whole
story.'' But he apologized for a campaign flier distributed in New
Hampshire that accused Gore of ``uncontrollable lying,'' saying the
release was ``unauthorized.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley called Medicaid a program that looked good to Washington
insiders, but one that was failing to reach 40 percent of the
nation's poor. He claimed his program would reach 30 million of the
nation's 44 million uninsured, while Gore's graduated approach
would reach only 7 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real question is whether you're willing to deal with a big
problem ... in a way that ensures middle-class Americans some
help,'' Bradley said. ``Al does nothing for middle-class
Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Both men dodged questions about how they would implement their
programs if budget surpluses disappeared. In a national crisis,
Gore said, ``all bets are off.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will guarantee that in a Gore presidency, you will have the
leadership to solve whatever problem confronts Social Security and
Medicare without raising the retirement age,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is going to let Medicare or Social Security go
bankrupt,'' Bradley asserted.
</P>
<P>
   NBC host Tim Russert grilled Gore about his claim, issued on the
day of President Clinton's impeachment, that history would record
Clinton as one of the nation's greatest presidents. When Russert
asked if Gore would include Clinton with Presidents Washington and
Lincoln, Gore answered, ``Of course not.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think that his accomplishments are going to be regarded
by the history books as far more significant than his personal
mistakes,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked to name the ``greatest'' presidents, Bradley
pointedly excluded Clinton and instead named Presidents Lincoln,
Washington, Franklin Roosevelt and Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   Gore declined to accept Russert's characterization of the 1996
campaign finance scandals as ``overly aggressive, perhaps
unethical.''
</P>
<P>
   He conceded only that Democrats had succumbed to ``pushing the
limits.'' Bradley called the scandal an embarrassment. But he also
conceded that his 1990 Senate campaign, which generated $12
million, raised ``too much money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I discovered that you can have too much money in a political
campaign,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   Russert also pressed Bradley to defend his 1991 vote against
using force in the Persian Gulf to expel Saddam Hussein from
Kuwait, given that the use of force in Kuwait ultimately drove
Saddam out. Bradley said he would not take the vote back.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
