<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-19 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3401 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-AIRPORTS20-COX     12-19 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRPORTS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta airport soon to surpass O'Hare in traffic
 &HT;    By Gary Hendricks
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For years, Chicago's O'Hare International Airport was
the king of the crowded concourses. A fixture in the business
world's lexicon was, ``Sorry I'm running late, but I'm stuck at
O'Hare.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the past decade, Atlanta's Hartsfield started to fit that
picture. Last year, it surpassed Chicago by handling the most
passengers a year. Now, if Federal Aviation Administration
projections hold, it will be No. 1 in another category: the most
planes landing and taking off in a single year.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA says it expects Hartsfield will surpass Chicago O'Hare
with about 910,000 landings and takeoffs this year _ or about
10,000 more than O'Hare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bet we won't miss (that projection) by more than 100 or so,
because our folks are pretty good at that,'' said Stanley Zylowski,
air traffic manager for the FAA's Southeastern Region.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Atlanta beating out Chicago _ perennially the
leader in passengers and operations _ would have set off
civic-pride boasts. Airports like the title ``busiest'' because it
is a marketing tool to attract more airlines.
</P>
<P>
   If an airport has the most passengers, international carriers
are more likely to come knocking at the door, said Hartsfield
spokesman Miguel Southwell, because that airport will have the most
connections to other cities in the country.
</P>
<P>
   But being top dog has its downside, too: Travelers have to deal
with crowded gates, long lines at ticket counters and delays from
backed-up runways.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction in Chicago this time: Atlanta, you be the world's
loudest, most congested airport for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means more airplanes in the air, more noise. I'm sure the
folks in the suburbs will appreciate that,'' said O'Hare
spokeswoman Monique Bond.
</P>
<P>
   Southwell said he wasn't ``ready to declare victory'' until he
sees firmer figures on both passengers and operations. The current
figures on passenger and operations volume from Airports Council
International, which keeps track of more than 700 airport
worldwide, only run through July.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of fanfare over leadership in departures/arrivals comes
at a time airlines are having a tough time dealing with delays and
crowded planes.
</P>
<P>
   Delta Air Lines, which accounts for 75 percent of Hartsfield's
passengers, has recently improved its rate of bumping passengers.
Hartsfield is averaging delays of six to eight minutes per flight.
Officials are pushing to get a fifth runway built by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Delta has contributed most of the operations increase at
Hartsfield, accounting for about 1,300 of the airport's daily rate
of 2,500 departing/arriving flights.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman John Kennedy said Delta has added new cities,
increased flights to major cities and added overseas schedules
since 1994, when it flew about 1,100 flights a day into and from
Hartsfield.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Chicago falling behind Atlanta produced some excuses from
the airport there.
</P>
<P>
   Operations fell off at O'Hare, because of labor problems earlier
this year at one of its major tenants, American Airlines, Bond
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, we have some suburbanites who drive right past O'Hare to
get to Midway because of 20 percent lower fares (on regional
airlines),'' Bond added.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
