<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-19 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3402 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-OUTLOOK-MOVIES-2TAKES     12-19 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTLOOK-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILM'S DIGITAL POTENTIAL HAS HOLLYWOOD ON EDGE
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The executive offices, with a half-dozen
paper-strewn desks in two rooms of a third-floor walk-up, are just
across the street from the basement nerve center where more than
two dozen people hunch over laptops and chatter to one another in
the dull glow of the computer screens. In other words, the ragged
bifurcated headquarters of iFilm looks pretty much like a cliched
rendering of an Internet start-up company, which is what it is.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also, in its way, a movie studio of the future.
Throughout the entertainment industry, from the major studios to
Internet start-up companies, people are trying to figure out how
the rapidly emerging digital technology will affect the movies that
people see and the ways that they see them. What iFilm is doing _
distributing digital films through the Internet to anyone with a
computer while also providing a forum for filmmakers and industry
executives to find each other _ is a good example of how this
technology is mutating the power structures that have governed
Hollywood since the advent of the talkies in the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of a movie studio is changing as we watch,'' said
Rodger Raderman, one of iFilm's founders and its co-chairman.
``What is a studio? If you think of it as a place where movies are
developed, produced, marketed and distributed, then we are very
close to having a technology where one person can do that all by
himself. Each person can be his own studio.''
</P>
<P>
   For Hollywood, an industry that claims to have its finger on the
pulse of mass audience tastes, it is a perplexing time.
</P>
<P>
   The movie business is moving into an interesting, perhaps
perilous and largely unknown period when the economics of
filmmaking and the very foundation of the power structures that
have governed the business for almost a century are more fluid than
at any time in its history. The pace of change and the revolution
in technology are outstripping entertainment executives' ability to
comprehend and control their business. Unease is the mood of the
day.
</P>
<P>
   Web sites devoted to producing digital films or, like iFilm,
providing a forum for digital films produced by others have been
proliferating in recent months as wave after wave of innovative
software and hardware have begun to ease what many see as the
inevitable transition between an old film-based technology and a
new digital movie world. The common wisdom among industry analysts
is that it will take three to five years for a sufficient number of
American households to acquire either digital television sets or
broadband capabilities for their computers, making it easy and
profitable for companies to pipe films to them on the Internet.
Sometime after that, they say, in maybe another two to three years,
the technology will be in place to allow people to call up movies
on demand _ simply ordering up whatever they want, when they want
it _ obviating the need for scheduled programming or video stores.
</P>
<P>
   So what happens to Hollywood then? Will people still go out to
the movies?
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry, Raderman said, iFilm is not out to eat Hollywood's
lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The studios are not the enemy,'' stressed Skip Paul, a
longtime Universal Pictures executive who founded Sega GameWorks,
the arcade company, with Steven Spielberg and was named iFilm's
other co-chairman last month.
</P>
<P>
   What iFilm wants to do, Raderman said, is ``enable'' filmmakers
and entertainment executives to meet each other in a kind of
high-technology forum where digital films can be shown through
their Web sites, where filmmakers can trade information about their
craft and where Hollywood agents and producers can gossip with one
another on a protected site and shop around for fresh ideas and new
talent. The ``communal experience'' of the movie theater will
remain important to consumers, Paul said.
</P>
<P>
   Is that the future: some youngster in Indiana making a movie on
his hand-held digital camcorder, editing it on his laptop and
shipping it to someplace like iFilm, where it can be piped into
every living room in America in a blink? Will filmmaking finally
become, as Orson Welles once described it, the best toy train set a
kid ever had?
</P>
<P>
   ``The technology is evolving so fast, and we want to be in the
catbird's seat when broadband becomes a reality,'' said Spielberg,
whose DreamWorks SKG studio is joining Imagine Entertainment to
create Pop.com, a Web site that will present short, original
digital films.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strides that the technology has made in the last year,
really in just the last six months or so, has led me to believe
that this is really the birth of a new medium, a shift from
information to entertainment on the Internet, which will create
some great opportunities for creative people to do new kinds of
work,'' said Ron Howard, the director who co-founded Imagine, one
of Hollywood's most prolific movie and television production
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood is nervous about the coming years because three things
are happening simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   First, movie technology, from the way films are made to the way
they will be shown, is riding an incredible high-technology wave
driven by the marriage of new digital movie-making gizmos and the
Internet, from digital cameras to digital editing software to
digital projectors.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, traditional movies have become more and more
expensive to produce. Driven by huge salaries for the top talent,
escalating production costs and more expensive marketing demands,
movie studios are struggling to find new formulas to make movies _
at a profit _ that will satisfy an increasingly fickle and
unpredictable audience. Because all the major studios are owned by
larger corporations, which increasingly see them as mere divisions
within a larger money-making machine, these dwindling profits have
led to growing cost-cutting demands from corporate patriarchs.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is the demographic bulge _ the so-called boomer
echo generation, even larger than the boomers who gave birth to
them _ that in the next decade will come into their adolescence and
early adulthood, their prime movie-going years. So much money to be
made. Can anybody figure out what these movigoers will want to see
_ and how they are going to want to see it?
</P>
<P>
   If the future is, as many believe, somehow brewing out there in
the world of digital technology and broadband distribution, then
its larval state must be here, in the basement nerve center of
places like iFilm. Raderman recently huddled over a screen,
watching a display of new iFilm software that makes viewing films
on a computer screen more pleasurable (it blacks out all of the
screen but the window showing the film, like a letterbox format).
</P>
<P>
   Basically, there are three technical issues that are being
resolved at this very moment by iFilm and other cybercompanies,
Raderman said. Movies have been available on the Internet for
years, but they have been an unsatisfying experience for most
viewers; available only in partial screen windows, taking forever
to download on most currently used modems, often herky-jerky when
played on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   The first breakthrough has been compression software, which
allows the computer to read the image as it is playing and refresh
only those parts that are changing _ say, lips and facial
expressions if a person is talking into a camera against a static
background. Much time is saved, and the image moves more smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   The second technical issue is so-called streaming video.
Previously, to play a film on a home computer, viewers had to
download the whole film and then play it back. With streaming
video, now available on most home computers, the movie begins to
play when it is only partly downloaded; the remainder of the film
downloads in the background while the first portion plays, thus
reducing waiting time.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Raderman said, there is the issue of the ``size of the
pipeline'' _ that is, how the digital images are transmitted into
the computer or television set, whether by modem or cable or
satellite. There are almost constant improvements to the capacity
of the line, he said, and in getting more information through
existing lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``My belief is that this becomes a viable company when 20
percent'' of the people have the technology for watching movies on
the Internet, said Lucas McDonough, iFilm's other founder and its
president. ``That's coming soon. These things are going to be
resolved simply because there is so much money to be made in
resolving them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
