<SLUG> BC-GATSBY-OPERA-1920S-ART-990(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GATSBY' AS OPERA, FOX TROTS AND ALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also GATSBY-OPERA-LYRICIST) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When John Harbison began working on his third opera,
``The Great Gatsby,'' he faced a particular musical challenge that
has stymied many opera composers before him.
</P>
<P>
   The iconic F. Scott Fitzgerald novel, on which the opera is
based, is set in the Jazz Age, the early 1920s. So the narrative is
filled with popular songs, dance music and show tunes from the
period. Jay Gatsby is always giving parties at his fancy house on
the Long Island shore, and his house resounds with music: jazz
bands and pop vocalists, dance combos playing fox trots and tangos.
Sometimes real tunes turn up significantly in Fitzgerald's prose,
like ``Ain't We Got Fun'' and ``The Sheik of Araby.''
</P>
<P>
   What was Harbison to do? Incorporate pop standards into his
opera? His own music would very likely have been blotted out by the
familiar tunes, and the tunes might have jarringly interrupted the
musical-dramatic flow.
</P>
<P>
   Far from being intimidated by the challenge, Harbison welcomed
it. The technique of evoking vernacular music has a long heritage
in opera, and Harbison conceived ``The Great Gatsby'' as an
extension of the tradition. The work receives its world premiere
Monday night at the Metropolitan Opera, with James Levine
conducting.
</P>
<P>
   Audiences are often startled when a living composer evokes
vernacular music, as William Bolcom does, for example, in ``A View
From the Bridge,'' which recently received its premiere at the
Lyric Opera of Chicago. The familiar music can seem incongruous
with what is perceived as operatic style. But older operas are
filled with evocations of vernacular music, though today's
audiences often miss this because the evoked styles are from
another era.
</P>
<P>
   Verdi's operas are rich with vernacular music; for example,
``Rigoletto.'' After an ominous orchestra prologue, the scene opens
at the Duke's palace, where an offstage band, exactingly evoked in
the orchestra, plays dance music for a bawdy party. The trick, as
Verdi realized, was to blend the vernacular idioms into a
contemporary musical language.
</P>
<P>
   Verdi did not provide his impressions of dance bands from
16th-century Mantua, the opera's setting, but music that his
audience in the 1850s would have recognized from any village square
in Italy. And before long the dance music builds subtly but
steadily into a full-fledged, complex choral ensemble, the kind of
music an audience of the day would have encountered only in a Verdi
opera.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes opera composers must invent vernacular music to suit
their purposes. Verdi obviously knew nothing about the music of
ancient Egypt when he composed ``Aida.'' So he fashioned a
19th-century Italian composer's impression of it, quite
convincingly, Harbison said. ``It works for me,'' he said recently
during a break in rehearsals for his opera at the Met. ``If it's
not Egyptian, it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Tchaikovsky used many real and made-up Russian songs and folk
tunes in his operas. Wagner's ``Meistersinger'' is a veritable
compendium of German folk songs, hymns and dances. Even a weighty
work like ``Tristan und Isolde'' has Wagner's versions of sailors'
songs, shepherds' plaints and hunting calls. Berg's ``Wozzeck,''
despite its expressionistic atonal language, evokes soldiers'
songs, children's ditties and even some maudlin barroom piano
music.
</P>
<P>
   As an opera composer, Mozart is practically Mr. Vernacular. In
her 1983 book, ``Rhythmic Gesture in Mozart,'' the scholar Wye
Jamison Allanbrook demonstrates that virtually every aria and
ensemble in ``Le Nozze di Figaro'' and ``Don Giovanni'' is based on
some 17th- or 18th-century dance form that Mozart's audiences would
have found familiar.
</P>
<P>
   They might not have exactly identified, say, a musette as a
musette. But they would have recognized the style and intuitively
understood its implications, much as Harbison's listeners may not
identify one of his rumbas as such but will get the point.
</P>
<P>
   His solution to the problem of evoking music from the 1920s in
his 1990s opera was the only one possible. Though he wrote his own
libretto, he asked Murray Horwitz to write '20s-style song lyrics
for which Harbison composed music. The songs and dances are spiked
with contemporary harmonic touches and blended into the continuous
musical flow of the score, which has a consistent compositional
voice.
</P>
<P>
   Of course you cannot evoke 1920s music without having a feel for
it. Harbison, who turns 61 on Monday, does. From the age of 8, he
listened faithfully to the radio broadcasts of the Metropolitan
Opera, and his father, a history professor at Princeton University
and an amateur musician, periodically took him to Met performances.
At the same time, though, he was excited by jazz.
</P>
<P>
   In junior high school he formed a Dixieland band called, to his
continuing embarrassment, the Harbison Heptet. He played piano. At
14 he applied to the musicians union and, after swearing under oath
that he had never been a member of the Communist Party, was
admitted. In high school he played in jazz bands and wrote
arrangements of pop standards.
</P>
<P>
   Harbison's formal training as a composer came later, at Harvard,
where he studied with Walter Piston, and in graduate school at
Princeton, where he worked with Roger Sessions and Milton Babbitt.
</P>
<P>
   But pop and jazz styles are still second nature to him. There
are 17 original vernacular pieces in ``Gatsby,'' including tangos,
charlestons and jazzy songs. Yet a close examination of the
piano-vocal score reveals the skill with which Harbison wove the
vernacular styles into the fabric of the entire score, even its
most intense and thorny moments.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, what works on the page may not work on the stage.
Whether ``The Great Gatsby'' succeeds will hinge on questions that
can be answered only in performance. But in this specific, and
central, matter of using vernacular idioms in a contemporary
fashion, Harbison's know-how is a model that could benefit any
opera composer.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For example, in an early scene, Tom Buchanan, the husband of the
heroine, Daisy, takes her cousin Nick Carraway, a jaded young
stockbroker, to meet his mistress, Myrtle, at the garage run by
Myrtle's unaware husband. There Tom turns on the radio to a jazzy
song. A jaunty oompah-oompah fox-trot rhythm carries the music
along, the tune is sunny and singable, and the words are just
right, not too fancy:
</P>
<P>
   ``Why am I kind of flying
</P>
<P>
   In a sky kind of blue?
</P>
<P>
   It's not 'cause my head's in the clouds, dear.
</P>
<P>
   It's just 'cause I'm thinking of you.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the chords are juiced with little ``off'' notes here and
there, and a sustained inner voice noodles around, slightly
blurring the clarity of the key. The harmonic richness is very
subtle. But even the most untrained ear will subliminally sense
that this supposed fox trot is kind of edgy.
</P>
<P>
   Harbison is trying to evoke the sound of earlier Dixieland, when
the rhythm section used a banjo and a tuba. Later, when these
instruments were replaced by the guitar and string bass, the music
became more genteel.
</P>
<P>
   Even when vernacular songs and dances are not explicitly evoked,
the music of ``Gatsby'' is charged with the energy and swing
rhythms of the '20s. In the opening scene, when Daisy is lounging
about her house with her friend Jordan, and Nick shows up, the
music is easygoing on the surface, with conversational vocal lines
and jazzy rhythmic riffs.
</P>
<P>
   But the chords are pungent, the rhythmic flow asymmetrical. The
music alerts you to the pretense of Daisy's cheerfulness. She knows
her husband is cheating. Jordan is protective of Daisy and guarded
about Nick, and the interchange between them is uneasy.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, this is a tragic, bitter story, and the opera
reaches for those emotions in extended passages that explode with
dissonant-saturated, atonal intensity. Musically they do not seem
incongruous, for the composer has prepared the listener's ear with
the buried intensity of the vernacular music.
</P>
<P>
   Harbison said he was ``going to enjoy taking people sometimes to
places harmonically which are as challenging as moments in `Moses
und Aron.''' You can understand why.
</P>
<P>
   Schoenbergian angst is not what most people would associate with
Harbison. He calls himself a ``chromatic tonalist,'' meaning a
composer who writes music essentially grounded to tonal centers but
harmonically free-roaming and wayward and, in his case, jolted now
and then with the sounds of the cutting-edge musical styles.
</P>
<P>
   Though Harbison had notable tenures as composer in residence
with the Los Angeles Philharmonic and the Pittsburgh Symphony, he
has lived most of his adult life in the Boston area, teaching at
the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. He said it does not
bother him that he had been dubbed a ``New England composer,''
which he defined as reserved, conscious of craft and comfortable
with religious themes.
</P>
<P>
   Though he may fit his own definition, Harbison, who won the 1987
Pulitzer Prize in music for a sacred cantata, ``The Flight Into
Egypt,'' likes to discombobulate listeners periodically by going
against his nature _ as when he wrote a piece called ``Three City
Blocks'' for wind ensemble, which was given its premiere in 1992 by
the U.S. Air Force Band at a big-band convention in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Some people told him they didn't know he could write ``such a
dirty piece, with all that junk in it,'' he said, which he took as
a splendid compliment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gatsby'' may not be dirty, but it is often gritty, squalling
with the earthy energy of '20s dance music and jazz. Harbison said
he knew that using vernacular music, even in his up-to-date
adaptations, was risky. The subtlety of his technique may not reach
the audience.
</P>
<P>
   But given the stylistic diversity of music today, an inevitable
reflection of the stylistic battles that have characterized the
20th century, it is important for composers to be true to their own
sensibilities. Harbison is dismayed, he said, when he encounters
young composers whose concert works bear no stylistic connection to
the music they listen to for fun or the music they loved when they
were growing up.
</P>
<P>
   The great opera composers had no such disjunction. Mozart loved
to dance, loved dance music of all kinds and loved a snappy
alehouse tune. All of those loves come through in his operas, no
matter how sophisticated the score. He enjoyed a good show and was
never happier than when working in the opera house.
</P>
<P>
   He and John Harbison would have a lot to talk about.
</P>
</TEXT>
