<HEADLINE>
POOR JUDGMENT, BAD BREAKS, BIG BLUNDERS 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has been a century of success for American business. General
Motors grew to be the world's largest car company, Coca-Cola became
ubiquitous around the globe, with McDonald's not far behind, and
Walt Disney's Mickey Mouse may be known to far more people than any
president ever has been. Microsoft, although not yet 25, is already
the world's most valuable enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   But there were still plenty of missteps over the past 100 years,
even by the most successful companies. Some failed to pursue new
opportunities and were left to stare jealously as upstarts
surpassed them. Sometimes changes looked good to experts, but
outraged customers. Company founders underestimated the value of
what they had created and sold out before the real wealth arrived.
</P>
<P>
   What follows, in chronological order, are 12 of the biggest
business blunders of the past 100 years. It would not be a stretch
to bet that similar mistakes will be made in the next century as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Carnegie Takes Bonds
</P>
<P>
   When Andrew Carnegie agreed to sell his Carnegie Steel in 1901
to the steel trust being assembled by J.P. Morgan _ the U.S. Steel
Corp. _ he was convinced that the shares being sold to investors in
the new company were ridiculously overvalued and sure to fall in
price. So Carnegie demanded, and got, his $250 million payment in 5
percent bonds, thus assuring him a more than ample income for the
rest of his life. But he was supplanted by John D. Rockefeller as
the nation's wealthiest person. Had he taken the stock instead, he
almost certainly would have maintained his status.
</P>
<P>
   Sears Sells Out
</P>
<P>
   Richard Warren Sears, one of two founders of Sears, Roebuck and
Co., took on Julius Rosenwald as a partner after Alvah C. Roebuck
left in 1895. But Sears and Rosenwald quarreled over how to run the
company. Among other things, Rosenwald insisted that Sears stop
selling something called a ``Heidelberg Belt,'' an electrified
device that was said to cure a variety of ailments, including
impotence, for only $12.
</P>
<P>
   After Rosenwald insisted on cutting expenditures in the face of
a recession, Sears quit in 1908. For five years, he held onto his
stock, but in 1913 he sold. As a result, his heirs _ Sears died
just one year later _ were left to watch the company's phenomenal
growth from the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Ward's Pulls Back
</P>
<P>
   As World War II neared its end in 1945, the conventional
economic forecast for the United States was gloomy. Perhaps all
those soon-to-be-unemployed soldiers would plunge the country back
into depression; certainly a recession would arrive as the
government drastically reduced its spending.
</P>
<P>
   Sewell Avery, the president of Montgomery Ward, the
Chicago-based retailer, believed the forecast and husbanded cash
for the inevitable downturn. The chain's crosstown rival, Sears,
meanwhile, bucked the conventional wisdom and borrowed money to
build in the expanding suburbs. Sears' bet proved right. World War
II had produced a lot of savings and pent-up demand, and the
doomsday forecast was wrong. Ward's would never recover from its
error.
</P>
<P>
   A Journal Drops Stocks
</P>
<P>
   Coming out of World War II, the two largest business newspapers
in the United States _ The Journal of Commerce and The Wall Street
Journal _ were neck-and-neck in circulation and influence. Then The
Journal of Commerce decided in 1951 to drop stock tables, which it
felt were of relatively little interest and costly to produce, and
to concentrate on narrow business areas. The Wall Street Journal
took off from there, aided in part by a growing public interest in
the stock market, and it now has a circulation of 1.75 million.
Today's Journal of Commerce circulation? About 17,000.
</P>
<P>
   Railroads' Narrow Track
</P>
<P>
   For the first half of the century, the railroads were the
undisputed masters of national transportation. But since they
thought of themselves as railroads rather than transportation
companies, they never tried to expand into either trucking or
airlines at a time when their capital could have given them the
edge. In mid-century, many of the rails went through bankruptcy
reorganization, and it was decades before they began to make good
money through intermodal service _ the shipping of goods by a
combination of rail and trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Perot's $60 Million Loss
</P>
<P>
   Few culture clashes in the world of business have been greater
than the one set up when Ross Perot, the Texas-based founder of
Electronic Data Systems, was induced in 1970 to come to the rescue
of Francis I. duPont &AMP; Co., a Wall Street firm with a great past
and a struggling present.
</P>
<P>
   Lured by the opportunity to save the company while building the
business of the EDS unit that provided record-keeping services for
brokerage firms, Perot yielded to the entreaties, which included
pressure from Nixon administration officials worried about the
effect a Wall Street bankruptcy would have on public confidence.
</P>
<P>
   What he saw appalled him. Perot could not believe how badly Wall
Street ran its operations; Wall Street executives were equally
appalled by the interloper they considered a hick from Texas. Perot
was left holding the bag when duPont's successor firm, duPont
Walston, collapsed in 1974. He lost at least $60 million in the
fiasco.
</P>
<P>
   A Bonded Failure
</P>
<P>
   John R. Bunting, the chief executive of the First Pennsylvania
Corp., the owner of Philadelphia's biggest _ and the nation's
oldest _ bank, put more than $1 billion of the bank's money into
Treasury bonds in 1976, and thus proved that you can go broke
lending to a borrower with perfect credit.
</P>
<P>
   Having suffered losses on real estate loans, Bunting turned to
Treasuries yielding 8 percent. But interest rates rose to
previously unthinkable levels, sending the value of the bonds down
and causing huge losses as the bank paid more interest to
depositors than it was earning on the bonds. Eventually, it had to
be bailed out by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation. The
bank survived, but its shareholders suffered. Eventually, it was
acquired by another bank.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Schlitz Is Penny Wise
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1970s, Schlitz was the nation's No. 2 beer company,
behind Anheuser-Busch. Trying to improve profits, the company
changed its brewing process to cut production time to four days
from 12 and cut costs with a variety of additives.
</P>
<P>
   When that did not scare off customers, it made one more change,
adding a new ingredient known as Chill-garde to prolong the beer's
shelf life. Unfortunately, that interacted with a foam stabilizer
the company had added earlier, making the beer look milky. And that
led to a huge recall in 1976 that destroyed the brand's image.
Schlitz became a minor player.
</P>
<P>
   Amax Spurns a Suitor
</P>
<P>
   At the height of the oil boom, Chevron looked around for
somewhere to spend its windfall profits and settled on Amax, a
metals company whose share price had risen on talk that all natural
resources would be in short supply. Amax fought off the 1981 bid,
calling it too low, and Chevron backed off. Shareholders who could
have enjoyed the gains from the sale instead watched Amax's share
price collapse as natural resource values plunged in the 1980s.
Eventually, Amax merged into Cyprus-Amax and spun off its
gold-mining operations to shareholders, who got far less than they
could have had in a marriage with Chevron.
</P>
<P>
   IBM FailS to Think
</P>
<P>
   When IBM entered the personal computer arena in 1981, it
imme set the standard for what had been a fragmented market.
That led to monopoly profits for the company that controlled the
standard _ but that was not IBM. It was Microsoft, the upstart that
developed and owned the computer's operating system. The failure of
IBM _ which was known for the THINK signs posted throughout its
plants _ to secure any ownership interest in Microsoft or its
operating system may have been the most costly mistake ever made by
a major American company.
</P>
<P>
   Recipe for Disaster
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola was the most popular soft drink in the world by a wide
margin in the mid 1980s when the company decided to conduct taste
tests. Those showed that most people liked a sweeter taste, one
more like that of Pepsi-Cola, the company's prime competitor. So in
1985 the company scratched the old formula and, with much fanfare,
introduced a new one. So confident was Roberto C. Goizueta, the
chairman of Coca-Cola, of the test results that he called the
decision ``one of the easiest we have ever made.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, most of Coke's fervently loyal customers did not agree.
Only three months later, the company yielded to consumer outrage
and brought back the old formula. The new one was supposed to stay
around, but it eventually vanished. Coke went on to prosper again,
but the New Coke humiliation remains vivid to those who endured it.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T Misdials
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's attempt to become a major player in the computer business
with its $7.4 billion takeover of NCR in 1991 wins the award as
worst big merger of the century. NCR faltered under AT&AMP;T's control
as expected synergies proved evanescent. Five years _ and billion
of dollars in losses _ after the takeover was completed, AT&AMP;T
washed its hands of NCR by spinning it off to its shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   But AT&AMP;T did not merit the dishonor without competition. Other
really bad deals include Xerox's 1969 purchase of Scientific Data
Systems (a $1 billion investment that ultimately proved worthless);
Mobil's 1974 takeover of Montgomery Ward (which lost money until
the company was finally sold to a leveraged buyout firm in 1988,
nine years before it filed for bankruptcy); Sony's 1989 acquisition
of Columbia Pictures (which Sony still owns, a few billion in
losses later), and Quaker Oats' 1994 purchase of Snapple for $1.7
billion (which the cereal company sold for $300 million in 1997).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
