<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Chronicle Publishing Company &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHY SANTAS ARE STRIKING OUT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   No fewer than four holiday Santas have been relieved of their
duties at a downtown San Francisco mall, spies tell Personals. One
Santa was late, one was drunk, one was stealing and one was mean.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, here's a mistletoe tip from the Stanford University
Medical Center: ``New Analysis Reveals Human Mouth Carries More
Germs Than Expected.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the center's press release, researchers using old
and new methods to scrape plaque from a mouth ``found evidence of
37 unique bacteria that microbiologists had never before recorded.
Some were closely related to bacteria that scientists are familiar
with, but others were very different.'' So, it's not only ``more
germs,'' it's yuckier germs.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Seasonal offering on the menu of a Powell Street coffee
shop: egg nog latte. Meanwhile, the alchemist  &UR; Mr. Mystic  &LR; is
trying to turn merriment into money by selling Mr. Mystic Y2K
Edible Confetti (``If chaos breaks out, keep it as a food
supply''), which looks something like Trix breakfast cereal. More
information at mrmystic.com, of course.
</P>
<P>
   And if you act now, you can ``Eat Your Way Through Y2K'' with
Golden West's newly published recipes for the millennium, which
utilize stored food. Mass Hysteria Macaroni and Tuna Salad, for
example, includes Thousand Island dressing, a can of diced mixed
vegetables, dried onion and cooked macaroni shells. (Oh, and  &UR; Ann
Byington  &LR; learned at a class at Ramekins in Sonoma that a heating
pad can be used to maintain the temperature of melted chocolate.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; - &UR; Tom Sweeney &LR; , doorman at the Sir Francis Drake, was stuck in
an elevator in a downtown Monterey hotel when an operator
instructed the passengers that help was on the way, ``and whatever
you do, don't go anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   - Rock 'n' rolling Spin magazine has named the Body Part of the
Year 1999: the Butt.
</P>
<P>
   - San Francisco's  &UR; Paula West  &LR; sang in Carnegie Hall as part of
the  &UR; Noel Coward  &LR; Centennial Celebration, sings with a big band in
``Bicentennial Man'' and opens at the Plush Room next month.
</P>
<P>
   - Driving behind a black pickup truck in Berkeley,  &UR; Ellen &LR; 
 &UR; Meyers &LR;  was left pondering the meaning of its bumper sticker: ``God
is my girlfriend.''
</P>
<P>
   - Transportation gazette: &UR; David Greenlee &LR;  says the Sporty's
Pilot Shop catalog is selling tiny pin-on wings that identify
wearers as members of the Mile High Club. And BART says the recent
reader sighting of cars on a rig in Iowa must have been mistaken;
on the other hand, says spokesman  &UR; Mike Healy &LR; , the cars could have
been there on ``the tail track for the BART-Reno extension.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEXT ITEM, PLEASE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Another in a series of occasional peeks backstage at the
Personals plant. A letter from a kindly source:
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday I wrote you about the young man who called over the
loudspeaker, `Where are the cards for the Jews?' Well, first of
all, it wasn't Nordstrom; it was Toys R Us. Secondly, it wasn't
Walnut Creek, it was Concord. Also, aside (from) the fact that I
misspelled Nordstrom, everything else is correct.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. A recent correction in the Augusta (Georgia) Chronicle: ``A
photo accompanying an `in the spotlight' item in Monday's editions
of the Augusta Chronicle incorrectly identified  &UR; Sean &LR; 
 &UR; Connery  &LR; as  &UR; Dennis Rodman &LR; . The Chronicle regrets the error.''
</P>
<P>
   P.P.S. And here's a journalist's trick: TV reporters who go on
movie junkets, where they each get five minutes to interview a
star, resort to writing their names on the bottom of their shoes
and then crossing their legs during the interview. This allows the
star to say such profound things as, ``I'm glad you asked me that,
Bob.'' According to the New York Post, though, that fun-loving  &UR; Mel
Gibson  &LR; `delights in calling the interviewer anything but what is
written on the shoe leather.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans have bought into the romantic Jeremy Irons-Kenneth
Branagh England. It's phony. It's fake. Merchant-Ivory? Bollocks.
Notting Hill, all those mannerisms and flawless turns of phrase,
people don't really talk like that in England. ... British films
are manufacturing fairy tales and Americans are going for it like
they are buying picture postcards.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Tim Roth &LR; , 38, to Personals spy  &UR; Baird Jones &LR; , at a premiere
party in New York for the movie ``The War Zone.''
</P>
