<HEADER>
A3417 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-OUTLOOK-HEALTH-NYT &LR;      12-19 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTLOOK-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH CARE CONSUMERS CAN EXPECT CHANGE, AND A SHOCK OR TWO
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Americans who have complaints about the health care system may
soon be in luck _ or maybe not. Many health care professionals
expect the medical system in the United States to be overhauled so
remarkably during the next two decades that many patients will not
be able to recognize it.
</P>
<P>
   While such a notion may excite some consumers _ who hasn't
fantasized about the death of health maintenance organizations? _
others will no doubt be riled by new procedures that actually
provide less medical care and coverage than before.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing that is sure to happen is a lot of change across
the whole health care industry,'' said Dr. David B. Skinner, the
chief executive of New York Presbyterian Hospital. ``A better
quality system has started, but it is going to take several decades
to develop.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumers should brace themselves for a few shocks. Many patient
advocates and Democratic representatives in Congress would like a
government-sponsored health care system, similar to many of those
in Europe. But some health providers _ notably the pharmaceutical
companies _ snarl at the mention of more government involvement,
given the likelihood of a federally mandated reduction in drug
prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The insurance of last resort is the government,'' said Joseph
Zammit-Lucia, the chief executive of Cambridge Pharma Consultancy
in New York, which advises drug companies. ``But you never know
what insurance you may be able to buy in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if health care in the United States remains in private
hands, change will be dramatic. One of the biggest changes during
the next 10 to 20 years is expected to be the increasing role of
the patient in choosing his or her treatment. Instead of relying
only on their doctors' advice, consumers will also use medical
information from the Internet and prescription-drug ad campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Currently, health care is professional-driven,'' Zammit-Lucia
said. ``But with the Internet and consumer ad campaigns, I will
know about as much about my illness as the doctor does. I'll use
him as a professional adviser, similar to how I use a financial
planner now.''
</P>
<P>
   Patients will also get their medications in new ways. Health
experts are confident that drugs will routinely be bought through
the Internet, including treatments for serious conditions.
Pharmacists, long the prime instructors of how medications should
be taken, will dole out more advice in cyberspace, especially as
consumers become brand loyal to their health care Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Medications are also likely to change. Scientists predict that
hospital-bound treatments like chemotherapy may eventually be
administered as pills that can be taken at home. Patients will also
have more choices about how they take their medications, such as
through injection, patch, nasal spray or inhaler.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's realistic to believe that cancer will become a chronic
illness,'' said Dr. Scot Remick, head of clinical trials at the
University Hospitals of Cleveland. ``We're not curing all cancers
yet, but patients will be able to live longer with a good quality
of life.''
</P>
<P>
   The increasingly enormous amount of medical knowledge will also
change patients' visits to their doctors. Using models of a
person's gene structure, scientists will soon be able to tell which
infants can be expected to develop certain illnesses _ including
some cancers and diabetes _ and what medicines have little risk of
side effects.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors say that breakthroughs in genomic technology will allow
consumers to know what diseases they are likely to get and what
measures to take to prevent them. Yet patient advocates worry that
the insurers may use genomic information to deny or limit coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a brave new world, it is frighteningly realistic to imagine
an insurance industry that knows more than it should about the
lifestyle and family history of every American,'' said Diane
Archer, president of the Medicare Rights Center, a consumer
advocacy group in New York. ``Through health profiling, an insurer
can refuse affordable coverage to everyone with a perceived health
risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Charles M. Cutler, chief medical officer of the American
Association of Health Plans, a trade group representing managed
care companies, said that insurers would use genetic information
not to deny coverage but to provide better care. He noted that some
illnesses can be diagnosed now during pregnancy, but insurers have
still provided coverage to these infants.
</P>
<P>
   That's hardly the last of a consumer's worries. During the next
20 years, Americans will have to deal with increasingly large and
powerful health care organizations. Almost all of them will demand
higher prices.
</P>
<P>
   The consolidation that has swept the drug industry _ with Pfizer
and American Home Products battling now to acquire Warner-Lambert,
and Zeneca Pharmaceuticals of Britain buying the Swedish drug giant
Astra last year _ will continue until there are a handful of
companies, each with 10 percent of the global market, double their
current share. Only five companies currently have more than a 4
percent share of the worldwide pharmaceutical market, according to
IMS Health, an industry consultant. Cambridge Pharma forecasts
that, as a result of more costly technology, drug prices will
increase to 30 percent of medical expenditures in the United States
during the next 20 years from 10 percent at present.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers are going to have to pay for routine drugs out of
their own pockets'' as insurers scramble to control costs,
predicted Zammit-Lucia, citing generic painkillers as an example.
``What will happen is that insurance will only pay for what is not
affordable.''
</P>
<P>
   By most accounts, HMOs will not live long into the next century,
but many health care experts are not sure what type of insurance
will take their place. Everyone agrees that traditional indemnity
plans are history, even though consumers are demanding an
unrestricted choice of doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with managed care is that it became so intrusive
in the relationship between patient and doctor,'' said Dr. Thomas
R. Reardon, president of the American Medical Association. ``The
HMOs were spending more money than they were saving. We have to
find a method to provide appropriate care. But that may not mean
all the care the patient wants.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing on which health care experts agree is that the
insurers of the next two decades will be substantially larger than
any of the entities that have preceded them. Several doctors
predicted that HMOs would eventually be replaced by large hospital
systems, with local clinics and hospices, that contract with
employers to provide medical insurance and treatment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
