<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-19 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3418 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-OUTLOOK-HOTELS-700&AMP;AD     12-19 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTLOOK-HOTELS-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR HOTELS, QUIET BELLS AND WHISTLES 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nine years after the Wright Brothers ushered in the era of
powered flight at Kitty Hawk, N.C., in 1903, Harold Donaldson
Eberlein, a prolific Philadelphia writer and futurist, published
predictions of the impact of air travel on American cities.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in American Homes and Gardens magazine in September
1912, Eberlein foresaw a proliferation of roof gardens atop large
hotels to provide a pleasing view from on high. (``What a pleasant
place over which to aviate must Babylon have been with its hanging
gardens!'' he wrote.)
</P>
<P>
   And since the hotel roof was destined to become as important as
the ground floor, he added, travelers could expect to find ``clerks
and bellboys posted on the top floor ready to attend to the
immediate wants of tourists who have just arrived by aeroplane.''
Aerial taxicabs ``will circle like vultures over the hotel,'' he
added, ``waiting for a doorman to signal one of them to alight and
pick up a departing guest.''
</P>
<P>
   Eberlein's failure to prove as prescient as Jules Verne does not
necessarily mean that the aerial garages and aerial taxis he
envisioned were off the wall. But it does underscore the warning by
John W. Reps, professor emeritus in the department of city and
regional planning at Cornell University, that the Eberlein article
``suggests the difficulty of predicting the impact of technological
innovations.'' (Reps put the article on the Internet, along with
two introductory paragraphs that included this warning.)
</P>
<P>
   Yet a number of technological and hotel companies are wrestling
with designing the hotel of the future and so far, at least, do not
seem to be straying very far afield. In fact, even in the era of
the Internet, which seemingly came from nowhere and has expanded
with the speed of light, most of the hotel innovations proposed for
the future are still largely incremental. The only eyebrow-raising
proposal _ that Hilton Hotels Corp. was planning to build a luxury
resort somewhere in space _ came in a September wire-service report
that was picked up widely in the press and on radio and television,
but it was quickly, forcefully denied.
</P>
<P>
   At the Conrad N. Hilton College of Hotel and Restaurant
Management at the University of Houston, faculty members and
students are less preoccupied with space hotels than with adequate
space and other comforts in the hotel of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two biggest concerns we're looking into improving are
guest security and comfort through technology,'' said Alan Stutts,
dean of the hotel and restaurant management college. ``We've
determined that if you can create an environment that's comfortable
and efficient, you can lengthen guests' stay by a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Achieving those goals primarily means eliminating or reducing
sleep distractions and stress, each of which is being studied in a
living lab _ the campus' 86-room University Hilton Hotel. Among
possible changes under review are:
</P>
<P>
   _ Alarm clocks that awaken guests by increasing the amount of
light in the room, rather than by a buzzer, bell or radio.
</P>
<P>
   _ Room-entry technology that replaces room keys or cards by
reading thumbprints or fingerprints.
</P>
<P>
   _ Beds with air mattresses that can be adjusted by a hand-held
compressor, or beds with springs that can be easily adjusted for
comfort.
</P>
<P>
   _ Treadmills and other exercise equipment in the privacy of
one's room.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reduction of irritating room noise by using the sound of
water, for which volume and tone can be adjusted to anything from a
trickle to a torrent.
</P>
<P>
   _ And, for guests in a windowless, or viewless, room of the
future, the option of choosing an ocean or mountain or other
``window'' view generated by a computer. ``You could create any
window you wDean Stutts said, ``including a winter landscape
or a rain forest.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A worldwide survey for Inter-Continental Hotels and Resorts, a
unit of  &UR; Bass &LR;  PLC, released last year did not turn up demands for
anything futuristic, only for more high-technology features in
rooms, hotels in safe neighborhoods, enhanced safety and security
features in hotels, more nonsmoking rooms and a wider choice of
in-hotel restaurants serving more healthful food.
</P>
<P>
   None of those should be hard to deliver, since each already
exists to some degree, although not all in the same hotel rooms and
not always in the United States. Dozens of upscale hotels
throughout the Asia Pacific Rim, for instance, are equipped with
many high-tech features, including systems that allow guests to
watch television and surf the Internet on the television
simultaneously, and to hook their laptops to high-speed direct
Internet access in their rooms without the need for a local
Internet service provider. So it is only a question of time until
those features are available in United States hotels _ especially
when many of the Asia Pacific Rim hotels, including Sheraton on the
Park, Sydney, as well as Inter-Continentals in Singapore, Taipei,
Taiwan, and Tokyo are allied with U.S. hotel companies.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months guests at many Choice Hotels have been able to
leave their laptops at home and still have access to the Internet,
e-mail, entertainment and the latest financial news.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not modular building designs are the future of hotel
construction, Holiday Inn Express has been experimenting with
modular designs that fit various sites and allow walls to be moved
within the building, depending on size and shape of the land.
</P>
<P>
   As for hotels in space, the September story may have been
premature for Hilton, but the topic has not gone unaddressed. The
World Tourism Organization, whose membership includes 138 nations
and territories, predicted in 1998 that low-orbit space trips might
be only a few years away and that space vacations would be
commonplace by 2020. If so, tomorrow's space vacationers presumably
will be no more inclined to spend their entire vacation in a space
vehicle than today's vacationers are willing to spend theirs
cramped up in a circling airplane, and so hotels will need to be
part of the big plan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
