<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-19 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3419 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-COX-RUSSIA-VOTE1220     12-19 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-RUSSIA-VOTE1220 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MODERATES GAIN IN RUSSIAN VOTE
 &HT;    Editors: Please update actual results when available as
warranted
 &HT;    By Charles W. Holmes
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW Voting across 11 time zones, Russians gave pro-reform
parties unexpectedly strong support in parliamentary elections
Sunday
</P>
<P>
   Moderate political forces appeared to garner roughly half votes,
marking a victory for the Kremlin and its widely popular Prime
Minister Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
   The newly formed Unity party, forged by the Kremlin only three
months ago and stocked with young, fresh-faced candidates, will
finish a strong second behind the Communists, the country's biggest
party, exit polls and early results showed.
</P>
<P>
   The race, widely viewed as a dress rehearsal for next year's
presidential campaign to replace Russian President Boris Yeltsin,
offered good news for Putin, 47, who has emerged as the uncontested
frontrunner.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Communists proved they remain the tenacious
opponents to reform by registering a higher proportion of vote than
the party earned in the last parliamentary balloting in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   At stake were all the seats in the 450-member Duma, the lower
house of parliament. The late fall elections were eclipsed by the
internally popular war against rebellious Chechnya and tainted by a
bitter, mudslinging campaign that pitted Kremlin loyalists against
their rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Exit Polls for the the NTV television network showed the
Communists still the largest party with 28 percent. But four
moderate and liberal parties between them claimed 54 percent of the
vote. Unity was running in second place with 24 percent of the
vote. An allied pro-reform party, the Union of Right Forces, ran
surprisingly strong with 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   With 7 percent of the actual vote counted, Unity led with 28.6
percent, followed by the Communist Party with 24.9 percent, about
the same as their 22.3 finish in 1995. Vladimir Zhirinovsky's
ultra-nationalist bloc had 8.2 percent. The Union of Right Forces
garnered 7.2 percent, followed by the centrist Fatherland-All
Russia with 6.5 percent and the social democrats of Yabloko with
5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 26 parties and some 2,300 candidates competed in the
Duma election. Half of the seats will be filled by the vote for
party lists, with groups getting more than 5 percent of votes
winning places. The other half will be filled through individual
races in electoral districts.
</P>
<P>
   Final results from the balloting are not expected until late
Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the results reflected increased sophistication
among voters, who distinguished between pro-reform political
parties and the unpopular Yeltsin, whose second term as president
expires next summer.
</P>
<P>
   The results also reflect an apparent desire among Russians to
see a continuation of democratic and economic reforms despite the
painful decade of transition since the Soviet Union was dissolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told the people: 'We are young guys, that we ourselves
committed a lot of mistakes. But we can and we want to pull the
country up from the dirt,''' Yevgenia Albaats, an independent
journalist and political analyst, said of the strong results for
the Union of Right Forces. Former Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko
and former Yeltsin advisor and reformer Boris Nemtsov founded the
party.
</P>
<P>
   Another new party, Fatherland-All Russia, appeared to be running
weaker than expected, with about 11 percent of the vote, according
to exit polling.
</P>
<P>
   The successful centrist bloc is led by former Prime Minister
Yevgeny Primakov and Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov, both prominent
opponents of the Yeltsin administration.
</P>
<P>
   Before Putin appeared on the political scene, Primakov, 70, was
the leading contender to replace Yeltsin, according to polls.
Luzhkov, also believed to have presidential aspirations, won
reelection Sunday as Moscow mayor with 70 percent of the vote, but
he consistently polls badly in nationwide surveys of potential
presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, a former KGB spy and Russia's security chief, was
handpicked from obscurity in August by Yeltsin to become prime
minister. Yeltsin also named Putin as his leading candidate to
succeed him as president. Putin has since soared in surveys,
leading the popular war against Islamic guerillas in the breakaway
republic of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Putin has become the most popular Russian politician since
Yeltsin's early zenith as the pro-democracy leader as the Soviet
Union collapsed in 1991. Yeltsin's approval ratings plummeted years
ago as reforms stalled and the country's economy collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   While Putin is not a member of Unity and his name was not on the
ballot Sunday, he endorsed the new party, which clearly benefited
from his allure. In the closing week of the campaign, Putin also
made positive comments about the Union of Right Forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're tired of old governments consisting of morons only
capable of reading from notes and relying on aides,'' said
Alexander Dezegilenko, 38, a marketing specialist from Moscow who
supports Putin and who voted for the Union of Right Forces. ``We
need new faces, more democratic minded.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia's Communist Party was expected to retain the largest bloc
of seats in the Duma; currently they hold 157 seats. By aligning
themselves with nationalists and others, the Communists have been
able to thwart Kremlin-backed market reforms before parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The Communists are virtually the only nationally organized party
in Russia's young democracy, having inherited the party structure
from the Soviet era.
</P>
<P>
   How the moderate and reform parties in the new Duma might align
themselves is uncertain. While they share common policy interests,
they also may have competing candidates vying for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia needs the kind of Duma which will get down to business,
make laws rather than politicize,'' said Yeltsin, 68, after he cast
his vote at a Moscow polling station.
</P>
<P>
   By escalating the conflict in Chechnya, Putin and the Kremlin
altered the character of the campaign, overshadowing their rivals'
criticism of Russia corruption-riddled system with the themes of
war and restoring national pride.
</P>
<P>
   Putin was the tough-talking leader directing the military
campaign, while Unity Party leader Sergei Shoigu, who is Minister
for Emergency Situations, was dispatched with Chechnya to oversee
handle the refugee crisis caused by the war.
</P>
<P>
   Between them, they have dominated news coverage in recent weeks
and muted criticism of the government. Meanwhile, media outlets
owned by tycoons who support the Kremlin gave favorable coverage to
Putin and Unity, while attacking Primakov and Luzhkov.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were only two parties - the party of traitors and the
party of patriots. Nothing else mattered,'' complained Valery
Siakin, a former Moscow mayor during the 1980s and a candidate for
Duma for the Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   Turnout exceeded 57 percent among the more than 100 million
registered voters, a fairly good showing in a country where many
people are disenchanted with post-Soviet democratic reforms and
widespread official corruption.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
