<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-19 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3420 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-OUTLOOK-RUSSIA-ART-NY     12-19 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTLOOK-RUSSIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD NEWS AND BAD NEWS ON THE ECONOMY OF RUSSIA
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: A graphic on the Russian economy is being sent to NYT
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By NEELA BANERJEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ After weathering a year of debt defaults, a currency
crash, an absentee president and governments that change with the
seasons, Russians have one piece of good news: The economy has not
collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   In the months after the August 1998 crash of the stock market
and the ruble, and the appointment of a government heavy with
ardent Communists, many analysts feared a return to fixed prices,
shortages of consumer goods and a ceaseless printing of rubles that
would have once more ignited hyperinflation. ``It was all lined up
for catastrophe, and it just didn't happen,'' said James Fenkner,
equities strategist for the Moscow brokerage firm Troika Dialog.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the three different prime ministers and their
respective cabinets this year have held to the tight monetary
policy of their predecessors and so have kept inflation under
control and the currency relatively stable. But the governments
that rotated through Moscow have also continued a tradition of
inaction, more unwilling than unable to overhaul onerous tax and
customs systems or to rein in corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Investors express some hope that next June's presidential
elections may bring gradual improvement. But few are confident
enough to invest here. ``People hope things will happen'' after the
elections, said Stephen O'Sullivan, co-director of research at the
United Financial Group. ``But if in the past Russia's problems
weren't appreciated, now it's only the problems that are
appreciated.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there have been periodic rallies, the Russian stock
market has failed to attract serious interest this year. Daily
volumes were less than $1 million at the start of the year, but
since the spring they have climbed to $15 million to $20 million,
largely on the strength of rising oil prices. That is still,
however, a fraction of the market volume before the August 1998
crash. And while the country's RTS stock index had more than
doubled by July, to 148.14, from the start of the year, it has
since slipped more than 30 points from that level and is far below
its October 1997 peak of 571.66.
</P>
<P>
   While still low compared with other emerging markets, foreign
direct investment picked up in 1999. Economists estimate that
Russia could attract $2.5 billion to $3 billion this year, up from
$2.2 billion last year. Several big foreign companies have gone
ahead with sizable projects here. Caterpillar, Gillette, Philip
Morris and BMW, for example, have built new factories.
</P>
<P>
   Their decision to expand rather than leave is driven in large
part by Russia's currency devaluation. When the ruble's value
plunged against the dollar after the August 1998 crisis,
dollar-denominated imports became too expensive for most Russians.
Some foreign companies concluded that the best way to thrive in
Russia was to begin manufacturing here. The devaluation revived
Russian factories, too, from macaroni plants to car parts makers,
as they rushed to fill the gap left by the dearth of imports.
Domestic production is estimated to be up 10.5 percent in 1999 over
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it would be hard to rekindle the optimism investors had
for Russia through most of the decade. This year, they have come to
understand how far the government and Russian business are from the
notions of fair play and rule of law needed for an attractive,
prosperous market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Discussions about the investment climate in Russia have no
meaning,'' Vadim Arsenyev, a columnist, wrote recently in the
business daily Kommersant. ``The investment climate in Russia isn't
good or bad because there isn't one. That's because we're still
very far from democracy, a market and respect for shareholder
rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The government, for example, defaulted on $40 billion of
domestic debt last year and is essentially in default now on most
of its foreign debt, except for eurobonds. The government has asked
the London Club of commercial creditors to write off 40 percent of
the more than $30 billion it owes.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Russia's largest banks have gone bankrupt, defaulting on
loans to Western creditors and confiscating the deposits of their
domestic clients. ``Russians clearly can't handle debt,'' Fenkner
said. ``The attitude here is, `Take the money and run.'''
</P>
<P>
   Foreign investors have been alarmed by a series of bankruptcy
and corporate governance disputes and the government's apparent
inability to resolve them. BP Amoco has essentially lost its
half-billion-dollar investment in the oil concern Sidanko, whose
assets have been peeled away in bankruptcy procedures that many
analysts suggest were rigged to help a rival Russian oil company.
</P>
<P>
   The country's second-biggest oil company, Yukos, has proceeded
with share swaps that vastly dilute the value of shares in its
subsidiaries. A court in St. Petersburg repealed the privatization
of the Lomonosov porcelain factory on a technicality, thereby
annulling the 51 percent stake held in it by executives of Kohlberg
Kravis Roberts &AMP; Co. and the U.S.-Russian Investment Fund.
Together, those developments led to the resignation of Dmitri V.
Vasiliev, chairman of the Federal Securities Commission, who was
regarded by foreigners as the lone government official backing
protection of shareholders' rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The signal this sends is that foreign investment isn't safe in
Russia,'' O'Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   Scandal has further tarred Russia's already questionable
reputation. In the spring, it was disclosed that Russia's Central
Bank invested money through murky offshore companies with close
ties to Russian business and as such, hid reserves from the
International Monetary Fund. Then in August, the United States said
it was investigating possible Russian money laundering through the
Bank of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the parliamentary elections held Sunday and the June
presidential vote have kindled some optimism among investors. ``You
see now the rise of a centrist political class that will do well in
the parliamentary race and win presidential elections,'' said Jeff
Costello, a director at the investment bank Brunswick Warburg.
``That's good because it means that the legislature and the
president, both broadly pro-market, will be able to work together,
as opposed to now.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expect some money to flow in soon after the
presidential vote, but unlike in 1996, vast sums are not expected.
Moreover, many investors will look for signs of progress on such
issues as tax reform and corporate governance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The euphoria's not there,'' Fenkner said. ``The question is
what type of market and democracy will Russia have, and that's much
harder to see.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
