<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-19 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3425 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-OUTLOOK-SCAMS-2TAKES-     12-19 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTLOOK-SCAMS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OF CROOKS AND CONS, SCANDALS AND SCHEMES
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DIANA B. HENRIQUES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the mid-1980s, a Swedish sociologist named Malin Akerstrom,
in her book ``Crooks and Squares,'' examined the remarkable
similarities between the personality traits of career criminals and
those of successful entrepreneurs. Her findings prompted another
prominent scholar to reflect that such criminals ``have learned the
lessons of capitalism too well.''
</P>
<P>
   The past century is certainly rich in scandals that bear out
that conclusion. Indeed, some of the century's greatest scoundrels
_ Charles Ponzi, Ivar Krueger, Robert Vesco _ were originally
assumed by their victims to be brilliant capitalists.
</P>
<P>
   A few of the century's scandals led to social reforms, while
others simply revealed new fault lines in the economic landscape.
Some involved colorful characters worthy of a story by Damon Runyon
or Tom Wolfe, and others were dull, faceless tales of stupidly bad
behavior. But taken together, they offer the dot-com generation a
timely reminder of what can go wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Following are some of the most significant scandals of the
century:
</P>
<P>
   A Smell From the Jungle
</P>
<P>
   It is a rare novelist who can claim to have almost
single-handedly altered business history. One writer with a valid
claim to that distinction is Upton Sinclair, who based his 1906
novel ``The Jungle'' on his investigations into unsanitary
conditions in the meat-packing industry. The disgusting disclosures
prodded Congress to adopt laws requiring federal inspection of
meat-packing houses, and led _ despite intense business opposition
_ to a broader government role in ensuring the safety of consumer
goods.
</P>
<P>
   The Original Ponzi Scheme
</P>
<P>
   In 1919, a dapper Italian immigrant named Charles Ponzi
established the Old Colony Foreign Exchange Company, with offices
in Boston and New York. He promised investors a suspiciously high
return, 50 percent or more, on foreign postal coupons, which he
claimed could be purchased abroad at a discount and resold in
America at a premium. Prosecutors soon found he simply used the
money taken in from latecomers to pay the promised dividends to
earlier investors. For decades, con artists had called this
technique the ``Peter-to-Paul'' swindle; from Ponzi's time on, it
would be known as a ``Ponzi scheme.''
</P>
<P>
   The Swedish Match King
</P>
<P>
   Some of the smartest investment bankers in America were taken in
by the elegant Ivar Krueger, a Swedish entrepreneur whose supposed
wealth was fed by a monopoly on the kitchen-match business in
various European countries. In fact, he was running an elaborate
fraud involving dubious accounting and forged assets. Facing
exposure at last, Krueger shot himself in his Paris apartment in
March 1932, and his empire collapsed on his creditors and
investors. It was one of the first great international swindles of
the century.
</P>
<P>
   How the Mighty Fall
</P>
<P>
   Few business leaders commanded more respect in 1930 than Richard
Whitney, president of the New York Stock Exchange and brother of a
partner in the House of Morgan. By 1935, he embodied Wall Street's
implacable resistance to the New Deal's market regulations. But in
March 1938, he pleaded guilty to charges that he had stolen money,
both from his own customers and from a stock exchange fund set up
to benefit the widows and orphans of members. As he served his time
in a federal prison in Ossining, N.Y., Wall Street's resistance to
the reform efforts of the Securities and Exchange Commission began
to disintegrate.
</P>
<P>
   A Big Price-Fixing Scandal
</P>
<P>
   In early 1960, a dozen manufacturers, including General Electric
and Westinghouse, were indicted on federal charges that they had
conspired for years to fix prices and rig government bidding for
several types of electrical equipment. The elaborate conspiracy,
which one writer said lacked only sinister music to qualify as a
full-fledged spy movie, cost the government and other industrial
customers millions of dollars. The charges and subsequent guilty
pleas shocked American consumers and led the courts to impose some
of the stiffest antitrust penalties that American business had
faced up until that day.
</P>
<P>
   The Cornfeld Connection
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1950s, a gifted American salesman named Bernie
Cornfeld built a foreign mutual fund empire known as Investors
Overseas Services, based outside Geneva and held together by
dubious sales practices throughout the world and the questionable
use of fund assets.
</P>
<P>
   When IOS began to falter in 1970, its board dismissed Cornfeld
and brought in an entrepreneur, Robert Vesco, perhaps the only man
who could make Cornfeld seem sober and prudent. Accused by
prosecutors of completing the looting of the company, Vesco fled in
1972 to various Caribbean havens, but was later jailed in Cuba on
unrelated fraud charges. Although the crimes occurred abroad, the
twin scandals smudged the reputation of the American mutual fund
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Programmed for Crime
</P>
<P>
   The computer was already starting to reshape American business
in the second half of the century; with the Equity Funding scandal,
it began to reshape American swindles. This once high-flying mutual
fund and insurance conglomerate used phony computer records to make
it appear that business was booming. In fact, the company was a
fraud that collapsed in April 1973 after a controversial analyst
named Raymond L. Dirks learned of the scheme and alerted his
clients to it. Regulators accused Dirks of trading on inside
information, but the U.S. Supreme Court exonerated him on the
ground that he had not been seeking personal profit.
</P>
<P>
   A Bust in the Oil Patch
</P>
<P>
   After the 1973 Arab oil embargo, few Americans could imagine
that energy prices would ever tumble. So nobody raised an eyebrow
when, in early 1976, some new high-living managers began to
transform the tiny suburban Penn Square Bank in Oklahoma City into
an aggressive oil and gas lender. Behind a boom-town facade, they
routinely made new inflated loans to bail out earlier inflated
loans _ a Ponzi-like shuffle that ended with the bank's collapse in
July 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Two major banks, the Continental Illinois National Bank and
Trust Company and Seattle First National Bank, had purchased some
of the bank's dubious loans and were nearly destroyed as a result.
Penn Square depositors whose accounts exceeded federal insurance
limits lost millions, shaking public confidence in federal banking
oversight.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   `The Greed Decade' on Trial
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, they still call it ``Boesky Day'' _ Nov. 14,
1986, when federal prosecutors disclosed that Ivan F. Boesky, a
trader who had speculated handsomely on the takeover deals of the
decade, would plead guilty to insider-trading violations and
testify about the misdeeds of others. The most famous defendant he
named was Michael R. Milken, whose transformation of the brokerage
firm Drexel Burnham Lambert into a bottomless war chest for
corporate raiders had ignited a national debate over junk bonds and
hostile takeovers. In 1990, with Drexel itself in bankruptcy,
Milken pleaded guilty to a handful of securities law violations,
for which he served two years in prison and paid a record fine of
$1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The Fall of Lincoln Savings
</P>
<P>
   It cost American taxpayers $3.4 billion to bail out Lincoln
Savings and Loan in 1989. Lincoln, which was run by Charles H.
Keating Jr., was one of hundreds of savings institutions to fail in
the late 1980s as misguided federal legislation, inadequate
regulatory supervision and old-fashioned fraud and greed combined
to undermine an entire industry. Keating, who came to symbolize
what Americans ruefully called the ``S.&AMP;L. crisis,'' pleaded guilty
in April _ after years of legal wrangling _ to four counts of fraud
in connection with Lincoln's collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing Down Barings
</P>
<P>
   It seemed impossible that one young corrupt trader, Nicholas W.
Leeson, could single-handedly destroy Barings Bank, the oldest
investment bank in Britain. But in 1995 that is what happened.
While working for the bank as an options trader in Singapore,
Leeson embarked on a secret trading spree that left the bank facing
fatal losses of roughly $1.3 billion. Leeson spent more than three
years in a Singapore prison before being released in July, at age
32, suffering from colon cancer. His crime awakened older bankers
and regulators to the risks posed by the esoteric financial
products that were traded by their young computer-savvy employees _
but that knowledge came too late to save the 233-year-old British
bank, which was taken over by a Dutch financial group.
</P>
<P>
   A Nasdaq Censure
</P>
<P>
   It began quietly, with an academic study in 1994 that questioned
why traders on the Nasdaq market always seemed to sell every share
of stock for at least 25 cents more than they had paid for it. Why
not 12.5 cents? Guided by the study, class-action lawyers promptly
sued the nation's top brokerage firms, accusing them of illegally
conspiring to fix the prices of Nasdaq stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits produced a historic $1 billion settlement and led
regulators to censure Nasdaq's parent, the National Association of
Securities Dealers, in 1996 for inadequately regulating the
marketplace. As a result, Nasdaq prices became fairer and more
visible to public investors _ but Nasdaq itself is still scrambling
to adjust to the leaner profits and tougher competition that
followed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-19-99 1750EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
