<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-19 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3427 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-OUTLOOK-COMMODITIES-N     12-19 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTLOOK-COMMODITIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMODITIES PRICES HAVE FIRST POSITIVE YEAR SINCE 1995 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the decade of the '90s was the greatest ever for stock
prices, it was one of the poorer for commodity prices. But as the
decade ends, there are signs of life in commodities.
</P>
<P>
   The Commodity Research Bureau/Bridge index of 17 commodities is
on its way to showing a gain of around 7 percent for 1999. That may
sound less than impressive to investors used to significantly
heftier increases in the stock market _ and it will still mean the
index ends the decade below where it began _ but it would be the
first positive year for the futures index since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The rise reflects expectations that world economic growth will
pick up next year as Asia and Latin America rebound from the global
financial crisis that began in July 1997, Japan bounces back from a
decade in the doldrums, and Europe's pause ends. Already, in
addition to crude oil and gasoline, the year's big gainers include
pork bellies, lumber, copper, cattle and platinum. Among the losers
are cocoa, soybeans, wheat, cotton and gold.
</P>
<P>
   But since much of the 1999 rally was powered by rising crude oil
prices after major oil exporting nations cut their production, some
analysts expect the upward pressure on commodity prices to slow or
give out next year, even as world economies grow. If oil prices
rise again, the increase will be much less than this year, analysts
argue. And some expect oil prices to be lower than they are now by
the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Commodity prices, in general, do not appear to be rising,''
William E. Byers, the director of futures research at Bear, Stearns
&AMP; Co., noted.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the decline in commodity prices led by oil,
helped keep consumer prices in check. But this year the surge in
oil was largely responsible for pushing the Consumer Price Index up
2.6 percent in the 12 months through November. In 2000, however,
any effect is expected to be minimal.
</P>
<P>
   Even if oil prices finish next year at $30 a barrel, a 20
percent increase, that would be far below the 121.9 increase so far
in 1999, to $26.74 a barrel. And if the relationship between oil
price increases and retail gasoline price rises remains constant,
that would mean pump prices would rise about 6 percent next year
compared with the 1999 jump of 36.1 percent. The resulting impact
on the Consumer Price Index would be much smaller.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, modestly rising commodity prices would not be
expected to have a significant impact on Federal Reserve policy,
particularly if the increase is largely attributable to oil. Wages,
compensation and the unemployment rate will have much more
influence as the central bank makes interest rate decisions. This
is because Federal Reserve policy makers can be expected to focus
on the core consumer inflation rate, which excludes food and
energy.
</P>
<P>
   A convenient way to look at the future for commodities is to
divide them into three groups: crude oil, industrial commodities
that are critical to production and construction, and agricultural
commodities.
</P>
<P>
   Crude oil is the key. It has been the main contributor to the
rise in major commodity indexes this year as the price of a barrel
has jumped from $12.05 to a peak of $27.07 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, many analysts had suggested that the surge was
ending, with some experts predicting that the price would fall by
the end of next year to about $20 a barrel. If that were the case,
then there would be downward pressure on broad commodity indexes at
the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
   But now some analysts, including Michael Rothman, senior energy
analyst at Merrill Lynch, expect crude oil prices to move closer to
$30 a barrel this winter. They cite declining crude oil
inventories; the apparent willingness of major oil-exporting
countries to extend their production cuts beyond the one-year
agreement that ends in March, and a new tolerance for higher prices
among producers.
</P>
<P>
   Rothman is now forecasting that the price of oil will average as
much as $22 a barrel next year, which is about $3.00 above this
year's average of $19.05. But by the end of the year he still
predicts the price will have declined below current levels, which
means any impact on consumer prices would be temporary.
</P>
<P>
   Industrial commodities, which include copper, steel, zinc, tin,
aluminum, plywood and rubber, have also been rising this year. But
their increases are much more modest than the jump in crude oil,
which is also an industrial commodity. The cash copper price is up
22.7 percent, to 84 cents a pound; nickel is up 80.9 percent, to
$8,017 a metric ton, steel scrap is up 76.6 percent, to $124.50 a
ton, and rubber is up 2.7 percent, to 38.50 cents a pound. The
Journal of Commerce index of 17 industrial commodities, including
crude oil, is up 5.2 percent. Any inflationary pressure would be
much less than from oil because these commodities are such a small
portion of the factors that determine consumer prices. Still, there
are signs that the recent increases are now coming through in the
producer price of many goods before they reach the consumer level.
</P>
<P>
   While one can see supply and demand affecting both oil and
industrial commodity prices, agricultural prices are basically
hostage to supply, Byers of Bear, Stearns said. And that means many
of these commodities run through up-and-down cycles that have more
to do with the weather than anything else. In addition, producers
often force major swings in prices, which is what happened among
hog farmers in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1997, a hog farmer could get $46 for every 100
pounds of meat. But a year later, an oversupply of pigs generated
by rising demand for pork and a bumper supply sent prices down to
levels not seen since 1971: 100 pounds of hog was going for $17.
</P>
<P>
   But the cutback in production that followed, with some farmers
shooting their hogs in the pen rather than taking them to market,
has pushed the price back up. A hundred pounds of hog now goes for
around $36.50. Still, food price increases have been slowing in
recent years, rising 2.8 percent in 1995, 3.3 percent in 1996, 2.6
percent in 1997 and 2.2 percent in 1998. For the last 12 months
through November food prices are up 1.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Commodity prices, in other words, appear to remain under
control, notwithstanding the 1999 surge in oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-19-99 1755EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
