<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, Dec. 20, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Arctic air will continue to pour southward across the Middle
West on Monday in the wake of a sharp cold front stretching from
the Great Lakes to the western Gulf Coast states. Patches of snow
or ice are possible as far south as northwest Louisiana and
northeast Texas, although broken areas of chilly rain will be
interspersed across the region.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, an area of low pressure will develop along the
southern end of the cold front southeast of Brownsville, Texas,
setting the stage for precipitation to intensity later Monday
across northeast Texas, Louisiana and southwest Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   Rain will become heavy at times, particularly along the
Louisiana seaboard, where moist Gulf air is rapidly lifted by a
jet-stream disturbance trailing the cold front. Rainfalls in excess
of 2 inches are possible by Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Bands of moderate to locally heavy snow showers will stream off
the southern coast of Lake Superior and the eastern coast of Lake
Michigan as arctic air is moistened in transit over relatively
tepid waters. Increasing winds and visibility lowering toward
one-quarter of a mile could produce near-blizzard conditions across
Michigan's upper peninsula, particularly the Keweenaw Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds will thicken over the northern Middle Atlantic States as
milder air arriving from the southwest is forced to rise over
unyielding chilly air bolstered by a surface high-pressure system
over Maine. Some drizzle or freezing drizzle is possible in the
central and northern Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Daylong Rain
</P>
<P>
   Winter is Florida's dry season, but steady rains on Saturday
washed away daily rainfall records at Melbourne and Orlando, where
1.68 and 1.26 inches were measured, respectively. Rain was
triggered by a disturbance in the subtropical jet stream. This
channel of fast-flowing air near 40,000 feet originates over low
latitudes and is thus a conveyor of moisture. It was the last of
the major weather features to be discovered. Indeed, during World
War II, American aircraft flying toward Japan were sometimes
brought to a standstill by winds as fast as 200 mph in the core of
the subtropical jet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
