<HEADLINE>
AN OVERSTRETCHED MARKET FACES ELECTION-YEAR WILD-CARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The upward march of the stock market indexes has
become so inexorable in recent years that most strategists no
longer weigh whether the market will rise next year. Instead, they
speculate on just how much higher it will go.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily, this might be cause for alarm since consensus views
on stock prices have, in the past, been a harbinger of a major move
in the opposite direction. But, with the Dow Jones industrial
average up more than 22 percent so far this year and the Nasdaq
index up a blistering 71 percent, these are no ordinary stock
market times. Indeed, just as countless investors have fared quite
well disregarding traditional measures of valuing a stock based on
earnings or cash flow, the fact that many bears seem to have left
may not signal anything meaningful either.
</P>
<P>
   What market strategists are discussing now is the array of
concerns that the stock indexes will shrug off in 2000 as they make
their northward climb. The bears may have been burned as the Nasdaq
sprinted ahead on the strength of hot technology stocks, but the
famed wall of worry still stands.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, there are the wild cards, events strategists point to
as possibly upsetting the market. But while some believe that
stocks may undergo some turmoil in the first half of the year,
maybe even a decline of 10 percent, most strategists are remarkably
upbeat about where the major indexes will be at the end of the new
century's first year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conditions that lead to significant bear markets are
continually accelerating inflation and interest rates, pressure on
profit margins and possibly a profit recession,'' said Christine A.
Callies, chief U.S. market strategist at Credit Suisse First
Boston. ``And we think the odds are very low of that until sometime
in 2002 at the earliest. Really, all we need to start a new bull
market that continues for many months is lower interest rates. But
we don't see that either, so we think the market is going to
churn.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Callies predicts the agitation will be more up than down,
however, because she expects both the economy and corporate profits
to be strong in 2000. And as profit momentum rotates through
different areas of the market, she expects that a broader group of
stocks may respond positively.
</P>
<P>
   Another point of agreement among analysts is that next year,
even more than the last, all investors' eyes will be on the Federal
Reserve Board and its chairman, Alan Greenspan. That is because the
Fed has been in a rate-raising mood lately, and investors will be
on the lookout for any marked change in this stance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably going to be the most difficult year for the
Federal Reserve, which will determine the course of the market,''
said Alan W. Kral, vice president at Trevor Stewart Burton &AMP;
Jacobsen, a money management firm in New York. ``We've had a
rip-roaring strong equity market built on the back of one of the
strongest real economic moves in decades, but there are a number of
warning signs out there that, if the Fed chooses to address, could
result in some problems.''
</P>
<P>
   If, for example, the economy comes in as hot in the first
quarter as it has in recent months, the Fed might raise rates again
in February, and more drastically, to try to cool things down.
Similarly, if any of the closely watched economic data revives
inflation fears, rates could ratchet up even without a move by the
central bank.
</P>
<P>
   Making this coming year even trickier for the Fed is the fact
that any move it feels compelled to make will be politically
charged since it is an election year. Moreover, Greenspan's term as
chairman will be up this summer, so if he wants to be renominated,
he must please his boss as well as do the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   Promises by leading presidential candidates in the months ahead
of the election could also disturb the market. James E. Moltz, vice
chairman of International Strategy and Investment, an investment
research firm in New York, said: ``There are battle lines being
drawn on the fiscal front which are very important because we have
an economy that is admittedly stretched. If we get into a situation
where candidates promise significant expenditures or tax cuts, you
run the risk of aggravating inflation not in the year 2000 but
further ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   James Paulsen, chief investment officer at Wells Capital
Management in Minneapolis, unlike most strategists, predicts that
the economy will slow in 2000 because of the Fed's recent
tightening. As a result, he forecasts that interest rates will fall
in mid-year and that the market will respond with gains as it did
in 1995. That year, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index had a
total return of 37.58 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're looking at those returns, but the
character will be similar,'' he said. ``Inflation fears will
dissipate, and the economy will slow faster than people expect.
Bond yields will drop to around 5 percent, and stocks will go to
higher highs on lower rates.'' Paulsen says both stocks and bonds
will have returns of 10 to 15 percent in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But do not count on value stocks rebounding, Paulsen advised. If
the economy decelerates and growth becomes harder to find, there
will be an even bigger move away from value stocks, cyclical
companies and small-capitalization concerns. Investors will focus
instead on the same favored growth stocks, expanding perhaps to
include electric utilities, which will benefit from lower interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
   A common question is what 2000 will bring for investors in
technology stocks. With the technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index
up 71 percent so far this year, a repeat performance seems
unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   L. Keith Mullins, head of emerging growth research at Salomon
Smith Barney, forecasts a painful shakeout in some of the smaller
technology stocks in the first quarter of the year. And, unlike the
sharp decline in Internet stocks last spring, which did not spread
to other market sectors, the coming drop, he said, will hurt the
major market indexes. When biotechnology stocks tanked in 1992, he
pointed out, they dragged unrelated issues down, too, although not
so much as the highfliers.
</P>
<P>
   Though the losses will hurt, he said, the shakeout will
ultimately be healthy for the overall market, which will rebound.
``A lot of people own these stocks but have no idea what they
own,'' Mullins said. The shakeout would help because it would
probably broaden the types of stocks participating in the upswing
that he expects would follow.
</P>
<P>
   There will be other headlines in the new year that could have
significant impact, said Stefan D. Abrams, chief investment
officer, asset allocation, at the Trust Co. of the West. ``We will
see an enormous flood of takeovers in financial services, friendly
and hostile,'' he said. ``Wireless will emerge as an important,
even dominant, force in data transmission, and drug companies will
be a whipping boy for politicians in an election year, and the
stocks will reflect it.''
</P>
<P>
   Moltz of International Strategy summed up the investment scene
this way: ``Someone who is a traditionalist has got to approach the
market, with these stretched valuations, with a certain amount of
care. But the classic things that would cripple a market _ the Fed
overdoing it or the economy really rolling over _ to date are not
there. So you approach it with a measure of caution but recognize
that the life in the existing trends is still pretty healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
