<SLUG> BC-OUTLOOK-SHOPPING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE REAL RETAIL REVOLUTION: IT'S WAL-MART, NOT THE NET 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The trend that is driving so much change in retailing at the
dawn of the new century is as obvious to spot as a Mack truck
bearing down on your rear bumper.
</P>
<P>
   It is, of course, the Internet. If you believe the hype, the
Internet _ which will generate an estimated $20 billion in United
States sales this year and is expected to grow by 200 percent to
300 percent a year _ promises nothing short of a revolution that
will change how Americans shop forever.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, it is not the biggest challenge on the retail highway.
</P>
<P>
   The changes remaking retailing come not only in the medium
shoppers use to make their purchases, but in what they expect their
dollars to buy _ which is a lot more than they did even five years
ago. In the end, it is less the Internet that is transforming
traditional retailing as this century closes, than one giant
discounter: Wal-Mart Stores.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart, the world's largest retailer _ famous for wringing
every excess penny out of product cost _ is expected to report
nearly $143 billion in domestic revenue for fiscal 1999, which will
end Jan. 31. That is roughly 7 percent of the U.S. retail market,
according to Jeffrey Feiner, an analyst at Lehman Brothers, and
seven times all Internet sales combined for this year, as estimated
by Forrester Research, the Boston digital consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Online retail sales will reach $184 billion in 2004, Forrester
predicts, edging closer but still not catching Wal-Mart, which by
that year should have $243 billion in revenue domestically,
according to Feiner. He even predicts that Wal-Mart, which sells
everything from fresh lettuce to power tools, will produce $1
trillion in revenue worldwide by 2015.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart is, of course, emblematic of a new kind of retailer.
Not long ago, consumers on a tight budget expected to sacrifice
quality for cost, generally finding mediocre goods in drab environs
at the discount chains. But then the discounters remade themselves
by offering fashion, brands and great merchandising, all at prices
lower than those that rivals, either department stores or
independents, could match.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the real revolution: Kmart offers Martha Stewart
200-thread-count sheets in colors like pewter and eggshell; Target,
a unit of Dayton Hudson, has au courant fashion like embroidered
jeans and little beaded black purses, and Ikea will customize maple
kitchen cabinets.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers of all income levels have quickly become addicted to
the new equation of quality and value, and they are handing over
market share to chains that provide both _ a trend that is likely
to continue. Not only are stock analysts predicting that Wal-Mart
will experience staggering growth, but chains like Target, Home
Depot, Costco and Kohl's are all expected to expand rapidly, eating
up ever-larger chunks of the $2 trillion Americans spend on retail
annually.
</P>
<P>
   And it is not just that today's winning merchants will continue
to dominate the land masses; it is expected they will use their
formidable buying power and brand names to conquer cyberspace as
well. Only a year ago, the e-retailers that ran nothing but virtual
stores _ like Amazon and Etoys _ were crowing about how their
land-based cousins were dinosaurs bound for extinction. Since then,
mass merchants _ discounters and specialty stores like Gap Inc. _
have shown the draw of a household name in cyberspace and in some
cases catapulted in front of their virtual brethren in Web sales.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts who once predicted that all the online shoppers would
flock to the first Web entry into any category of merchandise, like
books, now accept that a retailer's tortoise-like thoroughness in
the race into cyberspace is not necessarily a bad thing if the
company has the financing to outlast early rivals. Wal-Mart, for
instance, will not even have introduced its new Web site by this
Christmas, but no one is counting it out as an e-retailer in the
year 2010.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wal-Mart will challenge Amazon for worldwide e-retailing
dominance by the year 2005,'' Burt Flickinger, managing director of
Reach Marketing, in Westport, Conn., predicted. ``Ultimately, the
land-based retailers of size will be able to inflict real pain on
their Internet competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that some Web-born businesses will not
blossom and that the Internet, no matter who is succeeding there,
will not have its effects on bricks-and-mortar retailers. It will
force them to be better, to entertain, to attract business or to
offer a point of view.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stores are going to have to be consumers' editors; they have
to make big statements on `this is the fashion,''' Richard Baum, an
analyst at CS First Boston, said. ``If you go into the store, you
will have to know what they think you should be wearing.'' Already,
retailers like American Eagle Outfitters and Ann Taylor excel in
such opinionated retail.
</P>
<P>
   Another trend that will intensify as the Internet grows stronger
is shopping as family entertainment. Malls across America are
putting in entertainment features like Hard Rock Cafes and
20-screen cinemas as fast as they can. But that is just the start.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will use shopping as an escape from the technology that
will consume their lives,'' said Laurence C. Siegel, chairman and
chief executive of the Mills Corp., a Virginia-based mall developer
that is expanding rapidly. Siegel is placing big bets on gated
attractions to rival the cultural and entertainment venues of the
great cities _ Mills, for instance, is exploring partnerships that
would let it build concert halls and museums. He sees a future of
malls that offer Broadway shows and Have community gardens on their
rooftops.
</P>
<P>
   While those are pretty grand visions, Siegel has one even more
radical. ``Everyone in my business perceives the Internet as a
rival,'' he said. ``In five years, the two will be married. The
experience of being on the Internet is going to land in the
shopping center.'' He goes on to predict a world of Internet
retailers that have actual stores on the concourse that sell actual
goods (very pre-Internet). He even forecast the currently
unimaginable: ``EBay and Amazon are going to have presences in the
mall.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
