<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-19 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3439 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-GATSBY-OPERA-LYRICIST     12-19 1263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GATSBY-OPERA-LYRICIST-ART-470&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAB YOUR BABY AND DANCE BY THE PALE MOONLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also GATSBY-OPERA-1920S) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By RALPH BLUMENTHAL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Murray Horwitz has been a clown and worked for the
New York state Assembly (not at the same time). He has written
newscasts for WINS radio, acted on ``Kojak,'' staged performances
at the White House, toured as Sholom Aleichem, directed the opera
program at the National Endowment for the Arts, brought ``Ain't
Misbehavin''' to Broadway, and for the last 10 years run cultural
programming for National Public Radio.
</P>
<P>
   So when the composer John Harbison was looking for an
enterprising lyricist to give an authentic 1920s flavor to pop
songs in his new opera, ``The Great Gatsby,'' which receives its
world premiere at the Metropolitan Opera on Monday night, he turned
to the eclectic Horwitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was clearly not something I was cut out to do,'' said
Harbison, who otherwise wrote all the music and words for
``Gatsby,'' which he adapted from the F. Scott Fitzgerald novel.
</P>
<P>
   Over a period of four months in 1995, in a process he likened to
``making antiques,'' Horwitz, who can bring to mind Kevin Kline on
lithium, fashioned lyrics to five of Harbison's songs reminiscent
of the period, performed live by a band vocalist or played over the
radio during the opera. With an eye to a potential CD of ``Gatsby
Songs,'' Horwitz, 50, later wrote words for eight more numbers that
are heard in the opera as instrumentals only.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a gig,'' said Horwitz on a recent visit to the Met for
rehearsals. More seriously, he said he had found the work ``as hard
as anything I've ever had to do and more fun than anything I've
ever had to do.''
</P>
<P>
   One song, ``Cool,'' wafts from the radio as the mysterious Jay
Gatsby and his lost love, Daisy Buchanan, meet in her house with
Daisy's unfaithful husband, Tom, and Daisy's cousin Nick and the
flirtatious Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like the summery ocean breeze,
</P>
<P>
   Cool _
</P>
<P>
   Like the earliest morning dew.
</P>
<P>
   When my heart with fiery flame is burning,
</P>
<P>
   Then I run to quench my desire with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, at Gatsby's mansion, a band pounds out another of the
songs, a party anthem:
</P>
<P>
   ``One foot in,
</P>
<P>
   One foot out,
</P>
<P>
   Do that old ``Carolina Shout.''
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing out-of-date about
</P>
<P>
   A happy old Saturday night to-do.''
</P>
<P>
   The music melts into a fox trot that draws Nick and Jordan to
the dance floor:
</P>
<P>
   ``Night's gleaming _
</P>
<P>
   The lights beaming _
</P>
<P>
   And I'm dreaming of you.''
</P>
<P>
   (There is one song that Horwitz has no claim on: a tango that
Harbison set to a poem by Fitzgerald.)
</P>
<P>
   Horwitz, who reads music and can pick out melodies on a piano,
said, ``The music sang to me.'' He had long studied the tricks of
Cole Porter and other masters _ ``Lorenz Hart may have been the
best of them, of us, dare I say it,'' Horwitz said _ sometimes
writing dummy lyrics to intuit the rhymes, while taking care not to
parody the genre.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It was a circuitous road that led him to Gatsby and the Met. A
native of Dayton, Ohio, where his father, a doctor, attended
Orville Wright on his deathbed in 1948, Horwitz attended Kenyon
College in Gambier, Ohio, where, years later, he teamed up with an
older fellow alumnus, the comedian Jonathan Winters, in a local
cabaret act, beginning a long-term friendship.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a funny guy,'' Winters said recently. ``I get a kick out
of him. I still do. He's fast.'' And Winters added, ``He's fairly
bright.''
</P>
<P>
   Horwitz did not run away to join the circus; it was part of
college. For his drama thesis, he spent five weeks at the clown
school of the Ringling Bros. and Barnum &AMP; Bailey Circus. He left to
finish college but then returned to spend two years as a clown:
Ringling Bros.' first with a B.A., or so he was told. The other
clowns called him Shakespeare. The circus was a priceless tutor,
Horwitz said. ``I learned to get in, get your laughs and get out,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving the circus after two years, Horwitz came to New York
where he found work at the all-news radio station WINS, packing the
world into 22-minute summaries.
</P>
<P>
   In record time, too, he picked out a life's companion. Meeting a
mezzo-soprano, Lisa Miller, who was also from Dayton and was
studying voice in Manhattan with the singer Jennie Tourel, he took
her out on a Friday night and by the following Wednesday they were
making wedding plans. Twenty-five years later they have two sons
and a daughter, ages 13 to 19.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile he put together a traveling one-man show, ``An Evening
of Sholom Aleichem,'' and studied Yiddish with the poet and teacher
Wolf Younin. ``My religious education ended with my bris,'' he
confessed, referring to the Jewish rite of circumcision.
</P>
<P>
   Long interested in politics _ he manned the lonely Democratic
tents at county fairs in Ohio _ he took a job in 1973 as deputy
spokesman for the Assembly speaker, Stanley Steingut of Brooklyn.
``Stanley tried to make a mensch out of me,'' Horwitz said. ``He
taught me how to talk, how to dress, how to act. I had a rough
edge.''
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1970s, after leaving Albany, Horwitz, a lifelong
jazz fan, had put together a musical tribute to one of his idols,
Fats Waller. The show, ``Ain't Misbehavin','' made it to Broadway
not once but twice, in the original hit 1978 production and a
successful 1988 revival. Horwitz collaborated on lyrics for some of
the songs Waller never finished, a task that won him song-writing
awards from ASCAP and later drew Harbison's attention.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I always said Murray will always have a job, because he always
comes up with ideas,'' said Richard Maltby Jr., the co-writer and
director of ``Ain't Misbehavin'.'' ``He's a tremendous
enthusiast.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s Horwitz stepped up his pace. He staged the
90th-birthday celebration for Carnegie Hall in 1981 and continued
to act on television, in film and theater.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, during the Reagan administration, he was named acting
director of the opera and musical theater program of the National
Endowment for the Arts, a post he held until 1989, when he became
director of jazz, classical music and entertainment programming for
National Public Radio. He was soon promoted to vice president for
cultural reporting, a job he still holds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's astounding,'' said Kevin Klose, NPR's president. ``I
don't know anybody who knows more about American culture past and
present. Jazz, classical, funk, rock. You name it, he knows it. He
also knows comedy and drama, film, tape, stage, radio. He's
amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years Horwitz has, if anything, branched out, staging
celebrations at the White House for NPR's 20th anniversary in 1995
and the 1997 ``President's Summit for America's Future.'' He also
narrated young people's jazz concerts with Wynton Marsalis at Town
Hall and in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   This month he was interviewed on NPR for a Hanukkah documentary,
``Mostly Meshugah!,'' on another of his idols, Mickey Katz, the
musical comedian, klezmer virtuoso and father of the actor Joel
Grey. And next month he will be honored with induction as a
Chevalier des Arts et Lettres by the government of France for
musical exchanges with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But Horwitz set store by an even greater distinction. ``On my
tombstone you can carve, `He was once a straight man for Jonathan
Winters,''' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
