<P>
   POLITICAL
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-MEETPRESS _ WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore challenges
rival Bill Bradley to abandon expensive TV ads and instead wage
their campaign for president in a series of twice weekly debates.
(Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)MOVED
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-VOTE _ MOSCOW _ Voting across 11 time zones, Russians
gave pro-reform parties unexpectedly strong support in
parliamentary elections Sunday. (Holmes, Cox News Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   POLIO _ Once last week, and again Sunday morning, strangers had
rapped on the wooden lintel of Salim's doorway and urged him to
bring his children to the booth by the tea stall for the drops that
would protect them from disease. And so Salim brought them. Babua,
3, Nisha, 5, and Nicut, almost 6, stepped forward one by one,
opening their mouths for two drops of oral polio vaccine. Three
down, 134,999,997 to go. All over India Sunday, the same scene was
repeated. Today and tomorrow, the same volunteers will fan out
across the country, carrying vaccine from house to house in search
of children 5 and younger who do not bear the telltale purple
stain. By Tuesday evening, they hope to have immunized 135 million
children. When they are done, it will be the third time _ in three
months _ that India has staged such a campaign. (McKenna, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   AIRPORTS _ ATLANTA _ The Federal Aviation Administration says it
expects Hartsfield International Airport in Atlanta will surpass
Chicago's O'Hare International Airport with about 910,000 landings
and takeoffs this year. Last year, Hartsfield surpassed O'Hare in
passenger count. (Hendricks, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
