<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-19 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3441 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-WIESEL-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     12-19 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIESEL-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AND THE SEA IS NEVER FULL': SHY, BUT HISTORY IS TUGGING HIS
SLEEVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(lb) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the first volume of his memoirs, ``All Rivers Run to the
Sea,'' the novelist and Holocaust survivor Elie Wiesel described
the first four decades of his life, from his birth in 1928 up to
his marriage in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   He sums up that first volume in the sequel to it, ``And the Sea
Is Never Full'': ``My peaceful childhood, my turbulent adolescence,
the uncertainties of my formative years. Full stops and shaky
beginnings. Wanderings, wrong turns, changes of direction. Years
marked by messianic dreams and challenges, ecstasy and mourning,
separations and reunions.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow he emerged from this journey a world-renowned figure, an
icon of suffering and survival and a champion of the oppressed, who
would eventually win the Nobel Peace Prize.
</P>
<P>
   In his new volume he turns outward. ``Until now I have attempted
to narrate mostly that which I see within myself; from here on I am
also obligated to turn my attention to those who have been judging
me,'' he writes. ``The introvert will yield to the extrovert.''
</P>
<P>
   The resulting book is patchwork, a grab bag of speeches he gave,
the great and the near-great he met, causes he could not refuse to
get involved in, conferences he helped to organize, ideological
battles he fought and infrequent bursts of eloquence about the
ineffability of Auschwitz.
</P>
<P>
   Except for these last, the prose is too often the language of
agendas and travelogue. ``I'' elides too often into ``we'' (and not
necessarily because the author is including his wife, Marian, who
translated this book from the French). Mstislav Rostropovitch is
identified redundantly as ``the world-famous Russian-born
cellist,'' as if his world fame couldn't speak for itself.
</P>
<P>
   With its tolerance for words like ``prioritize'' and ``impact''
(as a verb), the writing here (at least as it's translated) makes
you feel as if you were slogging through an acre of marshmallows
piled 6 feet deep.
</P>
<P>
   Here and there Wiesel arrests your attention on specific
subjects: his abortive friendship with Francois Mitterrand, who he
feels misled him over his relations with Vichy France; his
political struggles over the building of the Holocaust Memorial
Museum in Washington; his challenge to President Ronald Reagan not
to memorialize the German military cemetery at Bitburg; the
experience of winning the 1986 Nobel Peace Prize.
</P>
<P>
   Of his return to Birkenau in 1979 for the first time since 1945
he writes hauntingly: ``The silence of Birkenau is a silence unlike
any other. It contains the screams, the strangled prayers of
thousands of human beings condemned to vanish into the darkness of
nameless, endless ashes. Human silence at the core of inhumanity.
Deadly silence at the core of death. Eternal silence under a
moribund sky.''
</P>
<P>
   But what is most fascinating about this volume is the tension
between his professed humility and his wonder at all he has
achieved without the apparent exercise of his will. He has no taste
for politics, he keeps repeating. He is merely a yeshiva boy from
Sighet, Romania, who wants nothing out of life but to study and
write. He is shy and interior. He hates to speak in public. He
suffers from terrible stage fright.
</P>
<P>
   Yet history keeps tugging at his sleeve and calling him to
Israel in times of war, to the Soviet Union to speak on behalf of
oppressed Jews, to Washington to form committees, to New Haven,
Conn., to teach at Yale, to the 92nd Street Y in New York to
deliver his annual lectures on religious subjects.
</P>
<P>
   He calls on Presidents Carter, Reagan, Clinton, Gorbachev and
Walesa. They in turn call on him. (When Reagan telephoned him at
home, in his confusion he blurted out, ``Mr. President, how did you
find my phone number?'' at which the president burst out laughing.)
</P>
<P>
   Some good came out of these summonses from on high. Wiesel used
his prestige as a Nobel laureate to free Russian Jews and to
pressure Gorbachev on the treatment of Andrei Sakharov, the
scientist and dissident. He has kept alive the memory of those who
perished in the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   He argues quite rightly that if the life of a single child is
saved by his efforts, then all his exertions are justified. As you
read ``And the Sea Is Never Full,'' you become persuaded that
something about his combination of seeming innocence and moral
honesty has the power to move if not mountains then those who have
the most power.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a fair amount of nonsense emerges as well. What strikes one
as particularly fatuous is that it took Wiesel's gathering a
multitude of Nobel laureates to identify ``human rights, priority
for education, scientific cooperation, encouragement for research
in molecular biology, disarmament'' and ``aid to developing
countries'' as the leading problems facing the world, when a single
schoolchild could have come to a conclusion just as profound.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand this may not be quite as silly as Wiesel's
remark at the conclusion of his conference on ``The Anatomy of Hate
and Conflict Resolution'' _ ``I don't know whether as a result of
our debates hate diminished throughout the world'' _ as if just
possibly it had.
</P>
<P>
   Reading these passages, you become persuaded that Wiesel is not
entirely innocent of political skills and that his motives for
entering the public arena are not all connected to self-sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the ultimate clue to his attitude lies in the subtitle,
``Memoirs, 1969-.'' This suggests that the story he tells here
doesn't end in 1998, the last date referred to in the book, or in
1999 with the book's publication, or even in 2099. Instead his
story is implied to be never-ending, possibly because he sees
himself as having transcended the limitations of time.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `AND THE SEA IS NEVER FULL'
</P>
<P>
   Memoirs, 1969-
</P>
<P>
   By Elie Wiesel
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. Translated by Marion Wiesel. 429 pages. Alfred A.
Knopf. $30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
