<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-19 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3454 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-OUTLOOK-CORPORATIONS-     12-19 1292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTLOOK-CORPORATIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEY FORCES FOR BUSINESS SUCCESS: CREATIVITY AND A LOCAL TOUCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By FRED ANDREWS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For five years now, a klatch of management scholars and
forward-looking executives have met at the Sloan School of
Management at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology to ponder a
question: What will be tomorrow's model for business success?
</P>
<P>
   Their collective answer goes well beyond the usual suspects, the
likes of Dell Computer, Amazon.com, Qualcomm or Priceline _ all
commonly hailed as prototypes for the age of the Internet. Instead,
this business academy with its dazzling virtuosity in technology
seems at pains to reassert that technology is not enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Success takes a balance of forces; technology is not always
necessary and is almost never sufficient,'' said Michael S. Scott
Morton, professor of management. Dr. Scott Morton has been
co-director of MIT's initiative on Inventing the Organizations of
the 21st Century, a research project involving a score of scholars
and engaging dozens of companies in its deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   A specialist in corporate strategy, Scott Morton maintains there
is less than meets the eye in the Internet land rush. He sees more
activity than results from the celebrated Web start-ups. In the
long run, he expects ``the bigger and longer-lasting impacts'' will
come from established companies that successfully reinvent
themselves in imaginative ways, using technology to enlarge their
fundamental business vision and to support an inspired work force.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, this leaves a great variety of possibilities, and
the roughly 200 executives and scholars who met in mid-November for
a valedictory summing-up of the five-year inquiry heard a good many
of them. Tomorrow's model company might be gigantic, or it might be
tiny _ either possibility was seen as entirely consistent with the
power of the Internet. Tomorrow's company might be in continuous
flux, its operations put together and pulled apart like a Lego toy.
The model enterprise might be acutely sensitive to its physical and
human environment, or it might be lean and terribly mean, asking no
loyalty and offering none.
</P>
<P>
   But within the forest of possibilities, there seemed a consensus
on several broad principles:
</P>
<P>
   _ Highly decentralized systems will be far more important than
they are today. Not a soul took issue with that. A great many
companies have concluded that if they are to move quickly and
adroitly, as many decisions as possible should be made by those
closest to the customer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Activities _ not organization charts _ will become the key
building blocks in business. As outsourcing and alliances become
even more common, basic functions like recruiting or training or
sales promotion may be turned over to outside specialists. So
product design, an activity, will remain essential, but not
necessarily an in-house design department.
</P>
<P>
   _ Companies, large or small, will be both global and local. To
compete effectively, global giants will require the local touch.
And with the borderless Internet, even small businesses will reach
customers around the world _ and face global competition, as well.
</P>
<P>
   The MIT covey's most celebrated member is Peter M. Senge, who
wrote ``The Fifth Discipline'' a decade ago and touched off a
corporate quest to create the ``learning organization.'' Speaking
by video hookup from Paris, Senge said he now expected
``environmental sustainability'' to become a cornerstone of
corporate strategy. ``Waste is an artifact of the industrial age,''
he declared. ``Nature actually has no waste _ none.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Senge's models for tomorrow is Xerox, which designs new
copiers for remanufacture, having discovered it can save money in
building new copiers by reprocessing parts from old ones. Another
is Interface Inc. of Atlanta, the nation's largest maker of
commercial carpeting, which has made a signature commitment to
``sustainability'' through recycling and waste reduction. (Its Web
site at www.interfaceinc.com is as lofty and luminous as a New Age
greeting card: ``More than just a carpet company, we represent
peace of mind.'')
</P>
<P>
   The idea, one Interface executive wrote, is ``to deliver better
service and increased value, not more stuff.'' Its Terratex,
Solenium and Deja Vu fabrics and flooring are made from recycled
materials. Its ReEntry program reuses or recycles customers' old
carpeting. ``We guarantee your old carpet won't end up in a
landfill, period.''
</P>
<P>
   In looking for companies with foresight and imagination, Scott
Morton singled out Schneider National of Green Bay, Wis., the
nation's largest full-load trucking company and a pioneer in using
Qualcomm satellite technology to direct its fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Schneider has transformed itself from a routine over-the-road
hauler to a sophisticated carrier that provides an essential
service in today's manufacturing economy. It provides ``just in
time'' parts delivery, guaranteed, come hell or high water, for
customers on the nationwide scale of General Motors.
</P>
<P>
   Schneider has also expanded its conception of its business.
Through subsidiaries, the company will design, install and run
logistics systems for other companies, including owning and
operating dedicated fleets. It buys and finances trucks for others,
and it matches loads to available trucks for more than 1,000
carriers.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Morton credits the creativity and courage of Donald J.
Schneider, president and chief executive. Schneider, true to
character, credits the company's 17,000 ``talented associates.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas W. Malone, a professor of information systems and Scott
Morton's co-director, veered from the more traditional models of
his two colleagues and expressed a vision that is drenched in the
power of the Internet. But he was less taken with the current
fervor over e-commerce than with what he saw as a more profound
change, a coming golden age for ``microenterprises.''
</P>
<P>
   As the communication costs fall to next to nothing,
``essentially everyone'' can be well enough informed to make good
decisions, he said. That power will be a boon to the highly
motivated, the creative, the innovative. He expects a vast Internet
marketplace in business services to take shape, enabling the
smallest businesses to rent the talents and capabilities to compete
with the largest companies. Large portions of the business economy
will consist of very small enterprises, as few as one to 10
talented people, and that sector will take on the radically
decentralized character of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Malone's prototype enterprise is TopsyTail, a tiny Dallas-based
company founded a decade ago to produce a plastic hair-styling
tool. Relying on a score of vendors, from design firms to injection
molders through fulfillment houses, TopsyTail has produced more
than $100 million in sales at retail with only three employees (a
chief financial officer, a marketing director and a general
assistant). Its latest product is a collapsible foam-lined cowboy
hat to prevent ``hat hair and hot heads.''
</P>
<P>
   Its founder, Tomima Edmark, who once sold large systems for IBM,
says she turned to extreme outsourcing by hunch and by necessity.
She champions the technique as an inexpensive, fleet-footed way to
bring out a product. ``I always felt it would work,'' she said in
an interview, ``I needed to ramp up quickly, and I didn't have much
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Edmark assembled her network of TopsyTail vendors the
old-fashioned way _by phone, personal contact and trial and error.
But her newest venture is more purely Internet: a Web store to sell
brands of women's underwear online, starting in February.
Outsourced as usual, the site is being built by a New Jersey
Webmaster.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-19-99 1834EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
