<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-19 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3474 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-FLYERS-NEILSON-2T     12-19 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-FLYERS-NEILSON-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLYERS' COACH NEILSON USES HIS GOOD NATURE AGAINST CANCER
CHALLENGE 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The chemotherapy begins Monday. A doctor will cut
the skin high on Roger Neilson's chest and insert a small plastic
device. The attached pump will deliver timed doses of two drugs
into his bloodstream. The process will last four days and will be
done in three cycles over two months.
</P>
<P>
   After that comes the bone marrow transplant that will force
Neilson to stop coaching the Philadelphia Flyers for at least six
weeks in late winter. Neilson could become weak and uncomfortable
while battling a bone cancer called multiple myeloma. He might lose
his unruly mop of curly hair, a distinguishing characteristic. He
and the Flyers' general manager, Bob Clarke, have joked about
Neilson's wearing different wigs to every game, like his rotation
of loud neckties. Neilson elicits chuckles when he says his
recovery plan is well-timed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doctor Brodsky and I both agree that the most important thing
is winning the Stanley Cup,'' Neilson said, with a wry smile, ``and
so I think he's got it worked out that we'll be ready for the
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   When he turned serious, Neilson said: ``It is my faith that
keeps me going. Any tough situations, I always turn them over to
the Lord. This happens to be His plan for my life right now, so I'm
just going to work as hard as I can through it. It's more up to Him
than it is up to me. I don't worry about it. That's the way it
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Neilson's illness has sent a worried shiver through the National
Hockey League this holiday season. At age 65, coaching his seventh
team, Neilson is the NHL's favorite bachelor uncle, a little
eccentric but a mensch, one of the elders of his craft with 23
seasons in the league. In a business where some people easily make
enemies, Neilson has few. In an environment known for both casual
and serious cursing, Neilson never uses profanity. He rarely drinks
alcohol. He never smokes. He mails more than 1,000 Christmas cards
each year and gets at least that many back.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sends out 500 gifts,'' said Eric Lindros, the captain of
the Flyers. ``He's a whirlwind. He hasn't slowed down.''
</P>
<P>
   Neilson suffered flu-like symptoms during training camp, and
when they continued into November, he was first diagnosed with
pneumonia. But he could not regain 12 pounds he had lost, and more
tests were done.
</P>
<P>
   He does not look that ill and he certainly does not look old. He
is lean and fit from workouts that include riding a bicycle to the
practice rink, even on cold days. As he moves about arena corridors
before and after games, people hug Neilson and pat him on the back
and say ``good luck'' and ``God bless you.'' He hunches his
shoulders, bows his head and thanks them. Before Saturday night's
game against Tampa Bay, Neilson's office visitor was John Cullen,
the Lightning assistant coach who is a cancer survivor. ``He talked
about what it was like for him and what I can expect,'' Neilson
said. ``It was really good for me and nice of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in last Thursday night's game against Phoenix, when a
whistle stopped play, the video screen on the scoreboard showed
Neilson's craggy face. The officials skated away from the face-off
circle so that players had time to rap their sticks on the ice and
boards while the fans stood to applaud. Neilson waved, exhaled with
puffed cheeks and licked his lips.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are very sympathetic to someone who has cancer,''
Neilson said. ``It's one of those diseases that everybody hopes
they don't get. We've had people phoning and sending things in from
all over the country. It's been really amazing. I have had so many
phone calls that I can't possibly return them. It's so very nice to
know you've got friends and that support.''
</P>
<P>
   Neilson's disease is an aggressive one; the five-year survival
rate for multiple myeloma patients treated with chemotherapy is 29
percent. Last week, Neilson's doctor, Isadore Brodsky, head of
hematology and oncology at Hahnemann University Hospital, said his
prognosis for Neilson was excellent because the disease was
identified at an early stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would easily put Roger's life expectancy as beyond five
years,'' Brodsky said. ``Maybe even 10 to 15. He's going to be
around for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The mood around Neilson is uncertain, however, a mix of
optimism, pessimism and a celebration that Neilson does not seek.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing is getting more publicity than it deserves,''
he said. He might be right. Many anonymous people suffer more from
worse things, but sports figures serve as surrogates and symbolic
relatives. Just as fans project disproportionate love and anger and
envy toward them, so too do they express sympathy. The concern is
more personal for the hundreds in the business who know Neilson
from his major and minor-league jobs in St. Louis, Chicago, New
York, Dallas, Vancouver, Toronto, Edmonton, Buffalo, Florida and _
before all that _ Peterborough, Ontario, one of those hockey
cradles, where he coached juniors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roger didn't have a family,'' Lindros said. ``Every team he
goes to, every player in the room, that's his family.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Lindros said that even players who disagreed with Neilson's
coaching philosophy never resented him personally. Lindros might
know _ he is also an admirer of Mark Messier, whose rebellion
against Neilson's style led to Neilson's dismissal from the Rangers
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Neilson softened the announcement to the players on Dec. 10 by
preceding it with a Monty Python video. ``We know there are tougher
days coming for Roger,'' Flyers forward Keith Jones said. Mark
Recchi, another forward, said Neilson ``is probably the one who is
the most optimistic and positive about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The day before Neilson announced his illness, his team
squandered a lead. Harry Neale, his old boss in Vancouver, ribbed
Neilson about it. The day after the announcement, Neale saw Neilson
again and began to offer sympathy. ``I was horrified when I heard
and I told him I'd pray for him,'' said Neale, now a television
commentator. ``He looked at me and saw the tears in my eyes and he
told me three funny stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Many anecdotes are making the rounds: of Neilson the marathon
runner, Neilson the bungee jumper and Neilson the world traveler,
and of how Neilson sometimes locks himself out of his office and
sometimes sleeps there. People tell of how he occasionally forgets
to pay utility bills and never holds grudges or lashes out behind
people's backs, and of how he pioneered the use of videotape for
scouting two decades ago, and of how, before that, he forced
officials in junior hockey to change the rule about penalty shots.
He would replace his goalie, they recalled, with a defenseman, who
would simply leave the net and challenge the shooter up ice, often
successfully. And there was that time with Vancouver when Neilson
led his players in a protest against the officials by waving white
towels of surrender on the ends of their hockey sticks.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Nichols of Dallas, who worked for Neilson when he coached
the minor league Dallas Blackhawks, has been a close friend for
more than 20 years. She spoke of how Neilson has often let sons and
grandsons of friends board at his house and has mentored them and
provided them with jobs in his coaching clinics and hockey schools
in Canada and Israel. She recalled how Neilson delivered newspapers
in Toronto while teaching high school when he was in his 30's.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Neilson's legendary absentmindedness _ he sometimes
gets lost when driving even familiar routes _ Nichols said: ``It's
not an act. It's not premeditated. It's truly him. He's a quirky,
Magoo kind of guy. He's such a spaceman. That's why everybody loves
him.'' Nichols said she will come to Philadelphia to help nurse
Neilson back to health after his surgery and that they both will
use the playoffs, which begin in April, as motivation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are going to have a goal to get through anything like
this, the Stanley Cup will do,'' she said. ``He's goal oriented. He
has incredible faith, a built-in coping system. I'm going to be
Roger's coach. He's not going to like that. But we've had a long
history of taking care of each other. I'll do my time so I can get
my Stanley Cup necklace.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the recent outpouring of support for Neilson,
Nichols said: ``It's a big love-in. Welcome to it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
