<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTLOOK-FED-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY, ECONOMIC BOOM FORCING FED TO RETHINK MONETARY POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In his nearly half-century as an economist, Alan
Greenspan, the Federal Reserve chairman, has watched the nature of
the American economy change fundamentally.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quintessential manifestations of America's industrial
might earlier this century _ large steel mills, auto assembly
plants, petrochemical complexes and skyscrapers _ have been
replaced by a gross domestic product that has been downsized as
ideas have replaced physical bulk and effort as creators of
value,'' Greenspan said in a recent speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, economic value is best symbolized by exceedingly
complex, miniaturized integrated circuits and the ideas, the
software, that utilize them,'' he said. ``Most of what we currently
perceive as value and wealth is intellectual and impalpable.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the continued importance of basic industry to the economy,
Greenspan may have overstated his case a bit. But there is little
doubt that sweeping technology-driven shifts are under way in the
structure and operation of the economy and that they are forcing
Greenspan and his colleagues at the Federal Reserve to rethink
their approach to monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the Fed policy makers face problems at the
beginning of the new decade that generations of their predecessors
would have welcomed.
</P>
<P>
   Having forced inflation down to quite manageable levels, they
have the luxury of debating whether it is better to allow prices to
rise slightly each year, or whether they should aim for absolute
price stability.
</P>
<P>
   But with unemployment hovering near 30-year lows, they have been
forced to re-examine the assumption that a strong economy will
inevitably generate inflation if joblessness falls below a certain
level. With traditional forecasting models no longer terribly
reliable, they face considerable uncertainties as they try to
predict the economy's course.
</P>
<P>
   There is mounting evidence that productivity _ the single most
important determinant of the economy's growth potential _ is
benefiting from huge investments in technology and is surging at a
rate that would allow the economy to retain substantial momentum
without igniting inflation.
</P>
<P>
   But no one is certain how long the surge will continue.
Likewise, it is anyone's guess whether the booming stock market is
a reflection of and contributor to the economy's improved long-term
prospects or a bubble that will end in tears.
</P>
<P>
   It is also unclear whether the length of the current expansion _
barring an unforeseen collapse it will become the longest in the
nation's history in February at eight years and 11 months _ means
that the business cycle has been tamed or simply that the United
States is benefiting from a remarkable string of good luck.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed faces these challenges from a position of relative
strength. Thanks to his success in taming inflation and his
flexibility in responding to the rapidly changing economy,
Greenspan has tremendous credibility and leeway among investors and
political leaders. With both Democrats and Republicans pledging to
maintain fiscal discipline, monetary policy is becoming even more
important in managing the economy. The Fed's independence from the
government of the day and its focus on inflation-fighting have
become the standard for central banks around the world, which
constantly look to Greenspan for their cues.
</P>
<P>
   Central banks, led by the Fed, ``now find themselves in a
position of power and responsibility unrivaled in their history,''
said Mervyn King, deputy governor of the Bank of England. ``A
commitment to price stability is now seen as the key to achieving
broader economic stability.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan still has his critics. Farmers, beset by commodity
prices that are low or falling, contend there is little
justification for higher interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Some manufacturers say Greenspan does not seem to understand how
little power they have to raise prices or to appreciate fully how
technology and global competition are driving them to become more
efficient. And many liberal economists contend Greenspan seems to
have forgotten that the Fed's mandate includes a commitment to
achieving full employment.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next year, Greenspan is likely to face some
particularly difficult choices. If the economy continues to defy
predictions that it will slow to a sustainable pace, he may feel
forced to follow this year's three quarter-point rate increases
with additional tightening. Fed policy makers meet Tuesday but are
not expected to raise rates then, given their current neutral
policy stance. That puts further action off until 2000, an election
year, which could create tremendous political pressure on the Fed.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan, who will turn 74 in March, has proved willing and
able to take the heat when necessary, and so far he has given no
indication that he is tired of the job, which he has held more than
12 years. President Clinton seems almost certain to nominate him to
a fourth term next year, providing continuity in monetary policy
whatever the outcome of the presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, policy makers in Washington are already speculating
about a post-Greenspan Fed. Assuming Greenspan serves only one more
term, the next president would get to choose his successor, a
selection that could carry tremendous economic and political
significance.
</P>
<P>
   It is too early to think in terms of Greenspan's legacy. Still,
his constant re-examination of assumptions about how the economy
works and his focus on technology as a transforming force have
already changed the approach to their jobs of officials at the Fed
and at other central banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that if central banks are to retain their central
position in economic policy making, they must face up to the
intellectual and technological challenges that lie ahead,'' King
recently told a gathering of central bankers, including Greenspan.
``Unless they do so, popularity will turn to disillusion.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
