<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-19 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3483 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-OUTLOOK-BIOTECH-ART-1     12-19 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTLOOK-BIOTECH-ART-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOTECHNOLOGY'S COMING TREASURE-TROVE OF DRUGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For several years, the big quest in biotechnology has been to
determine the complete sequence of human DNA, the genetic code of
life. Now, however, that task is nearing completion, and the
biotechnology industry is facing an even tougher job _ deciphering
that code so that new drugs and diagnostic tests can be developed.
</P>
<P>
   The coming post-sequencing era will bring huge changes to the
industry. The causes and mechanisms of various diseases that now
defy treatment will become known so that drugs can be developed
much more precisely. Drug discovery will rely as much on software
and databases of genetic information as it will on test tubes and
white mice.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most important change could be a shift from the
``one drug fits all'' approach to treatments tailored to individual
patients based on their genetic profiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the genome being completed, I think we're literally going
to move from statistical-based medicine, where we're thinking about
entire populations, to personalized medicine,'' said Kenneth
Conway, president of Millennium Predictive Medicine, a
majority-owned subsidiary of Millennium Pharmaceuticals in
Cambridge, Mass. ``I think we're going to look back 10 years from
now and think of medicine as being in the dark ages.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, many of the predictions made by biotechnology
executives in the past proved overly optimistic. Still, as the
biotechnology industry nears its 25th birthday in 2001 _ dating
from the formation of Genentech in 1976 _ it has finally started to
bring to market the promised treasure-trove of drugs. Biotechnology
companies now have about 300 drugs in advanced stages in clinical
trials, according to the Biotechnology Industry Organization, a
trade group.
</P>
<P>
   One of the hottest approaches now, for instance, is monoclonal
antibodies, which are proteins that can zero in on a
disease-causing agent and neutralize it. These were first developed
in the 1970s, but only in the last few years have companies
succeeded in making effective drugs from them, such as Reopro from
Centocor, which fights blood clotting, and Herceptin from
Genentech, for breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   In the next few years, many other antibodies are expected to
reach the market, including one from Genentech for asthma and
allergies. Imclone Systems is working on one for head and neck
cancers. IDEC Pharmaceuticals and Coulter Pharmaceutical are each
hoping to sell the first antibodies linked to radioactive isotopes,
which would allow radiation to be directed specifically to tumors,
with less harm to healthy tissue.
</P>
<P>
   Other drugs besides antibodies, of course, will continue to be
developed. One that is expected to be approved soon is Visudyne
from QLT Phototherapeutics, which would be the first drug for
age-related macular degeneration, a deterioration of the retina
that is the leading cause of near blindness in the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest opportunities and challenges are expected to
come from genomics, the study of the human genetic code. The Human
Genome Project, sponsored by the federal government, is expected to
finish the ``rough draft'' of the genome by spring and to be
completed in 2003. Private efforts by such companies as Celera
Genomics and Incyte Pharmaceuticals are also racing ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The full sequence consists of about 3 billion chemical bases,
amid which are 100,000 or more genes that code for the production
of particular proteins, which actually carry out functions in the
body. But unless scientists can determine the functions of the
genes and proteins and how they work together, the sequence alone
is just an enormous overload of information.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing the gene sequence in many ways tells you where to
start looking, but not much more,'' said James Gower, president and
chief executive of Rigel Inc., a South San Francisco start-up
involved in what many consider the new thing _ functional genomics,
which figures out the functions of genes.
</P>
<P>
   A related discipline that could see growth in the next few years
is so-called proteomics, which is the study of proteins. And, since
the human mind alone cannot keep track of billions of bases and
thousands of genes, companies are springing up in the new field of
bio-informatics, the melding of computer science and life science.
</P>
<P>
   As the mechanisms of the body are better discovered,
biotechnology companies will be better able to develop drugs based
on knowledge of how the body functions than by trying random
chemicals to see what works.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole drug-discovery business is now a biology-based
business and not a chemistry-based business,'' said Richard van den
Broek, biotechnology analyst at Hambrecht &AMP; Quist, an investment
bank. ``It's been a chemical business for 50 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Progress should be made on diseases for which there is little
understanding or treatment, including neurological diseases like
Alzheimer's and autoimmune diseases like lupus.
</P>
<P>
   William Haseltine, chairman and chief executive of Human Genome
Sciences Inc. in Rockville, Md., said genes and growth factors are
already starting to be used to grow new blood vessels and, in the
more distant future, it will be possible to grow entire new organs.
</P>
<P>
   One approach to trying to determine gene function is to learn
which genes are turned on in different types of cells, such as
those turned on in cancer cells compared with normal cells. This
has opened up opportunities for companies selling tiny chips that
can quickly analyze thousands of genes at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, companies are now racing to figure out genetic
differences among people. Differences of a single base _ known as a
single nucleotide polymorphism, or SNP (pronounced ``snip'') _ can
determine eye color or make the difference between health and
illness.
</P>
<P>
   Such information could lead to personalized and preventive
medicine. People found to be susceptible to a disease might take a
regimen of pills or change their diet to prevent it. And medicines
will be tailored to each individual, a discipline called
pharmacogenomics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Snips will make a quantum leap toward patient-specific
medicine,'' said G. Steven Burrill, chief executive of Burrill &AMP;
Co., a San Francisco merchant bank that specializes in
biotechnology.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A precursor is Herceptin, the Genentech drug for breast cancer.
It works in only 25 percent to 30 percent of cases, those in which
the breast tumors produce unusually large amounts of a protein
known as Her2. Patients are tested beforehand to see if they
qualify.
</P>
<P>
   Millennium plans to introduce a genetic test next year that will
predict whether melanoma, a skin cancer, will spread through the
body. Patients whose tumors will not spread might be spared
chemotherapy or radiation treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Personalized medicine will change the economics of the business,
with fewer blockbuster drugs. ``There will be a lot of
fragmentation in the market,'' said Jeffrey Casdin, chief executive
of Casdin Capital Partners, a biotech investment fund. He said,
however, that since personalized drugs would be more effective and
would have fewer side effects than mass market drugs, they would
fetch higher prices.
</P>
<P>
   Genetic profiling of patients raises privacy issues. Should, for
instance, a person's susceptibility to a disease be used by
insurance companies to raise premiums or by employers in hiring
decisions?
</P>
<P>
   That is just one of the ethical and political issues likely to
confront the biotechnology industry in the next decade. A huge
backlash has already developed against bioengineered crops. There
are controversies over cloning and the use of stem cells _ the
progenitors of all other cells in the body _ that can come from
aborted fetuses or from embryos made in fertility clinics.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another issue could be a budding backlash against rising
drug prices, which are commanding an ever growing percentage of
total health care spending. Some drugs offered by biotechnology
companes can cost tens of thousands of dollars a year, though
companies argue that drugs can save money overall by reducing the
need for operations and hospital stays.
</P>
<P>
   Financially, the biotechnology industry enters the new century
in modest shape. A severe shortage of financing that plagued the
industry a year ago has abated somewhat, but the industry seems to
be stratifying into haves and have-nots.
</P>
<P>
   An index maintained by Burrill &AMP; Co. of stocks of the biggest
biotechnology companies, like Amgen and Biogen, the ones with
profits and products, has risen more than 120 percent this year.
Burrill found that midsize companies, many with products on the
horizon, rose more than 70 percent, but stocks of the smallest
companies, many in early stages of development, rose, by
comparison, only 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Private companies are still having trouble raising venture
capital or going public. With a biotechnology company typically
taking 10 years to show a profit, Internet companies seem like more
attractive investments.
</P>
<P>
   A long-predicted consolidation _ through mergers and, in some
cases, bankruptcies _ seemed to begin in earnest in 1999, and that
is expected to continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still dealing with an industry that has too much
capacity,'' said Peter Drake, managing director of Prudential
Vector Healthcare Group. There are an estimated 300 publicly traded
biotechnology companies and about 1,000 private ones.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the acquisitions of biotech companies in 1999 were made
by big drug companies. Johnson &AMP; Johnson bought Centocor; Merck
bought Sibia Neurosciences, and Warner-Lambert acquired Agouron
Pharmaceuticals. The drug companies need new products to continue
growth and replace products with expiring patents. And tapping into
the technology of biotechnology companies looks like one good way
to get them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
