u f BC-OUTLOOK-ASIA-ART-2TAK     12-19 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTLOOK-ASIA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASIA WATCHERS NOW LOOKING AT ECONOMIES OF U.S. AND JAPAN
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By WAYNE ARNOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SINGAPORE _ Southeast Asia's battered economies have bounced
back this year, and the most serious concern in the year 2000,
economists say, will not be the region's enduring banking mess but
the possibility that things could unexpectedly turn ugly in the
United States or Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Demand for exports _ together with high personal savings, low
interest rates and government deficit spending _ have restored
stable economic growth to the region. To be sure, many of the
politically painful prescriptions of the International Monetary
Fund and other foreign diagnosticians have been rejected, leaving
the region's financial system nearly paralyzed.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the region's growth continues, economists say, depends
largely on whether Alan Greenspan, chairman of the Federal Reserve
System, can continue to steer the American economy in for a soft
landing and whether the Japanese government can preserve its own
flickering economic recovery. The answer to both questions, most
economists predict, is yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard to tell a negative story,'' said David
Fernandez, an economist at J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   This happy ending to Asia's financial crisis may confound those
expecting a clear-cut victory of free markets over crony
capitalism, but, it appears, good things can happen to bad
economies, if they are small, developing and populated by savers.
</P>
<P>
   This is the tale being told in hindsight: A tsunami of foreign
loans and investment set the stage for the 1997-98 financial
crisis, swamping a region that had yet to develop the legal and
regulatory framework needed to ensure that the money was spent
wisely. The wave of funds lifted the region's manufacturing
capacity to excess, spilled over into speculative real estate bets
and left companies swimming in debt.
</P>
<P>
   When anxious investors pulled the plug in Thailand in mid-1997,
local currencies plunged, and all those overseas loans became too
expensive for companies or even countries to pay. The IMF came to
the rescue and, seeing a Latin America-style situation of
overheated economies and out-of-control debt, told the victims to
raise interest rates and rein in spending.
</P>
<P>
   What the IMF appears to have overlooked was that, unlike Latin
Americans, Asians are big savers. So are their governments.
Surpluses are common. With austerity, currencies stopped falling,
but as interest rates spiraled upward, so did deposit rates and
loan payments. Savers saved, debtors defaulted, and banks went
under even faster than before.
</P>
<P>
   Reversing course, governments began pushing interest rates down
and spending themselves into deficits. With scant demand for loans,
banks invested their depositors' money in stocks, fueling a rally
that helped take pressure off debtors by raising the value of their
assets. Meanwhile, heavy demand for Asian exports, especially
electronics, kept money flowing in.
</P>
<P>
   Among the results: current account surpluses, rising credit
ratings, and economies that are expected to grow 5 percent on
average in 2000, and 5 percent to 6 percent in 2001. ``It's a
natural bounce,'' said William Belchere, head of fixed-income
research at Merrill Lynch. Even Indonesia is emerging from
recession, though only just, with a new government lending the kind
of stability that could lure back foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
   With exports playing such an important role, however, much
depends on what happens outside the region. ``If there's a
recession in the U.S., all bets are off for Southeast Asia,'' Manu
Bhaskaran, economist with SG Securities, told the World Economic
Forum here in October.
</P>
<P>
   Others say Japan's feeble recovery depends too heavily on
government spending, posing another threat to Asian exports. ``At
some point, sooner rather than later, the Japanese government will
have to rein in expenditure,'' Kenneth Pinkes, chief credit officer
at Moody's Investors Service, told the forum.
</P>
<P>
   Exports are only a stopgap, however. Ultimately, economists say,
Southeast Asia will need to rely on its own consumers to drive
growth. While households have survived the crisis in much better
shape than companies, and private spending appears to be reviving,
consumers will be reluctant to spend more until they are more
confident that their lot has improved.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in the way, investors and economists say, is the mire
of bad debts preventing Asia's banks from lending to growing
companies. While the crisis rendered many debtors unable to pay,
the biggest obstacles now, economists say, are ``strategic'' loan
defaults. Borrowers have the money but withhold payment to squeeze
a deal from their bankers. Weak bankruptcy laws and old-boy
networks shelter big, politically powerful debtors.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, 45 percent of all loans by Thai banks are still
nonperforming. Although the number is falling, the central bank is
concerned that banks are reducing their bad-loan portfolios largely
by agreeing to defer payments and lower interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   In Indonesia, government efforts to revive the banking sector
have foundered over a political corruption scandal involving
efforts to refinance one ailing commercial bank. In the meantime,
not only are billions of dollars in interbank claims frozen, so is
at least $38 billion in assets the government needs to sell to pay
for its bank bailout.
</P>
<P>
   Consultants and foreign investors complain they have seen little
constructive change at all in Malaysia's financial system, which
fended off the IMF and pressure for change by locking in its
exchange rate and putting controls on the withdrawal of capital,
then riding along with the region's recovery. The economy is
growing, but investors are still leery of a country that seems
determined not to join the increasingly free-flowing global market
for capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not seeing enough reform,'' said J. Mark Mobius,
president of Templeton Emerging Markets Fund. ``We'd like to see
investors, particularly foreign investors, treated more fairly.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Some economists contend that such complaints are typical of
foreign investors eager to snatch up assets on the cheap, as well
as of free-market absolutists who want to see wholesale change in
government officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a lot of people, restructuring means seeing lots of bodies
in the streets, and that's just not part of the social contract in
these places,'' said Fernandez at J.P. Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   It is not fair to say that Asia is not changing, such economists
say. The crisis set into motion an inexorable process of change
that has already brought the end of a 34-year-old regime in
Indonesia and a new constitution in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   Others argue that the advent of the information age will make it
imperative that Asia catch up to address the increasing power of
the small, mobile investor. In Asia, for example, the crisis taught
the dangers of overly relying on banks for dispensing credit and
highlighted the need for a dynamic market for corporate bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Developing one will require overhauling tax structures and
encouraging the growth of derivatives, economists say, not to
mention increasing transparency in corporate dealings. So far, Asia
has been able to finance its recovery domestically, but foreign
investors warn that in the Internet age, even domestic capital can
emigrate at the push of a button.
</P>
<P>
   Economists predict that greed will quickly wear down foreign
investors' truculence. The region still offers the best possible
returns, they say, change or no change. Overseas capital will be
back, they say, and Southeast Asia's tiger economies will burn, not
as brightly as before the crisis, but brightly nonetheless.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
