<HEADER>
A3492 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-OUTLOOK-PATENTS-NYT &LR;      12-19 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTLOOK-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATENTS CONSIDERED VITAL TO THRIVE ON THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By TERESA RIORDAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   How important will intellectual property be in the new economy?
</P>
<P>
   ``Excruciatingly important,'' said Glover Ferguson, co-director
of the electronic commerce program at Anderson Consulting.
</P>
<P>
   A case in point is the victory that the online bookseller
Amazon.com scored earlier this month when it obtained a preliminary
injunction against Barnesandnoble.com. The injunction prevents
Barnes &AMP; Noble from using the one-click system patented by Amazon
that enables repeat online customers to place orders without having
to re-enter mailing and credit card information.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to put some real boulders in the way of the
Barnes &AMP; Noble check-out line system,'' said Kevin Rivette,
co-author of ``Rembrandts in the Attic,'' a new book from the
Harvard Business Press that proselytizes on the power of patents.
``The lawsuit also has put everyone else on the Net on notice.''
</P>
<P>
   Walter Hanchuk, a partner at the New York law firm of Morgan &AMP;
Finnegan, concurred, saying the ruling ``clearly highlights the
importance of intellectual property in all technologies.''
</P>
<P>
   Intellectual property, in Rivette's view, is what is going to
separate many winners and losers on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's easy to put up a Web site, when it's easy to get
financial backing, this is where some of the shake-out is going to
happen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Much attention so far has been paid to the new wave of so-called
business-method patents on the Internet. But Mark Lemley, a
professor of law at the University of Texas, points out that the
scope of what can be patented is growing every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a patent on a method for holding a golf putter,''
Lemley said. ``There's a patent on allocating assets in a divorce
settlement. This is a great expansion of patentable subject matter
beyond what has traditionally been the technological arts.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivette, who is chief executive of Aurigin Systems, a
patent-strategy consulting company, predicted that ``one of the
biggest things that will occur in the next three to five years is
the proliferation of well-funded patent `factories.'''
</P>
<P>
   Rivette said he had heard of about half a dozen such enterprises
modeled along the lines of Walker Digital, the controversial _ and
extremely successful _ patent-incubation venture that gave birth to
Priceline.com. The Priceline.com business is based on a patented
method for letting prospective customers propose a price for a
product or service, with the online order being filled if the
seller is willing to sell at that price. The patent is one of 30
received by Walker Digital, which has another 300 patent
applications pending.
</P>
<P>
   Like Walker Digital, which kept a very low profile until it
started Priceline.com, these ventures are stealthily amassing
patent empires that will become apparent only when they are ready
to start businesses, Rivette said.
</P>
<P>
   Rivette predicts that the high mortality rate of Internet
businesses will create new opportunities for patent expertise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be just like what happened in the biotech community in
the 1980s,'' he said. ``There's going to be opportunity to buy
property rights and turn around and sell them to market leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hanchuk, the patent lawyer, expects this sorting-out period
to be tumultuous. As patent portfolios fatten and as e-commerce
continues its explosive growth, he said, ``we will inevitably see a
significant increase in patent litigation involving e-commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   And the suits may not come only from competitors. Companies that
fail to protect their innovations may face lawsuits from
shareholders, warns Charles Eldering, president of Telecom Partners
Ltd., a company based in New Britain, Pa., that develops strategic
patent portfolios for telecommunications and Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   Rivette and others predict that within a few years many
companies will have the equivalent of a vice president for
intellectual property _ not a lawyer who shepherds applications
through the patent office, but rather an MBA who thinks
strategically about intellectual property.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see a chief patent strategist or the equivalent in most
corporations in the next three years,'' Rivette said.
``Intellectual property touches too much of the corporation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet already has become home to a number of online
intellectual property bazaars _ sites where companies can swap
technology through licensing deals or sell off trademarks, patents
or copyrights that the owner does not need but that another company
might find valuable.
</P>
<P>
   Among these new sites are www.yet2.com, which uses technology
developed by Rivette's Aurigin Systems;  &UR;  &LR; www.pl-x.com, which
specializes in technologies developed by universities, and
IPnetwork.com, which is weighted toward trademarks and copyrights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will bring in lots of new players,'' said Christine Hearst
Schwarzman, the president of IPnetwork. ``I have hundreds and
hundreds of companies from places in the world that are chronically
underrepresented areas of the licensing world.''
</P>
<P>
   And what will patents themselves look like in the future?
Ferguson of Anderson Consulting predicts that _ instead of
consisting of text and drawings as they have for more than two
centuries _ patents are likely to become mixed-media affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting into things that are darn difficult to explain
in prose,'' Ferguson said. ``Imagine the most graphical interface
possible,'' he said, referring to computer screens on which users
interact with images instead of issuing verbal commands. ``It's
almost impossible to describe it in text. But as soon as you see
the thing, you say, `Oh, I get it.' There may be a gap in the way
we have chosen to memorialize inventions.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
