<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTLOOK-AD-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET MAY PRECIPITATE TEMPEST FOR TRADITIONAL BRANDS AND
ADVERTISING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shakespeare's exclamation ``O, brave new world'' is an
appropriate way to begin an examination of what advertising will be
like when years no longer begin with 19. It is even more
appropriate that those words are from ``The Tempest'' because the
changes facing Madison Avenue in the next decade will be nothing if
not tumultuous.
</P>
<P>
   The primary reason is, of course, the sudden emergence of
interactive communications as a significant way to sell goods and
services. The Internet is a transforming technology; between it and
the frenetic pace of the digital revolution, advertising will never
be the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the Internet becomes part of the fabric of our existence,
the ad dollars are going to follow the consumers,'' said Kevin
O'Connor, chief executive at DoubleClick in New York, the
interactive advertising network. ``And consumers will be on the
Internet for everything: communications, transactions, getting
one-to-one broadcasts of interactive TV, reading classified
advertising, even voting online.''
</P>
<P>
   His forecast was echoed by Kyle Shannon, chief creative officer
at Agency.com in New York, an interactive shop whose clients
include Bank of America, Compaq Computer, Sprint and Texaco. ``The
Internet won't be just a place you go when you get on the
computer,'' Shannon said. ``It will become like a dial tone, part
of everyday life.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the fundamental shifts that will take place as a result,
Shannon listed: ``immediacy, people will want it right now, 24
hours a day; ubiquity, they will want it wherever they are;
transparency, they will be able to find out anything, and
relevancy, they will want it to relate directly to them, not to a
mass market.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is going to change the nature of relationships
between marketers and customers, online and off-line,'' he said.
``You're going to have the opportunity of true one-to-one
marketing; advertising that's segmented, accountable, increasingly
sophisticated.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Patrick Keane, senior analyst and director for
online advertising strategies at Jupiter Communications in New
York, the consulting company, predicted a day when ``advertisers
will be able to buy consumers by targeted profiles, saying, `I want
Cadillac-driving golfers who like to knit.''' The consumer, in
turn, will be able to click on the ad and buy, say, an expensive
golf sweater or a kit to knit golf club covers.
</P>
<P>
   To make that happen, advertisers will require ``a persistent
Internet connection in the home that's on all the time, like your
electricity,'' Keane said, ``as opposed to what we have now, when
people find it a pain to fire up the PC and dial into the modem.''
But that should not be a problem, he added, as interactive
technology continues to advance. In fact, Jupiter predicts that
online ad spending will nearly quadruple to $11.5 billion for the
year 2003 from $3.2 billion this year and $4.7 billion next year.
</P>
<P>
   What will this mean for advertising?
</P>
<P>
   ``What advertising accomplished in the 20th century was to
create equity for brands,'' said G.M. O'Connell, chairman and chief
executive at Modem Media.Poppe Tyson in Norwalk, Conn., an
interactive agency that works for marketers including American
Express, Citigroup and Intel.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 21st century, what companies do on the Internet _ how
they communicate, do business, serve customers _ will drive more
equity into brands, but in a completely different way,'' he added.
``Advertising on the Internet is not going to work the way
advertising on TV works.''
</P>
<P>
   ``TV advertising lets you get close to a brand by laughing,
crying, feeling emotion,'' O'Connell said. ``Internet advertising
lets you get close to a brand by understanding how it serves you:
helping you plan a vacation, make dinner, get the kids off to
school on time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We watch TV; we read print; we use the Internet,'' he added.
``So if advertising isn't useful, it won't work for the consumer _
or the advertiser.''
</P>
<P>
   That, clearly, will have profound implications. ``The Internet
will inevitably, in the long term, slow the growth of ad spending
in all traditional media,'' said Chris Charron, research director
at Forrester Research in Cambridge, Mass. ``But as interactive TV
takes hold, the distinction between interactive advertising and
traditional broadcast TV advertising will be obliterated.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Interactive TV will, in a sense, be the savior of broadcast
advertising,'' he added, ``because now a lot of money goes into
broadcast with no real ability to generate or gauge response. In
the future, we'll combine the advantages of broadcast advertising,
the richness, the entertainment values, with the opportunities for
direct selling, direct commerce, you get with the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   The agencies that grow, Charron said, will be those ``that
provide solutions for advertisers across different media, that
collect data across different media, that take a much more
integrated view of marketing.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the fastest-growing category for most types of
traditional media like television, radio, print and outdoor is ad
spending by the dot-coms and other online marketers. According to
Competitive Media Reporting, which tracks ad spending, dot-com
spending in off-line media soared to $546.2 million in 1998 from
$278.7 million in 1997. The Myers Report, a media newsletter,
estimated the 1999 total will be at least $1.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   There are no estimates for 2000 or beyond, but in one field at
least spending will be higher next year. Dot-coms are buying
commercial time on Super Bowl XXXIV on Jan. 30, 2000, for an
estimated average of $2.1 million to $2.2 million for each
30-second spot, with some spots selling for as much as $3 million.
That compares with about $1.6 million for a 30-second commercial
during the Super Bowl in 1999, $1.3 million in 1998 and $1.2
million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the influx of dot-com dollars, the head of one of the
world's largest agencies agreed with Charron that agencies must
change. ``We will have to transform our organizations,'' said Keith
Reinhard, chairman and chief executive at the DDB Worldwide
Communications Group in New York, the unit of the Omnicom Group
that works for marketers as varied as Anheuser-Busch, Clorox,
McDonald's and Volkswagen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have to understand brands so well that we're not only
building new brands and restoring and refreshing existing brands,''
Reinhard said, ``but creating brands and licensing them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And we will be advising clients on every aspect of brand
strategy,'' he added, assuming tasks now performed by consultants.
As the media now considered old and new, like television and
personal computers, come together in what is known as convergence,
agencies will become content providers, Reinhard said, reclaiming a
role they played from the 1930s through the 1950s, first in
national network radio and then in TV's early days.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if we're going to be in the content business, I would not
be surprised if a big ad agency merged with a big entertainment
company,'' he added. ``The convergence we should be thinking of is
the convergence of entertainment, information and interactive
one-on-one selling as inter-tainment.'''
</P>
<P>
   Does ``That's Inter-tainment'' have the same ring as ``That's
Entertainment''? It's one more question to be answered as the new
millennium unfolds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
