<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTLOOK-READER-VISIONS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELEPORTATION, POLYGRAPH IMPLANTS AND OTHER WAYS TO IMPROVE LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., N.J., Ill., Md., N.Y.)  (mk) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Asked for proposals to improve the human condition in the next
century, people were generous with their ideas. Many visions fell
into broad categories like health, nutrition, education and
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Proposals, including those of Times editors who could not resist
the challenge, ranged from cures for all ailments and correction of
genetic flaws to eternal youth and immortality. There were
suggestions for a morning-after pill for undisciplined eaters;
cheap, nonpolluting energy; suburban mailboxes with solar-powered
interior lights; self-erasing blackboards; and a universal
operating system for all computers.
</P>
<P>
   And on a shrinking but linguistically diverse planet, more than
one reader suggested devices to provide instant translations.
</P>
<P>
   Many readers will surely applaud the idea of a ``hold time''
detector, a device to inform a telephone caller of the projected
wait until a real human being answers. And what about homes (with
absolutely silent air-conditioners) where uncomplaining robots
would clean, cook, do the laundry and get rid of the trash? And
would the electorate vote for a polygraph chip to be implanted in
all public officials, political candidates, industrial leaders and
others as needed?
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, many people want more time. Some would settle for an
extra day to be squeezed between Sunday and Monday to deal with the
weekend's unfinished chores. But real visionaries, like Dean Kross
of Pittsburgh, go all out for expanding time by slowing the earth's
rotation, thus lengthening each day by an hour or two.
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Soloway of Geneva, Ill., foresees a sensor cuff, like a
blood pressure monitor, that will help her diet. Just as she is
doing well on tofu and cottage cheese, in comes an invitation to
dinner. On goes her cuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine: I've been rehearsing an order of spaghetti with just
a bit of olive oil, but my mouth is beginning to form `ravioli with
three cheeses,''' she writes. ``At that moment, the cuff, which is
already measuring my guilt-induced blood pressure, is also gauging
the rising output of my salivary glands. Both mounting measures
cause the sensor in the cuff to react.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have choices here. Barbaric: a slight shock similar to the
invisible fence some poor doggies contend with. Inspirational: a
voice _ I'll choose Bette Midler's _ singing out: `You can do it,
girl. Resist!' Visual: On the tiny built-in video display, up pop
`Before' and `After' photos linked to my pending food selection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, for my device to really work, it must produce immediate
rewards. Since we're being asked to be truly creative, here's my
wish: Just as soon as I nix the ravioli and cheese dish and opt
instead for the lighter version, my clothing size slides down one
number. At the same time, on the spot, one facial wrinkle
disappears. Forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Contemplating the workplace, Gil Gordon, of Monmouth Junction,
N.J., said he would like to sneak into the bedrooms of the 1,000
top chief executives one night and implant a ``get a life'' chip
into their brains.
</P>
<P>
   ``This chip would cause them to walk around their offices at 6
every night and ask people at their desks, `Why are you still
here?''' Gordon writes. ```Why couldn't you get your work done
earlier and be out of here by now?'
</P>
<P>
   ``We have slipped into a work culture where long hours are
rewarded _ often independent of any assessment of incremental value
added. It's time to stop rewarding desk time and face time and
start rewarding improved effectiveness and smarter work habits,
and, in the process, help today's overworked employees start to
regain some time for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Michael Pennacchia of Manhattan asks: ``How about the universal
chip card? It's one card that, through a chip or some advanced
technology, serves as a driver's license, credit card, bank card,
employee ID, gym membership, phone card, debit card, key card,
etc., and eliminates the waste, bulk and confusion of having so
many cards.''
</P>
<P>
   For those tired of losing umbrellas, Marc Wallace of Manhattan
proposes a force field, like an invisible bubble, that will repel
precipitation.
</P>
<P>
   And Bonnie Hilton of Chicago would dearly like to read an actual
book _ not something on a computer screen _ while (1) lying down
and (2) without having to hold it. In fact, while doing any sort of
desk work or reading, she would like to rest her neck on a plush
pillow in bed or on the beach without the effort of gripping the
materials. ``Your neck and back get total rest while you are
getting your work done,'' she writes.
</P>
<P>
   Weary of the strains of travel even in the age of supersonic
flight, many people wished for speedier trips _ teleportation, say.
``I cannot wait until the day that I simply step into a chamber and
am conveniently whisked from that location to any location on earth
that is predetermined and encoded into the machine prior to
departure,'' writes Tachi Taylor of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The creation of such a technology will have tremendous impact
on the future of our world; it would render all forms of
conventional transportation obsolete, not to mention conventional
civic structures, such as freeways and airports. It could result in
significant reductions in pollution, congestion and accidental
death from auto and plane crashes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I, for one, cannot wait until that day when I never have to
get on a bus, plane, ferry, subway or taxi ever again. What a
wonderful world such an innovation would create!''
</P>
<P>
   But what's the use of such high-speed travel if the baggage is
still stuck in the low-tech era?
</P>
<P>
   As a frequent airline traveler, Julius Westheimer of Baltimore
has no doubt what he wants _ substantial improvement of baggage
claim.
</P>
<P>
   He writes: ``Despite all the technological advances of this
century _ autos, radios, jet travel, television, men on the moon,
camera on Mars, computers, etc. _ one thing has not changed in over
50 years: the way we mill around like cattle (often tired, hungry
and impatient after a long flight), endlessly awaiting our luggage
and then clumsily grabbing and lifting it as it crawls around the
carousel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not an engineer, but there must be a better way.''
</P>
<P>
   For the earthbound, Andy Kaplan of Lawrenceville, N.J., proposes
cars with electronic navigators, all of them networked by
satellite. ``Passengers only have to type in a destination, and the
driving computer will operate the car,'' he writes. ``Because of
the navigational network, every car will know where every other car
is headed. This will reduce or entirely eliminate accidents and
will allow for increased speeds of travel. This hands-free and
nonpersonal driving will eliminate road rage as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the bravest of all the futurists is Dorothy Dworkin of
Lido Beach, N.Y., who says she is submitting her major suggestion
``at the risk of being labeled a curmudgeon.'' Finishing up a list
of proposals like banning cell phones in public places, closing
chat rooms, confining e-mail to business and confiscating the
television sets of parents who permit young children to exceed a
watching limit of an hour a day, she says:
</P>
<P>
   ``We are on our way to becoming a nation of `e-strangers,'
unable to communicate with one another in a face-to-face manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``For our own benefit, and the benefit of mankind, I propose a
moratorium on the design of further electronic devices. We need the
time to assess where we are headed and where we want to go as a
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone has to be a codger, and it might as well be me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
