<SLUG> BC-OUTLOOK-OUTDATED-PRODUCTS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE HAVE YOU GONE, FLYPAPER, TYPEWRITERS, WINDUP WATCHES, ET AL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Phonograph records, flypaper, typewriters, windup watches,
carbon paper. They are products that most people of a certain age
grew up with but that have largely vanished, usually with little
notice, from everyday life. Something presumably better has taken
their place.
</P>
<P>
   But while they are forgotten by many, they are not gone.
</P>
<P>
   At least not entirely. These venerable products, though long
past their heyday, live on in tiny niches of the giant U.S.
economy. Indeed, unlike, say, rotary telephones, which linger in
numbers large enough to command special treatment by answering
machines but are no longer placed in service, they are still
produced.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, on the eve of the 21st century there are Americans who go
to work each morning to make typewriters _ not, of course, the type
your father used in college but the genuine article nonetheless.
Some of these machines _ descendants of the first practical
typewriters marketed in 1874 by E. Remington &AMP; Sons, a gunsmith in
Ilion, N.Y. _ find their way to technophobes or slaves to habit,
others to consumers who find them irreplaceable for certain tasks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We dominate a shrinking market,'' said Jim Joseph, a spokesman
for Lexmark International, a spinoff in Lexington, Ky., from the
International Business Machines Corp. that is the nation's last
remaining typewriter manufacturer. But while its typewriter
business is so small that it does not even rate a mention in the
annual report, an undisclosed number of customers fork over $695
for its Wheelwriter 1000 for home and classroom use, or $1,845 for
its top-of-the-line Wheelwriter 7000.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, according to Joseph, typewriters were in persistent
demand for addressing envelopes, but the word processor and
computer have now largely usurped this function, leaving multipart
forms _ themselves under technological siege _ one of the few
remaining efficient applications.
</P>
<P>
   But typewriter traditionalists do not need gobs of money as long
as they are content with a foreign make, like the $189.95 portable
made by Olivetti S.p.A., prominently on display just inside
Hammacher Schlemmer's store on East 57th Street in New York and
advertised in its catalog. This one, made in Italy, is billed as an
``updated classic'' boasting automatic paragraph indentation and
other refinements.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of people who wouldn't convert'' to computerized
ways to write, said Simone Williams, a sales clerk.
</P>
<P>
   A company spokeswoman, Sabrina Balthazar, said Hammacher sells
dozens of Olivettis each day through its three stores and by
catalog and Web site, &UR;  &LR;  enough demand to justify stocking them
year-round rather than just at Christmas. While some of this year's
sales appear to be related to Year 2000 fears of crashing word
processors, she added, ``We have no plans to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's flypaper,  &UR;  &LR; created by a German baker in 1861 who
grew tired of shooing insects attacking his strudel, and &UR;  &LR; 
sometimes &UR;  &LR; still &UR;  &LR; found on America's patios.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's still a common item,'' said Dale Garbutt, a salesman at
Barson Hardware, also in Midtown Manhattan, explaining that today's
electronic bug-zappers are not fully up to the task. ``You'd never
catch a mosquito'' with them, he said, while the traditional,
though unsightly, stuff that results in a lingering death is said
to work on all kinds of winged pests.
</P>
<P>
   Christine Morrello, office manager at the Walco-Linck Co., a
Rockland County, N.Y., packager of flypaper mostly from Korea, said
it still seemed to be popular with people who run horse farms and
waterfront restaurants and that on occasion someone will inquire
about shipping an order to relatives in South America.
</P>
<P>
   As for mechanical watches, they are actually in the midst of a
comeback, even though the Timex Corp., the nation's No. 1 watch
producer, closed its last factory making them, in Waterbury, Conn.,
three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony J. D'Ambrosio, executive vice president of Tourneau, a
leading retailer of luxury watches, &UR;  &LR;  said sales of mechanical
watches began to pick up in the mid-'80s, largely coinciding with
stock market gains.
</P>
<P>
   The revival also comes in the face of the dispiriting fact that
with few if any exceptions, the cheapest of modern quartz watches
will keep better time than the most expensive of windups.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers clearly have more than exactitude in mind when buying
mechanical watches, however; most are imported from Geneva and
other French-speaking parts of Switzerland and are quite expensive,
with prices starting at several hundred dollars. One David Yurman
mechanical design _ featuring a stainless steel and sterling silver
pave diamond case with diamond bezel and sapphire cabochon crown,
silver dial and diamond markers _ retails for $14,000 at Tourneau.
</P>
<P>
   Another presumed casualty of the age is carbon paper, which
turns out to be as persistent in the market as it is in smearing
clothing or hands. A few thousand tons are still produced for
purposes ranging from business forms _ it is especially valued in
cold climates where its carbonless successor can fail _ to dress
patterns to impressions of teeth, for use in in dental offices.
Frye Tech of Boca Raton, Fla., has absorbed competitors and is now
the biggest maker.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most unlikely of the survivors, perhaps, is the vinyl
phonograph record, which, despite the fact that it requires a
similarly superseded mechanism to play, remains in demand,
especially among disc jockeys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies make them pretty much to sell to the D.J.'s,'' said
Michael Davis, manager of Academy Records &AMP; CD's off lower Fifth
Avenue in Manhattan. ``They like to play vinyl because they
manipulate the turntable'' to pinpoint certain passages. D.J.'s and
others also use the old-fashioned record _ only 33 r.p.m.'s are
thought to be still manufactured _ to create new musical blends,
like acid jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, contended Blake Lindberg, an Academy salesman,
audiophiles often prefer vinyl, still made by companies like Blue
Note Records and Analog Productions, to its audiotape and CD
successors for sheer quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot warmer sound,'' he said. ``It's so much fuller. I
can hear a lot more.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, sales of vinyl records peaked more than 20 years ago, at
344 million units in 1977, and will total only an estimated 2.8
million this year, according to the Record Industry Association of
America. Records now account for only one-half of 1 percent of the
market for new music, and a whole generation has grown up having
never even seen one.
</P>
<P>
   This means they will probably have no clue when the quizmaster
asks that standby trivia question from Mom's generation:
</P>
<P>
   How many grooves are there on a record?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: two (one on each side).
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-19-99 1932EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991219.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-19 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3498 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-SYRIA-NYT &LR;      12-19 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-SYRIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK HOPES SYRIA WILL AGREE ON CORE ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Prime Minister Ehud Barak told his Cabinet on Sunday
that Israel would seek an initial ``core agreement'' with Syria
when the two sides start intensive talks near Washington on Jan. 3,
fleshing out the details of a full peace treaty later.
</P>
<P>
   Reporting to his government on the resumption of talks with
Syria in Washington last week, Barak said the two sides had
discussed the future ``product'' of their negotiations. An
understanding was reached to work toward a preliminary agreement on
the major points in dispute as a prelude to a final treaty, Israeli
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Barak told the Cabinet that ``there's no point in a brief
document, and no logic in completing hundreds of pages of a full
peace treaty'' in the talks that begin next month, his office said.
``We should strive for a core agreement that will summarize the
main issues,'' it quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
   In a television interview on Saturday night, he suggested that
it should not take months to complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to find a way to walk between a thin, meaningless
one-page document of principles, for which it's not worth risking a
crisis, and a full, detailed peace treaty, which is a document
hundreds of pages long and which can take months to write,'' Barak
told Channel 2 television.
</P>
<P>
   Several teams of Israeli and Syrian negotiators are expected to
meet simultaneously to discuss borders, security arrangements,
water rights, establishment of normal relations and the situation
in southern Lebanon. Guerrillas there, backed by Iran and Syria,
are fighting to oust Israeli troops holding what Israel considers a
buffer zone to prevent cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Barak told the Cabinet ministers that he had made no prior
commitment to meet a Syrian demand for a full Israeli withdrawal
from the Golan Heights to lines held before the strategic area was
captured in the 1967 Arab-Israeli war.
</P>
<P>
   But in his televised remarks, Barak indicated that he was
building on understandings reached in previous negotiations and
contacts, which Syria asserts included the promise of a full
withdrawal. Israel denies that.
</P>
<P>
   ``My government has no prior commitment to the Syrians,'' Barak
said. ``On the other hand, we are not erasing the past.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited talks with the Syrians at the 1991 Middle East peace
conference in Madrid, negotiations conducted by Prime Ministers
Yitzhak Rabin and Shimon Peres from 1993 to 1996, and secret
contacts pursued by Barak's immediate predecessor, Benjamin
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations ahead will be tough, and their outcome is far
from certain, Barak warned the Cabinet. ``I have no doubt that just
as the Syrians were bitter rivals in battle, so the thought that
the negotiations will be like margarine is an exaggerated
expectation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to concerns voiced by Palestinian officials that he
might slow down the talks with them as he negotiates with Syria,
Barak told the Cabinet that he had made clear in Washington that he
would ``conduct straightforward negotiations without manipulation
between the parties.''
</P>
<P>
   On television Barak promised, ``We have no intention of playing
one track off the other, of trying to maneuver the Syrian track
against the Palestinian and vice versa.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Palestinian concerns were heightened when Barak canceled a
meeting Sunday in Jericho with Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian
leader. Barak accused the Palestinians of disclosing in advance
what was to have been a secret meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Some Palestinian officials and analysts have expressed fears
that the prime minister will prove unable to withstand domestic
political pressures against making territorial concessions on two
fronts at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   They worry that resistance from rightist Jewish nationalists to
a troop withdrawal and removal of Israeli settlements from the
Golan Heights could harden Barak's position on a pullout from the
West Bank and Gaza Strip, where the Palestinians want to declare a
state.
</P>
<P>
   Rabin moved slowly in talks with the Syrians as he negotiated
controversial accords with the Palestinians and reached a peace
treaty with Jordan. Peres broke off talks with the Syria in
February 1996 after a series of Palestinian suicide bomb attacks in
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, in contrast, asserts that he is ready to pursue parallel
talks with the Syrians and Palestinians with equal vigor. What is
at stake, he says, is no less than an end to a 100-year war and a
breakthrough to the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peace with our neighbors,'' he told the ministers, ``is the
realization of Zionism.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
