<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REDSKINS-COLTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANNING'S TURNAROUND AGAINST REDSKINS SYMBOLIZES COLTS THIS
SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ It had been a rough Sunday afternoon for
quarterback Peyton Manning. He was taking some good shots to the
body, and one to the knees, from a suddenly perky Washington
Redskins defense. The man who tosses footballs as if his brain has
radar was uncharacteristically overthrowing his receivers.
</P>
<P>
   Then came one of those drives when Manning, the quarterback for
Indianapolis, showed why he could likely play in the next 10 Pro
Bowls. He gathered his composure and his aching body and led the
Colts on a seven-play, 80-yard drive that would be the beginning of
the end for the Redskins. On that drive Manning's first pass was a
dart to his favorite receiver, Marvin Harrison, for 28 yards. His
last was a 1-yard touchdown to tight end Ken Dilger that floated
between three bewildered defenders, making the score 17-13 early in
the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   On the first play of the Colts' next drive, Manning threw an
11-yard strike to running back Edgerrin James. The Colts later
scored and led by 11. Indianapolis' defense, led by the former
Giants defensive end Chad Bratzke, then took over the game and
stopped a late comeback by the Redskins to ensure the Colts' 24-21
victory.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson is, that while it is possible to frustrate Manning,
to slow him, to bludgeon him, no one has found a way to stop him
completely.
</P>
<P>
   If you put Manning's blood under a microscope, those little DNA
strands would probably be in the shape of a football. When a player
is blessed with such natural instincts, he is practically
impossible to lock up for an entire game. The Redskins tried.
Defensive coordinator Mike Nolan reached deep into his bag of
tricks and pulled out Bill Belichick, or at least what Belichick
has done this season with the Jets to hamper Manning.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins used a variety of blitzes to hurry Manning's throws
and mixed up their secondary coverages so that Manning rarely knew
which Redskins player was doing what at the pre-snap read. What no
defensive guru can account for, however, is that desire to win that
Manning has.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake about it: The reason the Colts captured the A FC
East was Manning. It is no coincidence that this season was the one
in which Manning developed into a premier player and Indianapolis
went from division cellar-dweller to champion. The Colts have won
10 straight games and their nine-game improvement thus far from
last year ties a league record held by the 1929 Giants and the 1963
Oakland Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it's been a fast turnaround,'' said Manning, who
completed 23 of 37 passes for 298 yards and one interception.
``It's definitely come faster than we expected. We knew we'd be a
better football team this year, but we didn't know we'd be this
good.''
</P>
<P>
   The Colts are 12-2 and piling up records the way a New Year's
Eve party host stocks up champagne. The Colts won their first
division title since the strike-shortened 1987 season, and their 12
victories are one shy of the team-record 13 set in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis' division crown is all the more impressive because
it won by far the toughest division in football rather easily after
most prognosticators said the Colts would finish last.
</P>
<P>
   Bratzke was with the Giants when they won the NFC East in 1997
but said this one was sweeter because ``no one, I mean no one,
thought we would do this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And to be honest, very few people in this locker room ever
imagined this would happen,'' said Bratzke, who is having a Pro
Bowl season with 12 sacks. ``I can't blame people if they picked us
last. But that tells you how much heart this team has.''
</P>
<P>
   It showed late in the game against Washington. After the Colts
took a 24-13 lead with just over five minutes left, the Redskins
started a comeback. Running back Brian Mitchell scored from 6 yards
out and Washington converted the 2-point attempt when quarterback
Brad Johnson (16 of 30 for 237 yards) found wide receiver Michael
Westbrook in the right corner of the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Washington (8-6), which still can win the NFC East, was making
its late-game run without its leading rusher, Stephen Davis, who
seriously injured his ankle late in the second quarter and did not
play the second half. He had run for 70 yards on 14 carries.
</P>
<P>
   After their touchdown, the Redskins' James Thrash, a backup wide
receiver, tracked down Brett Conway's wobbly onside kick at
Washington's 46-yard line. But the Redskins were not able to take
advantage. On fourth down and 9 at Washington's 47, Johnson threw
to Westbrook on the left sideline, but the ball sailed far over his
head.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game was ours to control towards the end, but we just
didn't come up with plays,'' Redskins defensive end Dan Wilkinson
said. ``I am never going to feel good about losing this game
because I felt we were the better team.''
</P>
<P>
   After Johnson's pass fell incomplete, the Colts began
celebrating on the field, acting as if they had just earned a trip
to the Super Bowl. But excuse them for being giddy.
</P>
<P>
   The Colts had just won their first division title in 12 years.
They are entitled to a little leeway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-19-99 1954EST &QL; 
