<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-YOUNG-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENTS SEARCH FOR SPIRITUAL ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MAUREEN JENKINS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's 7 o'clock Sunday night during finals week at Arizona State
Univer sity, and there's standing room only at the All Saints
Catholic Newman Center Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Most weekends, about 1,300 stu dents pile in to the
non-traditional sanctuary for the center's five Masses. During
finals, the Rev. Nathan Castle says, the number swells about 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Do they come to pray for good grades? Some probably do, Castle
jokes. But for those who regularly attend, the Newman Center Mass
offers a connection that goes beyond the liturgy and familiar
hymns.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the 21st century, at ASU and secular schools
across the Phoenix area, students are exploring things spiritual _
whether through organized religion or less defined means.
</P>
<P>
   Picking up on that interest, schools are offering new courses,
and students are taking part in campus groups that let them delve
into spirituality and faith on their own terms.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Castle says, they're looking for ``a place to ask the
questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Rachel Morgan, 25, comes to the Newman Center weekly, hoping a
word from Father Nathan's homily _ or the flute and guitar band up
front _ will send her back to her books spiritually refreshed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does feel more comfortable knowing everybody here is your
age,'' said Morgan, a doctoral chem istry student from Missouri.
``It's nice to know God is alive in the hearts of young people.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Baldenegro, 27, a junior, comes every two or three weeks,
craving the fellowship the Newman Center provides.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I feel I get caught up in things I shouldn't get
caught up in,'' the aeronautical engineering major said, ``and
(Mass) brings me back to my roots. It makes me realize what is
important, or what should be important.''
</P>
<P>
   Betty DeBerg, a University of Northern Iowa professor conducting
a national study of college students' attitudes toward religion,
said young adulthood ``has been traditionally been understood as a
time when people begin to question the values and perspectives in
which they were reared.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only are they the right age,'' she said, ``but they're
taking classes that expose them to ideas they'd never faced before.
In many ways, they're seeking and putting together their own
identity.''
</P>
<P>
   Her three-year project, conducted jointly with professors at
Indiana University and the University of Wyoming, looks at campus
life at four U.S. schools.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent CNN/USA Today/Gal lup poll, 48 percent of American
young adults 18 to 29 said religion was ``very important'' in their
lives. In the Phoenix area, similar interest shows up at the
college level.
</P>
<P>
   For example, students at Estrella Mountain Community College in
Avondale formally launched a Christian Students Association this
semester _ and it's already the largest student group on campus.
</P>
<P>
   Over the decade, student interest led ASU's religious studies
depart ment, already one of the nation's largest, to expand to 82
classes this year from 51 classes in 1991. One of the newest looks
at religions in the American Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   Prompted by years of requests, Paradise Valley Community College
finally added a class on personal spirituality this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Miller, 25, couldn't wait to sign up.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, I'd been searching,'' said Miller, who thinks
she might like to study anthropology or social work. ``I was kind
of curious to see what other people say about life and God, and
religion in general.''
</P>
<P>
   The course, instructor Jim Rubin says, was ``about asking the
ques tions that 99.9 percent of people never ask themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who grew up without religious instruction, feels discon
nected from ritual and dogma. Taking Rubin's class helped her
validate her own spiritual path, which includes meditation,
enjoying nature and reading about Eastern faiths.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made me feel more comfort able in my non-religiousness,''
she said. ``Because it's a very non-judg mental class, it's easy to
say how you feel or what you believe in, and no one is going to say
you're wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   According to 1998's The Ameri can Freshman, an annual survey
from the Higher Education Research Institute at UCLA, nearly 15
percent of all two- and four-year college freshmen reported being
unaffiliated with any religion. Just 10 years before, about 12
percent made this claim.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's hard to quantify whether today's students are more
or less spiritually minded than those decades ago, ASU Professor
Mark Woodward says some things haven't changed.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to college-age searching, ``most of the religious
themes that are operating today were established in the late
'60s.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't use the word then, but the notions of New Age reli
gions, alternative religions _ all those paradigms were really
estab lished (then),'' said Woodward, who teaches classes on
religion and popular culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Distrust of establishment and institutions that came about at
that time really never went away.''
</P>
<P>
   But what is different, Woodward says, is where today's students
look for answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the late 1960s, it was largely an undifferentiated
search,'' he said. ``Now, there are alternative institu tional
churches and organizations they'll get involved in, from neo-pa
ganism to a host of Buddhist organizations.''
</P>
<P>
   Some groups are mainstays on secular campuses _ Campus Cru sade
for Christ, Fellowship of Chris tian Athletes, Hillel student
centers for Jewish students. Not affiliated with the colleges they
draw from, and often located off-campus, these groups let students
express their faiths without the tie of specific houses of worship.
</P>
<P>
   But some, such as the Muslim Students Association at ASU, use
the nearby Islamic Cultural Center for daily prayers. During the
holy month of Ramadan, which Muslims now are celebrating, students
go to the mosque in the evenings for prayer and to break their
daytime fasts.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Holcomb, 21, a Jewish student at ASU, says it's impossible
to separate his faith from his daily life. The Phoenix native is
active at the Hillel Jewish Student Center, which, besides being
``somewhere to hang out,'' also gives students a place to bond with
those who share their tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a freshman living in the dorms, the only way to
have a Jewish lifestyle was to join Hillel,'' he said. ``There are
so many things customwise. So much of what Judaism does is in a
group. You can't be Jewish alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Hillel hosts Friday night Shabbat dinners celebrating
the Sabbath, Holcomb and other students drop in between classes or
late-night study breaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is both my temple and my meeting place,'' he said. ``Hillel
has really been the answer book, I suppose, to any questions I
have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
