<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-19 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3526 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-GIANTS-RAMS-NYT &LR;      12-19 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-RAMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH A DAZZLING CLINIC,THE RAMS GET THE GIANTS `OUT OF WHACK' 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The shoving after the whistle started early and
intensified, until there seemed to be an altercation after every
play _ a furious demonstration of the game's high stakes.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis Rams were playing to be the chief playoff hosts in
the NFC, with the advantage of home field throughout, while the New
York Giants were trying to prove they deserved at least an
invitation to that party.
</P>
<P>
   In this frenzied atmosphere, before the numbing roar inside the
Trans World Dome, the Giants unraveled as the Rams proved their
mettle.
</P>
<P>
   First, the game got away from the Giants, then the Rams ran
away.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis (12-2) proved why it is the NFC's best team Sunday,
disorienting the Giants offense and slicing through an overworked
Giants defense in a precise, unrelenting 31-10 victory that
glaringly displayed the difference between the conference's elite
and those chasing them.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams played at a different speed than the Giants (7-7),
churning out big plays even when the Giants defense was in proper
position. And the Rams played with poise while the Giants made one
destructive mistake after another _ two interceptions returned for
touchdowns, costly penalties, a missed field goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants even literally tripped over each other at the goal
line, ruining a chance for what might have been a pivotal
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, the Giants did not play with any of composure or
efficiency evident during the two-game winning streak they brought
to Sunday's game. The Giants got so caught up in after-the-whistle
altercations, they scrambled about the field, running just six
first-quarter plays. The Rams, as if by default, took a 10-0
first-half lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got too much into the emotion of the game,'' said Giants
coach Jim Fassel, whose team might still qualify for the playoffs
with victories over Minnesota Sunday and Dallas the week after.
``That hurt us because we didn't play evenly, we got too
up-and-down, too emotional.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants six penalties stunted the team's momentum and though
the Rams started slowly and dropped several early passes,
eventually a tired Giants defense saw the Rams big play makers _
quarterback Kurt Warner and running back Marshall Faulk _ turn the
game into a rout.
</P>
<P>
   ``A game like this,'' said Giants quarterback Kerry Collins.
``You can get out of whack. I think that's what happened to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins tried to settle his teammates in the huddle in the first
half but the Giants were still unbridled in their play. One
after-the-play fracas actually cost the Rams their touted left
tackle Orlando Pace, but other excesses of a similar kind cost the
Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the first half, when the Giants appeared to have stopped
the Rams deep in their territory and would have likely taken
possession in good field position, defensive tackle Keith Hamilton
was penalized for roughing the passer, killing any chance the
Giants had to diminish the Rams 10-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Giants started the second half with an impressive
drive, as a 22-yard pass from Collins to Tiki Barber brought the
Giants to the 2-yard line. But a first down pass failed, as did a
second-down run. On third down, attempting a new play, Giants guard
Ron Stone stepped on Collins' right foot as the quarterback pulled
back from center, and Collins fell to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The field goal the Giants kicked may have cut the Rams lead to
10-3, but it demoralized the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our momentum right there kind of stopped,'' Barber said. ``A
touchdown was what we needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Giants were out of the game. They even recovered a
Rams fumble on the next series. But the Rams defense seemed quicker
than the Giants anticipated. They shut down Giants running back Joe
Montgomery, who rushed for just 41 yards on 12 carries, and that
frequently forced the Giants into lengthy second and third-down
attempts.
</P>
<P>
   It was on one such third-and-11 that the game turned in the Rams
favor for good. Collins, throwing off his back foot, tried to
connect with wide receiver Ike Hilliard who was trying to find a
seam in the Rams secondary.
</P>
<P>
   Hilliard made a move during his route that slowed his progress
down the field, something Collins didn't anticipate. The pass was
long and the Rams' Devin Bush intercepted it, returning it 45 yards
for a 17-3 Rams lead.
</P>
<P>
   When the Giants' Cary Blanchard missed a 42-yard field goal
attempt early in the fourth quarter, what hope the Giants had left
seemed to dissipate.
</P>
<P>
   On the second play of the Rams next possession, Warner threw a
short pass Az-Zahir Hakim, who was cutting across the middle of the
field.
</P>
<P>
   Giants linebacker Jessie Armstead, who did not play to his usual
level and who seemed slower, as if he were injured, was the first
Giant to miss Hakim.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Emmanuel McDaniel then was faked out of his tackle
attempt. The last Giant with a chance, Percy Ellsworth, was blocked
and Hakim had a 65-yard touchdown pass.
</P>
<P>
   The last of the Rams points came when Mike Jones intercepted a
Collins pass and returned it 22 yards for a touchdown. The Giants
added an inconsequential 7-yard touchdown pass from Collins to
Hilliard late in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kerry didn't play real well,'' Fassel said. ``He missed some
passes. It was a lot like the rest of the team. Lots of mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   After the game, many Giants respectfully acknowledged that the
Rams had out-played them and there was a lesson in that.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game had a playoff game intensity,'' said Hamilton.
``That didn't surprise us. We knew what kind of game it was going
to be. But when you play a good team like this in this kind of
atmosphere, you have to keep yourself together and composed.
</P>
<P>
   ``And clearly, we didn't do that. We made too many bad
mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   By the game's end, there were no more fisticuffs on the field,
just celebration for the Rams, who relished their status as the
conference's winningest team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The road to Super Bowl goes through St. Louis,'' said Bush.
``There's no way to describe how much that means to this franchise,
which was down not too long ago. We've come a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants, meanwhile, left the field quietly _ without the
emotion they brought to the Trans World Dome roughly three hours
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In their locker room, Fassel was also calm. He told the team to
forget about the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Learn from this lesson,'' he said. ``But all our focus is on
Minnesota now. That's who we have to beat right now to keep this
season alive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
