<HEADER>
A3527 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS &LR;      12-19 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
The game was there for the taking.
</P>
<P>
   And this time, for a change, the Rockets took it.
</P>
<P>
   A team that couldn't win down the stretch suddenly was making
all the right moves _ well, most of them, anyway _ to pull out a
six-point victory over the Boston Celtics on Saturday night at
Compaq Center.
</P>
<P>
   The win, the Rockets' first in the post-Charles Barkley era,
ended a streak of five losses, snapping a seemingly endless string
of mental mistakes, missed shots and errors of omission and
commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was gigantic to have a game that became close and then
finish it out and get the win,'' said Rockets coach Rudy
Tomjanovich. ``Still, though, we created situations for them that
they didn't create for themselves by a decision of pressuring up in
the backcourt when we didn't have to (instead of) getting back and
making them go five-on-five.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I like learning situations when you still get the win.
Many times this year the mistakes that we made cost us the game,
and hopefully that's enough. But this was a positive, and I'm very
happy for the guys. They've been working hard; we've been so close,
and to get a tangible reward (is good).''
</P>
<P>
   And things haven't been so good for the Rockets since losing
Barkley to a ruptured quadriceps tendon Dec. 8. Since then, they
rallied from a 25-point deficit at Boston only to falter down the
stretch in a four-point loss. After getting blown out by New
Jersey, the Rockets came home to play New York, and their
fourth-quarter mistakes cost dearly in a 101-90 loss.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Wednesday's game at San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Despite playing the second game in a back-to-back situation,
having gone through the physical Knicks the night before, the
Rockets went toe-to-toe with the defending NBA champions. But,
again, crucial fourth-quarter mistakes gave the Spurs an 83-77
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was definitely important because just every other time we
had the lead in the fourth quarter, we let it go,'' said point
guard Steve Francis. ``And (against Boston on Saturday) we held on.
We had a couple of mental lapses, so I understand what coach was
mad about. We just have to get better at stuff like that in the
fourth quarter. We have to execute.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Rogers agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a big accomplishment for us to be able to hold
on in that fourth quarter because for some reason that seems to be
our nemesis,'' Rogers said. ``I think we think too much in the
fourth quarter instead of continuing to do the same things (that
got them the lead).
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have the fast break, then we're hesitant to run in the
fourth quarter instead of just going and completing plays. Once we
get that fourth quarter out of our minds and just play it like
basketball, we'll be a pretty hard team to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially when they execute the offense the way the Rockets did
against Boston on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just basketball,'' Tomjanovich said. ``The offense
makes the defense adjust by rotating a player in and double-teaming
_ and it could be on a post-up like we've seen in the old days with
Dream (Hakeem Olajuwon), it could be out on the floor in an
iso(lation) or it could be a pick-and-roll _ but two guys are on
one man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, if you get into good spacing and you have a guy cutting
to the basket, a big guy, which (Kelvin) Cato was doing last
(Saturday) night, then there are going to be open people. And now
it's just getting the ball to those open people _ knowing where
they are going to be and then getting used to those shots. Those
things take time, and we're doing better at that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earlier, they would double-team and we couldn't get the ball
out of the double. So their gamble, and it's really a gamble to put
two guys on one guy, was working for them. But now we're making
them pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich's system, thought by many to be structured and
rigid, Saturday night showed how fluid it can be. While still
reliant on spacing and predicated on offensive players drawing
double teams, the Rockets' system now draws that doubling defense
on the perimeter, where lightning-quick players such as Francis and
Cuttino Mobley use the expanded offensive area to create for
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better if they double farther out on the floor because it
creates another passing angle on the strong side (the side with the
ball),'' Tomjanovich said. ``And it's finally clicking in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
