u w BC-KENNEDY-PROFILE-ART-N     12-19 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCANDAL SPOKESMAN ON MOVE, EYES WIDE SHUT NO MORE 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It was just a year ago that James Kennedy, scandal
spin controller for the White House, experienced the worst day of a
very bad year.
</P>
<P>
   Bombs were falling on Iraq, the speaker of the House of
Representatives stunned the country by resigning over a sex
scandal, and the House was poised to impeach the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a sense of things spinning out of control that was
palpable,'' Kennedy said in an interview late last week. ``We were
looking over the edge into some sort of abyss and it caused the
body politic to step back and catch our breath. It was ultimately a
cathartic moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, faint echoes of the Clinton scandals were heard in
Washington, as Monica Lewinsky took the stand in the Maryland
wiretapping trial of her former friend Linda Tripp, and John Huang
testified before Congress on the fund-raising abuses of the 1996
presidential campaign. But in a sign of how things have changed,
the events were mere blips on the media radar as the nation has
turned its attention to investing in Internet stocks, shopping and
the 2000 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   And after 10 relatively quiet months on the scandal front, the
White House announced this week it was shutting its scandal spin
control shop.
</P>
<P>
   Some might say this represents a victory of hope over history.
The Clinton White House and its pursuers in Congress and the
independent counsel's office have generated a seemingly endless
series of scandals and investigations.
</P>
<P>
   But the Washington scandal industry has gone into a slump since
the Senate acquitted President Clinton in February, and the White
House now feels emboldened to reassign Kennedy, its laconic scandal
mouthpiece, to the more peaceable environs of the press office.
</P>
<P>
   That is not necessarily a good omen. Two weeks after Kennedy
accepted the job in the White House counsel's office in January
1998, the Lewinsky matter erupted. But Joe Lockhart, the White
House press secretary, expressed confidence last week that the
president's last year in office would be dominated by debates over
Social Security and foreign policy and not by some new blue-dress
bombshell.
</P>
<P>
   So Kennedy will move from the counsel's office to the White
House press office, where he will address questions on education
and entitlement reform and leave behind the world of subpoenas and
executive privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said he was delighted. At the peak of the impeachment
battle, his beeper sounded as many as 100 times a day with queries
from reporters. In the last six months, he said, he has rarely been
paged more than five times a day, and the question is apt to arise
from a relatively mundane issue like campaign finance or Chinese
nuclear espionage.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, 46, is something of an accidental tourist in the realm
of scandal spin. He grew up in Wallingford, Conn., the son of
Robert T. and Beatrice Kennedy, a television repairman and an
office worker. He was a devotee (but not a relative) of the
Massachusetts Kennedys and remembers seeing President Kennedy in a
motorcade in 1962. Not a Boys' Nation handshake in the Rose Garden,
perhaps, but it helped hook him on politics.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy was an aide to Sen. Joseph I. Lieberman, D-Conn., for 18
years, without encountering a whiff of serious scandal. So it was a
shock for him to enter the White House last year and immediately be
inundated by questions on his boss' truthfulness and sexual
behavior. Clinton, forced to confront the truth in August 1998,
admitted that his actions were ``indefensible,'' leaving aides
stuttering to explain how they had spent seven months defending
them. Kennedy has a well-rehearsed answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I was ever called upon to defend what
happened,'' he said in the interview, over a beer at the Oval Room,
a restaurant near the White House. ``What we did was defend the
presidency and the people's choice in the last election.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's self-effacing manner is a contrast to that of his
predecessor at Spin Central, Lanny Davis, who wrote about the art
of selective packaging of facts in a book called ``Truth to Tell.''
The White House press office has drawn up a list of self-promoters
among current and former White House staff members. Kennedy is not
on it; Davis is solidly in the top 10.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy says he was handicapped for most of his tenure by being
in the dark about most aspects of the president's actions and his
legal team's strategy in the Lewinsky matter. His superiors in the
counsel's office provided little information _ in part to protect
him from an independent counsel's subpoena _ and he did not have
the authority to question the president directly. For much of 1998,
Kennedy was a spokesman with little to speak about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I couldn't know more,'' he said. ``That made it
difficult to build relationships with reporters that were based on
exchanges of information. I understood my role and simply tried to
be as responsive as I could under the circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said that he hoped everyone learned a lesson from the
impeachment debacle and that his old office was closed forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the position never has to be opened again, in this or
any other administration,'' he said. ``I hope part of the lesson of
the past year is that no good comes of the politics of scandal and
investigation. I hope that issues dominate the next campaign. I may
be naive, but I think the public wants that, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
