<HEADLINE>
THIS WEEK'S TV HIGHLIGHTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
TODAY 
Yikes! The Vikes have become the ``Not Ready for Prime Time
Players.'' And any comparison to the post-'70s ``Saturday Night
Live'' can't be a good thing. After winning five straight,
Minnesota has lost its last two _ both played under the lights for
the national TV audience. This'll be No. 3. It plays right into
Brett Favre's injured hand. NFL: Green Bay at Minnesota, Channel 7,
6 p.m. 
TUESDAY 
Jim Valvano and Pete Newell may have been complete opposites as
college basketball coaches _ one was flamboyant and full of
emotion, the other calm and calculated _ but each got similar
results. To honor them, tournaments in their name continue,
appropriately, on opposite sides of the country. College
basketball: Jimmy V Classic in East Rutherford, N.J.: North
Carolina vs. Indiana, ESPN, 4 p.m. and Florida vs. Rutgers, ESPN, 6
p.m.; Pete Newell Challenge in Oakland: Stanford vs. Mississippi
State, FSN, 6 p.m.; Cal vs. Gonzaga, FSN, 8:30 p.m. 
WEDNESDAY 
Fat, drunk and stupid is no way to go into a couple of important
Pacific Division contests. NHL: Kings at San Jose, FSN, 7:30 p.m.
(Also: FSN has the Kings' home game Sunday against Phoenix at 7:30
p.m.) 
THURSDAY 
There are the nightly hissy fits by enraged ex-lovers on
``Springer,'' and then there's the clay-flinging brawls of
Celebrity Deathmatch. Even in Play-Doh, a Ben Affleck vs. Matt
Damon slapfest provides greater entertainment than a WWF Smackdown
bout. At least sponsors haven't pulled their ads from this series.
``Celebrity Deathmatch'' marathon, MTV, 5:30 p.m. to 10 p.m. 
FRIDAY 
'Twas the day before Christmas and all through the league, not a
franchise was stirring, except these two dweebs. NFL: Dallas at New
Orleans, Channel 11, noon. 
SATURDAY 
So what has changed over the past six months since the Spurs ran
over the Lakers on their way to an NBA title? Anyone... anyone? The
Lakers have a new coach, yes. And a new arena, yes. And they have a
new power forward to help Shaq out against Duncan and Robinson...
uh, no. Check under the tree. Did we miss that present? NBA: San
Antonio at Lakers, Channel 4, 6:30 p.m. (NBC also has the New
York-Indiana game at 4 p.m.)  
SUNDAY 
If the best-game-available theory applies to L.A. _ and don't you
think it oughtta? _ we get a pretty good shot at watching at least
one of these titanic battles. NFL: Buffalo at New England or
Jacksonville at Tennessee, Channel 2, 10 a.m.; Green Bay at Tampa
Bay, Channel 11, 1 p.m. 

