<HEADLINE>
YOU WANNA SHOW US SOME I.D., SON?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Jest-case scenario for the Dodgers and this
!ital!stinky Adrian Beltre situation:
</P>
<P>
   Baseball says the Dodgers can keep him.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre's people file a grievance.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers renegotiate and sign Beltre to a huge contract.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre and agent Scott Boras go out to celebrate. Boras buys
Beltre a drink. Gets arrested for serving alcohol to a minor.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers nix Beltre's salary from the payroll, trading him to the
Cubs for a snowplow....
</P>
<P>
   __The Dodgers let Matt Herges wear No. 55 last year. Now, put it
down and back away....
</P>
<P>
   __Sure, this won't become Orel-mania II, but it could be an
incredible stimulation....
</P>
<P>
   __The Angels can't figure out how to give away the same Jim
Edmonds they decided was too valuable to send to Oakland for Mark
McGwire....
</P>
<P>
   __No matter where Ken Griffey Jr. ends up, Seattle fans will
have one more time to vent. Safeco Field hosts the 2001 All-Star
Game....
</P>
<P>
   __Did Notre Dame's punishment fit the crime? They'll eventually
have to answer to a higher authority _ the boosters....
</P>
<P>
   __Those nutty Rush brothers oughtta just sign with WB for their
own sitcom while they're a hot item....
</P>
<P>
   __Stanford's climb to the top of the basketball polls will no
doubt draw more attention to the Collins twins and their complete
opposite demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   Such as: In the Cardinal press guide, each player supplies
answers to a list of questions to go with their bio. When asked
``If a movie was made of my life, I would have the following actor
play me,'' Jason Collins answered ``Samuel L. Jackson. Jarron
Collins answered ``Gary Coleman....
</P>
<P>
   __Among the really cool activities that the Stanford football
team will do leading up to the Rose Bowl is take in a Clippers
game. Causing the Stanford players to wonder if winning the Pac-10
was worth all that trouble....
</P>
<P>
   __Danny Ainge had to figure that whining from his kids would be
much easier to tolerate than that from Penny Hardaway....
</P>
<P>
   __On The Sporting News' latest list of the 100 most powerful
people in sports: No. 78 Jim Rome and No. 82 Keith Olbermann....
</P>
<P>
   The bigger surprise is that Olbermann got sucked into a debate
about the 50 greatest athletes of the century when the century
isn't even over....
</P>
<P>
   __All you need to know about Canadian sports _ Nancy Greene
Raine was voted the country's athlete of the century. Today's quiz:
What sport did she compete in _ A) dog mushing, B) log rolling, C)
curling or D) some other activity of which we're clueless about the
rules....
</P>
<P>
   __Anyone who knew she was an Olympic gold-medal-winning skier in
1968 is not only lying, but also apparently unaware of anything
Wayne Gretzky accomplished....
</P>
<P>
   __Marv Albert will stop by the Office Depot Outlet to do the
Lakers-Spurs game for NBC on Christmas Day. If you happen to see
him, be nice....
</P>
<P>
   __Of course Rae Carruth will have every chance to prove his
innocence. Just as soon as he's done running away from
authorities....
</P>
<P>
   __Informed that he once owned Steve Beuerlein, Raiders boss Al
Davis looked even more confused....
</P>
<P>
   __Make all the bogus boxing matchups you want, but the only guy
we'd actually pay to see remains Oscar De La Hoya....
</P>
<P>
   __And finally, our warm-n-fuzzy holiday moment: It was 50 years
ago this week _ Christmas Eve, 1949 _ when Hall of Fame pitcher
Grover Cleveland Alexander, who had been suffering from epilepsy
and alcoholism, was found in an alley in Hollywood, unconscious and
missing an ear.
</P>
