<HEADLINE>
NO FEAR: RAMS RUB OUT BROWNS ON SECOND CHANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As the year 2000 approaches, here's a look at some
of the interesting anniversaries that will occur this week in Los
Angeles sports history (followed by the ranking of the event from
the book ``Unforgettable: The 100 Greatest Moments in Los Angeles
Sports History'' in parenthesis, if applicable):
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 20, 1981: In the first year the NCAA sanctions the women's
volleyball championship, USC outlasts UCLA 9-15, 15-7, 10-15,
15-13, 15-7 for the title.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 22, 1971: The Lakers set a major-league professional sports
record with their 27th straight win, 127-120 over the Bullets in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 22, 1966: UCLA's 84-74 win over Colorado State is the 500th
victory of coach John Wooden's career.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 23, 1986: Magic Johnson scores a career-high 46 points in
an overtime victory over Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 23, 1951: One year earlier, the Rams lost the 1950 NFL
title game to Cleveland 30-28 on Lou Groza's 21-yard field goal
with 17 seconds left. But revenge is sweet. Norm Van Brocklin, in
relief of Bob Waterfield, hits end Tom Fears on a 73-yard pass play
to give the Rams a 24-17 win in the NFL championship game before
57,522 at the Coliseum. (20)
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 25, 1934: Santa Anita Race Track opens to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Birthdays: Wednesday: Former Dodgers first baseman Steve Garvey
(51).
</P>
</TEXT>
