<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-DEBATE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO RADIO OR TV? NO WAY, BRADLEY RESPONDS TO GORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: A 1STTAKE will follow by 8:45 p.m. ET.) 
(sw) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore said on Sunday he would halt
all radio and television commercials in his presidential campaign
if Bill Bradley did the same. But Bradley scoffed at what he called
``a ridiculous proposal'' and spurned it, almost laughingly, as a
shallow political gimmick.
</P>
<P>
   In a challenge that set off the most pointed and personal
exchanges thus far between the two Democratic competitors, Gore
proposed that rather than saturate the airwaves with advertisements
costing millions of dollars, the candidates debate twice a week
during the primary season.
</P>
<P>
   Offering his right hand to Bradley as they sat side-by-side in a
debate on the NBC program ``Meet the Press,'' Gore said, ``I'm
willing to do it right now, if you're willing to shake on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, looking unruffled and somewhat amused as he declined
the handshake, said, ``Al, that's good. I like that hand. But the
answer is no. I mean, why should I agree now? I'm not someone who's
interested in tactics, Al.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's advisers said afterward that they had not expected
Bradley to take up the challenge. Instead, they said they intended
to knock him off stride as well as tap into voter disgust with
political advertising, which some Americans consider the most
repellent aspect of campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president also sought to counter Bradley's claim that
he was the most authentic reformer in the race and overcome harsh
publicity about Gore's fund-raising practices in the 1996 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Bradley held a high-profile town meeting with Sen.
John McCain of Arizona, a Republican presidential contender, to
urge tighter campaign finance laws. The issue is of particular
appeal in New Hampshire, which holds the first primary and is one
state where both Democrats are running neck and neck in the polls,
though Gore remains ahead in national polls.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Bradley had accepted the offer, it would be more in
Gore's interest to eliminate commercials because the he is already
better known than Bradley. And at this stage of the contest,
Bradley is spending more than Gore on television advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   But in trying to engage his rival, Gore risked appearing too
anxious, even desperate. And by mounting his challenge, the vice
president overshadowed one of his greatest assets, which had been
on display for the first half-hour of the debate: his mastery of
the issues.
</P>
<P>
   While the quarreling over Gore's challenge made for the
scrappiest, most revealing moments of the 60-minute encounter, the
candidates sparred over health care, foreign policy, education,
campaign finance and the Lewinsky scandal. Throughout the debate,
Gore sighed loudly at many of Bradley's claims, as when the former
senator described his proposal to replace Medicaid with a
subsidized health insurance program.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Bradley appeared calm and not particularly defensive, at
times he responded sarcastically to the vice president. After Gore
said he would rule out raising the entitlement age for Social
Security benefits _ and criticized Bradley for having once toyed
with the idea _ Bradley insisted that such a move must have been
broached in the Clinton White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``You didn't discuss it in all of your Social Security forums
out there?'' Bradley asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly didn't,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   To that, Bradley fired back, ``No one ever did, right? No one
ever did? Give me a break.''
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates ruled out raising the retirement age.
</P>
<P>
   At another point, questioning Gore's involvement in pressing for
campaign finance proposals, Bradley said he remembered visiting the
White House in 1993 with other party leaders and urging the
president to push for reforming the campaign finance system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if you were in the loop or not,'' Bradley said
dismissively, ``but the fact of the matter is that no action took
place.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason, Gore responded, was ``because all the Republicans
voted against it.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-19-99 2016EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
