u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-N     12-19 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIS LIFE RUINED BY A RUSSIAN MISSILE, A MAN ASKS, `WHY ME?' 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also RUSSIA-ELECT, RUSSIA-VOTERS) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Locator map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOZDOK, Russia _ Mikhail Kashpurin is a frail old man with years
of valorous service in the Soviet army, an unblemished labor record
and a story to tell.
</P>
<P>
   And that story is this: He was in the wrong place at the wrong
time. The place was Grozny, and the time was Russia's military
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Kashpurin, 76, is an ethnic Russian and no friend of the armed
rebels, some of them Islamic militants, who now roam the streets of
the Chechen capital. Born in Grozny, he lived with his wife in a
small wooden house on the southern outskirts of the city.
</P>
<P>
   They had no children, but enjoyed their friends and seemed to
have enough to get by. Kashpurin worked in a factory, and the
couple had a dog, a cat and 25 chickens. Kashpurin proudly
decorated his living room wall with 13 military awards from the
Great Patriotic War, as Russians call World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Grozny's residents have endured so much hardship that not even
the prospect of a war necessarily impels them to flee. So when the
Russians began their attacks in Chechnya this fall, the Kashpurins
decided to keep an eye on the only property they had, take to their
cellar and ride out the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   They were hardly the only ones. As many as 45,000 civilians are
still trapped in Grozny, according to official Russian estimates.
What the Kashpurins, and thousands of other residents, did not
anticipate was that the airstrikes and artillery barrages would be
so fierce, even worse than the Russian bombardments during the
1994-96 war in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   ``The military announced: `Don't worry. It will be precision
fire aimed at militants,''' Kashpurin recalled from his bed in this
southern Russian town. ``So we calmed down a bit. But then they
were hitting real hard. The artillery was very active, especially
the rockets and the large-caliber mortars. You practically don't
hear the shot, but the ground shakes when they explode. Oh, Lord, I
hate to even think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The barrages never seemed to silence the militants, who
Kashpurin said had apparently hidden their anti-aircraft artillery
on a nearby hillside, then fired away at Russian warplanes as they
streaked by.
</P>
<P>
   As the bombardment continued, life in Grozny became almost
medieval. Even before the latest conflict, the Kashpurins had been
living without electricity, a legacy of the disorder that followed
the last Chechen war.
</P>
<P>
   Now the supplies began to dwindle as well. So they put a stove
in their courtyard and scrounged up some firewood for heat and for
preparing the kasha, or gruel, on which they survived. There was no
market in their neighborhood, but like other war-hardened residents
they had stored their own supply.
</P>
<P>
   It was not just the bombing that kept them close to home.
Kashpurin, one of the few who have escaped Grozny to have given a
foreign reporter such a description of life inside the city, said
he lived in fear of bands of militants roaming Grozny's streets.
Tolik, his neighbor, walked with a limp from birth, but the
militants tried to press him into service and make him dig
trenches.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was crippled and could not handle the shovel, so eventually
they let him go,'' Kashpurin said. ``I don't think they could have
made me dig trenches. I am too old. But I might have been taken as
a hostage.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came Nov. 27, the day that shattered his life. ``I was
lying in bed when a plane zoomed by and fired a missile,'' he said.
``My wife was in the kitchen and was blown to pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   Kashpurin paused and appeared bewildered as if he could not
believe that this awful event had really happened to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was on Dalnaya Street,'' he said. ``Forty houses were wiped
out like they never existed. So this street does not exist
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Kashpurin, now bedridden, is a bit hazy on what happened after
that. He knows that the ceiling collapsed and a heavy wardrobe
fell, pinning him to the ground. He knows that Tolik pulled him out
of the debris and that he lay on a concrete floor in a basement for
several days.
</P>
<P>
   Then a neighbor, an old woman, decided to help. She was planning
to flee to her son, who lived in the Krasnodar region of southern
Russia, and she offered to take Kashpurin as far as Mozdok,
northwest of Chechnya. ``There was a problem getting out of
Grozny,'' Kashpurin said. ``There was no transportation, and I am
not one of these rich people who has a car.''
</P>
<P>
   Rumors circulated through Grozny that the Russian government was
organizing a bus convoy to take civilians out of the city, but the
buses never appeared.
</P>
<P>
   Kashpurin was unable to walk, and his neighbors put him on a
sled and hauled him through the bombed-out streets until they found
a driver with an old Volga sedan who was willing to drive him out
of the Chechen capital for a fee.
</P>
<P>
   To minimize the risk of being caught in cross-fire, the driver
avoided the main highway and instead headed out of town on the
bumpy Goragorskaya road, eventually arriving in the town of
Sleptsovsk across Chechnya's border in Ingushetia, a Russian
republic west of Grozny. ``The driver was afraid to go any farther
with Chechen license plates,'' Kashpurin said. ``So another driver
was hired to go to Mozdok.''
</P>
<P>
   Kashpurin now spends his days in bed in a small home in Mozdok,
which has taken in other ethnic Russians fleeing the fighting in
Chechnya. In a bitter twist, Mozdok is also the home of the Russian
military base that planes and helicopters use to pummel Grozny, and
the roar of the warplanes can be heard throughout the city as they
take off.
</P>
<P>
   ``So now I am alone without any rubles,'' he said, breaking out
again in a wail of tears. ``All my documents, my war veteran's
certificate and my 13 decorations have been lost. My God, what a
problem! I, Mikhail Aleksandrovich, am not a criminal. I have never
even been in a courtroom in my life. Why of all people did this
have to happen to me?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-19-99 2018EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
