<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-19 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3549 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-R-OUTLOOK-INTERNET-AR     12-19 1340
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-OUTLOOK-INTERNET-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALKING THE FUTURE WITH MARY MEEKER AND JEFF CAMP
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Repeating to add art note.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By   KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just think what the language would be like without the Internet.
Until five or six years ago, ``Amazon'' was a very long, very big
river. ``Yahoo'' was a favorite expression of delight _ or, to
students of Jonathan Swift, a brutish creature. A ``web'' was for
spiders. ``Space'' was _ well, it was space. ``Dot-com,'' ``B2B,''
``e-commerce,'' ``e-mail.'' Whaaa?
</P>
<P>
   Consider the economy, and its Net effects.
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago, only 90,000 Americans, mostly academics, were
wired. Today, 80 million people in this country, and nearly 200
million worldwide, are online. Within two years, those numbers
could double.
</P>
<P>
   Online retail sales have risen from nothing to about $20
billion. Business-to-business transactions _ that B2B thing _ have
grown to $109 billion. By 2003, Forrester Research estimates,
online retail sales will grow to $144 billion, and B2B business
e-commerce will jump to $1.3 trillion. (That's just in the United
States, folks.)
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is the stock market. Without the Internet, the
initial public offering market would be pretty dead. Without the
Internet, a slew of day traders might be otherwise engaged. Without
the Internet, the Nasdaq composite index almost certainly would not
be up more than 70 percent this year, and price/earnings ratios
would make a lot more sense.
</P>
<P>
   So much for the past.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, with about six weeks left in the century, Mary
Meeker, head of the Internet research team at Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter, and Jeff Camp, who follows Internet data services for the
firm, sat down to talk about the future.
</P>
<P>
   Following are excerpts from the conversation:
</P>
<P>
   Q: There have been more than 200 Internet initial public
offerings this year. Is that pace sustainable in the coming 12
months?
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Meeker: As long as the economic environment remains robust,
and as long as new categories of companies keep coming on, it
certainly seems as though it should. I think many people would
welcome a slowdown because each crop of companies is riskier than
the last one. That said, the aggregate opportunity is quite high
for high-risk/high-reward companies.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So what sorts of companies will we see? And how have the
waves gone so far?
</P>
<P>
   A: Increasingly, there will be new infrastructure plays.
Broadband is becoming increasingly real. Providing services to
build that business will be another big opportunity. Wireless is
another one. And many things are needed to provide for a better
user experience across the board. But the B2B theme, general
business re-engineering, will continue to be a big theme.
</P>
<P>
   It is also our view that sometime in the next year a traditional
company will throw out its traditional business model and become
more Internet-like, where it focuses on the long term and gets away
with it. To date, no one has had the guts to do it or has done it
successfully.
</P>
<P>
   Up to now, we have had an infrastructure wave, including
companies like UUnet, PSI and Netccom; &UR;  &LR; a software wave, with
companies like Netscape and Spyglass; &UR;  &LR; a content wave, with
companies like Lycos, Yahoo and Excite, and retail and e-commerce,
like CDB Now and Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Each year a new crop of companies in a new category have
captured peoples' imaginations and created real businesses and real
wealth. Right now we are seeing a lot of opportunity in the
business-to-business area. Two years from now people may be focused
on something else.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there any reason to think that business-to-business
companies will generate profits faster than retailers like
Amazon.com?
</P>
<P>
   A: B2B will probably have a shorter ramp-up to profitability
compared to an e-commerce company like Amazon, if only because
Amazon's ambitions are so vast. And operating losses at these
companies will also probably not reach the level of e-commerce
companies. Right now it is too early to tell which companies are
going to be the big winners on an ongoing basis. One of the reasons
it is tough to predict is that many of these new companies are
looking at the history of the Internet and asking what lessons can
be learned from what has happened in the past. They have their eyes
much more wide open and are adapting a lot more quickly than
companies in the business-to-commerce area.
</P>
<P>
   I would feel comfortable saying that a year from now we will
have a lot more clarity about winners and losers. Often, the
biggest threat is not a market threat or a competitive threat, but
management error. That is something you can't predict.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Which Internet infrastructure companies look promising?
</P>
<P>
   Camp: Four companies are worth highlighting: Exodus, which is
dominant in the high end of the United States Web hosting market;
InterNAP, which provides Internet connectivity services that
greatly increase performance and speed of company Web sites;
Akamai, a pioneer in the market for intelligent content
distribution services; and Verio, the largest Web hosting company
to small and medium-sized businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If you were constructing an Internet portfolio you could not
trade at all for the next five years, which stocks would have to be
included?
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Meeker: America Online, Yahoo, Amazon.com and Cisco Systems.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Nearly all of these companies, and a good chunk of their
managers, have never lived through a recession. What sort of impact
would a downturn have on Internet companies?
</P>
<P>
   Camp: If you think B2B, businesses are getting online for cogent
economic reasons: It reduces procurement costs; it increases
productivity; inventory management and so forth. It is unlikely
that a recession would derail that overall trend.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Meeker: It could accelerate it.
</P>
<P>
   Camp: It may impact what consumers do, but my guess is that the
much larger part of the Internet, which is business-related, is
going to be moving along that trend for the reasons I just
mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   You can make a decent argument that parts of the Internet are
going to be recession-proof. If you are a business going online,
you need a Web site, you need Internet access and all the different
tools and components that go into it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Despite its rapid growth, the move to the Internet is still
in its infancy. Where are we, and how much of a lead does the
United States have on the rest of the industrialized world?
</P>
<P>
   A: It seems as if the Internet is everywhere, but it is really
concentrated in the hands of a group of very large companies.
Ninety percent of large businesses have a Web site or are doing
something on the Web. Ten percent of small businesses do. When you
consider that small businesses represent half the gross domestic
product in this country and represent 99 percent of all businesses,
a large part of the market is not engaged yet.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Meeker: In terms of development, Europe is probably where
the United States was in 1995 or 1996. There are a few reasons for
this.
</P>
<P>
   First, personal computer penetration isn't as high as it is in
the United States. Second, telecommunications availability is more
restrictive, and costs are higher. And regional boundaries _
language and other things _ are part of the landscape.
</P>
<P>
   That said, Internet growth is accelerating in those markets.
Financial service companies are more aggressive about online
banking than they have been here. And wireless Internet
connectivity is going to happen faster in Europe than here. That is
a big opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, though, more than half the usage by European
consumers appears to be targeted at American sites. For example, we
believe Yahoo is probably the leading Web site in France, Britain
and Germany. From a content perspective, the Yahoo and America
Online of Europe may be Yahoo and America Online.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: It sounds as though experience is a great comparative
advantage. Is that the case?
</P>
<P>
   A: People who wring their hands whenever Amazon's or eBay's or
Schwab's site crashes should remember that those companies are
making mistakes many companies only wish they could make, because
they are servicing so much volume. They get smarter and smarter and
smarter.
</P>
<P>
   Something on the order of 50 percent of all e-commerce knowledge
resides in the brains of Amazon.com employees or Amazon
programmers. They know the patterns when an average American or
foreigner goes online. That knowledge has helped these companies
become so big and to understand how to move into new markets in a
very competitive and aggressive way.
</P>
<P>
   I would not want to compete with Microsoft or Netscape or Yahoo,
or go toe-to-toe with Amazon.com or eBay. The leading companies of
today will not be failures because of start-ups. If they fail, it
will be because they made a tactical error or one of the other
leaders morphs into their business.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Speaking of Microsoft, what do you think is going to happen
with the antitrust case? Will the company be broken up?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think the best thing to happen here is that they settle the
case and go forward.
</P>
<P>
   The focus I have had is on whether an adverse ruling will
fundamentally change the company's business model. But the things
that will fundamentally change Microsoft's business model are
already in place.
</P>
<P>
   For them, the bad news is that they will not have the kind of
market share on the Internet that they had on the personal computer
platform. The good news is that the Internet, whatever it is, is
much bigger, and they are in a position where they potentially
could have smaller market shares in many markets, so that might not
be such a bad thing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-19-99 2024EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991219.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-19 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3552 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-R-OUTLOOK-MOVIES-ART-     12-19 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-OUTLOOK-MOVIES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILM'S DIGITAL POTENTIAL HAS HOLLYWOOD ON EDGE
</HEADLINE>
 
 (EDS: Repeating to add art note.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The executive offices, with a half-dozen
paper-strewn desks in two rooms of a third-floor walk-up, are just
across the street from the basement nerve center where more than
two dozen people hunch over laptops and chatter to one another in
the dull glow of the computer screens. In other words, the ragged
bifurcated headquarters of iFilm looks pretty much like a cliched
rendering of an Internet start-up company, which is what it is.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also, in its way, a movie studio of the future.
Throughout the entertainment industry, from the major studios to
Internet start-up companies, people are trying to figure out how
the rapidly emerging digital technology will affect the movies that
people see and the ways that they see them. What iFilm is doing _
distributing digital films through the Internet to anyone with a
computer while also providing a forum for filmmakers and industry
executives to find each other _ is a good example of how this
technology is mutating the power structures that have governed
Hollywood since the advent of the talkies in the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of a movie studio is changing as we watch,'' said
Rodger Raderman, one of iFilm's founders and its co-chairman.
``What is a studio? If you think of it as a place where movies are
developed, produced, marketed and distributed, then we are very
close to having a technology where one person can do that all by
himself. Each person can be his own studio.''
</P>
<P>
   For Hollywood, an industry that claims to have its finger on the
pulse of mass audience tastes, it is a perplexing time.
</P>
<P>
   The movie business is moving into an interesting, perhaps
perilous and largely unknown period when the economics of
filmmaking and the very foundation of the power structures that
have governed the business for almost a century are more fluid than
at any time in its history. The pace of change and the revolution
in technology are outstripping entertainment executives' ability to
comprehend and control their business. Unease is the mood of the
day.
</P>
<P>
   Web sites devoted to producing digital films or, like iFilm,
providing a forum for digital films produced by others have been
proliferating in recent months as wave after wave of innovative
software and hardware have begun to ease what many see as the
inevitable transition between an old film-based technology and a
new digital movie world. The common wisdom among industry analysts
is that it will take three to five years for a sufficient number of
American households to acquire either digital television sets or
broadband capabilities for their computers, making it easy and
profitable for companies to pipe films to them on the Internet.
Sometime after that, they say, in maybe another two to three years,
the technology will be in place to allow people to call up movies
on demand _ simply ordering up whatever they want, when they want
it _ obviating the need for scheduled programming or video stores.
</P>
<P>
   So what happens to Hollywood then? Will people still go out to
the movies?
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry, Raderman said, iFilm is not out to eat Hollywood's
lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The studios are not the enemy,'' stressed Skip Paul, a
longtime Universal Pictures executive who founded Sega GameWorks,
the arcade company, with Steven Spielberg and was named iFilm's
other co-chairman last month.
</P>
<P>
   What iFilm wants to do, Raderman said, is ``enable'' filmmakers
and entertainment executives to meet each other in a kind of
high-technology forum where digital films can be shown through
their Web sites, where filmmakers can trade information about their
craft and where Hollywood agents and producers can gossip with one
another on a protected site and shop around for fresh ideas and new
talent. The ``communal experience'' of the movie theater will
remain important to consumers, Paul said.
</P>
<P>
   Is that the future: some youngster in Indiana making a movie on
his hand-held digital camcorder, editing it on his laptop and
shipping it to someplace like iFilm, where it can be piped into
every living room in America in a blink? Will filmmaking finally
become, as Orson Welles once described it, the best toy train set a
kid ever had?
</P>
<P>
   ``The technology is evolving so fast, and we want to be in the
catbird's seat when broadband becomes a reality,'' said Spielberg,
whose DreamWorks SKG studio is joining Imagine Entertainment to
create Pop.com, a Web site that will present short, original
digital films.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strides that the technology has made in the last year,
really in just the last six months or so, has led me to believe
that this is really the birth of a new medium, a shift from
information to entertainment on the Internet, which will create
some great opportunities for creative people to do new kinds of
work,'' said Ron Howard, the director who co-founded Imagine, one
of Hollywood's most prolific movie and television production
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood is nervous about the coming years because three things
are happening simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   First, movie technology, from the way films are made to the way
they will be shown, is riding an incredible high-technology wave
driven by the marriage of new digital movie-making gizmos and the
Internet, from digital cameras to digital editing software to
digital projectors.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, traditional movies have become more and more
expensive to produce. Driven by huge salaries for the top talent,
escalating production costs and more expensive marketing demands,
movie studios are struggling to find new formulas to make movies _
at a profit _ that will satisfy an increasingly fickle and
unpredictable audience. Because all the major studios are owned by
larger corporations, which increasingly see them as mere divisions
within a larger money-making machine, these dwindling profits have
led to growing cost-cutting demands from corporate patriarchs.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is the demographic bulge _ the so-called boomer
echo generation, even larger than the boomers who gave birth to
them _ that in the next decade will come into their adolescence and
early adulthood, their prime movie-going years. So much money to be
made. Can anybody figure out what these movigoers will want to see
_ and how they are going to want to see it?
</P>
<P>
   If the future is, as many believe, somehow brewing out there in
the world of digital technology and broadband distribution, then
its larval state must be here, in the basement nerve center of
places like iFilm. Raderman recently huddled over a screen,
watching a display of new iFilm software that makes viewing films
on a computer screen more pleasurable (it blacks out all of the
screen but the window showing the film, like a letterbox format).
</P>
<P>
   Basically, there are three technical issues that are being
resolved at this very moment by iFilm and other cybercompanies,
Raderman said. Movies have been available on the Internet for
years, but they have been an unsatisfying experience for most
viewers; available only in partial screen windows, taking forever
to download on most currently used modems, often herky-jerky when
played on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   The first breakthrough has been compression software, which
allows the computer to read the image as it is playing and refresh
only those parts that are changing _ say, lips and facial
expressions if a person is talking into a camera against a static
background. Much time is saved, and the image moves more smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   The second technical issue is so-called streaming video.
Previously, to play a film on a home computer, viewers had to
download the whole film and then play it back. With streaming
video, now available on most home computers, the movie begins to
play when it is only partly downloaded; the remainder of the film
downloads in the background while the first portion plays, thus
reducing waiting time.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Raderman said, there is the issue of the ``size of the
pipeline'' _ that is, how the digital images are transmitted into
the computer or television set, whether by modem or cable or
satellite. There are almost constant improvements to the capacity
of the line, he said, and in getting more information through
existing lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``My belief is that this becomes a viable company when 20
percent'' of the people have the technology for watching movies on
the Internet, said Lucas McDonough, iFilm's other founder and its
president. ``That's coming soon. These things are going to be
resolved simply because there is so much money to be made in
resolving them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
