<HEADLINE>
POPE PLANS A SIX-DAY TOUR OF THE HOLY LAND IN MARCH
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Pope John Paul II plans to fly to Israel on March 21
for a six-day tour of Christian holy sites in Jerusalem, Bethlehem
and the Sea of Galilee region, Israel's government said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The visit would make John Paul just the second pope to travel to
the Holy Land, and the first to make an official visit to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   While in Jerusalem, the pope is also expected to visit Yad
Vashem, the Israeli Holocaust memorial, and is considering a stop
at the Western Wall, a site venerated by observant Jews, said Moshe
Fogel, the director of the Israeli government's press office.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement on Sunday was the first official Israeli
confirmation of the long-anticipated papal visit, though the
Vatican would not confirm the plan. Fogel said, however, the dates
for the visit have been fixed by the Holy See and that details of
the pope's daily schedule were being arranged.
</P>
<P>
   A Vatican diplomatic team departed Israel for Rome Sunday after
planning a tentative six-day itinerary that would begin at Tel
Aviv's Ben Gurion Airport, where the pope is expected to be
received by Israel's president and prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Pope Paul VI visited the region briefly in 1964, entering Israel
for what was termed a private one-day visit to Nazareth. The
Vatican did not extend full diplomatic recognition to Israel until
1994.
</P>
<P>
   This time the visit is to be an official one, and the pope's
first destination after arrival is scheduled to be Jerusalem, where
he is planning to stay in a Roman Catholic Church residence on the
Mount of Olives, Fogel said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mount of Olives is in the largely Arab eastern section of
the city, where the Vatican, like most nations, does not recognize
Israeli sovereignty. The pope also plans to spend at least a day in
Palestinian territory, meeting with the Palestinian leader, Yasser
Arafat, and saying Mass at the 1,500-year-old Church of the
Nativity in Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
   After visiting Nazareth and the Sea of Galilee region, the pope
is expected to return to Jerusalem for Mass on March 26 in the
Church of the Holy Sepulcher, traditionall considered the site of
Jesus' tomb.
</P>
<P>
   The ancient church has only a single narrow door. Israeli
security authorities, concerned about a large crowd at the Mass,
have been unable to persuade the often-quarreling Christian
denominations that control the church to open a new emergency
entrance in time for the pope's visit.
</P>
<P>
   Local church leaders had said the pope's trip might be
jeopardized by Israel's authorization of the construction of a
mosque in Nazareth next to the Basilica of the Annunciation,
believed by Christians to be the place where the angel Gabriel told
Mary she would give birth to the Messiah.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the controversy, the pope's schedule is to include a
visit to the Nazareth church on March 25 for the celebration of the
Feast of the Annunciation, Israeli officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Reneging on an agreement with Israeli authorities, Muslim
activists in Nazareth recently reinstalled a large tent on the site
of their future mosque, which is adjacent to the Basilica walls.
Though a cornerstone for the mosque was laid last month,
construction was postponed until after the pope's expected visit
under a compromise brokered by Israel's Ministry of Internal
Security.
</P>
<P>
   A few miles east of Nazareth, on the shores of the Sea of
Galilee, the pope plans to celebrate an outdoor Mass at a Catholic
youth gathering.
</P>
<P>
   Among the sites he may visit in the Galilee area are the
lakeside hill where Christ is traditionally believed to have
delivered his Sermon on the Mount, and the nearby Church of the
Heptapegon, revered as the place where Jesus fed a multitude with
five loaves of bread and two fishes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
