<SLUG> BC-TERRORIST-THREAT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS ARE WARNED TO BE VIGILANT OVER HOLIDAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States' top national security official
Sunday urged Americans to be ``vigilant'' as they proceed with
their holiday plans, ands worry about the threat of domestic
terrorism seems to have spread after an Algerian man was charged
with smuggling bombmaking materials across the border from British
Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Although National Security Adviser Samuel R. Berger said he was
unaware of any other specific threat against U.S. targets and law
enforcement officials said they had taken every step possible to
ensure the public's safety, they nonetheless acknowledged a
heightened risk of terrorism against Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The warning about domestic terrorism at home follows a State
Department alert recently issued for Americans traveling abroad,
which Berger called a ``yellow light, not a red light.'' But, taken
together, they underscore the concern that has been wrought by the
arrest of Ahmed Ressam, 32, identified as an Algerian national
traveling on fake Canadian identity papers and linked to extremists
using Montreal as a North American base of operations.
</P>
<P>
   Ressam was charged Friday in Seattle with carrying more than 100
pounds of bomb-making supplies and a sophisticated detonating
device across the border in a rental car.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the U.S. Customs Service began the first day of beefed
up patrols at the 301 ports of entry into the United States,
including several in Maine and Vermont, following a high alert the
agency put in place Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result of the arrest and seizure last week, we are
redoubling our efforts,'' said Customs Service spokesman Dennis
Murphy. ``We're having more eyes and ears out there to be alert to
anything that might be out there. Inspectors need to be vigilant,
to look out for anything that could be out of the ordinary or
unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   Given Ressam's arrest and the unanswered questions about the
nature of the plot he was allegedly involved in, Berger, speaking
on the CBS's ``Face the Nation'' said: ``As we head toward the New
Years, the millennium, the end of Ramadan, this is a period of
heightened risk of terrorist actions involving Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that Americans should be vigilant as they go about
their plans for the New Year,'' he said. ``If they see something
suspicious, or see packages or activities that they think are
unusual, they should obviously let law enforcement people know.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger said U.S. officials were not aware of ``any other
specific threat against particular targets in the United States,
and, obviously, if that changes we'll alert the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   While refusing to discuss details of how security is being
beefed up in Washington and across the country for end-of-the
century celebrations, FBI spokeswoman Debra Weierman said ``there
is heightened security at this time because it's the millennium,''
and said the agency was working with state and local law
enforcement agencies to ensure that security was adequate.
</P>
<P>
   ``All precautions that can possibly be made have been made and
will undergo activation'' once the festivities start, Weierman
said, including the mass events on the Mall in Washington and in
New York's Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokeswoman Nanda Chitre refused to discuss possible
security around the White House complex, but echoed Berger in
saying ``there are risks out there'' about which the public needed
to be aware.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and Canadian authorities say they believe that Ressam may
be part of a larger conspiracy stretching from Montreal and other
Canadian centers to hideaways of Islamic extremists around the
world. A massive cross-border manhunt continued Sunday for the
accomplice who apparently had been with Ressam at a motel in
British Columbia for three weeks prior to Ressam's passage into the
United States. The FBI is reportedly also investigating links
agents believe Ressam has to other Islamic extremists in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said law enforcement authorities were trying to determine
the nature of the potential plot Ressam may have been involved in
and who or what may have been his target.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe a conclusion has been reached with respect to
what his plan or motivation or affiliation was,'' Berger said. But
he acknowledged that investigators were looking into whether Ressam
was affiliated with any terrorist group, including the Islamic
group of Osama bin Laden, the millionaire Saudi militant based in
Afghanistan and for whose apprehension the US State Department has
posted a $5 million reward.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said that in response to Ressam's arrest, the Customs
Service was concentrating its resources along land-border
locations, specifically protection of the northern and southern
borders of the United States. The northern border ports include
Derby Line and Highgate Springs in Vermont, and several points in
Maine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-19-99 2038EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991219.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-19 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3565 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-DEMS-DEBATE-2NDTAKE-N     12-19 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-DEBATE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: against it.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This was the third televised encounter between the two
Democrats, both of whom dressed in almost identical blue suits and
red-patterned ties. It was far more revealing and tightly paced
than a debate between Bradley and Gore just two days before in
Nashua, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting only inches apart, neither candidate was willing to cede
the last word to the other. Again and again, Gore shook his head
when Bradley spoke, or talked over him. Bradley, for his part, was
more calm than his rival but, compared to the last two debates, was
more inclined to stand his ground. ``That's wrong _ that's not
correct,'' he said of Gore's description of his health care plan.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Russert, the moderator of ``Meet the Press,'' prodded the
candidates to speak in specifics and, notably, pressed Gore into
discussing his missteps in fund-raising in the 1996 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to describe his most glaring mistake in fund-raising, Gore
replied, ``Oh, you know, I think that's pushing the limits, all
this was reviewed and no charges were brought. But I think it was a
mistake nonetheless.'' He said, ``Obviously we would do things
differently if we had it to do over again.''
</P>
<P>
   Recalling how Gore once called President Clinton one of the
greatest presidents, Russert asked if he was in the same company as
Washington and Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course not,'' Gore said. ``But I think that his
accomplishments are going to be regarded by the history books as
far more significant than his personal mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the most striking exchanges came during a discussion of
unregulated campaign contributions known as soft money, when Gore
posed his challenge to Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll make you this offer right now,'' Gore said. ``If you will
agree, I will stop running all television and radio commercials
until this nomination is decided. That can get a lot of the money
out of the presidential campaign and accomplish one of the best
reforms. What about it?''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley replied, ``It sounds to me like you're having trouble
raising money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Gore shot back. ``As a matter of fact, I'm not.''
</P>
<P>
   Appearing somewhat perplexed by the challenge, Bradley went on:
``I mean, this is a ridiculous proposal. You know, the way you
communicate with people is when you talk to them. I love to talk to
them in town meetings, that's my favorite place. I've been doing
that since January. But I also love to talk to them over television
in their living rooms.''
</P>
<P>
   While Gore questioned the value of 30-second commercials,
Bradley said, ``That's not so difficult to do if you know what you
believe. And if you know where you want to take the country. If you
have a positive vision.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Gore persisted, saying he and Bradley, his former
colleague in the Senate, should ``just go face to face about the
issues and get rid of all these television and radio commercials.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not do that?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   The triggered a testy response from Bradley, who said, ``You
know something? For 10 months that I was running for president, you
ignored me, you pretended I didn't exist. Suddenly I started to do
better and you want to debate every day. It's ridiculous. We're
having debates.''
</P>
<P>
   Showing further disdain, Bradley said, ``The point is, Al, and I
don't know if you get this, but a political campaign is not just a
performance for people, which is what this is, but it is rather, a
dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not what I'm doing,'' Gore objected.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley dismissed Gore's offer as ``nothing but a ploy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Debates aren't ploys,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Bradley replied, ``to come here, shake my hand. That's
nothing but a ploy.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gore insisted that his was ``a serious proposition,'' and
said that through more frequent debates the public ``will find out
a lot more about what we believe and what we're proposing.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At another point, Gore offered himself as the true reformer,
saying, ``I have fought for this for 20 years. Bill went 17 years
in the United States Senate before he ever sponsored a campaign
finance reform bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Shrum, a media consultant for Gore, said the vice president
modeled his challenge to Bradley after one made in the 1998
campaign by John Edwards of North Carolina against Sen. Lauch
Faircloth. Faircloth also rejected the challenge, and went on to
lose to Edwards. Shrum was also a consultant for Edward's campaign,
but he said it was the vice president's idea to pose the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   He said Gore was ready to make the challenge in the debate on
Friday, but that the right opportunity never arose. ``He wasn't
going to force it in a debate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Touching on other issues, Russert asked Bradley if he regretted
voting against using force in the Persian Gulf in 1991, and his
warning that it would become a long battle that could destabilize
the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that my judgment is that it turned out that it worked
well,'' Bradley said. ``But I made the call and I'll stand by that
call.''
</P>
<P>
   While both candidates said they wanted to preserve Social
Security and Medicare benefits without raising the retirement age,
neither delved into specifics about how they would forestall an
expected cash shortfall in those programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to get into going down the whole list of
possibilities,'' Bradley said. ``When you are out there you have a
negotiation and you're trying to get together people so this does
not remain a political football.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore described his education proposal as far more comprehensive
than Bradley's. ``Senator Bradley has a variety of little
nibble-around-the-edges proposals,'' he said. ``He doesn't reduce
class size; he doesn't improve teacher quality; he doesn't fix
crumbling schools. My plan does all of that and provides universal
preschool.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley said he was just as committed, saying, ``I think the
differences Al proposes in education program, many of the things
that, you know, I don't have a problem with, but it comes from
Washington as an education program, as opposed to helping people
where they live their lives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
