<SLUG> BC-MACAO-HANDOVER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH POMP, CHINESE FLAG RISES OVER MACAO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MACAO _ As the five-star red flag was hoisted and a military
brass band rang out the national anthem, China at midnight took
back the last remaining land it had lost to European expansion, and
turned its sights on the major piece of Chinese soil still outside
of Beijing's control _ the island of Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   After an emotional final day of Portuguese rule over this
once-bustling port that linked lucrative trade routes from Canton
to Mexico, Portugal's red-and-green banner came down at 11:57 p.m.
Sunday night, closing the book on 442 years of colonialism in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Macao, today a casino haven-cum-colonial tourist attraction,
returned to China 2 1/2 years after Britain relinquished the
financial hub of Hong Kong. China's President Jiang Zemin bid
goodbye with a broad grin to Portugal's President Jorge Sampaio in
this second handover that confirmed Beijing as a rising global
power.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal was the first European country to gain a foothold in
Asia and the last to go. But the Portuguese left Macao under far
less acrimonious or violent circumstances than the French in
Vietnam, the British in India or the Dutch in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang repeated his vow to preserve ``one country, two systems,''
the pledge that Hong Kong and Macao will continue to enjoy their
``capitalist system and way of life'' for at least 50 years after
the handover.
</P>
<P>
   China will now pursue ``an early settlement of the Taiwan
question and the complete national reunification,'' Jiang told the
crowd of 2,500 guests, and a Chinese television audience estimated
in the hundreds of millions.
</P>
<P>
   To the blare of trumpets, a uniformed representative of each of
the three armed services of China and Portugal goosestepped toward
one another and turned to salute their flags. The Portuguese flag
was lowered and China's banner hoisted.
</P>
<P>
   In the streets of Macao Sunday night and this morning, Chinese
flags went up on taxi antennas and buildings. Spectators packed
into the cobblestoned main plaza to watch the ceremony on a giant
TV screen and cheer. ``It's exciting because it's Chinese ruling
Chinese,'' shouted Chang Hengsin, 21, a student.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Portuguese and mixed-race natives who are staying said
they were optimistic. ``At first we were terrified, but now no. We
feel safe and happy,'' said Isabel Ferreira, 42, a former civil
servant. Like other Macanese, or Eurasian locals, Ferreira hopes
Macao will retain its fusion of East and West apparent in Macao's
architecture, festivals and food.
</P>
<P>
   But the smooth handover was tarnished, and the promises of
continuing freedoms called into serious question by dozens of
arrests and deportations in the last days of members of a religious
sect, democracy activists and even actors conducting an
unsanctioned handover performance.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in Hong Kong, where the world diplomatic corps and media
monitored the handover under a magnifying glass, making Beijing and
local authorities determined to prove their good will, the return
of tiny, somnolent Macao has generated little attention. Protests
at the Hong Kong handover were tolerated without incident, earning
China kudos at the time for preserving civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps because of a lack of media scrutiny, local
authorities did not hesitate Sunday to arrest over 30 followers of
a spiritual group that is banned in China, but still legal here.
The Falun Gong members were peacefully exercising to draw attention
to the repression of their group in China. Police confiscated
banners and dragged them away, including a 6-year-old girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sends a very bad signal about the freedom of expression .
. . in Macao,'' said Catherine Baber of Amnesty International,
calling the arrests ``gross overreactions sullying what otherwise
would be a grand day.''
</P>
<P>
   Early Monday, local authorities arrested about 22 artists who
were in the main plaza commemorating the handover with an
unofficial performance.
</P>
<P>
   Some 500 Chinese troops will march into Macao Monday at noon to
establish the former colony's defense force.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
