r a BC-GREEK-THEATER-BID-LAD     12-19 1318
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREEK-THEATER-BID-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREEK THEATRE CONTRACT A STEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BETH BARRETT 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; LOS ANGELES -- In the last 25 years, the Greek Theatre has
netted millions of dollars for its operator, but the city has
gotten nothing because it paid for virtually all the utilities,
repairs, maintenance and capital improvements, the Daily News has
learned.
</P>
<P>
   The operator, Nederlander Corp.'s reward from the City Council:
a five-year extension without being subjected to competitive
bidding from other would-be contractors that would have netted the
city an estimated $1 million extra.
</P>
<P>
   While the Recreation and Parks Department has for years paid the
utilities and done maintenance on most of its 50 or so facilities
run by its concessionaires, the Greek Theatre has been among the
least profitable, according to Linda Barth, Department of
Recreation and Parks senior management analyst in the Griffith
Metro Region.
</P>
<P>
   ``In retrospect, looking back over the contract you could say,
`Golly, what a good deal for them,' '' Barth said, adding the old
contract was representative of the way the city did business in the
1970s, a practice the department is trying to change.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1995 interoffice computer memo, Barth wrote, ``What was in
the minds of the people who prepared this contract originally? It
is written so consciously to the benefit of the operator.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What a sweetheart deal,'' said Kris Vosburgh, executive
director of the Howard Jarvis Taxpayers Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would really be news about the city of Los Angeles would
be that they're running a tight ship and that the private companies
that are benefiting from the use of city facilities are paying
their own way.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a city that can't give enough away.''
</P>
<P>
   Led by council President John Ferraro, who has a years-long
friendship with city-owned Greek Theatre lobbyist/attorney Neil
Papiano, the deal was approved Dec. 8. The extension was approved
even though other firms were offering up to $1 million more _
revenues city officials said would have been realized after several
years.
</P>
<P>
   Papiano, who signs official documents as Nederlander's
secretary, did not return phone calls Friday.
</P>
<P>
   As the battle over the contract heads into the courts, where the
argument will be whether the the city's bid requirements and state
environmental laws were followed, the autopsy of Nederlander's past
financial arrangements is getting more attention. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``It's a valuable contract,'' said Nederlander attorney Adam
Burke, with the downtown firm Iverson Yoakum Papiano &AMP; Hatch. He
defended the operator as a responsible company that paid its rent
and turned the theater into an important city attraction, providing
enjoyment for many people every year.
</P>
<P>
   The extension is a good business decision for the city in
ensuring its asset is upgraded, particularly the 72-year-old
bathrooms, few of them for women, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's become so popular that it's become unpleasant for people
to come here,'' Burke said.
</P>
<P>
   Nederlander Chief Financial Officer David Green estimated that
since 1991 the firm has netted between $500,000 and $1 million
annually. He said the only year it operated in the red was in 1984,
when Los Angeles hosted the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``One year may have been as strong as $1.5 million,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Green said as to the expenses the city historically has been
picking up, ``the city decided to do what it decided to do.''
</P>
<P>
   George Mihlsten, the Latham &AMP; Watkins attorney representing
plaintiffs House of Blues Concerts in the litigation, said the
financial records speak for themselves, in that the the city never
made money on the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Department of Recreation and Parks records show the city paid
for all the maintenance, repairs and utilities after the first
$50,000 each year, throughout the life of the contract. Those city
reimbursements, and capital improvements, equalized the $500,000 to
$1 million in gross rent the Greek paid each year, the records
show.
</P>
<P>
   And, while the Greek Theatre was making its required $50,000
deposit into the city's general fund, the city was spending about
$90,000 on its gas and water bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city even paid for the toilet paper,'' Mihlsten said. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Barth said the department is in the process of requiring its
other 50 concessionaires to take over the utility payments too,
which cost the city about $250,000 annually.
</P>
<P>
   Mihlsten said that was money that could have benefited the
entire city, not just the operators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the parks are in deplorable condition,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Barth said Nederlander won the bid in 1975 when the Greek was
struggling, and that the city was willing to help out financially
at the time, much like it did with other concessionaires.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the nearly $4 million in capital improvements paid
for by the city that made the Greek's situation far less profitable
for the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Otherwise, the city would have made a lot,'' Barth said.
</P>
<P>
   David DeFore, president of the Greek Theatre Advisory Committee,
said there was nothing to be done about ``past history.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why punish someone in a free market enterprise who negotiated
a deal and who only owes the city fulfilling their contract,''
DeFore said. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; He said that while the committee wanted to go out for bids, the
city dragged its feet in putting together the request for
proposals. Finally, the committee became convinced it would be in
the city's interests to let Nederlander keep the concession for
five years and for them to make $5 million in improvements. There
was some urgency, in part because the theater is preparing for its
70th Anniversary Celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I absolutely still want to do the RFP (request for proposal)
because I think it's best for the city,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The recreation and parks staff also recommended seeking formal
proposals this year, but when Recreation and Parks Commissioner
Lisa Specht proposed doing that, she couldn't get a second for her
motion. The commission then voted 3-2 to support Nederlander's
unsolicited bid offer with Specht and Steve Soboroff opposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a public policy matter it should be a competitively bid
project, since typically the city gets a better deal,'' said
Specht, a prominent attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Recreation and Parks General Manager Ellen Oppenheim said the
department stands by its recommendation to bid the concession.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't the most lucrative contract for the city,''
Oppenheim said.
</P>
<P>
   She added the department has not done a cost-benefit analysis of
the previous contract's terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Among our charges is to serve the community with programs at
the same time we're responsible to administer the city's resources
in the most cost-effective way,'' Oppenheim said.
</P>
<P>
   Burke said the theater has been meeting both those mandates, and
that the ongoing questioning is legal posturing by a firm that
represents House of Blues Concerts, operators of Universal
Amphitheater and the Greek's head-to-head competitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's propaganda from the other side,'' Burke said.
</P>
<P>
   Soboroff said that while he opposed the process that led to the
Nederlander extension, he would not have voted for a direct
competitor, like House of Blues, to get the city concession.
</P>
<P>
   ``They might have shut down the Greek,'' he said. ``You never
want that kind of control of the market.''
</P>
<P>
   City Councilman Joel Wachs said the council in approving the
contract looked only at how the terms of the extension were more
favorable to the city than the previous contract had been.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's really aggravating is that you had a chance to learn
from your past mistakes, but instead of going out and getting a
better deal they took care of their friends,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The comparison always was made to the past contract, rather
than to what could be.''
</P>
<P>
   --30--
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
