<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-19 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3570 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-LAUSD-SHAMBRA-LADN     12-19 1855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAUSD-SHAMBRA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER BELMONT PROJECT MANAGER SPEAKS OUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BETH BARRETT 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; LOS ANGELES -- As the Belmont Learning Center downtown sits
idled by environmental problems, Dominic Shambra -- the man who
``bears the ultimate responsibility'' for it -- lounges comfortably
in retirement at his San Gabriel Valley ranch.
</P>
<P>
   No guilt, no doubts, no question. In his mind, Mr. Belmont did a
great job and could have successfully completed that job if
political forces hadn't stopped him.
</P>
<P>
   In a financial audit last week, LAUSD chief investigator Don
Mullinax accused Shambra of having ``failed the children'' of Los
Angeles by mismanaging construction of the nation's costliest high
school _ a boarded-up, half-completed, $170 million complex that
might never be finished.
</P>
<P>
   Unfazed, Shambra told the Daily News during his first extensive
interview in nearly a year: ``I sleep like a baby.''
</P>
<P>
   In the next breath, he excoriated his former colleagues,
especially those he believes pigeon-holed him as the villain of
Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't screw them. They screwed themselves,'' he said. ``I
told them they'd rue the day they tried to screw me.''
</P>
<P>
   Mullinax can write all he wants in his audits, Shambra added,
because he's authoring his own book on the scandalous $282-million
construction project. He said he's picked up his pen not so much to
get revenge as to clear his clouded name.
</P>
<P>
   The working title: ``Truth of the Matter.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Looking tanned and slimmer at his home than he did during his
district days brokering speculative real-estate deals from a
downtown highrise, Shambra, 60, is as pugilistic, unrepentant and
blunt as ever.
</P>
<P>
   Unbowed by 14 volumes of environmental concerns raised by
investigators in September and last Tuesday's financial audit of
Belmont, Shambra asked:``What is the problem?''
</P>
<P>
   In his days as a senior administrator responsible only to the
superintendent for the nation's second largest school district,
Shambra said he and his team of consultants merely used the ``power
vacuum'' within the district to his advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just filled it,'' Shambra said. ``Nobody at the district
had ever stepped out of that little cocoon before, and I did. We
were blazing new territory, doing something different, changing the
paradigm of the district.''
</P>
<P>
   Shambra said he diligently jumped through the district's hoops
and claims he and Belmont had oversight, had people watching over
them. But in the end, he always got his way.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were all fools,'' Shambra said of the district hierarchy,
many of whom have been forced out since the first Mullinax report.
</P>
<P>
   Shambra even insists he got the best of Superintendent Ruben
Zacarias.
</P>
<P>
   Zacarias claims to have shut down Shambra's operation in July
1997, but Shambra produces invoices the superintendent signed
through November 1997 to prove he continued to run the project for
nearly six more months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zacarias never said a word to me,'' Shambra said. ``Never.''
</P>
<P>
   The district's auditors paint Shambra as Mr. Belmont, a renegade
bureaucrat who was running a fiefdom with unmonitored and possibly
overpaid consultants doing his bidding.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may try to defend himself by saying, `I had to do what I
had to do to get the job done,' but that doesn't make you
circumvent generally accepted accounting practices,'' Mullinax said
in an interview. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Raised in El Cerrito by Sicilian immigrant parents, Shambra was
used to scrapping and supporting himself.
</P>
<P>
   In 1961, he got a job as an LAUSD after-school playground
coordinator, where his first supervisor was Bill Anton, the man who
would become superintendent about the same time that plans for
Belmont were ripening.
</P>
<P>
   A friendship developed, with Shambra serving later as Anton's
best man. When Anton rose to an upper-management post in 1986,
Shambra followed him into the administration.
</P>
<P>
   Though technically without a managerial title, Shambra had
license to make deals for the district, assertions backed up by
LAUSD and audit records.
</P>
<P>
   Introduced to Orange County ``asset-management consultant''
Wayne Wedin, Shambra found a deal mate: ``A great guy, very bright,
well-connected, knows the process.'' A guy who would be key to
getting Belmont going.
</P>
<P>
   The two soon put together an ambitious, $122 million building
blueprint for the district, which called for six joint-venture
complexes, among them a ``comprehensive high school'' at the
historical Ambassador Hotel downtown, and three elementary schools
designed to educate more than 10,000 students. The San Fernando
Valley was to have gotten a high school and an elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate outcome was a parking garage at Grand Avenue and
17th Street _ and Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, what pleases Shambra most is how he quietly used the
garage to negotiate a deal whereby the Community Redevelopment
Agency agreed to contribute a percentage of its Hollywood tax
increments to the school district. The funds were placed
essentially under his control and allowed him to hire a team of
high-priced consultants to plan and develop Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked doing that kind of thing. It was exciting,'' Shambra
said, adding the district doesn't have the ``brains'' to realize
what that move was worth _ roughly $1 million. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Claiming he wasn't able to get a budget out of the district's
financiers, Shot only got funds from the CRA and the parking
garage. His account received ``contributions'' from the seller of
the largest portion of the Belmont property, Shimizu Corp. of
Japan, and the lead developer, Kajima. The gifts for his
department's work totaled $225,000.
</P>
<P>
   The board approved the donations and the money was deposited in
what was referred to in memorandums as ``Dom Shambra's account.''
</P>
<P>
   Mullinax said the deposits did not appear to be improper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had resources then,'' Shambra said.
</P>
<P>
   But they were sometimes hard to hang onto, according to Shambra
and district records.
</P>
<P>
   Former General Council Richard Mason used a portion of the
$2-million account to pay some of O'Melveny &AMP; Myers' legal fees on
Belmont. And on several other occasions, then-Superintendent Sidney
Thompson asked for money out of the account, Shambra said.
</P>
<P>
   The district is suing O'Melveny for legal malpractice, charges
the downtown firm denies.
</P>
<P>
   The cash that remained at Shambra's fingertips was doled out to
consultants, who were to be the brain trust for all the projects he
envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   In last week's report, LAUSD auditors questioned some of Wedin's
invoices, including work billed on Christmas Day 1995. They also
charged that an overpayment of $11,325 may have been made to
California Financial Services, a firm run by Betty Hanson, a woman
Shambra has dated for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Hanson declined comment for this story, but Shambra said one of
her contracts might not have been counted in the audit.
</P>
<P>
   Wedin earned more than $1.1 million in his 12-year relationship
with the district. In an interview with the Daily News, he chalked
up the failed projects to bad timing, and maintained his
$125-per-hour billings were correct.
</P>
<P>
   ``You work nights, weekends, whatever it takes,'' he said,
adding he even worked that Christmas Day.
</P>
<P>
   Shambra said he has askheed the FBI to review his personal
financial records, and claims to relish the idea of a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I supposedly didn't supervise two consultants. What's
criminal about that?'' Shambra said, adding he had his own methods
of keeping track of Wedin and other others.
</P>
<P>
   Of his detractors: ``I want to see those liars under oath.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Shambra's employment record shows he took over as acting
director of the Planning and Development Office in July 1992 when
Anton was superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   Belmont landed in his lap in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got the biggest gorillas around,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wedin, Hanson, O'Melveny &AMP; Myers' partner David Cartwright,
Ernst &AMP; Young accountants were all part of the ``dream team.'' The
accounting firm also has denied wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no experts in the district,'' Shambra said. ``We
went outside the bureaucracy on purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Shambra said he did all he could to keep district officials at
bay, saying he was purposefully mean and nasty at times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was survival,'' he said. ``Inside the district, I had to
deal with all these a--holes.''
</P>
<P>
   United Teachers Los Angeles President Day Higuchi, no fan of
Shambra's, said: ``Dom's whole way of operating, once he concocted
some kind of deal, was to bulldoze any opposition or questioning
out of the way. Pretty soon it was, `Don't ask.'
</P>
<P>
   ``If no one questions, you can steer the whole ship into the
rocks, which is what happened with Belmont. It was where the
district finally ran aground.''
</P>
<P>
   Shambra also could be a teddy bear when it served his interests,
throwing large receptions at his home, entertaining everyone from
the superintendent to state lawmakers, board members, secretaries
and clerks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a kind, soft side that he also showed to parents and
students,'' Wedin said. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Standing near a reproduction on his office wall of the
$30-million state check used to buy the tainted land for Belmont,
Shambra admitted he made one enormous miscalculation with regard to
Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   He underestimated the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in summer 1995, the hotel and restaurant workers'
union began to challenge the project mainly because it was trying
to organize the New Otani, owned by the parent company of Belmont's
lead development, Kajima International of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Shambra came to despise the union and the union's researcher
David Koff, who worked effectively against the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did a wonderful job of putting out his information,''
Shambra said. Koff will always be an``amoral man, without
scruples.''
</P>
<P>
   Koff began by providing the board with data on the financial
risks associated with Belmont in 1995, and later delved into the
project's environmental problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``He overestimated himself,'' Koff said. ``The Temple Beaudry
site won the war of facts.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; As Belmont rose against the downtown skyline, concern was
mounting, too.
</P>
<P>
   Glendale Democratic Assemblyman Scott Wildman's Joint
Legislative Audit Committee had begun to investigate the project,
to Shambra's irritation. He tried and failed to get then-Attorney
General Dan Lungren to intervene.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was driven to make this thing happen come hell or high
water,'' Wildman said.
</P>
<P>
   The state's Department of Toxic Substances Control and the
LAUSD's safety team by 1998 also were on board, and concluded that
testing on the site _ a former oil field that exudes potentially
explosive methane gas and toxic hydrogen sulfide _ had been
inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   ``They outnumbered me,'' Shambra said. ``It was all easily
(mitigable).'' Flanked by his husky and German shepherd dogs,
Shambra said he won't consider his 37-year LAUSD career really over
as long as Belmont remains unfinished.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a pit bull on Belmont, because there's nothing wrong with
Belmont,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   --30--
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
