<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-POPQUIZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN IS THE LATEST VICTIM OF POP QUIZ 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURLINGTON, Vt. _ Sen. John McCain had his own pop quiz Sunday
and did not fare much better than Gov. George W. Bush did when he
was unable to name some world leaders.
</P>
<P>
   McCain had just finished a lively town meeting, easily and
knowledgeably covering topics from energy conservation to the
increasing cost of prescription drugs to the Comprehensive Test Ban
Treaty and the lack of bipartisanship in foreign policy. But he was
stumped at a subsequent news conference, when a reporter posed a
pop quiz and asked McCain to name the prime minister of Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be Haughey, who's in serious trouble'' he said,
referring to the former Prime Minister Charles J. Haughey who is
being tried on charges of obstructing an inquiry into payments made
to politicians.
</P>
<P>
   As McCain searched his memory, he said Bush should have been
asked questions of substance about foreign policy instead of being
hit with a quiz. He offered his own policy views, saying he was
``pleased with the progress of the peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator Mitchell deserves enormous credit as does this
administration for moving that place forward,'' McCain continued.
He was referring to George Mitchell, the former Democratic senator
who oversaw the peace negotiations in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   McCain rattled off the names of Gerry Adams, president of Sinn
Fein, and David Trimble, the elected leader of the Ulster
Unionists. But he never came up with the name of Prime Minister
Bertie Ahern.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's questioner tried again with an inquiry closer to home:
Who is the governor of Vermont?
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be Snelling,'' McCain said, referring to Richard
Snelling, the governor for nine years. ``I just talked about him
last night,'' he said, stalling, ``He's a Democrat. He's a
doctor....''
</P>
<P>
   Taking pity on him, someone muttered ``Howard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Howard Dean,'' McCain said, ``and I believe he is a
physician.''
</P>
<P>
   If it was a glitch in a day of town meetings and large crowds,
the senator did not appear to take it to heart. Soon he was on the
phone from his campaign bus to a radio talk show host, answering
that he was feeling just fine today ``except for the fact that I
stumbled over the name of Howard Dean.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
