<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-19 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3581 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-R-OUTLOOK-JAPAN-ART-N     12-19 1290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-OUTLOOK-JAPAN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN'S CONTRADICTIONS CLOUD FUTURE DIRECTION OF ECONOMY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Repeating to add art note.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ To almost everyone's surprise, the Japanese economy
showed remarkable _ and remarkably diverse _ signs of life this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign investors, reassured by the seemingly endless stream of
corporate overhauls that began taking place, drove the stock market
higher, pushing the benchmark Nikkei 225 stock index up by more
than 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Topix index, a broader measure of the market, was up an even
more robust 50 percent, and an index of smaller Japanese stocks
more than doubled. Further, the need for yen to buy all those
stocks helped push the currency up against the dollar by 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
   But there the picture begins to get muddied. A stronger yen
crimps the earnings of Japan's exporting giants like Sony, Honda
and Hitachi, whose stocks are favorites of foreign investors. And
so those investors' enthusiasm for Japanese assets actually
imperils the very recovery in which they are so eagerly investing.
</P>
<P>
   Contradictions like this mark many aspects of what is shaping up
as Japan's economic renaissance after nearly a decade of decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a very bumpy ride ahead for the next five years as
reform battles against anti-reform,'' said Richard Katz, author of
``Japan: The System That Soured'' (M.E. Sharpe).
</P>
<P>
   That makes it difficult to be either optimistic or pessimistic
when it comes to Japan's prospects as the century turns.
</P>
<P>
   Take consumer spending. Economists were pleasantly surprised
earlier this year when consumers started opening their wallets
after the government shored up the financial system and offered a
menu of tax breaks to encourage the spending that is needed to
reinvigorate the economy.
</P>
<P>
   But in the face of falling wages, deferred bonuses, job cuts and
hiring freezes, the spending spree stalled late in the year.
</P>
<P>
   Tadashi Nakamae, a prominent economist here, noted that the
monthly Family Income and Expenditure Survey on which the
government bases some of its economic predictions was small and
included the responses of a disproportionate number of civil
servants, who have largely escaped the impact of the restructuring
sweeping the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, in the first three months of this year, when gross
domestic product was at first reported to have grown at a stunning
7.9 percent annualized rate _ later revised to 6.3 percent _ sales
of minicars were exceedingly strong because manufacturers, seeking
to dress up their performance in advance of the fiscal year-end in
March, offered deep incentives. The minicar sales boom soon
quieted.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, there are two interpretations of the economy, which
slowed significantly after that strong first quarter. The growth at
the start of the year was still better than generally expected and
probably ensures that the government will live up to the growth of
six-tenths of 1 percent it pledged for the fiscal year that will
end March 31, in contrast to a decline of 2 percent in gross
domestic product in the 1998 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   But a good part of the current life in the economy that has so
excited foreign investors comes from government spending _ a
whopping $177 billion at current exchange rates this year alone in
supplementary spending aimed at lifting the economy _ much of it
devoted to restoring moribund businesses.
</P>
<P>
   What happens when the government halts that spending, as it
surely must in the not-too-distant future because it cannot sustain
that level in light of its rising debt burden? If data issued at
the end of November _ when the effects of the government's previous
spending package were wearing off _ are any indication, consumer
spending will fall, housing starts will fall and construction
contracts will dwindle.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's fiscal situation is growing more worrisome. The nation
has unseated Italy as the industrialized world's biggest debtor,
with government debt climbing to an estimated 123 percent of the
country's gross domestic product. For the first time since World
War II, government bond issuance will exceed tax revenues in the
fiscal year that ends March 31, and economists expect the
government to go on spending next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our main concern is that, if the current economic stimulus
programs fail to create a self-sustaining recovery, they will not
be abandoned in favor of something else but rather they will be
redoubled,'' said Marshall Gittler, chief currency strategist for
Asia at Bank of America in Hong Kong, who recommends a halt to the
debt-financed supplemental spending.
</P>
<P>
   Bureaucrats, politicians and some economists argue that Japan's
vast savings and extremely low interest rates make the problem less
pressing than the numbers would suggest. Privately, however, many
of them worry that they are saddling future generations with an
enormous burden, particularly since Japan has one of the lowest
birthrates in the world.
</P>
<P>
   But while the government's finances fall into ever greater
disarray, the private sector finally seems to be addressing its
financial mess. Banks and corporations have started working to
repair their balance sheets, shedding both debt and underutilized
assets.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter sold the first set of
securities backed by bad real estate debts; it was the first sign
that banks are finally admitting that the problem loans that pushed
them so perilously close to collapse in 1998 will never be
recovered and must be cleared away.
</P>
<P>
   Hitachi and NEC have allied to manufacture commodity memory
chips; in the past each would have insisted on going it alone. And
Nissan Motors is writing off five factories that it is closing.
Throughout Japan, companies are finally acknowledging, and in some
cases writing off, huge deficits in their pension plans as they
face changes in accounting rules that will go into effect next
year, creating improved clarity for investors.
</P>
<P>
   There is a downside here, however. While these companies attempt
to put their houses in order, they are sharply curtailing capital
investment and, in the process, crimping the economy. When Nippon
Telegraph and Telephone said it would cut its spending by $8.5
billion, NEC, one of the telephone giant's biggest suppliers and
itself in the throes of an overhaul, groaned. It, in turn, will no
doubt cut its spending, passing the pain on to its own suppliers in
a ripple that is being repeated throughout Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I cut my costs, I also cut your sales,'' Katz, the author,
noted.
</P>
<P>
   As long as that sort of reorganization continues, the economy
will be under pressure. Most economists _ and several prominent
Japanese officials, including the head of Japan's central bank,
Masaru Hayami, and Koichi Kato, a potential candidate for prime
minister _ believe that the pain will eventually lead to
self-sustaining economic momentum as leaner companies begin to
perform more competitively.
</P>
<P>
   But a good deal of hard work remains. Robert Alan Feldman, chief
economist at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter in Tokyo, said that for
Japanese companies to raise their return on assets to the levels
they enjoyed in 1990 _ about 4 percent on average, which is meager
by Western standards _ they would either have to cut labor costs by
something like 13 percent or write off as much as 50 percent of
their assets, neither of which is feasible.
</P>
<P>
   ``In short,'' Feldman said, ``investors have probably
underestimated the required scale and scope of the restructuring
effort.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-19-99 2057EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991219.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-19 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3595 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CUBANS-PRISON-DEAL-95     12-19 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBANS-PRISON-DEAL-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. MADE DEAL WITH CUBA TO END LOUISIANA HOSTAGE CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
 (rk) 
 By MARC LACEY with DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ U.S. officials ended a hostage standoff at a
Louisiana prison by striking a deal with the Cuban government that
will permit the seven Cuban inmates at the center of the uprising
to be deported to Havana, federal officials said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The seven Cuban inmates, all deemed a threat to public safety by
the United States, had completed their prison sentences in this
country but were being held indefinitely because their deportation,
the usual procedure for felons who are not citizens, had been
blocked by the government of Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   But Cuba dropped its opposition in an agreement reached with the
State Department on Saturday, and late Saturday night the hostages
were set free and the inmates surrendered.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was highly unusual for two countries that do not
acknowledge each other diplomatically and cannot reach consensus on
far less sensitive matters. What it may portend for U.S.-Cuba
relations remains uncertain. The deal leaves unaddressed the status
of approximately 2,400 other Cubans who are in U.S. jails awaiting
deportation to Cuba, some of whom have resorted to violence in the
past to show their discontent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is clearly a great deal of frustration among the Cubans
who are under detention without any sign of deportation,'' said
Russ Bergeron, a spokesman for the Immigration and Naturalization
Service. ``We view this case as distinct from the others. Here, the
inmates specifically asked to be returned to Cuba and the Cuban
government agreed to take them. That is not the case in the bulk of
the 2,400 others.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials said the decision to grant the
inmates' demands was appropriate in this case because it coincided
with U.S. interests. Attorney General Janet Reno was closely
involved in the decision, aides said, as were officials in the
White House and the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``These inmates requested to be returned to Cuba,'' said Carole
Florman, a Justice Department spokeswoman, ``and if they had been
from anywhere else they would have been returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line,'' she said, ``is we have a resolution here
that's in the best interests of the United States. We have a
situation that might have ended in a messy way that ended
smoothly.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Department contacted Cuban officials through the U. S.
interests section in Havana and worked out a deal in which Cuba
would accept the inmates, a State Department spokeswoman said.
``We're grateful that the situation has been resolved in a peaceful
manner,'' the spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Around midnight, the inmates were taken from the prison in buses
to an undisclosed site under the custody of the Immigration and
Naturalization Service. Officials said the exact timing of the
deportation remained unclear, although it would most likely take
place within a few days. Because there are no direct commercial
flights between the United States and Cuba, the usual means of
deportation, the inmates could be returned on a charter flight, a
military aircraft or a Coast Guard cutter.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities in Louisiana said a chaplain, a Spanish-language
television producer and the mother of one of the hostage takers all
helped resolve the standoff. It was Mercedes Villar, the mother of
inmate Roberto Villar-Grana, who first disclosed a deal between the
United States and Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's over,'' Mrs. Villar told reporters, indicating that she
had seen a written agreement guaranteeing the inmates' safe passage
to Cuba. ``They're on the bus now and going to Cuba. They're going
to an airplane and going to Cuba.''
</P>
<P>
   The rare moment of cooperation between the United States and
Cuba came as the two countries remained at odds on another
immigration case _ that of Elian Gonzalez, a 6-year-old boy who was
rescued off the Florida coast on Nov. 25. The boy survived the
attempted trip to the United States, in which his mother and
stepfather drowned. Cuba has condemned the United States for not
immediately returning the boy to his father in Cuba. After initial
hesitation, the INS has sent signals recently that it intends to
send the boy home. It was unclear whether there was any connection
between the Gonzalez case and the deportation agreement. A Justice
Department official said she knew of no connection.
</P>
<P>
   Demanding to be released or senother country, the inmates
last Monday took over the prison in St. Martinville, La.. Wielding
a knife and screwdriver, the prisoners held as hostages the warden,
Todd Louvierre; a deputy, Jolie Sonnier, and five female inmates.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban prisoners arrived in the United States two decades ago
during the 1980 Mariel boatlift, during which Castro sent thousands
of Cuban criminals to Miami. After committing crimes in this
country _ offenses ranging from drug possession to rape and murder
_ they served their sentences and then found themselves in a legal
limbo.
</P>
<P>
   In all of their cases, an immigration judge had ordered them out
of the country, but the lack of a repatriation agreement between
the United States and Cuba made that impossible. Because they had
been deemed threats to society by an immigration judge, the INS
could not release them pending deportation, immigration officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   There are seven Cubans who are expected to be deported.
Officials said five were in the prison at the time of the
surrender, and two others were believed to be the inmates who gave
up earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
   Immigrants facing deportation can seek to be sent to a country
different from their country of origin as long as that country
agrees to accept them. ``If any third country had agreed to take
them, we would have sent them,'' said Russ Bergeron, a spokesman
with the INS.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The six-day ordeal ended shortly before midnight Saturday, when
a group of police officers and FBI swat team members began running
out of the prison, jumping up and down, cheering and throwing their
helmets and riot shields into the air. When reporters asked them
what was happening, they said the Cubans had given up.
</P>
<P>
   A few moments later, the jail warden who had been shackled to a
chair and held at knifepoint since Monday was wheeled out on a
stretcher to an ambulance. Louvierre, who had grown a beard while a
hostage, was sitting up, shaking hands and smiling. He had a black
eye and a cheek welt which he received during the initial fight
with his captors, but did not appear to be seriously harmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides what you see on my face, they didn't do anything, and
that's really nothing,'' the warden told reporters at a news
conference Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The other remaining jail employee, Jolie Sonnier, came out next,
and was not sitting up on her stretcher. She and Louvierre were
both taken to a local hospital, and officials said neither had been
seriously harmed.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, the hostage takers were led out of a side
door, unshackled, to a green and white motor coach bearing the
insignia of the INS.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts attributed the prison uprising to a flawed U.S.
policy toward Cuba, which has forced the immigration service to
keep as many as 2,400 Cuban inmates in prison well after their
sentences have expired.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they'd gone to the extreme of murder no one would have
supported these inmates,'' said Wayne Smith, who was the ranking
American diplomat in Havana under Presidents Jimmy Carter and
Ronald Reagan and is a leading critic of the embargo against Cuba.
``But you really have to sympathize with them. What are they
supposed to do, just sit there? They obviously became desperate.
Luckily, this situation has been resolved without bloodshed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
