<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ELECT-BOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CONTEST: MANY PARTIES BUT FEW ISSUES
</HEADLINE>
   (With RUSSIA-ELECT) 
(nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Russian voters Sunday elected a new Duma, or lower chamber of
parliament, to sit for four years. Here are some facts and figures
about the election:
</P>
<P>
   THE VOTE: Half of the 450 seats are decided on the basis of
party lists. Any party that gets more than 5 percent of the vote
will get seats in proportion to its overall vote. The other 225
seats are decided on individual constituency races, in which
parties also take part.
</P>
<P>
   THE PARTIES: Twenty-six parties are running, with about six
expected to break the 5 percent vote threshold. The Communists,
currently the largest party, are expected to do well, along with
several centrist parties, including Unity and Fatherland-All
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   THE ISSUES: The campaign has not paid much attention to issues.
Most of the debate has centered on the character of party leaders,
with a great deal of political mudslinging.
</P>
<P>
   THE PARLIAMENT: Russia's legislature consists of the elected
State Duma and a higher chamber, the Federation Council, which
consists of governors of Russia's regions and main cities.
</P>
<P>
   THE DUMA: The lower house has the power to enact legislation and
oversee taxation, but the constitution gives greater power to the
president, who appoints the prime minister and ministers who run
the government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
