<HEADER>
A3604 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-JETS-COWBOYS-NYT &LR;      12-19 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-COWBOYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS RALLY TO KEEP THEIR FAINT PLAYOFF HOPES ALIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ When it seemed their season was over, the New
York Jets continued to surprise Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   For a club given up for dead before a month had gone by, the
Jets took their tissue-thin playoff hopes into the final hours of
Week 14.
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight week they were a comeback team in the
fourth quarter. This time they halted the Cowboys, who had been 6-0
at home this season, 22-21. The winning score was the 37-yard field
goal by the enigmatic place-kicker, John Hall. Just last Sunday, he
missed two extra points against the Dolphins before kicking a
clutch fourth-quarter field goal.
</P>
<P>
   In lifting the Jets' record to 6-8 and his mark as a starter to
4-3, Ray Lucas led the winning drive as he continued to learn on
the job.
</P>
<P>
   As the jubilant Jets left for the flight home, they were
depending on the Arizona Cardinals to beat the Buffalo Bills Sunday
night to keep the Jets' playoff hopes alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids are still hanging _ without much to hope for,'' Coach
Bill Parcells said. His biggest complaint after the game _ or at
least one that he was willing to share _ was a bad play by Lucas on
which he fumbled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're keeping our fingers crossed,'' Wayne Chrebet admitted.
``Yeah, you think back one or two victories here and there _ but
the truth is, we won some games last year that you could say was
luck, too.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the Jets' fifth victory in their last seven games, and
while it left their future uncertain, it kept the Cowboys' division
rival Giants still firmly in the playoff picture.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets are looking more and more professional behind Lucas,
and they showed it against the renowned Cowboys, who are led by
Troy Aikman and Emmitt Smith and with a defense that is one of the
best against the run.
</P>
<P>
   The decisive drive began when the Jets took over with under six
minutes remaining on their 40. With Curtis Martin producing some
quality runs, the Jets moved to the Cowboys' 19.
</P>
<P>
   On the sideline, Hall was calm and focused. ``I don't even hear
Bill Parcells screaming at me when I've got to come in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Had he been concerned about last week's two extra-point misses?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what you're talking about,'' he told the
questioner.
</P>
<P>
   This was an often bizarre game: A back-up tight end named Eric
Bjornson, who has the arcane skill of being able to hold a football
for place-kicks, scored his second touchdown in the last three
years to put the Cowboys ahead by halftime.
</P>
<P>
   But Bjornson neither caught the ball nor received a handoff from
Aikman. Instead, he loped home 20 yards on a faked field-goal
attempt to give the Cowboys a 14-13 lead. His last touchdown
running came the same way a year ago _ on a faked kick.
</P>
<P>
   This worked so well the Jets gave him the complete right side of
the field and he had little trouble crossing the goal-line after
taking the snap from Dale Hellestoroe, as Eddie Murray lined up as
if to kick.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets had kept the Cowboys pinned back, for the most part.
But punting was to play a key role for both sides during the early
going.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets took a 6-0 lead on Hall field goals to cap their first
two possessions. The first, a 47-yarder, was the kicker's longest
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But on their third drive the Jets had to punt, and this set the
stage for the game within the game among Tom Tupa, Chris Hayes and
Deion Sanders. Tupa had said he wouldn't hesitate to kick the ball
toward Sanders, arguably the most dangerous punt-returner in pro
football. Tupa has supreme confidence in the Jets' leading
``gunner,'' Chris Hayes, who leads the club in special-teams'
tackles.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders lined up on his 40, waving the crowd on to cheer. Tupa
then launched a 55-yard bazooka shot that drove Sanders back toward
the right sideline. Hayes was off with the punt, trying to bear
down on Sanders. But the Cowboys had him covered and Hayes was
pushed continuously as the tried to find a hole to nail Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Sanders eluded everyone else for 26 yards, and that
helped position the Cowboys' first score.
</P>
<P>
   Smith handled the ball four straight times _ three runs good for
27 yards, and then a 14-yard pass to the right flat, where Smith
apparently was forgotten about by the Jets' defense. He rambled in
for the score to put the Cowboys ahead by 7-6.
</P>
<P>
   The next time the Jets punted, though, they produced another of
those big plays that has enabled them to stay competitive in this
learning season of Lucas'. Tupa's 51-yard punt was downed on the 1
by Dwight Stone.
</P>
<P>
   ``By then,'' explained Tupa, ``we just decided to kick it
straight and high _ do what we do best.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys could not dig out of the hole and the Jets got the
ball back in good field position. It got even better after Dedric
Ward drew a 34-yard pass-interference call against Kevin Smith that
put the ball on the Dallas 1.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas immediately drilled a touchdown pass to Richie
Anderson-Lucas's seventh scoring pass without an interception in
the last three games. He was to wind up firing two touchdowns,
although he was intercepted for the first time in 156 throws.
</P>
<P>
   That lead lasted only a few minutes, though, as Bjornson kept
alive his career. The Jets had a chance to go ahead as halftime
approached. Hall, though, was wide with a 49-yard attempt.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' lead expanded to 21-13 on another bit of trickery
in the third quarter. This time Rocket Ismail produced a 27-yard
score on an end-around.
</P>
<P>
   The surprises continued, though. Lucas, who had earlier thrown
the longest pass of his career, 35 to Keyshawn Johnson, connected
on one of 38 yards to Chrebet, then for 14 to Keyshawn _ and
finally a 2-yard scoring pass to Blake Spence.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first career score for Spence, the second-year tight
end who is one of the Parcells Five. They are the young players he
warned 10 days ago that their careers were on the line in these
final games.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing by 21-19, the Jets went for the 2-point play. But
Lucas, on a delayed keeper, was stopped short. It was only a
temporary embarrassment. After all, Lucas said, ``the game is
slowing down for me. I'm seeing things more clearly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
