u k BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT     12-19 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: TO STOP THE EAVESDROP
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Md., Calif., Fla.)  (nk) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Justice prosecutors protect Asian money agents John
Huang and Charlie Trie so they won't rat on higher-ups; a Clinton
appointee protects Buddhist money-raiser Maria Hsia lest she expose
Al Gore; the Arkansas Bar Association refuses to disbar a member
who misled a federal judge.
</P>
<P>
   Contrast that to the prosecution in Democratic Maryland of Linda
Tripp for daring to embarrass a Democratic president by taping her
calls with Monica Lewinsky. In a year of cover-ups and corruptions
of the law, the one person facing jail is the one who forced out
the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp's mistake was to rely on immunity issued by the
independent counsel. Because it had not yet been approved by a
federal judge, her subsequent taping is being prosecuted by an
ambitious pol currying Democratic favor by seeking vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   So this is a palpable case of selective prosecution for partisan
purposes, right? Yes, but. The famous Tripp taping of her
conversations with Monica, further publicized by this witch hunt in
Maryland, may do a lot of good for privacy in America.
</P>
<P>
   I became radicalized about this after learning of being
illegally wiretapped in 1969, when I was a Nixon speechwriter.
These third-party intrusions _ handing-around of transcripts of
private talks with my wife, doctor and rabbi _ were compounded by
the self-taping of calls by Nixon, following the ugly tradition set
by his Oval Office predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   That turned me into a privacy nut. In the '80s, I caught a
Reagan crony, then running the USIA, secretly taping many of his
calls. In D.C., this privacy invasion was no crime. His only
vulnerability came from calls he surreptitiously taped while in
Florida, a state that forbids such preying on its residents, but
the case was easily squelched.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with Maryland's active prosecution of Tripp's surreptitious
taping _ a shameful act _ being publicized far and wide, future
miscreants will no longer be able to profess ignorance that it can
be an illegal act.
</P>
<P>
   That's to the good. When your voice is recorded without your
knowledge, you may find yourself at the mercy of a blackmailer or
entrapper. If you speak with the reasonable expectation of privacy
_ as we do when speaking on the phone or in other private
conversation _ your friend or neighbor or business associate should
not be able to use your recorded voice to coerce or embarrass you.
</P>
<P>
   With the proliferation of small, cheap recording devices, the
sense of distrust in communication has grown. What is this doing to
our society? Are we becoming a nation of snoops and doublecrossers?
Do we have to guard everything we say lest it be played back
against us? Unrecorded, you can say you were misunderstood, or turn
forgetful; but with your voice on somebody else's tape, your
faithless friend or tricky competitor can prove everything you
thought you said in confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Secret taping is ethically wrong, but our ethical sense has been
eroded by easy technology and general thoughtlessness. Therefore,
we should lean on local legislators to make electronic
eavesdropping illegal, unless court-ordered for law enforcement.
That goes both for recording your own phone and wearing a wire to
entrap your friends.
</P>
<P>
   Where does the great state of New York, supposed bastion of
civil liberty, stand on this? Its latest so-called ``right to
privacy'' statute prohibits third-party wiretaps, but it allows the
taping of conversations with the consent of only one of the
participants. Some privacy; that gives New Yorkers the license to
record their callers, or to secretly tape-record anything said by
visitors to their homes or offices. Big Neighbor Is Bugging You.
</P>
<P>
   California, Florida, Maryland and 10 other alert states prohibit
that interpersonal snoopery. But states unconcerned with privacy _
New York and the rest of the sheep _ are waiting for federal law to
do their job for them. The telecommunications lobby won't let it
happen.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Tripp's justification for taping is that she needed proof
to protect herself when the White House came after her for
truth-telling. She did what she considered right wrongly. I hope
her presumption of immunity keeps her out of the slammer, but if it
does not _ and if she were to call me from jail _ she can rest
assured I would tape nothing without her advance consent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-19-99 2116EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991219.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-19 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3613 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-JAPAN-EXECUTIONS-NYT &LR;      12-19 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-EXECUTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN CARRIES OUT EXECUTIONS IN NEAR-SECRECY 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The deaths by hanging of Teruo Ono and Kazuo Sagawa last
week merited only a single sentence from the Japanese government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two condemned people were executed today,'' read the
announcement sent anonymously to the press on Friday. The names of
the condemned were not included.
</P>
<P>
   Repeated telephone calls to the Justice Ministry, which oversees
executions, produced little more. Officials declined to identify
the executed, or even to describe their crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The few facts known about the executed men _ their names, their
murder convictions and their lack of many relatives _ could be
learned only from lawmakers and rights advocates, and from Justice
Ministry officials who nervously confirmed the details while
insisting on anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Yet far from being unusual, the executions were part of what has
become a peculiar twice-a-year ritual in Japan, the only advanced
industrialized country besides the United States that still
executes prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   The United States executes far more people each year, but
opponents of the death penalty in Japan say this country is
distinguished by unusual cruelty in the conditions of detention and
the near-secret application of capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Prisoners remain on death row as long as 20 or 30 years, with
much of the time spent in solitary confinement, Japanese rights
groups say. Families are kept in the dark until the executions have
been carried out, and the condemned prisoners themselves are given
only an hour's notice. Indeed, until recently the government made
no announcement at all about its executions and refused to confirm
their occurrence.
</P>
<P>
   Japan has executed 32 prisoners in this fashion in the last 10
years, and 50 more remain on death row.
</P>
<P>
   The executions, which typically take place in the summer and at
year's end, are conducted when Parliament is in recess, to avoid
parliamentary discussion. Local news organizations, sparsely
informed, seem little inclined to probe the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we notify the prisoner beforehand,'' said a spokesman for
the Justice Ministry, ``the person's emotional state may become
disturbed. Therefore we can't notify anyone before the hanging,
including the prisoner. After the execution, we inform the family
as quickly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Rights advocates in Japan offer a different explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Japanese government has been trying to hide the death
penalty from public discussion, very successfully,'' said Julie
Morizawa, secretary-general of Amnesty International Japan. ``We
don't know beforehand what is happening with prisoners. The
government simply executes people and then sends out a one-line fax
announcing it. This is what they call disclosure of information, or
transparency.''
</P>
<P>
   For many critics this secretiveness speaks volumes about the way
Japanese society functions. Bureaucratic authorities typically make
decisions affecting the lives of large numbers of people after
little or no public debate.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of an outright crisis, the country's weak
nongovernmental organizations and civic groups make little noise
about policies that will affect them. The press registers the
passing of events, often serving more as an official gazette than a
critical institution, and the public quietly acquiesces.
</P>
<P>
   Making matters worse, there is a strong tendency to sweep away
painful, embarrassing or contentious matters, however important,
rather than air them or encourage open debate.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the death penalty is popular in Japan. Its critics say
any serious re-examination of the issue is all the more unlikely
since a number of spectacular recent crimes, particularly the
poison gas attack on a Tokyo subway in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a few critics, including members of Parliament, see the
silence surrounding the death penalty as contributing to what may
come to be seen as the wrongful death of the prisoners executed
last week.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment of his execution, a lawyer for Ono was petitioning
to reopen his case. But the Justice Ministry chose to ignore that
fact, said Nobuaki Futami, a legislator who is secretary-general of
the parliamentary Association for the Abolishment of the Death
Penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, a citizens group petitioned recently for a stay of
execution for Sagawa and succeeded in getting the Tokyo Detention
Center, where he was incarcerated, to offer its evaluation of him.
</P>
<P>
   Here again, before the prison could finish its review, the
Justice Ministry ordered that the punishment be carried out.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the United States,'' Futami said, ``notice is given to the
prisoner and to his family, and often a farewell dinner is even
held. If we had such practices in Japan, Mr. Sagawa would have
known that a petition had been filed on his behalf, and perhaps the
execution could have been delayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the ministry has become more bold in carrying out its
executions, and what we have is a big problem from the standpoint
of human rights.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
