<SLUG> BC-DEMS-DEBATE-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE AND BRADLEY AS PERFORMERS ON A POLITICAL STAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (With DEMS-DEBATE) 
(mk) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Their Tweedledum-Tweedledee wardrobes and demeanor said a lot
about what to expect from the debate between Al Gore and Bill
Bradley on NBC's ``Meet the Press'' on Sunday. Sitting side by side
in dark suits and nearly identical red ties, they even folded their
hands on the table the same way, a tableau of two Democrats
fraternally agreeing on the big issues while quibbling over such
details as how to finance health care.
</P>
<P>
   But halfway through the hour, Vice President Gore used a
question about campaign finance to drag in his immodest proposal:
that the men debate twice a week and eliminate all radio and
television commercials.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a ridiculous proposal,'' Bradley said, and the
five-minute exchange that followed revealed more strikingly than
ever their deep philosophical differences on political stagecraft.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley came off as a postmodern actor, demonstrating honesty by
calling attention to the theatrical artifice that is a political
campaign. With roots in the Method style of displaying emotions
directly, he worked to reveal ``candor.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore came off as an old-fashioned actor whose approach is to
ignore the artifice and pretend that what happens on stage is
``real.'' He was ready with his dramatic flourishes and props,
committed to the script.
</P>
<P>
   They may have looked like Tweedledum and Tweedledee but in
performance Bradley was Spalding Gray to Gore's Jack Lemmon, two
styles that do not belong in the same generation, much less the
same play. And performance style is not a flippant issue here; it
suggests how each man would act out the real-life role of
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could call it the `Meet the Press' agreement,'' Gore said
of his proposition. ``I'm willing to do it right now if you'll
shake on it.'' And he extended his hand to create the image
calculated to become the photo of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is, Al, and I don't know if you get this, but a
political campaign is not just a performance for people, which is
what this is,'' Bradley said, subtly gesturing to the set around
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not what I'm doing,'' Gore insisted, holding his hands to
his chest in a gesture of sincerity.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley continued, saying a campaign is ``a dialogue with people
where you listen,'' his smile suggesting the absurdity of the Gore
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   And he concluded by calling attention to Gore's media strategy:
``I'm not someone who's interested in tactics, Al. That was a very
interesting ploy on `Meet the Press.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``These aren't tactics, it's how we discuss issues,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Those strategies were not invented Sunday. After Bradley's
appearance on campaign finance reform on Thursday with Sen. John
McCain of Arizona, a candidate for the Republican presidential
nomination, a voter asked whether that staged handshake wasn't mere
``grandstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Accepting the need for media stunts, he answered, ``This is the
reality of campaigning.''
</P>
<P>
   But on a recent ``60 Minutes,'' Gore took Lesley Stahl home to
meet his mother in Tennessee and stood on the porch casually saying
he would be back for lunch, studiously avoiding any acknowledgment
of the cameras or the event's staginess.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these differences, both candidates seem to be warming to
the debate process. They were more engaged with each other's ideas
Sunday than they were during Friday's town hall meeting on ABC's
``Nightline,'' when they talked past each other, and Ted Koppel,
the moderator, seemed so reluctant to step in that the conversation
meandered without much purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's debate suggested that these candidates need a deft
moderator to keep them on track, which Tim Russert did with
detailed questions that helped cut through the campaign rhetoric.
And knowing when to step in and when to let the candidates go, he
smartly allowed the exchange about the Gore proposal to take its
course.
</P>
<P>
   But five minutes is long in television time, and Gore might have
won the battle of the sound bites. A CNN report, typical of the
debate coverage, began by noting that Bradley ``will not be taking
up Gore's offer'' to drop advertising. Playing a few seconds of the
conversation, it reduced a revealing exchange to the kind of skewed
news snippet that may be the media campaign's true defining force.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
