<SLUG> BC-NBC-INTERNET-500&AMP;ADD0NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBC TO SUPPORT A HIGH-SPEED INTERNET SERVICE OVER PHONE LINES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ill., Mass.) (EDS: Note (AT) in place of symbol in 20th graf) 
 (rk) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NBC, along with several affiliated companies, has agreed to
support a new nationwide service that will offer high-speed
Internet access over telephone lines.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, NBC's primary forays into the Internet have been
MSNBC, its cable and Internet news joint venture with Microsoft,
and the Snap.com Web service, a broad search and directory site, in
which it is the controlling shareholder. Both MSNBC and Snap.com
serve people who already have a connection to the Internet at their
homes or offices.
</P>
<P>
   Now NBC and affiliate companies are investing $70.5 million for
a 19.5 percent stake in Telocity, a company based in Cupertino,
Calif., that last month introduced a high-speed DSL, or digital
subscriber line, Internet service for $50 a month.
</P>
<P>
   The investment represents $37.5 million in cash and $33 million
in television advertising and online promotion and will be made by
NBC; its parent company, General Electric; NBCi, the company that
operates Snap; and Value Vision International, a cable shopping
channel in which GE has a large stake.
</P>
<P>
   High-speed Internet access, also known as broadband service, can
be offered either over cable television systems or telephone lines.
In either case, the speed of downloading information can be as much
as 20 to 30 times faster than using standard 56K modems. That is
fast enough to let users link to audio and video programming as
well as Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is NBC's turf,'' said Martin J. Yudkovitz, president of
NBC Interactive Media. ``High-speed broadband means video. And
finally the Internet is moving to a turf we understand as well as
or better than anyone else in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC is entering one of the most competitive and difficult areas
of the Internet. America Online, which dominates the market for
traditional slow-speed access, said on Friday that its subscriber
base had reached 20 million.
</P>
<P>
   The fastest growing segment of the Internet-access market,
however, is made up of companies offering deeply discounted or free
Internet services, including NetZero and new offerings from
Wal-Mart Stores and Kmart.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's entry into the high-speed market will compete with cable
companies, including AT&AMP;T and Time Warner, telephone companies like
Bell Atlantic, and newcomers like Rhythms NetConnections. America
Online has its own high-speed offering in the form of deals with
telephone companies, called AOL Plus, which also uses DSL
technology over standard phone lines. The growing competition is
likely to depress the prices for high-speed service, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current price is $49.95 a month, but prices will go way
down over the next 18 months,'' predicted Dave Burstein, the editor
of DSL Prime, a trade publication.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement calls for NBCi to create programming for
Telocity that would include the portal features of Snap plus
special audio and video programming that takes advantage of the
high speed.
</P>
<P>
   NBC will receive some Telocity subscription revenue and Telocity
will earn part of the revenue NBC earns selling ads on the service.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement lets NBC invest in rivals of Telocity, but
Telocity is prohibited from dealing with competitors of NBCi.
Indeed, Snap now provides programming for several other companies
that offer high-speed service, including Bell Atlantic.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Telocity was founded in 1997 by Peter Olson, a founder of Octel
Communications, a voice-mail equipment maker that was bought by
Lucent Technologies. It does not operate its own telecommunication
network; instead, it leases DSL connections from local telephone
companies. DSL allows a single telephone line to be used
simultaneously for voice calls and high-speed data.
</P>
<P>
   Telocity, however, employs a high-speed modem that enables
consumers to connect a computer to the DSL line without requiring a
visit from a technician. The device also contains a microprocessor
and has the capacity to offer other services like home networks,
video feeds to television sets and home security.
</P>
<P>
   Officially Telocity sells the modem for $99, though it is
offering it free in promotions. The cost to build the device will
be about $150 next year, as volume increases, said Patti Hart, the
company's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   The Telocity service is now available in Chicago and several
cities in the Southeast. It has 2,500 subscribers. By the end of
next year, the company plans to offer the service in 35 major
markets nationwide and in 50 markets by the end of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the market for high-speed access has grown slowly, in
large part because the services were not available to most
customers. The Yankee Group, a Boston consulting firm, estimates
that only 11 percent of homes in the United States can now get DSL
service and 25 percent can get high-speed cable service. So far,
Yankee estimates, there are 300,000 home users of DSL, with SBC
Communications as the technology's leading provider.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer than 2 million households now subscribe to high-speed
cable modem services. Excite(AT)Home, the high-speed Internet
service controlled by AT&AMP;T and a group of other cable companies,
has 1 million subscribers. Road Runner, backed principally by Time
Warner and the MediaOne Group, has 420,000 subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   But NBC is betting that these numbers will grow rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look eight years out, we believe that 60 to 70 percent
of the households will have broadband access,'' said Edmond
Sanctis, the president of NBCi.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-19-99 2138EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991219.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-19 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3630 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-TERROR-RDP-1STLD-WRIT     12-19 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERROR-RDP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE WARNS OF `HEIGHTENED RISK' OF TERRORIST ACTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS to insert `the state of' in lede for clarification.) 
(See also TERROR-BORDERS) 
(mk) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With security being tightened after the arrest of
an Algerian man who crossed the Canadian border into the state of
Washington with powerful bomb-making materials, President Clinton's
national security adviser warned Americans on Sunday to be more
vigilant over the next few weeks because of a ``heightened risk of
terrorist actions.''
</P>
<P>
   While the State Department has issued similar warnings in recent
weeks for Americans traveling abroad during millennial
celebrations, Sandy Berger, the White House's ranking security
aide, broadened the caution Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not aware of any other specific threat against
particular targets in the United States, and obviously if that
changes we'll alert the American people,'' Berger said on the CBS
program ``Face the Nation.'' ``But I would think that as Americans
go about their plans for New Year's, they simply should be
vigilant.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, ``If they see something suspicious, or see
packages or activities that they think are unusual, they should
obviously let law enforcement people know.''
</P>
<P>
   For several weeks, American officials have been walking a
careful line between urging citizens to exercise prudence on the
one hand, while on the other hand not seeming alarmist. But while
security forces have been put on alert in American cities that are
planning millennial celebrations, the main concern has been
overseas, because intelligence agencies have said they have
``specific and credible'' information that Americans abroad are
being targeted by extremists.
</P>
<P>
   Even without other such evidence about the risks of an attack in
the United States, the arrest in Washington state has prompted
tighter security at the borders.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said that investigators had so far been unable to discern
the motives, plans and possible affiliations of the Algerian, Ahmed
Ressam, who was arrested last week after he crossed the border by
ferry into Port Angeles, Wash., driving a car filled with the
ingredients for a powerful bomb.
</P>
<P>
   The car carried nitroglycerin, urea powder and timing devices
that officials said were capable of being used in a bomb that could
have caused substantial damage to an office building or a crowd of
people.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said that Ressam was being investigated for possible ties
to a wide range of terrorist groups, including the organization
headed by Osama Bin Laden, the exiled Saudi millionaire who lives
in Afghanistan and is accused of being behind the bombings of two
American embassies in Africa last year. Some officials have said
that Ressam may have had affiliations with the Islamic Armed Group,
a terrorist organization that operates primarily in North Africa
and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Montreal, where Ressam had lived, reported that
they had discovered evidence that he might have shared an apartment
with Karim Said Atmani, who was extradited by Canada to France
following charges that he participated in several bombings,
including one of a Paris subway in 1995 that killed four people and
injured 86.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian authorities were investigating possible ties between
Ressam and a group of 11 other men, most of Algerian origin, who
had been arrested over the last few months for thefts. Officials
say that the thefts, which consisted of more than 5,000 items, may
have been part of a broader scheme to help finance Algerian
terrorist activities. American officials have said that Ressam has
a Canadian criminal record for theft of property valued at under
$5,000, and that he was being sought on a Canadian arrest warrant.
</P>
<P>
   His arrest as he left Canada last week has prompted American
customs officials to tighten security even more than they already
had. Border guards, American embassies, military installations and
local police in big cities have also been on heightened alert.
</P>
<P>
   Customs officials in Washington said Sunday that they would add
at least 150 more inspectors at remote sites across the Mexican and
Canadian borders, including Port Angeles, in response to the arrest
of Ressam. The additional security would come from a combination of
redeployed customs inspectors and overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Kelly, commissioner of the Customs Service, said that
because of concerns about terrorist attacks during the year-end
holidays, Customs, like other law enforcement agencies, had been
placed on a ``heightened state of alert'' even before the latest
episode. The new steps, he said, were an additional tightening of
security.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is fair to assume that this person tried to cross at a
remote point because of the fairly minimal staffing we have
there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said that travelers would be unlikely to have longer waits
when entering the United States, either at remote places or the
largest international airports.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement agencies around the world have been taking steps
to head off possible terrorist acts. In Pakistan, authorities in
Islamabad said they had arrested more than 200 people, mostly
Afghan nationals, and tightened security in the largest airports to
avert attacks on American citizens, according to The Associated
Press. The arrests were made in Islamabad, the Pakistani capital,
and in northwestern Peshawar, which borders Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, officials in Jordan arrested 13 people who Jordanian
authorities said were planning attacks there after being trained in
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Canadian Security Intelligence Service said
Sunday that the potential for terrorist-related violence by Muslim
extremists has been a top concern of the agency in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   That concern has been heightened by the attention surrounding
millennium-eve celebrations and Ressam's arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Islamic extremists may use the millennial celebrations to
further their interests with terrorist acts, said Dan Lambert of
the CSIS.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
