<HEADLINE>
PERFECT GIFTS OF THE SEASON FOR A HIKER OR A CANOEIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By NELSON BRYANT   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you are still stumped on what to get a friend for the
holidays, you might consider a map. It can be a visual delight, an
essential navigational tool or a fascinating historical record.
</P>
<P>
   If your friend's digs are sufficiently commodious, consider a
wall map. The maps produced by Raven Maps and Images are not only
beautiful, they also give you the big picture of your state or
region at a glance. The company's offerings include maps of 43 of
the 50 states, one for North America and another for the entire
United States (minus Alaska and Hawaii), plus world maps.
</P>
<P>
   What makes these maps unusual is their almost three-dimensional
appearance, achieved through elevation tinting and shading that
enables the viewer to instantly see the contours of the land. The
tinting ranges from greens for the lower elevations, through
yellows, tans, browns, grays and, finally, white for the highest
points. The shading is applied as if the sun were in the northwest.
Those skilled in reading standard topographic maps can swiftly
discern mountains, hills and valleys, and river drainages, but it's
a knack that takes much time to master.
</P>
<P>
   Raven's state maps, which include major highways, cities, towns,
lakes and rivers, put landforms in perspective with minimal reading
effort. They would be an ideal gift for many, but are large in
order to accommodate their exquisite detail _ so large that you're
not going to find room for one of them in many places in the
average home. My Raven map of Maine, which measures 36 inches by 48
inches, will hang on the staircase wall of my family's lodge on
Maine's Salmon Stream Lake, alongside several topographic maps that
zero in on the specific area.
</P>
<P>
   Raven maps vary in size. The New York State map is 43 inches by
59 inches; the map of Alaska is 35 by 64; that of the lower 48
states is 37 by 58. On the other hand, Massachusetts, Connecticut
and Rhode Island are combined in one map that measures 32 by 36.
Obviously, the maps of some of the larger states and of the lower
48 are on a more condensed scale than the others.
</P>
<P>
   State maps cost $25, or $45 for a laminated version.
Information: (800) 237-0798 or www.ravenmaps.com.
</P>
<P>
   Raven maps are not, of course, for those who wish to find their
way on foot across the wilderness. For that, one's minimal needs
are a decent compass and topographic maps drawn to a suitable
scale. A topo map on a scale of 1:25,000, on which one inch equals
slightly more than 2,000 feet, is ideal, although maps with a scale
of about one inch to a mile are satisfactory.
</P>
<P>
   Costing only a few dollars each, topos also make good gifts, but
you have to know the precise area that the person _ hiker, hunter
or canoeist _ plans to visit. Such maps come in so-called
quadrangles and you might, for example, need to buy four of them to
embrace the area your friend intends to explore.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes you get lucky. I have before me the Errol (New
Hampshire) quadrangle of the topographic map series put out by the
United States Geological Survey, and it so happens that its
northern half completely covers the area where I frequently go deer
hunting. It is on a scale of 1:62,500, approximately an inch to the
mile. The map measures 17 by 12 inches, and most of my hunting is
confined to a four-mile-square area. A deer hunter poking along in
the boondocks rarely covers more than a few miles each day; if he
does, he's moving too fast. He obviously will need fewer maps than
someone who plans hiking or canoeing explorations of a region.
</P>
<P>
   Topo maps can often be had from sporting goods shops or
bookstores. In general, however, such stores only carry maps of
their own state or adjoining ones. Maps of the United States east
of the Mississippi can be obtained by writing Branch of
Distribution, U.S. Geological Survey, 1200 South Eads St.,
Arlington, Va. 22202, and requesting a map index for the state you
are interested in, or by ordering online at mapping.usgs.gov.
</P>
<P>
   If all this map searching seems too time-consuming, you could
make a gift of a Sierra Club paperback, ``Land Navigation
Handbook'' by W.S. Kals. It is a first-rate text on using map and
compass, and it lists many map sources. An equally good text is
``Be Expert With Map and Compass'' by Bjorn Kjellstrom (Scribners).
</P>
<P>
   Some maps can also lead one on a delightful journey to centuries
past. ``Mapping Boston'' (280 pages, MIT Press, illustrated, $50)
edited by Alex Krieger, David Cobb and Amy Turner, is a big,
handsome, brilliantly executed blend of old and new maps and
related essays on the social, political and physical history of
Boston as well as that of American cartography. Included are old
and rare maps from Norman B. Leventhal's unmatched collection.
</P>
<P>
   Surprising historical nuggets are constantly encountered in
``Mapping Boston,'' such as the information that large areas of the
city were built on land created by dredging muck from tidal flats
or salt marshes that once teemed with shellfish, ducks and rail
birds.
</P>
<P>
   To mark the book's publication, exhibits from Leventhal's map
collection run through Jan. 14 at the Boston Public Library and the
New England Aquarium. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
