<HEADLINE>
FEICK'S JUMP SHOOTING SURPRISES MUTOMBO AS NETS DOWN HAWKS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ In the 50 or so games since Jamie Feick
first emerged as a legitimate NBA player, he has become known as a
brawler, a strong and physical hustler who tracks down missed shots
with ferocity. But Feick has never seen himself in such limited
terms.
</P>
<P>
   In his mind, he has always been a good leaper, a solid passer
and the owner of a dependable jump shot out to 18 feet. All but
Feick's New Jersey Nets teammates and coaches have been less than
receptive to his view of himself, smiling and remaining silent as
he relates his various gifts. After Sunday night, however, the
notion of Feick as a jump shooter might finally gain acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets' 6-foot-8-inch center solved the league's most
intimidating interior defender, Atlanta's Dikembe Mutombo, by
drifting outside and draining jump shots from as far as 21 feet
away. Feick's shooting display, along with his team-high 13
rebounds, helped the Nets (8-17) defeat the Hawks, 96-88, before
11,990 fans at Continental Arena. The victory was the Nets' fifth
straight at home and their sixth in their last eight games.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, a clearly tickled Feick, who hit seven jump shots in
scoring a season-high 16 points on 8-for-13 shooting, recited the
spiel he has been setting before reporters since he arrived in New
Jersey on a 10-day contract on March 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got it; I just don't use it a whole lot,'' Feick said
with a smile, when asked about his outside touch. ``Today I just
felt like I was in a rhythm. Mutombo was sagging off of me, and I
just tried to bring him away from the basket to open things up. And
I had some open looks and just took the shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Feick, who entered the game averaging 7.2 points on 41.8 percent
shooting, did nearly all of his damage during critical stretches.
After Atlanta (10-14) used a 19-3 run to turn a 12-point deficit
into a 51-47 lead in the second quarter, he followed a 3-pointer by
Johnny Newman with consecutive 19-footers to keep the Nets from
going into the locker room without momentum.
</P>
<P>
   He sparked another rally in the third quarter by scoring three
straight Nets baskets to close a 69-65 gap and tie the game at 73
heading into the fourth. Stephon Marbury, who made two free throws
during the Feick run, teamed with his center for a fascinating
play.
</P>
<P>
   While Feick was cutting to the right side of the basket, Marbury
hit him with a bullet pass from the left wing. With his momentum
pulling him upwards, Feick caught the ball and managed to avoid a
flying Chris Crawford while keeping his left foot on the ground.
Now on the other side of the basket, he put in a layup to start the
surge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had to be ugly,'' Feick said of his basket, ``because it
sure felt ugly. I don't know how I did it. Just lucky, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Feick gave the Nets a 77-75 lead with a 19-footer early in the
fourth and then got beside himself. Apparently feeling his oats, he
lofted a long jumper from the top of the key on the Nets' next
possession and hit nothing but air.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got fouled on that one,'' Feick joked.
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted, he started the game-turning 14-5 run with a 16-footer
with 5 minutes, 43 seconds remaining that put the Nets ahead by
83-79. Kendall Gill added two jumpers. Kerry Kittles scored on a
fast-break layup. Keith Van Horn scored consecutive baskets on
splendid inside moves, and then Feick closed the spurt with another
19-footer with 19.5 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Mutombo, who had 13 rebounds but just four points in a lethargic
offensive effort, was stunned by Feick's shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know he was capable of making shots from out there,''
Mutombo said. ``I take my hat off to him. I didn't want to chase
him.''
</P>
<P>
   As has been their style during their resurgence, the Nets'
offense was characterized by balance. Van Horn led with 20 points
and eight rebounds. Gill added 15 points, five assists and two
steals while Kittles scored 14. And Marbury, shooting 5 for 13, had
12 points and 11 assists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
