<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-19 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3639 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-GEORGE-COLUMN-NYT     12-19 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GEORGE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PRO FOOTBALL: GIANTS LEARN THAT RAMS ARE A PRETTY GOOD TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (With FBN-GIANTS-RAMS) 
 (rk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The Rams believed the Giants saw them this way:
</P>
<P>
   As puppies. Soft and cuddly. No experience at being a
frontrunner or a champion. A bunch that had not beaten a winning
team and therefore was living a dream. A team they could run on. A
team they could score on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We respected the Giants before they came here; we didn't say
too much,'' said Rams linebacker Mike Jones. ``But here was all
this stuff last week coming from them about not being in awe of us
and how they could run the ball on us. We took this game very
personally. You could tell by all of the pushing and shoving out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   And jawing and baiting. One Ram, Orlando Pace, fell for it _ he
was tossed for fighting a little more than seven minutes before
halftime of Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That team, they talk a bunch of smack and it ain't pretty,''
said Rams cornerback Todd Lyght. ``They did a good job getting
Orlando out of the game. They knew with all of our guns they had no
chance of beating us.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said: ``Howard Cross was yelling at us before the game:
`West Coast offense! Soft offense!' All they did all day was bring
the noise.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Fassel, the Giants head coach, said no, he was sure his team
respected the Rams. He said studying films revealed to his players
that the Rams were physical.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe all of the raw attitude surrounding Giants-Rams was simply
gamesmanship, Fassel said. And emotion.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, especially for the Giants, there was too much of it.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Agnew, a defensive tackle, used to play for the Giants. He
is a Ram now. ``The only thing the Giants said to me all day was,
`Hello, Ray,''' Agnew said, smiling. ``I know those guys. The
Giants have a lot of very confident players. Everything they say
they believe. When I was there we didn't think the teams from the
NFC West were as physical as the teams from the NFC East. I'm sure
the Giants thought that of the Rams. You can think anything you
want. The problem is when you have to go out and prove it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hello, Ray.
</P>
<P>
   He's got something there, because that is exactly where it got
sticky for the Giants in their 31-10 loss to the Rams here at the
Trans World Dome. The Giants could prove nothing. They pushed and
got shoved.
</P>
<P>
   They did not gain a first down until a few plays into the second
quarter. In the game's first 15 minutes, the Rams smacked the
Giants and were by far the more physical team. In the first quarter
the Rams won in first downs, 8-0. In yards, 141-13. In plays, 30-6.
After a quarter, the Rams led by 3-0, but it seemed like 30-0. And
then three plays into the second quarter, it was 10-0 Rams.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half, the Giants offense finally managed 10 points
_ but the Rams defense scored 14 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense outscored their offense for the game, 14-10, and
any time you do that, you can take great pride in that,'' Lyght
said. ``Obviously our offense is strong and we have the best
offense in the league. But our defense is special, too.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the league's No. 1-ranked defense against the run. The
Rams defense has now scored seven touchdowns, breaking its team
record of six set in 1978. It scored twice Sunday against the
Giants, with safety Devin Bush returning an interception 45 yards
for a score and Jones returning one 22 yards for another touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants must have been concerned with how the Rams offense,
especially in this building, had jumped on teams early and
strangled them and made the game over before halftime. The Rams
entered this game having outscored teams by 113-46 in the first
quarter and by 136-71 in the second.
</P>
<P>
   But it was only a 10-0 halftime deficit for the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   That score, however, was insurmountable for the Giants because
of the focus, determination, grit, power and physical play of the
Rams defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a long day for them,'' said London Fletcher, the Rams
fierce linebacker, who kept providing bit hits and big plays en
route to a team-high eight tackles.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said: ``Our defense has played well all year. But you know
that everyone wants to see people score touchdowns. Our offense has
been the highlight of our team and that is good. As long as we keep
playing well as a defense, we know what can happen. There will be
days where our offense doesn't click like it usually does and the
defense will have to make the statement of the game. And that's
what we did today. And that statement is we are a very physical
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rams are a 12-2 team. The victory earned them homefield
advantage throughout the NFC playoffs. Any NFC team with plans of
reaching Super Bowl XXXIV next month in Atlanta will most likely
have to meet this team in St. Louis first. They are unbeaten (7-0)
in their dome this season, on a fast turf track with a fast, quick
offense. A physical one, too. But they are even more physical on
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Rams have finally beaten a team that entered with a
winning record. That was a missing link for them, something that
hung over their heads like a black cloud. They won with defense.
They have homefield advantage in the playoffs. Their confidence is
bubbling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our theme this week was we didn't know how good we are or how
good we can be,'' said Dick Vermeil, the Rams head coach. ``I think
we're a pretty good football team.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the Giants, and all of the league, must agree.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
