<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ELECT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN VOTE BOLSTERS PRO-YELTSIN CAMP IN PARLIAMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs bgng, The final ..., after 12th graf with
more on early returns; ADDS optional 2nd take with fresh quote from
Yavlinsky.) 
 (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(With RUSSIA-VOTERS) 
(nk) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ An unexpectedly strong showing by pro-government
parties in Sunday's Russian parliamentary elections looked set to
give President Boris Yeltsin a more compliant legislature as he
heads into his last six months in office, and a firm launching pad
for his designated heir, Prime Minister Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls indicated that the Communist Party, the bulwark of
the anti-Yeltsin opposition, could still emerge as Russia's largest
single party with about 25 percent of the vote, cast on the basis
of party lists which will fill half of the 450 seats in the Duma,
the lower house of parliament. The Communists are expected to pick
up more seats in the 225 single districts, where final results will
be known later this week.
</P>
<P>
   But according to preliminary returns, the surprise winners of
the election were two parties _ including one composed of Yeltsin's
once-scorned team of liberal economic reformers _ that emerged out
of the political wilderness in the last few months, boosted by
their backing of a popular war in Chechnya and supported by a
ferocious propaganda campaign waged by the Kremlin and its allies.
</P>
<P>
   As returns trickled in, moving from east to west across Russia's
11 time zones, political commentators were speculating that the new
pro-government coalition might actually gain a majority in the
Duma, which for the last six years has been dominated by the
Communist-led opposition.
</P>
<P>
   If electoral trends hold up as votes are counted in Russia's
populous western regions, Yeltsin for the first time in his
presidency might take command of the legislature and, in what
remains of his final term, push through badly needed economic
reforms, including an overhaul of an unwieldy tax system.
</P>
<P>
   Widely seen as a test run for next summer's presidential
elections, the parliamentary elections confirmed the growing
authority of Putin, a 47-year-old former security officer whose
popularity ratings have soared in the four months since he was
named prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's endorsement of Unity _ also known as Medved, or Bear _
was seen by political analysts as the key behind its sudden
breakthrough onto the national political scene. Unity, an electoral
bloc concocted by the Kremlin in the last two months of the
campaign, positioned itself as a rival to a center-left
anti-Kremlin alliance headed by former prime miniter Yevgeny
Primakov and Mayor Yuri Luzhkov of Moscow, Russia's capital and
largest city.
</P>
<P>
   Luzhkov easily won re-election, turning aside a challenge that
in recent weeks had looked capable of challenging his once daunting
popularity. Exit polls showed him winning with more than 70 percent
of the city's vote. In his last race for mayor, Luzhkov won with
more than 90 perent.
</P>
<P>
   In the campaign, both Luzhkov and Primakov were pummeled by a
steady stream of negative, sometimes vicious broadcasts on national
television channels controlled by the Kremlin and its allies. By
Sunday, their electoral alliance, Fatherland-All Russia, which six
months ago boasted of being the next party of power, had plummeted
to just 10 percent of the vote, according to an exit poll conducted
for the private television station NTV.
</P>
<P>
   The same poll showed Unity now being the new party of the
political establishment, and as such a probable magnet for
office-seekers and politically attuned business leaders. In the
poll, Unity far exceeded expectations with more than 20 percent of
the vote. Also surprising were the results for the Union of Right
Forces, a party made up of reformers whose campaign was
stage-managed by Anatoly Chubais, the often maligned author of
Russia's privatization program. The Right Forces party looked set
to top 10 percent in the national vote, a remarkable comeback for a
political group that had been written off by many experts a few
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Here, too, Putin's influence seemed to play a role, after he
said last week he could agree with parts of the right-wing party's
economic platform. Leaders of the Right Forces, who publicly
supported Putin's tough conduct of the Chechnya war despite the
misgivings of some of their backers, have returned the compliment
by endorsing Putin for president.
</P>
<P>
   In a further sign of the consolidation of pro-government forces,
Putin paid a surprise visit Sunday night to the Right Forces
campaign headquarters. ``This is a very important victory for
everyone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (NEW MATERIAL BEGINS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   The final composition of the new Russian parliament will not be
known until votes from the 225 single districts are counted.
National parties that fail to gain at least 5 percent of ballots
will not be allowed into parliament, and their votes will also be
redistributed among the victors.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary returns showed only six of the 26 competing parties
making that 5 percent threshold. Among the losers were Our Home is
Russia, headed by former Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin and
created for the 1995 elections as the then ``party of power.''
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary returns showed the party of Vladimir Zhirinovsky,
the maverick nationalist leader who has supported the Kremlin on
crucial votes, winning more than 7 percent of the vote, thus
guaranteeing its place in parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Boris Berezovsky, the financier and media magnate who played a
key role in the dirty ``information wars,'' looked set to win a
parliamentary seat from the North Caucasus region of
Karachayevo-Cherkessia, according to early returns.
</P>
<P>
   (NEW MATERIAL ENDS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   The Chechen war _ loudly criticized in the West for its brutal
bombardments of civilians _ has galvanized Russian public opinion
and, according to most political experts, turned the national
debate away from a search for social stability toward an
endorsement for a strong state, headed by a strong leader.
</P>
<P>
   That shift in the national mood has been answered by Putin, a
former KGB officer who has given the Russian military a free hand
in its campaign against the Chechen guerrillas held responsible for
the lawlessness that had spread through Russia's southern regions
after the 1994-1996 Chechen war in which thousands of Russian
soldiers died.
</P>
<P>
   Yabloko, a liberal opposition party headed by Grigory Yavlinsky,
was the only party that called for a shift in tactics in the
Chechen war. That stance apparently cost Yabloko public support;
according to early election results, Yavlinsky's party seems
destined to remain on the political fringes, with an estimated 6 to
7 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kremlin's apparent triumph _ another in a string of
come-from-behind victories for Yeltsin and his allies _ has cast a
cloud on the political scene, as critics continued to decry the
rough and cynical methods used by the ruling circle to best their
centrist opponents.
</P>
<P>
   While the Kremlin turned its gun on the Fatherland-All Russia
electoral bloc, it all but ignored its historic opposition, the
Communist Party. The Communists showed that they still have a lock
on the anti-Yeltsin protest vote, particularly among elderly voters
who have suffered during the last 10 years of economic reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``By their exceptionally dirty campaign, the authorities again
got a result which offers good advantages to the Communists,
something they hated to see,'' Luzhkov said after the vote.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
