<SLUG> BC-CUBANS-PRISON-DEAL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. MADE DEAL WITH CUBA TO END LOUISIANA HOSTAGE CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ADDS 10th graf with no response to request for comment from Cuban
officials.) 
 (rk) 
 By MARC LACEY with DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ U.S. officials ended a hostage standoff at a
Louisiana prison by striking a deal with the Cuban government that
will permit the seven Cuban inmates at the center of the uprising
to be deported to Havana, federal officials said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The seven Cuban inmates, all deemed a threat to public safety by
the United States, had completed their prison sentences in this
country but were being held indefinitely because their deportation,
the usual procedure for felons who are not citizens, had been
blocked by the government of Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   But Cuba dropped its opposition in an agreement reached with the
State Department on Saturday, and late Saturday night the hostages
were set free and the inmates surrendered.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was highly unusual for two countries that do not
acknowledge each other diplomatically and cannot reach consensus on
far less sensitive matters. What it may portend for U.S.-Cuba
relations remains uncertain. The deal leaves unaddressed the status
of approximately 2,400 other Cubans who are in U.S. jails awaiting
deportation to Cuba, some of whom have resorted to violence in the
past to show their discontent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is clearly a great deal of frustration among the Cubans
who are under detention without any sign of deportation,'' said
Russ Bergeron, a spokesman for the Immigration and Naturalization
Service. ``We view this case as distinct from the others. Here, the
inmates specifically asked to be returned to Cuba and the Cuban
government agreed to take them. That is not the case in the bulk of
the 2,400 others.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials said the decision to grant the
inmates' demands was appropriate in this case because it coincided
with U.S. interests. Attorney General Janet Reno was closely
involved in the decision, aides said, as were officials in the
White House and the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``These inmates requested to be returned to Cuba,'' said Carole
Florman, a Justice Department spokeswoman, ``and if they had been
from anywhere else they would have been returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line,'' she said, ``is we have a resolution here
that's in the best interests of the United States. We have a
situation that might have ended in a messy way that ended
smoothly.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Department contacted Cuban officials through the U. S.
interests section in Havana and worked out a deal in which Cuba
would accept the inmates, a State Department spokeswoman said.
``We're grateful that the situation has been resolved in a peaceful
manner,'' the spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban government officials in New York and Washington did not
return calls seeking comment on the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Around midnight, the inmates were taken from the prison in buses
to an undisclosed site under the custody of the Immigration and
Naturalization Service. Officials said the exact timing of the
deportation remained unclear, although it would most likely take
place within a few days. Because there are no direct commercial
flights between the United States and Cuba, the usual means of
deportation, the inmates could be returned on a charter flight, a
military aircraft or a Coast Guard cutter.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities in Louisiana said a chaplain, a Spanish-language
television producer and the mother of one of the hostage takers all
helped resolve the standoff. It was Mercedes Villar, the mother of
inmate Roberto Villar-Grana, who first disclosed a deal between the
United States and Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's over,'' Mrs. Villar told reporters, indicating that she
had seen a written agreement guaranteeing the inmates' safe passage
to Cuba. ``They're on the bus now and going to Cuba. They're going
to an airplane and going to Cuba.''
</P>
<P>
   The rare moment of cooperation between the United States and
Cuba came as the two countries remained at odds on another
immigration case _ that of Elian Gonzalez, a 6-year-old boy who was
rescued off the Florida coast on Nov. 25. The boy survived the
attempted trip to the United States, in which his mother and
stepfather drowned. Cuba has condemned the United States for not
immediately returning the boy to his father in Cuba. After initial
hesitation, the INS has sent signals recently that it intends to
send the boy home. It was unclear whether there was any connection
between the Gonzalez case and the deportation agreement. A Justice
Department official said she knew of no connection.
</P>
<P>
   Demanding to be released or sent to another country, the inmates
last Monday took over the prison in St. Martinville, La.. Wielding
a knife and screwdriver, the prisoners held as hostages the warden,
Todd Louvierre; a deputy, Jolie Sonnier, and five female inmates.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban prisoners arrived in the United States two decades ago
during the 1980 Mariel boatlift, during which Castro sent thousands
of Cuban criminals to Miami. After committing crimes in this
country _ offenses ranging from drug possession to rape and murder
_ they served their sentences and then found themselves in a legal
limbo.
</P>
<P>
   In all of their cases, an immigration judge had ordered them out
of the country, but the lack of a repatriation agreement between
the United States and Cuba made that impossible. Because they had
been deemed threats to society by an immigration judge, the INS
could not release them pending deportation, immigration officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   There are seven Cubans who are expected to be deported.
Officials said five were in the prison at the time of the
surrender, and two others were believed to be the inmates who gave
up earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
   Immigrants facing deportation can seek to be sent to a country
different from their country of origin as long as that country
agrees to accept them. ``If any third country had agreed to take
them, we would have sent them,'' said Russ Bergeron, a spokesman
with the INS.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The six-day ordeal ended shortly before midnight Saturday, when
a group of police officers and FBI swat team members began running
out of the prison, jumping up and down, cheering and throwing their
helmets and riot shields into the air. When reporters asked them
what was happening, they said the Cubans had given up.
</P>
<P>
   A few moments later, the jail warden who had been shackled to a
chair and held at knifepoint since Monday was wheeled out on a
stretcher to an ambulance. Louvierre, who had grown a beard while a
hostage, was sitting up, shaking hands and smiling. He had a black
eye and a cheek welt which he received during the initial fight
with his captors, but did not appear to be seriously harmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides what you see on my face, they didn't do anything, and
that's really nothing,'' the warden told reporters at a news
conference Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The other remaining jail employee, Jolie Sonnier, came out next,
and was not sitting up on her stretcher. She and Louvierre were
both taken to a local hospital, and officials said neither had been
seriously harmed.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, the hostage takers were led out of a side
door, unshackled, to a green and white motor coach bearing the
insignia of the INS.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts attributed the prison uprising to a flawed U.S.
policy toward Cuba, which has forced the immigration service to
keep as many as 2,400 Cuban inmates in prison well after their
sentences have expired.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they'd gone to the extreme of murder no one would have
supported these inmates,'' said Wayne Smith, who was the ranking
American diplomat in Havana under Presidents Jimmy Carter and
Ronald Reagan and is a leading critic of the embargo against Cuba.
``But you really have to sympathize with them. What are they
supposed to do, just sit there? They obviously became desperate.
Luckily, this situation has been resolved without bloodshed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
