<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-19 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3654 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     12-19 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: GAINING SOME FAITH AND KEEPING IT, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The typical Jets fan will look at Sunday's
victory over the Dallas Cowboys with a mixture of exhilaration and
pain; pleased by the victory, haunted by what might have been and
what is likely to be. The Jets won for the fifth time in seven
games; barreled into Texas Stadium and handed the Cowboys their
first home defeat of the season.
</P>
<P>
   They came here Sunday, hoping against hope to keep their faint
hopes alive. Hoping that two of their three American Football
Conference rivals Seattle, Buffalo and Miami would lose.
</P>
<P>
   But for the Jets the playoffs are a pipe dream. A longshot at
best. What they had better be focusing on is the big, big picture
of who will own the franchise and the smaller picture of who will
coach the team. For the fans' purpose, the third and, in the long
run, most significant picture is who will play quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   What to do with Ray Lucas. Lucas' progress from the summer, when
he was the Jets third-string quarterback and suffered through a
disastrous preseason game against Green Bay, to Sunday's effort in
Dallas has been stunning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what a lot of you were saying after the Green Bay
game,'' Jets coach Bill Parcells said Sunday. ``He's come a long
way. I'm proud of him. He was less than perfect, but he was good
enough. This puts him over the top as a starter, and that's good
news.''
</P>
<P>
   No sooner had Parcells got the word ``starter'' out of his
mouth, someone asked whether he meant ``starting,'' as in next
season. Parcells was incredulous: ``You guys had him out of here,
now you're giving him the job. Close your eyes, tell me what I'll
do next.''
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, everyone, from Lucas to Parcells to several teammates
had doubts and pangs of panic in the week following Vinny
Testaverde's season-ending injury. Parcells didn't see him Lucas as
the answer, or even as a solution. Lucas was the poor man's Kordell
Stewart, a secret weapon, a special-teams players, a spark to go in
at quarterback and give the team a jump start. No one saw him has
the battery.
</P>
<P>
   The question is, do they now?
</P>
<P>
   Before the Miami victory last week, Parcells said he still did
not have enough information about Lucas in all situations to know
if he could even be a backup. Earlier this week Parcells said that
if Lucas continued to improve, he would make him Testaverde's
backup. ``Wouldn't you?''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas' problem-next year will be the growing perception that he
is no better than a backup. He came into the season as the Jets
third-string quarterback. He started six games _ and would have
started more had he not been injured _ and led the Jets to
victories over Miami, Buffalo and New England. Regardless of what
Lucas says publicly, the idea of being happy to be in the National
Football League, only playing at quarterback, disappeared several
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Of 11 quarterbacks starting for the first time, Lucas, has the
second-highest rating. He has thrown seven touchdowns in the last
three games with no interceptions. He has the lowest interception
percentage of any first-year starter in the NFL, and the least
experience, having spent three seasons as a jack-of-all-trades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I'm a starter,'' Lucas said. ``The biggest change
form the summer to now is opportunity: the opportunity to play, the
opportunity make mistakes the opportunity to grow with the offense.
Everything is moving a lot slower for me now.''
</P>
<P>
   The greatest burden on Lucas has been to make good decisions.
For the most part, he has succeeded. Sunday he fumbled a crucial
fourth-quarter snap on a crucial down. But in a game where Troy
Aikman was dismal, Lucas survived. Before the third-quarter
interception, Lucas had attempted 155 passes without an
interception.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde is the incumbent. Lucas is starting material. Maybe
not in New York, maybe not with the Jets, but somewhere. He may
back up Testaverde next season, as well he should if Testaverde
reports to camp healed and healthy. But he will be a starter
playing a backup's role. Does the coach see Lucas that way?
</P>
<P>
   The Jets dilemma comes when the coaches ask what happens if
Testaverde goes down. He conceded a few weeks ago that what
troubles him was that his injury was an age injury. He is concerned
that the same injury could happen next season. He said he could
tear the other Achilles in the shower. The farther Testaverde gets
from his miracle year _ and that is considerable for a 37-year-old
quarterback who was forced to take a year off. Is Ray Lucas the
Jets guy? Or do the Jets go out and trade for a quarterback they
consider to be starting caliber?
</P>
<P>
   Those are questions for another time. For now the Jets are
reveling in the glow of a strong finish. They must sweep the last
two games to reach .500. Sunday the Jets bought the Giants a little
time and kept their withering dream alive.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Lucas made a huge stride, too. But there are bigger
challenges to come. He will have to battle perception. That will be
tougher competition than anyone the Jets bring to camp. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
