<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-19 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3656 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HISTORY-THEATER-REVIE     12-19 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISTORY-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TRUE HISTORY AND REAL ADVENTURES': CHALFONT DELIGHTS, PLAY
DOESN'T 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Kathleen Chalfant can do almost no wrong. If she
wasn't already a star after playing a Mormon mom, a rabbi and Ethel
Rosenberg in the Pulitzer Prize-winning ``Angels in America,'' she
became one last year, winning every Off Broadway acting award in
sight as the dying poetry professor in the Pulitzer Prize-winning
``Wit.'' Now her devotees will follow her to ``True History and
Real Adventures,'' which opened Sunday night at the Vineyard
Theater, and they are bound to be disappointed, not in Ms.
Chalfant, who delights every time she steps onstage, but in what
surrounds her.
</P>
<P>
   What could Sybille Pearson have been thinking when she wrote
this scattered, seemingly aimless play? A play with occasional
music, in fact, but the music, by Mel Marvin, seems simply
intrusive most of the time. It's a bad sign when the interviews the
playwright and the director give about a work are more moving than
the work itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``True History and Real Adventures'' (a deadly title, although a
meaningful one, once you've analyzed the themes) begins in 1893. On
the surface it is about a young Scottish woman who sees a play
about Calamity Jane, becomes obsessed with her and eventually meets
her, after traveling America with a band of equally young,
ambitious, slightly dishonest fellow immigrants with plans and
problems of their own.
</P>
<P>
   What Ms. Pearson means this to comment on, she says, is the
theater's ability to tell truth through lies. Michael Mayer, the
director (whose recent noteworthy work has included ``Side Man''
and ``A View From the Bridge''), says the play's lesson is the need
to claim ownership of your own history. Calamity, of course, may
not have done everything she was said to do, and her young fan ends
up becoming a celebrity herself, complete with legendary incidents
that never happened and a fringed western pantsuit that would have
looked at home on the Grand Ole Opry in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Pearson also means to point out the similarities between the
1890s and the 1990s and finds a couple of amusing examples. At one
point, a character explains President William McKinley's
trickle-down theory of economics. And out West, the young
immigrants go into business selling a miracle tonic (mostly
cocaine), which they promote as the 19th-century equivalent of
Viagra. The townsfolk fall all over one another to buy it. The
sales team, it is presumed, leaves town before the customers learn
about cocaine's long-term effects on virility.
</P>
<P>
   But overall, the play is trying to say too many things without a
unifying insight. Several times, prejudice against the two major
black characters is powerfully demonstrated and forcefully
discussed. (A black man is shot dead for dancing with a white
woman, although she was the one who initiated the dance; a black
woman learns about the promise of the AME Zion Church.) Trouble is,
the racial theme is quickly abandoned each time, having thrown the
play off balance and left passions unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   Angela Goethals, whose career as a child actress brought her
such varied credits as the Roundabout Theater's ``Four Baboons
Adoring the Sun'' and a television sitcom about an adolescent
tennis pro (``Phenom''), is lovely as the central character,
Margaret Mackenzie. Margaret changes her name to Pearl Hart, but
unfortunately for Ms. Goethals, the character is missing a soul.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Chalfant, who is billed as Calamity Jane, isn't seen as that
character until near the end of the play, but she does wonderful
things with a series of other characters, most of which she plays
for one scene only. She even manages to put on a mustache, a top
hat and a German accent and play the cakewalk-dancing Count of
Glumbowitz with gender-irrelevant charm and believability. The rest
of the cast members, many of them so young they are literally
members of the class of '99, show lots of promise but have good
moments and bad.
</P>
<P>
   In the end they're all lost in a story with a message that the
script isn't articulate enough or focused enough to convey. When
young Margaret sees the play about Calamity's exploits, she goes
backstage, hoping to meet her new heroine. But Margaret's naivete
comes across as just that, the case of a girl who buys a theater
ticket but doesn't understand the concept of acting and
make-believe, not as a metaphor for the blurring of fiction and
reality.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes Ms. Pearson seems to intend the entire play as a sort
of warning against a collective American egotism, going into a new
century overconfidently. That may have been the mind-set in 1899,
but a hundred years later instant Internet millionaires are just
about the only Americans in that mood. Most of the rest of us can't
seem to look ahead much farther than Jan. 1, when we'll learn
whether our computers still work. ``True History and Real
Adventures'' continues through Jan. 2.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `TRUE HISTORY AND REAL ADVENTURES'
</P>
<P>
   By Sybille Pearson, with music by Mel Marvin; directed by
Michael Mayer; sets and costumes by G.W. Mercier; lighting by Kevin
Adams; sound by Bruce Ellman; musical direction by David Alan Bunn;
choreography by Rob Ashford; production manager, Kai Brothers;
production stage manager, Katherine Lee Boyer. Presented by the
Vineyard Theater, Douglas Aibel, artistic director; Barbara Zinn
Krieger, executive director and founder; Jeffrey Solis, managing
director. At 108 E. 15th St., Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   With: Kathleen Chalfant (Calamity Jane, Count of Glumbowitz,
Mrs. Crane and others), Angela Goethals (Margaret Mackenzie),
Donovan Patton (Rafe Bandmann), Daniel Bess (Dewi Owens), Adrienne
Carter (Sylvie De Vionnet), Damon Gupton (Abram Henry), Wally Dunn
(Klaus and others), John Michael Gilbert (Company Man and others),
Aleta Mitchell (Billy Jump, Lourinda, Mme. Jones and others) and
David Alan Bunn (the Piano Player).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-19-99 2207EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
