<HEADLINE>
PINCAY-VALENZUELA RACE IS DOWN TO THE WIRE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Laffit Pincay and Pat Valenzuela are going
down to the final day in their race for the Hollywood Park jockey
championship. No matter who wins it'll be an unlikely achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay, 52, leads Valenzuela, back since September from a nearly
two-year suspension, by 30 victories to 28 after both went winless
Sunday. Pincay is scheduled to ride seven horses today; Valenzuela
is named on eight horses, including a morning-line favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay hasn't won a riding title since the 1991 Hollywood Park
spring-summer meet. He'd be the oldest man to win a Southern
California jockey title.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be the icing on the cake,'' said Pincay, who broke
Bill Shoemaker's career-wins record with No. 8,834 on Dec. 10 and
is up to 8,842 now.
</P>
<P>
   Valenzuela, whose career is dotted with drug-related
suspensions, said he's thrilled with his Hollywood Park performance
even if he doesn't win the title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who'd have thought, two months after I started riding again,
that I'd be in this position?'' he said. ``It's an accomplishment
to be right behind (Pincay). Laffit's always been an inspiration.''
</P>
<P>
   Corey Nakatani rode two winners Sunday and, with 26 at the meet
and four scheduled mounts on the 12:30 p.m. final card, has a
mathematical chance to tie for the title.
</P>
<P>
   Surfside wins: Surfside, getting the kind of trip that jockey
Pat Day would have liked in the Breeders' Cup Juvenile Fillies, won
the $380,250 Hollywood Starlet by seven lengths over longshot She's
Classy and three other 2-year-old fillies.
</P>
<P>
   The daughter of Seattle Slew and Flanders had finished third
behind D. Wayne Lukas stablemate Cash Run in the Breeders' Cup race
Nov. 6 at Gulfstream Park after an indifferent start left her
racing wide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too bad, because I really think she's the best filly in
the country,'' Lukas said after winning his seventh Starlet.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas indicated he'd like to try Surfside against males in the
Triple Crown preps. Her 1:43.51 clocking for 1 1/16 miles was about
a length and a half slower than Hollywood Futurity winner Captain
Steve's 1:43.27 on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a big, long-striding filly, and if you want to take on
boys, she's the kind you'd do it with,'' Day said.
</P>
<P>
   The Overbrook Farms filly is 4 for 6. She has won two Grade I
races, the first the Frizette at Belmont Park.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Bob Baffert has clinched the training title. He holds a
14-11 lead over Richard Mandella, who didn't enter a horse on the
closing-day card.... The Daily News' Bob Ike leads Jack Karlik by
three winners in the newspaper handicappers' contest.
</P>
</TEXT>
