<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXING-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUGAR RAY ROBINSON RANKS AS A PERFECT NO. 1
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ He had no flaws.
</P>
<P>
   He could punch with both hands and he could take a punch. He
could box and he could bang. He could think and he had all the
right instincts.
</P>
<P>
   And he had the opportunity to use his divine skills.
</P>
<P>
   He had 202 professional bouts, winning 175, and fought a list of
opponents that reads like a Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   He was undefeated in welterweight bouts, holding the world title
from 1946 to 1950, was a five-time middleweight champion and was
competitive until the day he retired at 44 in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   He was Sugar Ray Robinson, the greatest fighter of the century.
</P>
<P>
   This list of the 10 greatest fighters pound-for-pound of
all-time is based on ability and accomplishments, which includes
quality of opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Here goes:
</P>
<P>
   1. Sugar Ray Robinson (175-19-6, 109 KOs) 1940-65. Ten years
into his career, mostly as a welterweight, he was 128-1-2. Of his
19 losses, 14 occurred after he turned 36 and 10 came after 40,
when he was fighting because he needed money.
</P>
<P>
   No fighter in history dominated his division as Robinson
dominated the welterweight class and he was almost as good as a
middleweight. He also was beating light heavyweight champ Joey
Maxim when he collapsed because of heat.
</P>
<P>
   He beat some of the greats _ Jake La Motta, Henry Armstrong, Kid
Gavilan, Randy Turpin, Rocky Graziano, Carmen Basilio and Gene
Fullmer.
</P>
<P>
   2. Henry Armstrong (150-21-9, 101 KOs) 1933-45. He personified
the destructive power of perpetual motion. He might've thrown more
punches _ and inflicted more pain _ than any other fighter in
history.
</P>
<P>
   He will be remembered for perhaps boxing's greatest
accomplishment: He held the welterweight, lightweight and
featherweight titles simultaneously and almost made it four belts,
drawing with Ceferino Garcia in a middleweight title bout.
</P>
<P>
   3. Muhammad Ali (56-5, 37 KOs) 1960-81. No one had the presence
of Ali and few could fight as well.
</P>
<P>
   In his prime, he could move more fluidly and had more speed than
any heavyweight in history. That, combined with a great chin and
immeasurable guile, made him all but unbeatable when he was at his
best.
</P>
<P>
   He also had the good fortune of fighting in the greatest era for
heavyweights. Among those he beat: Sonny Liston, Floyd Patterson,
Joe Frazier, George Foreman, Ken Norton and Jerry Quarry.
</P>
<P>
   The sad thing is that the 3{ years he was away because he
refused induction into the armed services might've been his best.
</P>
<P>
   4: Joe Louis (68-3, 54 KOs) 1934-51. He's ranked below Ali only
because of quality of opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The beloved ``Brown Bomber'' might not have had the foot speed
Ali had, but his hands were very quick and he had impeccable boxing
skills and crushing power. He also had a frightening killer
instinct.
</P>
<P>
   He defended his heavyweight championship a record 25 times over
an unfathomable 13 years (including a three-year hiatus during the
war). No one, not even Ali, dominated the division as Louis did.
</P>
<P>
   He, too, beat many fine fighters _ Max Schmeling, Jack Sharkey,
Max Bear and Jersey Joe Walcott, among them.
</P>
<P>
   5. Harry Greb (115-8-3, 51 KOs, 179 no-decisions) 1913-26. Greb,
the least known on this list, is regarded by historians as a
monster.
</P>
<P>
   He was called the ``Pittsburgh Windmill'' because of his style,
in which innumerable punches came from all angles and wreaked havoc
on helpless opponents. He also didn't care much for rules: He did
anything and everything he could get away with.
</P>
<P>
   His greatest victory was over future heavyweight champ Gene
Tunney in an American light heavyweight title bout, the only loss
of Tunney's career, and was world middleweight champ for three
years.
</P>
<P>
   Greb had a secret that was revealed only after his untimely
death at 32 and was proof of his greatness: He was blind in one eye
the last five years of his career.
</P>
<P>
   6. Benny Leonard (85-5-5, 69 KOs, 119 NDs) 1911-32. He might've
been the greatest boxer in history !ital!and had good power.
</P>
<P>
   He lost three times before he turned 17 and only twice more,
once on a disqualification and once at 36 in his last fight,
against the great Jimmy McLarnin.
</P>
<P>
   In between, he fought the best lightweights of his day and
invariably ended up on top. This was true even in the no-decision
era, during which law prohibited decisions but winners were in
effect declared by newspaper accounts the following day.
</P>
<P>
   He was lightweight champ from 1917 to 1923. He later came out of
a seven-year retirement because of financial difficulties and
compiled a record of 18-1-1.
</P>
<P>
   7. Jack Dempsey (61-6-8, 50 KOs) 1914-27. He was Babe Ruth of
boxing at the time the Bambino ruled baseball.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't beat his opponents, he mauled them. Of his 50
knockouts, 36 came in three rounds or less, a testament to his
unusual tenacity and power.
</P>
<P>
   His cruel beating of the much-bigger Jess Willard to win the
heavyweight title he would hold for seven years was one of the most
brutal in boxing history.
</P>
<P>
   It took a slick boxer like Tunney to take him down.
</P>
<P>
   8. Willie Pep (230-11-1, 65 KOs) 1940-66. Like Leonard, the
two-time featherweight champ was a boxing marvel.
</P>
<P>
   He was blazing quick and virtually impossible to hit. He once
won a round without throwing a punch, as the story goes.
</P>
<P>
   He was 134-1-1 before his first of three losses to the
rough-and-tumble Sandy Saddler.
</P>
<P>
   9. Roberto Duran (102-14, 69 KOs) 1967-98. We remember him first
as a welterweight, then as a middleweight and finally as a fighter
who hung on too long.
</P>
<P>
   However, he was at his greatest as a lightweight. With unnerving
viciousness and fine-tuned skills, he owned the 135-pound division
from 1972 to 1978. He lost only a decision to Esteban DeJesus
during that period and later avenged the loss.
</P>
<P>
   He was 73-1 at one point and suffered six of his losses after he
turned 38.
</P>
<P>
   His most publicized victory was his ``no mas'' loss to Sugar Ray
Leonard, but he had beaten Leonard by decision in their previous
bout.
</P>
<P>
   10. Archie Moore (194-26-10, 141 KOs) 1936-63. He had more
knockouts than all but a handful of boxers had fights during his
remarkable 28-year career.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't get his first championship bout until he was 39,
beating Joey Maxim for the light heavyweight title in 1952. His
last defense was at 48 in 1961, at which time he began
concentrating on the heavyweight division.
</P>
<P>
   He lost to Rocky Marciano and Patterson in two attempts to win
the heavyweight crown.
</P>
<P>
   The next 10: 11. Jack Johnson. Nat Fleischer, the editor of The
Ring magazine who saw every great fighter of the first half
century, said Johnson was the greatest heavyweight; 12. Billy Conn.
The great light heavyweight champ almost beat Louis in his prime;
13. Jimmy Wilde. The greatest British fighter dominated the
flyweight division early in the century; 14. Gene Tunney. The
before-his-time boxer beat Dempsey twice and Greb twice; 15. Sam
Langford. He never received a title shot because he was black but
won consistently between the lightweight and heavyweight divisions
early in the century; 16. Ezzard Charles. He's remembered as
heavyweight champion but was a dominating light heavyweight; 17.
Marvin Hagler. He was the best middleweight since Robinson. 18.
Aaron Pryor. The once-beaten junior welterweight could've been in
the top 10 if if weren't for drug abuse; 19. Stanley Ketchel. The
big punching middleweight champ once knocked down Jack Johnson. 20.
Sugar Ray Leonard. He captured the public's imagination and beat
the best of his time.
</P>
<P>
   Among others: Readers had many worthy suggestions for the top 10
who aren't listed here. Among them: Ike Williams, Manuel Ortiz,
Julio Cesar Chavez, Roy Jones Jr., Carlos Monzon and Kid Gavilan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
