<SLUG> BC-OUTLOOK-IPO-HUMOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A BIRD! IT'S A PLANE! YES, AND IT'S ALSO THE LATEST I.P.O.!
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Note (AT) in place of symbol used 9 times in 6th graf) 
 (rk) 
 By JOE QUEENAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The successful debuts of Martha Stewart Living Omnimedia and
World Wrestling Federation Entertainment _ enterprises that went
public side by side on Oct. 19 this year _ provide indisputable
evidence that the stock market has entered a thrilling new era
where the old rules do not apply.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years ago on that same date stocks were tanking, but now
they are flourishing and everybody wants a piece of the action.
Because of this, the early years of the new millennium are sure to
bring us initial public offerings far more exotic than any we have
witnessed to date.
</P>
<P>
   One reason traditional yardsticks are useless in measuring the
prospects of companies like Martha Stewart and the WWF is that each
is in the Zeitgeist industry, an enigmatic and very possibly
nonexistent segment of the economy where profits are directly
pegged not to specific products but to a particular consumer vibe.
The Zeitgeist industry may well be the fastest-growing segment of
the world economy, a sector that will one day overtake automobiles,
drugs and even high technology.
</P>
<P>
   Since the industry celebrates a public fascination, it is hardly
a coincidence that both Martha Stewart and the wrestling federation
are rooted in television, the ultimate arbiter of public taste. So
investors should not be surprised when Rosie O'Donnell, mistress of
the morning airwaves, goes public with Rosie O'Donnell Living.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Martha Stewart has tapped into the obsessive quest for
perfection of the upwardly mobile, Ms. O'Donnell has tapped into
the frantic search for adequacy of so many Americans. An adequate
stand-up comic herself who has evolved into an adequate actress and
a more-than-adequate talk-show host, Ms. O'Donnell is a goddess to
her legions of fans. By going public with a company that will
market comfort foods, comfortable clothing, functional appliances
and a cozy magazine, Ms. O'Donnell should be able to raise
billions.
</P>
<P>
   So should (AT).com. The power of this icon cannot be
underestimated. The ``(AT)'' symbol is perhaps the most vital
graphic linchpin of the Internet for without it e-mail messages
could not be delivered. Were it mutilated, destroyed, rendered
inoperative or even briefly held for ransom, electronic roadkill
would litter the Information Highway. Knowing this, the
entrepreneurs who take (AT).com public will be able to use the vast
proceeds of their market entry to infiltrate the communications
system even more by successfully introducing and copyrighting
symbol-words like h(AT), c(AT), r(AT)-a-t(AT)-t(AT) and
(AT)mosphere, employing the slogan: ``Saving keystrokes each day
keeps the ergonomist away.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all the IPOs of the infant millennium, of course, will be
rigorously pegged to the amorphous Zeitgeist _ anymore than were
this year's roaring successes: Goldman Sachs Group, Delphi
Automotive and United Parcel Service. Big offerings like these,
along with the ubiquitous dot-coms _ and the biggest success of
all, the Internet-related VA Linux Systems _ propelled the IPO
market to big bucks, a record volume of $69 billion through
mid-December. That's already above the 1996 record of $50 billion,
according to Thomson/ Financial Securities Data.
</P>
<P>
   Some new offerings will simply capitalize on any opportunity to
attract an ambitious, credulous investing public, whose appetite
for IPO's this decade grew more than fourfold, to $340 billion from
$75 billion in the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   Eager investors can be expected, for instance, to snap up Planet
United Nations. The U.N. sits on some very valuable Midtown
Manhattan real estate and could be a great place to promote a
restaurant with the cachet of a sophisticated international
clientele. The money it raises would once and for all end the
squabbles over nations that have not paid their dues.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of squabbling nations, with emerging markets once again
beating Wall Street, it might behoove the world to brace for an
unorthodox IPO or two, like Mujahedeen.com. Traditionally, third
world rebels have financed their operations by obtaining covert
funds from abroad _ an approach that prevents the insurgency-minded
public from directly participating in third world upheaval. In
taking Mujahedeen.com public, Afghan guerrillas will generate
profits by charging subscribers a monthly rate to watch live
Internet footage of clashes in the foothills of Pakistan and allow
subscribers to proffer hints on strategy to mujahedeen leaders in
interactive chat rooms every evening.
</P>
<P>
   Mujahedeen.com will also offer $65,000 adventure-travel packages
to baby boomers who, having found the climb up Mount Everest too
old hat, will get their kicks by locking swords in the Hindu Kush.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of old hat, old is really new in some quarters _ granny
glasses are in vogue, and today's close-cropped men could have
stepped out of a Jack Webb movie. Recognizing the trend, Irony
``R'' Us will make a bundle by reintroducing Disco Era
bell-bottoms, Nehru jackets, Clark Kent eyeglasses, Day-Glo
platform shoes and Louise Brooks hairstyles at the strategic
moment. With the funds raised from the IPO of Irony ``R'' Us, the
founders will be able to blanket the nation with a chain of
Saturday night restaurants called Trattoria Travolta and a line of
Village People casual wear.
</P>
<P>
   As the financial services industry restructures itself, unusual
marketing channels will become increasingly popular. That is where
the Girl Scouts come in. They are a marketer's dream: Trustworthy,
with outstanding brand recognition.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Girl Scouts have raised money for good causes by
selling cookies door to door. In the future, they will earn merit
badges for selling annuities, life insurance, emerging-market
mutual funds and high-yield bonds door to door.
</P>
<P>
   By going public, the Girl Scouts will not only raise enough
money to train young women in the art of financial planning but
will also have enough cash left over to get some new uniforms. With
their newfound capitalist prowess, after all, the girls will want
boardroom apparel.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of boardrooms, AMEX.com promises to become a real
highflier sometime in the next thousand years. Though it may come
as a surprise to many, the American Stock Exchange still exists,
and, like a bear emerging from hibernation, it may one day become a
force to be reckoned with. Like many IPOs, it will lure investors
with the promise of great profits _ the average IPO this year rose
50 percent on opening day, while the average Internet IPO doubled _
and then use the cash raised by going public to attract exciting
young companies, build an opulent new headquarters, hire an
attention-getting chairman and explain to the public, with the help
of a catchy new slogan, what function it serves.
</P>
<P>
   The slogan? ``At AMEX, We Make Money the Old-Fashioned Way. We
Go Public.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
