<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAILEY FILLS UCLA VOID
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When the week began, guard Ryan Bailey appeared to
have as much chance of sparking UCLA's struggling offense as wet
paper. His injury-plagued early-season performances were spotty,
and he didn't play against Gonzaga because of tendinitis in his
foot.
</P>
<P>
   But Bailey had other ideas. Missing the Gonzaga game had given
his painful foot a chance to heal. All he needed were a few good
practices, and he'd hop off the bench to save the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the exhibition season, my timing was so off it was
ridiculous,'' Bailey said. ``I hadn't played for a month. I wasn't
shooting well. I wasn't in shape.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest did wonders for Bailey's foot, although he felt
helpless during the Gonzaga debacle. He practiced long and hard
last week, and sure enough, he rescued the Bruins against DePaul _
charging off the bench for seven rebounds, five assists and three
steals in 26 minutes. He ran UCLA's fast break and half-court
offense the way they're designed, enabling Earl Watson to slide to
wing guard, his natural position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't shoot well, but I did a lot of other things,'' Bailey
said after the spirited 76-58 victory. ``Pushing the ball upcourt
is one aspect I bring to the team. That's my true position.''
</P>
<P>
   Without Baron Davis, Bailey is UCLA's only pure point guard.
Watson plays the position, but he looks to score more than
distribute, and he often makes poor decisions. Freshman Jason
Kapono is a deft ballhandler, but he's more effective as the vortex
than the initiator.
</P>
<P>
   As long as Bailey stays healthy, makes passing his priority and
plays sound defense _ it's his biggest weakness _ there will be
plenty of minutes available.
</P>
<P>
   On the other end: The Bruins spent most of the game in a matchup
zone designed to keep their big men out of foul trouble and contain
DePaul All-American Quentin Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   It worked on both counts. Dan Gadzuric played 35 minutes and
Jerome Moiso 30 in the best combined effort of their careers: 32
points, 20 rebounds and five blocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can keep the big men healthy, out of foul trouble and on
the practice floor, we can be a pretty good team,'' coach Steve
Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, probably the best player UCLA will face this season,
scored a game-high 22 points, but he needed 23 shots. Afterward, he
credited UCLA's zone for his shooting woes (8 of 23) _ a zone the
Bruins probably will use against the elite teams on their schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``The matchup zone I think gave (Richardson) a different look,''
Lavin said. ``We don't have a lot of foot speed, but we're long. We
get those branches out.''
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Reserve forward Sean Farnham, recovering from a
sprained knee, was available Saturday but didn't play (coach's
decision).
</P>
<P>
   Watson and Ray Young _ supposedly two of UCLA's best perimeter
shooters _ are 3 of 21 from 3-point range in the last two games.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA flew to Hawaii on Sunday and will hold a two-hour practice
this afternoon in preparation for Tuesday's game (3 p.m.) against
Maine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
