<SLUG> BC-NY-EDIT-HEALTH-CARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: LEGISLATIVE GAINS AND STALLS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, Dec. 20:
</P>
<P>
   With a year-end deadline looming, state legislators and Gov.
George Pataki have announced an impressive health care package that
offers coverage to thousands of uninsured New Yorkers and helps pay
for it by boosting the tax on a pack of cigarettes by 55 cents. The
agreement also draws on funds from a nationwide tobacco industry
settlement that is expected to bring in half a billion dollars a
year.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiated package looks like a significant, and long
needed, expansion in state support for the three million New
Yorkers who need medical insurance. Equally important, it will
maintain the financial ability of New York's hospitals to serve the
poor and to educate physicians. The only disappointment is that the
bill would set aside an average of $37 million a year for new
anti-smoking programs, which is a considerable boost to the $20
million currently being spent but still short of what is needed to
discourage smoking among adolescents.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal offers stability for hospitals, clinics and nursing
homes. It takes no additional cuts out of Medicaid funds and
maintains a surcharge on hospital fees for insured patients to help
pay the cost of medical education and charity cases. It also
expands the state's Child Health Plus plan to adults, offering
insurance to those at or near the poverty level. The plan now
covers about 400,000 children. It would be expected to cover about
180,000 adults over the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly is expected early this week to approve the
agreement, technically a recasting of the Health Care Reform Act.
Joseph Bruno, the Senate majority leader, has said he sees no harm
in delaying a Senate vote until the next scheduled session in early
January. But a good deal like this should not sit around, giving
special interests, including those unhappy about an increase in
cigarette prices, time to make it unravel. &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
