The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Monday, Dec. 20.If you have
any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
RELIGION-YOUNG (PHOENIX) _ It's 7 o'clock Sunday night during
finals week at Arizona State University, and there's standing room
only at the All Saints Catholic Newman Center Mass. Most weekends,
about 1,300 students pile in to the non-traditional sanctuary for
the center's five Masses. During finals, the Rev. Nathan Castle
says, the number swells about 20 percent. Do they come to pray for
good grades? Some probably do, Castle jokes. But for those who
regularly attend, the Newman Center Mass offers a connection that
goes beyond the liturgy and familiar hymns. On the eve of the 21st
century, at ASU and secular schools across the Phoenix area,
students are exploring things spiritual _ whether through organized
religion or less defined means. By MAUREEN JENKINS. Story will move
in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
