</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) CINCINNATI -- Dec. 19, 1999 -- TAILORMADE-MEDICINE -- Dr.
Stephen Liggett, a lung specialist and molecular geneticist at the
University of Cincinnati College of Medicine. Liggett's discovery
of a genetic variant and its effects on congestive heart failure
helps explain why patients responded differently to treatment.
(Mark Lyons/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) ST. PETERSBURG, Russia -- Dec. 19, 1999 -- RUSSIA-ELECT-3
-- Mariya Chashena, 78, of St. Petersburg, was unable to go to her
neighborhood polling station, so election officials came to her
apartment so she could cast her ballot in the Russian parliamentary
elections on Sunday. As of late Sunday Russian voters elected a new
Duma, the lower house that has the power to enact legislation and
oversee taxation, to sit for four years. (James Hill/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) ST. PETERSBURG -- Dec. 19, 1999 -- RUSSIA-ELECT-2 --
Russian voters turn out to cast their ballots in the Russian
parliamentary elections on Sunday. As of late Sunday Russian voters
elected a new Duma, the lower house that has the power to enact
legislation and oversee taxation, to sit for four years. (James
Hill/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) ST. PETERSBURG, Russia -- Dec. 19, 1999 -- RUSSIA-ELECT-1
-- Russian election workers at polling Station 1380. As of late
Sunday Russian voters elected a new Duma, the lower house that has
the power to enact legislation and oversee taxation, to sit for
four years. In this once opulent neighborhood near the imposing
fortress that was Peter the Great's landmark when founding this
city, now badly frayed by Soviet neglect and capitalist poverty,
perhaps half of the 1,450 registered voters turned out in winter's
half-daylight to cast their ballots. (James Hill/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) ROCKVILLE, Md. -- Dec. 19, 1999 -- OUTLOOK-BIOTECH --
Craig Venter of Celera Genomics examines a plate of bacterial
colonies about to be sampled for DNA sequencing by the robotic
sampler behind him. The biggest opportunities and challenges in
biotechnology for the millennium are expected to come from
genomics, the study of the human genetic code. The Human Genome
Project, sponsored by the federal government, is expected to finish
the ``rough draft'' of the genome by spring and to be completed in
2003. (Marty Ktaz/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Dec. 19, 1999 -- OUTLOOK-OUTDATED-PRODUCTS --
Ransom Bruce tries out a manual typewriter at Hammacher Schlemmer.
Phonograph records, flypaper, typewriters, windup watches, carbon
paper. They are products that most people of a certain age grew up
with but that have largely vanished, usually with little notice,
from everyday life. Something presumably better has taken their
place. But while they are forgotten by many, they are not gone.
(Barbara S. Alper/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) MOZDOK, Russia -- Dec. 19, 1999 -- RUSSIA-CHECHNYA --
Mikhail A. Kashpurin, 76, a frail old man with years of valorous
service in the Soviet Army now spends his days in bed in a small
home in Mozdok, which has taken in other ethnic Russians fleeing
the fighting in Chechnya. Grozny's residents have endured so much
hardship that not even the prospect of a war necessarily impels
them to flee. The Kashpurins, and thousands of other residents, did
not anticipate such fierce air strikes and artillery barrages. But
that all changed for Kashpurin on Nov. 27, the day that shattered
his life. ``I was lying in bed when a plane zoomed by and fired a
missile,'' he says. ``My wife was in the kitchen and was blown to
pieces.'' (James Hill/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) SAN FRANCISCO -- Dec. 19, 1999 -- OUTLOOK-MOVIES --
Rodger Raderman, one of iFilm's founders and its co-chairman. iFilm
distributes digital films through the Internet and allows filmakers
and industry executives to connect. ``The idea of a movie studio is
changing as we watch,'' says Raderman. ``What is a studio? If you
think of it as a place where movies are developed, produced,
marketed and distributed, then we are very close to having a
technology where one person can do that all by himself. Each person
can be his own studio.'' (Peter DaSilva/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) CORDOBA, Argentina -- Dec. 19, 1999 --
OUTLOOK-LATIN-AMERICA -- Fiat automobiles roll off the assembly
line in the Argentine province of Cordoba. latin America hopes its
difficulties are behind it. Still, to a large extent than in
advanced industrial regions, Latin America may not be fully the
master of its own fate. As the fallout from crises in East Asia and
Eastern Europe in recent years has shown, all that would be needed
to erase many of the gains expected in 2000 is the appearance of
new problems in, say, Indonesia and renewed skittishness among
investors. (Horacio Paone/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
