<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-19 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3875 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-FSU-AGENT-HNS &LR;      12-19 2162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FSU-AGENT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DANNY ROBBINS  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
If there was any hope at Florida State that the 1999 football
season would be a peaceful one, it went out the window on the
morning of July 8, six weeks before the season was due to begin.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Delta Airlines employee at Tallahassee Regional Airport
contacted the university's athletic department to report two
Florida State players were booked to travel later that day to
Houston. Because it was known that clients of Houston-based agent
Carl C. Poston III were gathering that weekend for a lavish party,
the call set off alarms. Because one of the FSU players due on the
flight was Peter Warrick, the alarms rang louder than usual.
</P>
<P>
   The call set in motion a chain of events that would include an
airport stakeout, questions for Warrick and two of his teammates
and an investigation of Poston's company, Professional Sports
Planning Inc.
</P>
<P>
   As Florida State has marched to an unbeaten season, a No. 1
ranking and a spot opposite No. 2 Virginia Tech in the Sugar Bowl,
investigators from the Florida State University Police Department
and the Florida Department of Business and Professional Regulation
have interviewed witnesses and obtained records attempting to learn
how Poston's company has tried to procure Warrick, the Seminoles'
star receiver, and other FSU players as clients.
</P>
<P>
   Potentially the No. 1 overall pick in the 2000 NFL draft,
Warrick will bring hundreds of thousands of dollars in commissions
to whomever serves as his agent.
</P>
<P>
   According to documents and sources familiar with the Florida
inquiry, investigators have developed information indicating a PSP
employee, Jeff Knox, arranged the purchase of airline tickets for
Warrick, FSU receivers Laveranues Coles and Ron Dugans, and
Warrick's former roommate, Joe Vegas, to travel from Tallahassee to
Houston on July 8, two days before the PSP party.
</P>
<P>
   Crucial to the case are statements made under oath by a Boca
Raton, Fla., travel agent, Angela Steffer. According to the
sources, Steffer told investigators she booked the flights and
issued the tickets at Knox's request and later followed his
directive to cover up his company's involvement when the matter was
scrutinized by Florida State officials.
</P>
<P>
   Coles traveled to Houston as scheduled, but the others did not,
their tickets scuttled after the Delta employee at the Tallahassee
airport noticed Warrick's and Dugans' names in his computer and
contacted Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   Using the ticket meant Coles had violated NCAA rules, which bar
student-athletes from receiving cash or other benefits from agents.
The matter caused him to miss the Seminoles' first game of the
season, against Louisiana Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Although Coles was the only FSU player to make the trip, the
matter could have serious repercussions.
</P>
<P>
   Sports agents operating in Florida must be licensed through the
state's Department of Business and Professional Regulation. The
process requires applicants to pass an examination, post a $15,000
surety bond, pay a series of fees and submit to a criminal
background check through the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Recruiting athletes attending Florida schools and engaging in
other agent-related activities in the state without a license is a
third-degree felony, punishable by a maximum of five years in
prison and a $5,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   Poston is licensed as an agent in Florida; Knox is not.
</P>
<P>
   According to Natalie Kelly, communications director for the
state Department of Business and Professional Regulation, a
licensed agent can be charged with criminal misconduct if an
unlicensed employee is conducting agent-related business in Florida
on the agent's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   A licensed agent involved in conduct contrary to NCAA
regulations also can receive administrative penalties, including
suspension or revocation of his or her license.
</P>
<P>
   FSU police spokesman Jack Handley said last week he could not
comment on the PSP case because it is an open investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an active, ongoing investigation as we speak in
conjunction with DPR,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Poston nor Knox responded to repeated messages from the
Chronicle. Eliot P. Green, a New York attorney who informed Florida
State he was representing Poston and PSP, also did not respond to
requests for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Green wrote FSU athletic director Dave Hart Jr. in October
advising him that no representatives of PSP would attend the
university's annual ``agent day,'' a school-sponsored event in
which players meet and interview potential agents.
</P>
<P>
   Green's letter, provided to the Chronicle by Florida State,
cited the ``media circus'' stemming from the investigation and
stated it had seriously damaged the company's reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is tragic that my client will not attend the FSU agent day
due to investigations that have produced no evidence of any
wrongdoing on the part of our client,'' Green wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Professional Sports Planning Inc. is the corporate name for the
high-profile sports agency operated by Poston, based in Houston,
and his brother, Kevin, who is based in Farmington Hills, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   The two brothers, both attorneys, have been agents for a decade.
They are perhaps best known for their representation of the Phoenix
Suns' Penny Hardaway, one of the NBA's most recognizable players.
They also have negotiated contracts for some of the NFL's recent
high draft choices, including Oakland Raiders cornerback Charles
Woodson, the 1997 Heisman Trophy winner and the fourth pick in the
1998 draft; and St. Louis Rams offensive tackle Orlando Pace, the
first player chosen in the 1997 draft.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Postons' clients are two former Florida State stars _
Kansas City kick-return specialist Tamarick Vanover and Miami
cornerback Terrell Buckley.
</P>
<P>
   Knox, based in Houston, was identified as Professional Sports
Planning's ``client services manager'' in company correspondence
with the Texas Secretary of State's office in 1995 and '96.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Minnix, Florida State's associate athletic director for
compliance, said Knox is a ``regular'' in Tallahassee and was in
Tempe, Ariz., when Florida State was there preparing for the 1999
Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick entered the season as one of the leading candidates for
the Heisman Trophy, but his chances were irrevocably damaged when
he and Coles were arrested in October on felony theft charges
stemming from an incident at a Dillard's department store in
Tallahassee. Warrick was suspended for two games before pleading
guilty to a reduced charge.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the suspension, Warrick caught 71 passes for 934 yards
and 12 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Coles was ruled ineligible by Florida State as a result of his
Houston trip but was reinstated immediately by the NCAA because he
had been withheld from the season opener. He subsequently was
dismissed from the team because of his involvement in the Dillard's
incident.
</P>
<P>
   Many states, including Texas, have laws relating to sports
agents, but few have shown Florida's zeal for enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   The state's attitude drew national attention as a result of the
Florida State Foot Locker scandal, in which eight FSU players were
found to have participated in a shopping spree financed by a
would-be agent at a Tallahassee Foot Locker store in 1993. The case
resulted in three individuals receiving fines or jail time for
failing to register as agents in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The shopping trip, disclosed by Sports Illustrated after Florida
State had won the 1993 national championship, also led the NCAA to
place the university on a year's probation for failing to monitor
and adequately investigate players' involvement with agents.
</P>
<P>
   Minnix, interviewed recently about the Poston case, said he and
others at Florida State became concerned when a Delta employee at
the Tallahassee airport who handles the university's charter
flights called Andy Urbanic, FSU's associate athletic director for
football operations, on the morning of July 8. According to Minnix,
the Delta employee was curious why Warrick and Dugans had been
switched to a later flight to Houston, a change that would
necessitate an extra charge of $75.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Every, a football recruiting assistant, was dispatched to
the airport to see whether FSU players were boarding that
afternoon's Delta flights for Atlanta, the first leg of the trip to
Houston. According to his report to Minnix, he watched as
passengers boarded flights at 1:30 p.m., 5:30 p.m. and 7:25 p.m.
and saw no players.
</P>
<P>
   Minnix said he found Warrick and Dugans in Tallahassee, and both
appeared to have no knowledge they were supposed to travel to
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Are you guys changing your tickets to go somewhere?'
They said, `Go where?''' Minnix said. ``Are they lying or not
lying? I don't know. But there was no indication to me they were
getting ready to go anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Minnix said he tracked down Coles in Houston and was told by the
player he was visiting a woman he had met previously in
Tallahassee, Kendra Baines, and was under the assumption she had
purchased his ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Baines, 20, grew up in Missouri City and attends Clark Atlanta
University.
</P>
<P>
   Although Baines told Minnix she had paid for Coles' ticket, her
story was laced with inconsistencies. Coles' fare was one generally
unavailable to the average traveler _ a 21-day advance purchase
price for a ticket issued eight days before departure _ and his
ticket had been issued through a travel agency in Boca Raton, Fla.,
400 miles from Tallahassee.
</P>
<P>
   Minnix said Baines told him her father travels frequently and
had recommended she use the Boca Raton travel agency, Travel by
Squires.
</P>
<P>
   Records provided to Florida State by Travel by Squires included
a note, purportedly written by Steffer, indicating Baines had been
designated to pay for tickets that would be used by Coles, Warrick,
Dugans and Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kendra Baines _ send money by Tuesday,'' the note read. ``OK
to (ticket) Warrick, Coles, Dugans, Vegas.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida State held Coles out of the Louisiana Tech game Aug. 28
as a precautionary measure and ruled him ineligible Sept. 9, seven
days after FSU police and state investigators had questioned
Steffer under oath.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State's report to the NCAA, prepared by Minnix and made
available to the Chronicle by the university, noted Steffer's
testimony linking Knox to Coles' ticket but made no mention of
Warrick or Dugans being involved.
</P>
<P>
   Steffer declined to be interviewed for this article, but sources
provided the Chronicle with details of her testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Steffer told investigators she had handled the PSP account for
about two months when the company provided her with a list of
clients who would require airline tickets to attend the party in
Houston. About the same time, she told investigators, Knox gave her
the names of Warrick, Coles, Dugans and Vegas and asked that she
book flights to Houston for them as well.
</P>
<P>
   The group was booked on a flight that left Tallahassee at 10:10
a.m. July 8, she told investigators, and their tickets were charged
to her account at the travel agency and issued electronically.
</P>
<P>
   On the day the group was to depart, Steffer told investigators,
she was asked by a PSP secretary to shift Warrick, Dugans and Vegas
to a different flight because the 10:10 a.m. flight conflicted with
their workout schedule. After making the change, she testified, she
received a call from a Delta employee in Tallahassee demanding to
know who had paid for the players' tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Steffer said she told the Delta employee she could not give out
information regarding a customer's method of payment. She said she
then informed Knox of the call. Knox initially did not seem
concerned, she testified, but he called back and directed her to
void the three remaining tickets.
</P>
<P>
   When Minnix and others at Florida State began seeking
information, she told investigators, Knox instructed her to say the
tickets had been purchased by Baines. According to Steffer's
testimony, she went so far as to prepare handwritten notes to make
it appear Baines had been responsible for the tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Steffer told investigators she was willing to cover for Knox
initially because she felt an obligation to help a client, but she
was not going to lie under oath.
</P>
<P>
   Minnix said the FSU police and state investigators had sought to
subpoena Baines' testimony but had encountered difficulty in doing
so because of resistance from Georgia authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Handley, the FSU police spokesman, declined comment on that
issue, citing his policy about discussing open investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts by the Chronicle to contact Baines through her father,
Ken Baines, were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Baines said he was not aware his daughter had invited a
Florida State football player to visit her during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he is a customer of Travel by Squires in Boca Raton,
Fla., he shook his head and said he rarely travels and never uses a
travel agency when he does.
</P>
</TEXT>
