<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOSCOPE-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 GENENTECH RIDES MOMENTUM OF ITS HIGH-FLYING STOCK INTO 2000  &HT;     By TOM ABATE 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wall Street seems bent on sending Genentech Inc. into the new
year in style. Shares in the South San Francisco biotech giant
gained another $11.38 Friday (December 17) to close at a dizzying
$125.06.
</P>
<P>
   Its stock has soared 158 percent since it returned to the stock
market in July, after its Swiss parent firm, Roche Holdings, spun
off part of it.
</P>
<P>
   The firm's momentum is all the more remarkable because Genentech
has taken some lumps along the way. It fought, nearly lost and
finally settled a nasty patent dispute by paying the University of
California $200 million, which should just about wipe out this
year's profit.
</P>
<P>
   But Wall Street has shrugged that off, to focus instead on the
products set to emerge from Genentech's drug discovery pipeline.
Next year, Genentech expects to launch a version of its Nutropin
growth hormone drug that can be injected once or twice a month
rather than daily.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech also expects Food and Drug Administration approval in
2000 to sell an improved version of its clot-busting drug.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's (December 17) stock surge occurred after Genentech
announced its intent to seek FDA approval for a new asthma remedy,
based on phase III clinical data that will remain partly secret
until the study results are presented to a scientific panel in the
spring.
</P>
<P>
   The market infatuation with Genentech may have gotten a bit
ahead of itself. FDA approval can never be taken for granted, and
the agency is likely to take an especially long look at Genentech's
proposed drug, which takes an entirely different approach than
previous asthma and hay fever remedies.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Genentech hopes to inject asthma and hay fever
sufferers with antibodies that would inactivate IGE, the chemical
that causes a range of asthma and hay fever symptoms. Other
remedies merely treat the symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   But investors seem to have discounted the risk of FDA rejection
and focused instead on the potential size of the market, should the
asthma drug win approval. Franklin Berger, senior analyst with J.P.
Morgan Securities, estimates Genentech, which is marketing the drug
in partnership with Novartis, is looking at a $750 million-a-year
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech is not the only biotech stock to find favor on Wall
Street of late. Since early November, when the AMEX biotech stock
index stood at 260, this basket of 15 biotech issues has risen 19
percent to 308.11.
</P>
<P>
   But Genentech has enjoyed a sharper, stronger climb than its
AMEX index brethren, who have had to carry Amgen, the Southern
California biotech giant, which slid 10 percent while the rest of
big biotech was rising.
</P>
<P>
   Unwelcome surprises may still lurk out there for Genentech. The
company is developing its time-release Nutropin in conjunction with
Alkermes in Massachusetts. In September, analysts from Merrill
Lynch questioned whether the Alkermes version would be as big a hit
as is generally expected by Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Such naysaying aside, the outlook at Genentech's South San
Francisco headquarters currently seems so rosy, management plans to
shut down between Christmas and New Year's, and give everyone a
paid holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Folks, there may need the break. When the New Year rolls around,
and people stroll back in the doors, their biggest challenge may be
figuring out how to top 1999.
</P>
<P>
   WORK IN PROGRESS: Jamie Court, with Consumers for Quality Care
in Santa Monica, Calif., is one activist health maintenance
organization executives love to hate. After years of gathering HMO
horror stories, Court recently assembled his best (or worst?) cases
into a book, ``Making a Killing: HMOs and the Threat to Your
Health.''
</P>
<P>
   Not content to see his charges in print, Court will open a new
front in his assault on stingy health insurers this week.
</P>
<P>
   With the consent of his publisher, Common Courage Press of
Maine, Court has posted his book on the Web at
www.makingakilling.org.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to letting people read other consumers' complaints,
the site will let visitors add their own tales to Court's growing
database.
</P>
<P>
   ``The site will allow readers to create a living history of HMO
abuses,'' he said _ and doubtless provide him more ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   PRESERVATIONISTS? Okay, so I was sucked in by the e-mail that
directed me to &LR;   &LR; www.SaveYourGenes.com, a Web site in Stockton that
sells $13 kits that allow you to save a copy of your genetic
material.
</P>
<P>
   The kit consists of a stoppered test tube, a label and a wooden
case. To save your DNA for posterity, simply toss a dozen strands
of hair or a few nail clippings into the test tube and insert the
plug.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site even offers several rationales for putting a copy
of your genes into a safety deposit box, suggesting that in case of
a kidnapping or other crime, or even in the diagnosis of a genetic
disease, a clean sample of DNA would come in handy.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you might accomplish the same purpose at no cost, by
throwing a lock of hair into an envelope, sealing it, and writing a
name on the outside. But then, the Web site points out, you'll miss
out on the smudge-proof label and attractive wooden box.
</P>
<P>
   Look for BioScope every Monday in the Business section. Send
your biofeedback to Tom Abate by e-mail at abate &LR; sfgate.com; fax
(415) 543-2482, phone (415) 777-6213.
</P>
</TEXT>
