<HEADER>
A3877 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-JETS-TEX     12-19 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-JETS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS DAMAGE COWBOYS' PLAYOFF HOPES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ On a day when one-third of their points came on
a fake field-goal play, the Cowboys saved their best work for after
the game when they kicked themselves.
</P>
<P>
   They kicked themselves clean across Texas Stadium, down the
tunnel, through the locker room and out the door, which may be
where their playoff chances have gone.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys blew a fourth-quarter lead and lost to the New York
Jets, 22-21, yesterday at Texas Stadium. In the process, the
Cowboys managed to suffer their first home loss of the season.
</P>
<P>
   And the operative word here is suffer.
</P>
<P>
   Because now, even if the 7-7 Cowboys can win their remaining two
games at New Orleans on Friday and against the New York Giants on
Jan. 2, they will still need help to get into the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' said Cowboys owner Jerry Jones, ``was as meaningful a
loss as far as what it did to our playoff chances as any time in my
11 years. We had a great opportunity today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knew it when we walked onto the field, because
Washington, New York \RGiants\S and Detroit all had lost ... and we
knew that if we could get a win, we'd probably get a home-field
playoff game. That's why this was so very disapppointing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets, trailing 21-19, drove 41 yards in 11 plays to set up
the game-winning field goal by John Hall _ his third of the game _
from 37 yards with 1:35 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   When the Cowboys got the ball with one last-gasp chance to
salvage the day, Troy Aikman hit Rocket Ismail for 23 yards to the
Dallas 39, then misfired four times in a row as the Cowboys lost
their first home game since the playoff-elimination loss to Arizona
last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't seize the situation,'' said Cowboys coach Chan
Gailey, trying to find the right adjectives to describe his
feelings and coming up with ``hurt ... upset ... mad,'' to name a
few.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys actually would have moved back into first place in
the NFC East with a win, technically tied with Washington but
holding an edge in the tiebreaker because of head-to-head
competition (2-0) with the Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   All this is what the Cowboys could have accomplished by beating
the already playoff-eliminated Jets yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Cowboys:
</P>
<P>
   Blew a second-half lead of 21-13 after Rocket Ismail's 27-yard
touchdown run on a reverse with 11:18 left in the third quarter.
Ismail, the Cowboys' leading receiver this season, actually wound
up with twice as many carries (two) as receptions (one) yesterday.
His lone catch came on the Cowboys' final drive as the Jets very
effectively rolled a safety to Ismail's side to shut him down for
most of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Turned the ball over twice in a span of approximately 7 1/2
minutes in the second half. Both were the result of Troy Aikman
interceptions. The first was Aikman's first in 217 pass attempts
dating to Oct. 18 at Giants Stadium. Then he went one pass attempt
in a row before he was picked off again.
</P>
<P>
   Squandered an early fourth-quarter drive to the Jets' 20 after a
Ray Lucas fumble from the shotgun, when he wasn't ready to receive
Jets center Kevin Mawae's long snap. Cowboys defensive end Kavika
Pittman recovered the loose ball at the New York 36. Four plays and
a penalty later, Aikman lofted a pass to Deion Sanders at the goal
line and it was intercepted by Jets safety Victor Green.
</P>
<P>
   Had four penalties for 35 yards in the pivotal fourth quarter.
For the game, the Cowboys drew eight flags for 92 yards, adding to
their NFL lead in penalties and penalty yardage. Twice in the
fourth quarter, penalties came on punt returns that both times
pinned the Cowboys back inside their own 20.
</P>
<P>
   When asked what he can do about the penalties that have dogged
his team all season, Gailey replied, ``You can talk to the players
about them. You can get on them about them. You can't fine them _
it's illegal. So, the best thing is to look at it real closely in
the off-season and evaluate what you have to do so that you don't
have \Rpenalties\S next year. And, meanwhile, try to eliminate them
the next two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman passed for 242 yards on 40 attempts against Philadelphia
last week. This week, he threw for only 158 yards, completing only
12 of 28 passes _ and five of those were to running backs Emmitt
Smith (team-high three catches for 36 yards and a touchdown) and
Chris Warren (two catches for six yards).
</P>
<P>
   With 110 yards on 19 carries, Smith posted his seventh 100-yard
rushing game of the season, and his fourth since breaking his right
hand Nov. 8 at Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to imagine we're 7-7 and can still be a playoff
team,'' Aikman said. ``I think we're trying to do what we can to
win games. We're trying to play to what we feel are our strengths,
which are defense, special teams and the running game.''
</P>
<P>
   Before penalties and turnovers led to the Cowboys' demise in the
second half, Smith turned a simple swing pass into a 14-yard
touchdown in the first quarter, marking his 146th career touchdown
and moving him ahead of Marcus Allen for second place on the NFL's
all-time list.
</P>
<P>
   In the second quarter, Cowboys holder Eric Bjornson turned what
appeared would-be a 37-yard field-goal attempt by Eddie Murray into
a 20-yard touchdown run on the fake.
</P>
<P>
   That was when the Cowboys were doing things right.
</P>
<P>
   But they obviously couldn't stand the prosperity.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
