<HEADER>
A3878 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-PRONTO-DSL-SFCHRON &LR;      12-19 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRONTO-DSL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PACIFIC BELL EXPANDING DSL AREA  &HT;     By PETER KUPFER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In recent months Pacific Bell and other local
telephone companies have launched aggressive marketing campaigns
for DSL, the broadband technology that transforms ordinary phone
lines into lightning-fast conduits to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But DSL, or digital subscriber line, is out of reach for
millions of Californians in rural and even some suburban
communities because the technology is distance limited. If you
happen to live or work more than 3-1/2 miles from a phone company
central switching office, you are basically out of luck.
</P>
<P>
   That's about to change. SBC Communications, the Texas-based
parent of Pac Bell, recently announced plans to invest $6 billion
in a program to extend the reach of its DSL service and provide
even faster connection speeds throughout its network. By the time
Project Pronto is completed in three years, Pac Bell says, more
than 80 percent of its customers in California will have access to
DSL, compared with about 50 percent today.
</P>
<P>
   In the densely populated Bay Area, DSL is currently available to
more than half of Pac Bell's customers, or about 1.9 million homes
and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   But there are still large patches of the San Francisco region _
including sections of Richmond, Berkeley, Hayward, Fremont, Walnut
Creek and Danville _ that are beyond the 3-1/2-mile range of the
technology. Once Project Pronto is completed, Pac Bell says, nearly
everyone in the Bay Area will have access to DSL.
</P>
<P>
   The technology that is enabling Pac Bell and other phone
companies to extend the range of DSL service is a device called a
digital loop carrier. DLCs are essentially mini-switching centers
that compress the signals from hundreds of copper phone lines into
a single fiber-optic pipeline that runs back to the central office.
</P>
<P>
   Although digital loop carriers have been around for years, they
were originally designed only to provide regular phone service to
outlying areas. So the equipment had to be redesigned to handle the
large chunks of data that are forced over the phone lines by DSL.
</P>
<P>
   ``This technology smashes the distance barrier of DSL. It will
allow a whole new universe of customers to have access,'' said a
spokesman for Alcatel, the French telecommunications equipment
giant whose Petaluma division is the world's largest manufacturer
of second-generation digital loop carriers and a primary supplier
for Project Pronto.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell officials say they expect to begin deploying the new
equipment, called neighborhood gateways, by the end of the year,
but they have not yet determined which communities will be first to
receive them.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, residents of communities that are not served by
DSL can, in some cases, obtain high-speed Internet access through
their cable lines. But high-speed cable service provided by
companies such as ExciteAtHome, though more widely available than
DSL, is still not offered in many areas.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to extending the reach of DSL, Project Pronto is
also designed to ramp up the connection speeds throughout Pac
Bell's DSL network.
</P>
<P>
   DSL customers are now guaranteed speeds of 384 kilobits a second
for $39 a month ($49 with unlimited access to Pac Bell's own
Internet service). Depending on the distance to the central office
and the condition of the phone lines, customers can get speeds as
fast as 1.5 megabits _ 50 times the speed of a standard 28.8
kilobit dial-up modem and equivalent to the speeds provided by
costly T-1 lines used by many large businesses. Pac Bell's premium
DSL service, which costs $129 a month, guarantees speeds of 1.5
megabits and can provide speeds as high as 6.0 megabits.
</P>
<P>
   Once Project Pronto is completed, Pac Bell says all of its DSL
customers will be guaranteed speeds of 1.5 megabits, and 60 percent
will get speeds of 6.0. Premium customers will be guaranteed 6.0.
</P>
<P>
   The faster connection speeds will enable home computer users to
take advantage of a host of functions that are not available or not
practical at the slower speeds provided by standard modems, such as
video-conferencing, downloading huge audio files and video clips,
and distance learning.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of interest among telecommuters and families
looking for multiple applications,'' said Shawn Dainas, a spokesman
for Pac Bell. Demand for DSL is especially high among college
students, he said, because they depend on the Internet for research
and other activities.
</P>
<P>
   Since Pac Bell and other SBC subsidiaries began their DSL
marketing push this summer, the number of customers subscribing to
the service has nearly tripled to more than 100,000, most of them
in California. But that's still a small percentage of the 6 million
Pac Bell customers who currently have access to DSL in the state.
</P>
<P>
   SBC expects to have 200,000 customers signed up for DSL by the
end of the year, and 1 million by the end of 2000, with the
majority of these being in California.
</P>
<P>
   As competition to provide high-speed Internet access heats up
between local phone companies like Pac Bell and cable operators
like AT&AMP;T, most analysts expect the cost of both services will
decline.
</P>
<P>
   A recent ruling by the Federal Communications Commission
requiring Pac Bell and other local phone companies to share their
lines with competing DSL providers is also expected to lead to
lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   Among the companies that stand to gain from that ruling are
Northpoint Communications of San Francisco and Covad Communications
of Santa Clara, Calif., both of which specialize in providing DSL
service to businesses but are now rapidly expanding into the
consumer market.
</P>
<P>
   Competition has clearly had an impact on Pac Bell's prices. When
it first offered DSL service on a wide-scale basis last May, Pac
Bell charged residential customers a $198 installation fee plus $89
a month for basic service. Pac Bell is now offering free
installation to some customers and has cut the price to $49 a
month, including ISP service.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Leutza, director of the telecommunications division of the
state Public Utilities Commission, said the PUC has received a
``stream of complaints'' from consumers about slow installation by
Pac Bell. But the PUC official said such complaints are not
surprising, considering the complexities of deploying an advanced
technology like DSL. ``You have to remember that this is not plain,
old telephone service,'' he noted. ``You have to send a technician
out to install a modem and connect the line.''
</P>
</TEXT>
