<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-19 23:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3879 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-HILL-COLUMN-TEX     12-19 1592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HILL-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANS KNEW COWBOYS' OFFENSE WAS GOING NOWHERE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ So when the Cowboys took the field for the final
time yesterday, trailing the Jets 22-21 with 1:35 to play and
needing just a field goal to win, did anybody actually think they
could pull it off?
</P>
<P>
   The sight of fans streaming out of Texas Stadium before
quarterback Troy Aikman set himself behind center at the Cowboys'
16-yard line spoke volumes.
</P>
<P>
   No, this is not about that bogus accusation that Aikman isn't a
comeback quarterback. He laid that to rest in the season opener
against the Washington Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's lack of faith _ which was supported by the Cowboys'
woeful rally attempt of a teasing 23-yard completion followed by
four incompletions _ was not necessarily about Aikman. It was about
the Cowboys' disappointing offense.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman did not have a good final series or a good game.
Completing 12 of 28 passes for 158 yards with one touchdown and two
interceptions confirms as much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I would be able to get us in position to make an
attempt,'' Aikman said. ``I accept responsibility as a quarterback.
That's my job, and I'm disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman also didn't get many opportunities; Cowboys coach Chan
Gailey called just 10 pass plays in the second half. Five came on
the last drive. The boos that rained down after the game were as
much for Gailey's play-calling as anything else.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that the Cowboys' offense _ save for the first
Redskins game and one or two others _ has been a disappointment all
season, even in many of their victories.
</P>
<P>
   Even running back Emmitt Smith wonders how it is that the
Cowboys can look ``so brilliant'' in some games _ like a 41-point
outing in the season opener in which they rallied to victory from a
21-point fourth-quarter deficit _ and so bad in others. Did we
already mention the pathetic final drive against Jets' 25th-ranked
pass defense?
</P>
<P>
   How is it that the Cowboys can execute so well at times, like
the 27-yard run for a touchdown by Raghib Ismail that capped an
81-yard drive to open the third quarter and give the Cowboys a
seemingly controlling 21-13 lead? And how is it they can do nothing
the rest of the way?
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, whose two first-half touchdowns were a 14-yard pass
to Smith and a 20-yard run on a fake field-goal attempt by tight
end Eric Bjornson, ended the game with six pitiful drives,
including:
</P>
<P>
   Three plays and a punt.
</P>
<P>
   Two plays and an interception, when Aikman tried to force the
ball into coverage to Eric Bjornson.
</P>
<P>
   Three plays and a punt.
</P>
<P>
   Five plays and another interception, when Aikman went for the
big play to a well-covered Deion Sanders. Aikman said he tried to
give Sanders a chance to make a play on the ball, which should be a
good thing to anyone who has complained about the Cowboys' throwing
the ball. The bad thing is that this gamble cost the Cowboys when
they were in field-goal range, which might have been the difference
in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Six plays and a punt. The drive was lowlighted by a tripping
penalty on center Mark Stepnoski, which forced the Cowboys to punt
from near their own end zone, setting the Jets up with good field
position for a game-winning field-goal drive.
</P>
<P>
   Five plays, game over.
</P>
<P>
   You want reasons for such lack of success? The Cowboys have
them: untimely penalties, turnovers, poor execution and injuries
that have robbed them of experienced players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had too many critical errors that we were not able to
overcome,'' Gailey said. ``We didn't execute when we needed to.''
</P>
<P>
   They also have frustrations, said Aikman, who specifically
points to the Cowboys' inability to convert on third downs as their
biggest problem. The Cowboys were 3-of-12 on third down yesterday
and are 65-of-195 for the season (33 percent).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a frustrating year,'' Aikman said. ``We are just
trying to fight through it. It doesn't matter how you break it down
or what caused it.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Cowboys don't have is answers to their problems, which
is the ultimate disappointment, considering that there two games
left in the season and they are still somehow in the playoff chase.
</P>
<P>
   But does anybody actually think they'll pull it off with this
offense? Defeat sours a milestone day for Emmitt
</P>
<P>
   Hardly a game goes by that Cowboys running back Emmitt Smith
doesn't surpass a milestone.
</P>
<P>
   That's just part of life when you are 10 years into one of the
greatest careers in NFL history.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's haul of honors for Smith, who already owns all the
Cowboys' rushing records and is the third all-time leading rusher
in NFL history, included:
</P>
<P>
   Breaking a tie with Marcus Allen and moving into sole possession
of second place on the NFL's all-time touchdown list. Smith's
14-yard reception in the second quarter was his 146th career
touchdown. Jerry Rice holds the NFL record with 178 career
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Becoming the Cowboys' all-time leading scorer. The touchdown
gave him 878 career points, surpassing Rafael Septien's former club
record of 874.
</P>
<P>
   Recording his seventh 100-yard rushing game of the season with
110 yards on 19 carries. It was also the 62nd of his career. The
Jets became the 20th different victim of his century-mark assault.
</P>
<P>
   Moving into eighth place on the NFL's all-time combined net
yardage, just ahead of former Cowboys running back Tony Dorsett.
Smith's 146 combined yards yesterday gives him 16,437 for his
career.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who has long stated that he is driven by winning and not
personal achievements, was true to form after yesterday's
devastating 22-21 loss to the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't mean anything,'' Smith said. ``It doesn't mean
anything when you lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost as notable as his accomplishments was that fact that
Smith even played. He missed almost all of last week's game against
the Eagles with a strained groin and practiced only one day during
the week.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said they worked to loosen the injury before the game, and
he rode a stationary bike during the game to stay loose.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the injury wasn't a problem.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem Smith had was losing.
\Nsubheds:Inside the Locker Room
So, was Michael Irvin's presence on ESPN's ``NFL Game Day''
yesterday a cameo or an audition? The Cowboys' all-time leading
receiver, who is sidelined for the season with an injured spine,
didn't reveal his future plans during the two-hour television
stint. He said he and owner Jerry Jones will sit down after the
season and make a decision on whether he's going to retire or
continue his career.
</P>
<P>
   There's no question that Irvin, 33, wants to play. The question
is whether he can convince his wife, Sandi, along with Jones and
the Cowboys doctors, to give him their blessing and, of course, at
what price. Speaking of money, Irvin said he's also rooting for the
Cowboys to get to playoffs and go as far as they can because he
gets a full playoff share. As far as Irvin's skills as an analyst,
let's just say he's already better than Sterling Sharpe. He was
funny. He gave insight and he wasn't afraid to flaunt his Super
Bowl rings.
</P>
<P>
   What is it about the Cowboys' running backs and running out of
bounds on pass receptions short of the first down? Chris Warren did
it and cost the Cowboys a score in the loss to the Cardinals four
weeks ago. Emmitt Smith ran out of bounds short of the first down
and cost the Cowboys a chance at points at the end of the first
half yesterday. Smith said he didn't think he could run over two
defenders. His coaches thought otherwise, as he said he was cursed
out for the play.
</P>
<P>
   So much for the Deion Sanders-Keyshawn Johnson showdown. Johnson
had a great day, catching six passes for 96 yards. However, none
came when he was locked against Sanders one-on-one. The matchup
occurred 16 times. The Jets didn't attempt one pass in Johnson's
direction when Sanders was covering him. In fact, the Jets called a
running play 12 times when the two were hooked up. Sanders wasn't
surprised, saying, ``Common sense goes a long way.'' Johnson did
most of his damage in slot against reserve cornerbacks and against
safeties in the Cowboy zone defense.
</P>
<P>
   Jets running back Curtis Martin's 113-yard day was the first
time in seven games that an opposing running back had topped the
century mark against the Cowboys' defense. Martin was most
successful when the Jets spread the Cowboys out with three wide
receivers. The Cowboys were forced to take a linebacker out of the
game for an extra defensive back, and then the Jets would gash them
with Martin on draws. Later in the game, Martin had success on
pitch plays around the end.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys certainly missed defensive end Greg Ellis, who is
out for the season with a broken leg. Leon Lett moved from tackle
to end and was not a factor. The move also weakened the Cowboys'
tackle rotation of Lett, Alonzo Spellman and Chad Hennings. The end
result was a less effective run defense and a nonexistent pass
rush. Inexperienced Jets quarterback Ray Lucas was not sacked in
the game.
\Nsubheds:Up Next at New Orleans, 2:05 p.m. Friday, KDFW/Ch. 4
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys (7-7) travel to New Orleans for a Christmas Eve
battle against the woeful Saints (2-12). What a gift. Not only will
the Cowboys be looking to keep their dimming playoff hopes alive,
but they will also be seeking some Bayou revenge, considering the
humiliating loss against the Saints last season. By the way, the
Cowboys have lost six in a row on the road.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
