<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-19 23:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3880 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     12-19 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' MIGHT IS JUST A MEMORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Final proof has come. Let there be no more
debate, and no more cross-examination of the witnesses. Clear the
courtroom. Dismiss the jury. Case closed.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Cowboys are guilty as charged, and as of Sunday have
been convicted of heartless, gutless, and disgraceful football
behavior. They are hereby sentenced to join the San Francisco 49ers
in that NFL hell-hole known as Memory Land.
</P>
<P>
   Trapped on one side by the salary cap, and the other side by
overpriced and fading former superstars, there is no known escape
from Memory Land.
</P>
<P>
   Falling from the top to the bottom in one decade is a long way
down. Getting back up again is a long time coming.
</P>
<P>
   When the Cowboys lost, 22-21, to the New York Jets here Sunday,
it wasn't, of course, exactly the first hint that the end of a
once-great dynasty had arrived. The obvious has been obvious for
awhile.
</P>
<P>
   And it wasn't about Jets backfield coach Maurice Carthon giving
receiver Keyshawn Johnson a playful shove on the way to the
victorious locker room, then telling him, ``I told you so _ they
are all hype.''
</P>
<P>
   In Memory Land, the Cowboys won't be subjected to such verbal
abuse. Time was, they were a big deal.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it all came down Sunday to Jets' head coach Bill Parcells'
postgame answer of ``If you like football and you like competition,
you're ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells was replying to why his team, far out of the playoff
hunt, had displayed more gumption over 60 minutes than the Cowboys.
The answer is not pretty for the losers.
</P>
<P>
   Before the kickoff, the Cowboys had been rewarded with
divisional riches. The Redskins had lost. The Giants had lost. By
continuing their seasonlong homefield dominance, the Cowboys would
control the NFC East. They already knew the playoffs were assured
by winning out in the final three games, but the early news Sunday
provided even more incentive.
</P>
<P>
   Despite it all, the competitive juices didn't flow. Or at least
the flow didn't equal that of the Jets. And that tells you
everything you didn't want to know about the demise of the Cowboys.
Now known as the official demise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to believe we're better than this, but maybe we're
not,'' quarterback Troy Aikman said of the 7-7 record.
</P>
<P>
   What's this ``maybe'' stuff? They're not. Period. And you could
see that coming weeks ago with those back-to-back losses to the
Eagles and Giants in October. Homefield flashes delayed the
inevitable, until the Jets ended the charade.
</P>
<P>
   When a team with nothing to play for is more competitive than a
team that has had a division handed to it _ even a very weak
division _ then there's nothing else to discuss. Memory Land, here
come the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   They lost Sunday because Aikman threw two senseless second-half
interceptions, the second one eliminating at least a field-goal
opportunity. Seeing Deion Sanders one-on-one at receiver, yet
well-covered, Aikman tried the jump ball gamble in the end zone. It
didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way I expected that ball to be intercepted,''
Aikman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get me caught up in that mess,'' said Sanders, typically
passing the blame to someone else. But in this case, he's right.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys lost Sunday because the defense, even as heralded as
it has been, could not make a game-saving stop when necessary. And
didn't again Sunday on the final Jets' drive to a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   The defense was also beaten by a gutty backup quarterback, Ray
Lucas, and by an offensive line that has two rookies starting.
Curtis Martin went for 113 yards rushing, helping the Lucas case.
</P>
<P>
   When the Cowboys went ahead 21-13 early in the second half, the
defense caved immediately as Lucas brought the Jets right back on a
touchdown drive.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson (six catches, 96 yards) was very good, as expected.
Wayne Chrebet, however, was even a bigger factor at receiver (eight
catches, 108 yards.)
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys lost because coverage and penalties on special teams
was not acceptable. But as always, penalties (six for 92 yards)
were an overall killer.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, however, the Cowboys lost this one because the offense
was not up to NFL standards. The Cowboys scored the three
touchdowns on a fake field goal, an end-around, and the dreaded
dinkeroo pass to the flat.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter the 110 yards rushing by Emmitt Smith, if you
can't throw the ball effectively, there will be no win. Or if you
don't commit to the pass, you also don't win. Chan Gailey called
five pass plays in the second half until the last fruitless series
once the Jets had the lead.
</P>
<P>
   None of these negatives are new _ not the passing game, the
penalties, the defense, the Gailey offensive philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday, they all hit home with an embarrassing thud. Sunday
was the worst of the season for all the obvious reasons. And now
the final sentence has come. The Cowboys will be locked away
forever in Memory Land. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
