<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN PARCELLS HAS PRAISE FOR LUCAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Much of the talk in the New York Jets' locker
room after their 22-21 victory against the Cowboys yesterday evoked
the continuing improvement of quarterback Ray Lucas.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't mistake-free in his sixth consecutive start and
seventh of the season, but the third-year quarterback from Rutgers
kept his poise in leading the Jets on a clock-killing 11-play,
41-yard drive to set up John Hall's 37-yard game-winning field goal
with 1:35 to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a little less than perfect, but he's been good enough
to put him over the top as a starter,'' Jets coach Bill Parcells
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas' teammates were more liberal with their praise on a day
when he notched his third consecutive 200-yard passing game and
outplayed his counterpart, veteran Troy Aikman. Lucas completed 20
of 34 passes for 229 yards, two touchdowns and one interception.
</P>
<P>
   ``To drive us down the field like that shows what kind of player
he is. He wants to win,'' said receiver Wayne Chrebet, the
recipient of eight passes for 108 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he continues to play like that, I don't see why he can't be
Vinny's \RTestaverde\S backup,'' said Keyshawn Johnson, who had six
catches for 96 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas is now 4-3 as the Jets' starter and has helped them win
five of their past seven games. On the game-winning drive, running
back Curtis Martin carried most of the load, rushing nine times for
43 of his game-high 113 yards. Lucas completed his one pass attempt
for eight yards, good for a first down to the Dallas 37. The drive
forced the Cowboys to burn all three of their timeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``My teammates believe in me, and they let me know it, too,''
Lucas said. ``I looked at their faces and knew we were going to win
the game.''
Keyshawn downplays matchup Keyshawn Johnson, as unusual as it might
sound, had little to say about his day against Deion Sanders,
primarily because the two did not go one-on-one for much of the
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not really a matchup, it's just two players trying to
help their teams win,'' Johnson said. ``It was fun. I had the
opportunity to play against him and run around a little.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, however, came up big with six receptions for an average
of 16 yards per catch. His 14-yard reception in the middle of the
field on the first drive of the second half landed the Jets at the
Cowboys' 9-yard line and set up Lucas' second touchdown pass to cut
the Cowboys' lead to 21-19. Stoutmire returns Former Cowboys safety
Omar Stoutmire, cut by the Cowboys during training camp, returned
to Texas Stadium and intercepted Troy Aikman with 4:32 left in the
third quarter, a time when the Cowboys had excellent field position
and were working on a 21-13 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys faced second-and-six at their 46 when Aikman's pass
split double coverage and bounced off Eric Bjornson's chest and
fell into Stoutmire's hands. He returned it 30 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't hold any grudges against them,'' Stoutmire said. ``Any
time you can come up with a pick against a guy like Aikman it feels
good.'' Glenn stalls Rocket Former Texas A&AMP;M defensive back and
Jets cornerback Aaron Glenn broke up a first-down pass from Aikman
to Raghib ``Rocket'' Ismail at the Jets' 48-yard line on the
Cowboys' final drive.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared Ismail was open and had room to make the catch, but
Glenn made a late read and knocked the ball down from behind
Ismail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the play coming,'' said Glenn, who attended Aldine
Nimitz High School.] The defensive line ``put pressure on the
quarterback, and I just reacted.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
