<HEADLINE>
MODANO ADDS CAPTAINCY TO ALREADY HEAVY DUTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALGARY, Alberta _ A couple of ounces, if that, of additional
weight were added when trainers sewed ``the'' ``C'' onto Mike
Modano's jersey before Saturday's game against Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Only, ``the'' ``C'' brings a weight that few can imagine.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas Stars defenseman Derian Hatcher had been shouldering all
the responsibilities that come with being the captain of the
defending Stanley Cup champions until a lacerated calf muscle on
Friday sidelined him for six to eight weeks. Now comes Modano's
turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, it motivates you,'' Modano said. ``It gives you some
responsibility to come to play every night. And now, you're going
to be a little more under the magnifying glass and people watch and
see how you respond.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Modano has been playing under such scrutiny all
season.
</P>
<P>
   First things first, Modano hasn't had his best season. He'll be
the first one to tell you that. He, of course, has heard the
criticism that comes with failing to live up to the expectations
that stalk big-name players. The Stars' early-season struggles
became linked with his own.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is, as Modano goes, the team goes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It always has been that way,'' Modano said ruefully. ``It's
the part that kind of eats me apart inside. I've been one not to be
vocal about that over the years. It's just something that has
festered, and it just eats you away. It makes the game unhappy and
tough to come to play knowing that it feels like you have more
doubters than believers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's been the case since Day One that I've been here. But
it's been a tough thing to shake. They figure as I go personally,
the team goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Is there any better evidence for people sharing that opinion
than Saturday night?
</P>
<P>
   The Stars were reeling, playing their second game in as many
nights and their first game without their best player in Hatcher
and their hottest hand in Joe Nieuwendyk. Two of the players who
had help to lead them through their first spate of injuries were
now among the injured.
</P>
<P>
   Who would lead them now?
</P>
<P>
   Modano answered with a solid two-way game, scoring two of
Dallas' four goals and assisting on the others. He played almost 24
minutes _ six more than any other Stars forward _ in a 4-2 victory
that brought the Stars to 8-3-1 in their past 11 games and helped
erase some of the doubts that losing a player such as Hatcher
creates.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, the Mike Modano that played (against Vancouver) was the
Modano that we need to play every game,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock
said. ``He wasn't just a good player because he scored. He was a
good player because he impacted every area of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Modano hasn't been that player for a lot of this season. He'll
tell you that, too. A season that began with talk of 100 points
instead has become an exercise in frustration. He had 22 points in
30 games before Saturday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Modano, along with linemate Brett Hull, will tell you that
Modano didn't do anything Saturday night that he hadn't been doing
all season. It wasn't a case of ``Hatcher's gone, I better start
producing.''
</P>
<P>
   No, Modano has been playing that way all season.
</P>
<P>
   He just finally had some points to show for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``See, people try to read so much into Mike,'' Hull said. ``He
plays the same every night. He plays hard, and he tries to do
everything that he's supposed to do. Some nights, it goes in.
Sometimes, it doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars need more of the former now.
</P>
<P>
   A lineup that was designed to blend in a few younger players at
the beginning of the season is now littered with them. A defense
that was supposed to replace only one starter from last season now
has to replace three. A team that had a captain it could always
look to when things got bad is suddenly in need of one.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said he considered both Modano and Nieuwendyk, but the
injury to Nieuwendyk made the decision for him. There are few
candidates better than Modano, a 24-minute forward with
game-changing ability. He's a scorer, a passer and a strong
defensive presence all in one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at a stage right now, where just on roster along, he has
to lead,'' Hitchcock said. ``Right now, I'm hopeful Mike takes the
ball and runs with it and carries other people with him.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
