<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-SIDER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS NEED HELP FOR PLAYOFFS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ On the heels of their 22-21 loss to the New York
Jets yesterday, the Cowboys know only this about their playoff
hopes: They can win out and still lose out.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys (7-7) could defeat the Saints in New Orleans on
Friday afternoon and the New York Giants at Texas Stadium on Jan. 2
and still not receive an invitation to the NFL's postseason party.
</P>
<P>
   Nine might not be enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're slim,'' Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said of his
team's playoff hopes. ``At best we're going to get nine wins, and
that's probably going to get into a lot of tie-breaking situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just got to play better. I don't see how we can be too
disappointed right today about the playoffs when we don't play
better than we did today.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the kickoff of their game, the Cowboys knew the
Washington Redskins (8-6) and the New York Giants (7-7) both had
lost. With victories against the Jets and the Saints, combined with
a Washington loss at San Francisco next week, the Cowboys would
have clinched a seventh NFC East title in eight seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Cowboys need help to win the division. The Cowboys,
who hold the tiebreaker against the Redskins by sweeping the season
series, need to win their last two games and have Washington lose
once.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, victories in their last two games won't assure the
Cowboys of even a ninth playoff berth in 10 seasons. If the
Redskins win their final two games, the Cowboys will be left to vie
for one of the three NFC wild-card berths. Besides the three
division winners, five NFC teams can reach nine victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew what we had to do going into the game, and we just
didn't get it done,'' Cowboys cornerback Deion Sanders said.
``We're going to need help now. We're going to have to sit back and
pray for a loss for one of those other teams.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no mulligans in the NFL. No provisionals either. Not
even five Super Bowl rings will buy the Cowboys a free pass into
the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a real opportunity. We let it go,'' Cowboys quarterback
Troy Aikman said. ``We've dug ourselves a hole. Right now, we're
7-7. It's hard to imagine being 7-7 and thinking you can still be a
playoff team, but we still could be. So until they sit there and
tell us the season is over and we don't get to play any more games,
we're going to keep going out there and giving it our best shot.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' next shot comes in New Orleans, where they lost
22-3 last December. They also haven't won on the road since the
season-opening victory at Washington and in their past two road
games the Cowboys have scored a total of 15 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very frustrating,'' Cowboys running back Emmitt Smith
said. ``Here we are again after seven losses saying what we could
do and how good we can be. Eventually that's got to stop. That has
to cease. Who are we kidding? In order to be better, you've got to
do better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-19-99 2339EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
