<HEADLINE>
TRICKERY WORKS FOR COWBOYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TRACEY MYERS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ It all came down to timing, and when the Cowboys
attempted a little trickery, the timing couldn't have been better.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys set up for a 39-yard field goal in the second
quarter, but Eric Bjornson instead ran for a 20-yard touchdown off
a fake. Bjornson, the holder, waited until the moment was just
right before scampering down the right sideline to give the Cowboys
a 14-13 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be patient and let them really run on \Rtheir\S
right side,'' Bjornson said. ``It's real easy to get antsy and run
out of there too quick, and if you do that you're going to be
stopped for nothing. You just have to stay composed and we executed
well and it was a perfect situation.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time in his career Bjornson had run for a
touchdown off a fake field goal. It also took some of the heat off
the Cowboys, who were booed loudly following a 1-yard run by Chris
Warren on a third-and-six.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd worked on it,'' Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said.
``\RSpecial teams coach\S Joe Avezzano's done a great job. He could
see we had an opportunity for that, and we had worked on that all
week.'' Making the rounds Wide receiver Chris Brazzell, who had
been picked up, cut and finally signed by the Cowboys, got to show
his former team what he could do.
</P>
<P>
   Brazzell, who was cut by the New York Jets early this season,
caught two passes for 62 yards, including a 53-yard breakaway catch
in the second quarter. With the Jets focusing on Raghib Ismail,
Brazzell got some opportunities yesterday, his second game with the
Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a team doesn't think receivers are good enough then they
can double Rocket and force me and Jason Tucker and Jeff \ROgden\S
to make plays,'' Brazzell said. ``If teams don't think we can make
plays they'll double Rocket all day.'' Costly call The Cowboys have
had their penalty problems this year, and a big one came in the
second quarter. Kevin Smith was flagged for interfering with the
Jets' Dedric Ward, who couldn't come up with a 34-yard throw from
quarterback Ray Lucas. The penalty, which Smith argued, moved the
Jets from the Cowboys' 35-yard line to the 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know any other way to play it,'' Smith said. ``The
rule is, if you look back for the ball and you're not impeding the
receiver, it's just as much my ball as it is his. Not to knock the
officiating, but I thought it was a decent play. If anything, no
flag should've been thrown.'' See Robert run Robert Thomas, who
switched from linebacker to fullback during training camp, got his
first rushing opportunities. Thomas, who became starting fullback
when the Cowboys released Tim Lester on Oct. 27, rushed four times
for 22 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just try to make the best of the opportunities I get,''
Thomas said. ``Sometimes I did good, sometimes I didn't. But I was
100 percent, giving it all I got.'' Briefly When Troy Aikman threw
the first of two interceptions in the third quarter, it was the
first one he'd thrown in a club-record 216 pass attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman's touchdown pass to Emmitt Smith in the second quarter
was his 154th, moving him to second behind Danny White, who has
155, on the Cowboys' all-time list.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday was the first time since Oct. 24 Raghib Ismail has not
tied or led the team in receiving yards. He finished with one catch
for 23 yards but now has a career-high 70 receptions.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
