r f BC-CHARITY-ONLINE-SFCHRO     12-19 2421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHARITY-ONLINE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 WEB SITES PROVIDE A NEW WAY TO GIVE  &HT;     By CARRIE KIRBY 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ At the Larkin Street Youth Center, where
runaways and other homeless kids turn for a safe bed and a warm
meal, a penny earned means a young person helped. But raising funds
is a struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spend a whole lot of money and time trying to raise money
for the work that we do,'' said Executive Director Anne Stanton.
</P>
<P>
   Several months ago, a Web site called iGive.com started sending
checks to the San Francisco emergency shelter, with no strings
attached. The money came from sales commissions on items bought at
iGive.com, one of the many ``charity malls'' that have emerged
online in the past year or so. Larkin Street Youth Center paid no
fees to get involved. Enough of the Web site's shoppers selected
the Larkin Street Youth Center as their beneficiary in the past
year to send about $1,000 to the shelter so far, in monthly checks.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the center's regular fund raising, getting donations
through iGive is almost effortless, Stanton said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonprofit organizations and schools all over &LR;   &LR; the country are
embracing the emerging breed of for-profit Web sites like
iGive.com, which promise to help individuals benefit their favorite
groups by doing things they'd do online anyway, like shop and
browse the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the potential promises of the Internet is that it can
create a low-cost method of raising money,'' said Bennett Weiner,
the director of the Better Business Bureau's philanthropic arm. The
potential of these sites is especially exciting to small nonprofits
without the resources to advertise or set up their own Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   But, Weiner pointed out, the field is so new and developing so
quickly that regulators (usually state attorneys general) are
struggling to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an area that is less regulated at the moment than
other charity areas,'' Weiner said. For now, the burden is on the
user to make sure a Web site is delivering on its promises, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   A sprawling suburb's worth of shopping mall sites _ close to a
dozen _ send visitors to online stores in exchange for a sales
commission. The charity mall then splits the commission with the
buyer's chosen nonprofit. The nonprofit ends up getting from 0.5 to
30 percent of the purchase price.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping sites have been a big hit with schools; in fact, there
are several charity malls that specialize in schools and
school-related groups.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to labor-intensive alternatives such as bake sales and
car washes, charity malls seem like money for nothing, explained
Susan von Felten, principal of Daves Avenue School in Los Gatos,
Calif., a public elementary school that has participated in a
shopping site called Schoolpop since May.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be the easiest way for schools to reach their
fund-raising goals,'' von Felten said. ``I basically do nothing,
and my teachers and parents do nothing; we just all shop there.''
</P>
<P>
   Daves Avenue School bought two printers with the $500 it has
received from Schoolpop so far.
</P>
<P>
   While charity malls are the dominant form of Internet fund
raising now, they may lose favor or even disappear as the field
evolves, said Mark Rovner, who heads the online division of
Cravers, Mathews, Smith and Co., an Arlington, Va., consulting firm
that helps nonprofits raise money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their whole business model is based on kickbacks,'' Rovner
said, referring to the commissions that individual stores give the
malls for sending Web shoppers their way. While e-commerce is in
its infancy, online merchants are willing to pay commissions to
acquire new customers. But ``no one knows if that will be a
permanent process,'' he said. ``If the kickbacks go away, the
shopping sites will go away.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all the Web companies trying to facilitate Internet fund
raising are shopping sites. Some, such as Working Assets'
GiveForChange, collect credit card donations and deliver them to
nonprofits, usually keeping a percentage as a commission. Others
conduct auctions of donated goods. Some players, such as
CharityCounts.com, combine shopping, auctions, donations and
charity-related content with the aim of becoming a clearinghouse
for all charitable online activities.
</P>
<P>
   KickStart.com, a Denver-based startup, gives nonprofits their
own easy-to-create online portals. KickStart.com splits advertising
and e-commerce revenues from the page with the nonprofit, after
deducting an annual fee of $100.
</P>
<P>
   A supporter of, say, the local kids soccer league can log on to
a start page that contains news about the soccer club, as well as
standard portal features such as weather and stock updates. On that
page, supporters can earn money for the group by viewing ads,
conducting Web searches and shopping, with a percent of each
purchase going to the soccer league. KickStart.com sells targeted
advertising banners on these personalized sites, operating on a
similar concept as programs that pay Web surfers for viewing ads.
</P>
<P>
   A few sites, such as the AOL Foundation's Helping.org and the
Hunger Site, which was created by a computer programmer as a good
deed, are operated on a not-for-profit basis.
</P>
<P>
   The sheer volume of charity sites could lead to problems as
these companies struggle to compete, said Daniel Moore, vice
president of the National Association of State Charity Officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always seen that businesses under financial stress are
areas where cutting corners is more likely,'' Moore said. ``Whether
those financial pressures cause new sites to breach the donors'
trust and fail to pass that money through to the charities, that's
what's going to give regulators concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Ami Kassar, founder of Shop2Give in Los Angeles, said that
proving his company is trustworthy is vital to its success.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want this field to go away because state charity
regulators get really concerned about fraud and put down
regulations to cripple the industry,'' Kassar said.
</P>
<P>
   IGive.com prominently displays the total amount it has raised
for charity since its founding in 1997: over $500,000. It provides
a statistics page where shoppers can track their history of
purchases. It also posts the check numbers and dates of all past
disbursements to each nonprofit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know exactly how much money is going to your cause,'' said
Robert Grosshandler, iGive.com's founder and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   But in the absence of government regulations, the practices of
charity Web sites vary, and not all of them are so open. Some newer
sites, such as CharityCounts.com, lack the tracking infrastructure
to show users where their money goes and when it gets there.
</P>
<P>
   While the National Association of State Charity Officials spent
much of this year's conference discussing online charity, they
haven't come up with any guidelines for it yet.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping to benefit a cause isn't a new idea, but e-giving
presents a new business model that is outside current regulations,
Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional fund-raising companies offer their services to
nonprofits, while most of the new Web sites offer their services
directly to individuals, to benefit the charity of their choice.
</P>
<P>
   Some sites sign agreements with nonprofits before listing them
as potential beneficiaries, while others simply list all 620,000
nonprofit organizations registered in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The latter approach ruffles the feathers of some nonprofits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't like that, and it's illegal,'' said Nancy Brady,
national director of strategic marketing for the March of Dimes.
Using an organization's name without permission is considered by
many to be a breach of trademark. ``Ask us, and if we want to be
involved, we'll say yes,'' Brady said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the large number of Web sites soliciting donations,
purchases and click throughs, online charity has a long way to go
before it can rival the $174.5 billion that nonprofits collected by
traditional methods in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's growing, but the numbers are still very low,''
Shop2Give's Kassar acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   ``All online fund raising should be considered experimental
right now, with one or two exceptions,'' said Rovner, the
consultant to nonprofits. One exception he noted was the American
Red Cross's online efforts during the Kosovo crisis, which raised
$1.26 million.
</P>
<P>
   Online or offline, the most effective way to help a charity is
to give the money directly to the group, Rovner said.
</P>
<P>
   ----------------------------
 &UR; THINK BEFORE YOU GIVE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By CARRIE KIRBY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Better Business Bureau offers these tips on
cybercharities:
</P>
<P>
   Shopping site cautions: If you visit an online shopping site
that states purchases will benefit charities, consider the
following:
</P>
<P>
   How much goes to charity? Look for clear and prominent online
disclosures that indicate the portion of the purchase price that
will go to charity. Watch out for vague references such as ``a
portion of our profits will go to charitable organizations.''
</P>
<P>
   When will the charity receive the funds? Some sites donate to
charities on a quarterly or other periodic basis or may require a
cumulative charity donation to reach a certain level (for example,
$10) before a check is sent to the designated group.
</P>
<P>
   Is any part of the purchase deductible as a charitable gift?
Generally, no portion of online purchases is deductible since items
are being sold at their ``fair market value.''
</P>
<P>
   Online charity auction cautions. Is there a disclosure as to
what portion of the winning bid will go to the benefiting charity?
Do not assume that the designated charity has given any approval or
is formally involved with the auction sale.
</P>
<P>
   Online charity chain mail. You might receive an e-mail message
that claims a few cents will go to a specified charity each time
the message is sent to another person. Such claims are invariably
untrue.
</P>
<P>
   Will the charity see the donor's personal information? Before
making online donations, see if the charity has an announced
privacy policy concerning the use of your name, e-mail address or
other personal facts. For example, does it ask donors for
permission to share this information with other charities or
companies?
</P>
<P>
   Is there security for online donations? Verify that the charity
site is using encryption technology to secure online credit card
donations. Look for visual alerts through your browser that inform
you when you are entering a secure area.
</P>
<P>
   Verify that the organization is a charity. Don't assume a Web
site is affiliated with a nonprofit organization just because .org
appears at the end of the Internet address. In addition, there are
many different types of nonprofit organizations; only some of them
are eligible to receive contributions that are deductible as
charitable gifts. To verify if a group is tax-exempt as a charity,
visit www.irs.gov/prod/search/eosearch.html.
</P>
<P>
   Research charities online. The Internet offers donors an
opportunity to get more detailed information from the charity's Web
site. Contact the charity via e-mail with any questions and/or go
to outside trusted sources, such as the Better Business Bureau
(www.bbb.org), for additional facts and to find out if a national
charity meets BBB charity standards.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MILLIONS EAT BECAUSE PEOPLE CLICK A BUTTON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By CARRIE KIRBY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Hunger Site's premise is so simple, it seems
too good to be true: All visitors have to do is click a button to
donate food to hungry people millions of miles away. No purchase
required. No filling in forms or typing in credit card numbers.
</P>
<P>
   So it's no surprise that many skeptics have a hard time
believing in it. John Breen, the 42-year-old computer programmer
who created the site, has a stock answer for people who e-mail him
asking if his site is just another hoax: Go to the United Nations
World Food Program's Web page, www.wfp.org/prelease/1999/
991216.htm, where the organization &LR;   &LR; confirms receiving more than
$200,000 so far from the Hunger Site.
</P>
<P>
   The money comes from advertisers who sign up to sponsor the page
for 24 hours at a time. During that day, the sponsors' ads appear
when someone clicks a button labeled ``Donate Free Food.'' For
every sponsor signed up, a half-cent is added to the donation,
which the World Food Program uses to buy 1/4 cup of rice or another
staple. The food goes to any of the 80 nations the World Food
Program serves.
</P>
<P>
   Each individual's donations are limited to one a day. It takes
the visitor about three seconds to complete the process.
</P>
<P>
   It takes Breen pretty much all of his time to administer the
site, however. The Indiana resident had to stop working and rely on
his wife's income as a college professor when response to the site
became overwhelming. He operates without any loans or grants.
</P>
<P>
   Breen started working on the site in January as a personal
project. ``I thought I'd just set up this simple little site and it
would run itself,'' he said. ``I wasn't planning on the massive
volumes of e-mail. It ended up taking up gobs and gobs of time.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, Breen wanted his Web page to work as a bulletin board
where people could find out about Third World schools that needed
educational materials. His sister had worked in Africa and told him
that children were in dire need of pencils and books.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I learned that hunger was a really big deal in these
developing countries,'' he said. According to statistics on the
page, 800 million people suffer from hunger worldwide. Instead of
asking for paper and pencils, he realized, many Third World
teachers who managed to access his site would be asking for food.
</P>
<P>
   So he launched his project June 1 as the Hunger Site. On June
10, Yahoo featured it as a Daily Pick, and the site's popularity
snowballed &LR;  as Web surfers everywhere e-mailed the URL around &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   In June, visitors sent close to 200,000 donations &LR; ; in July,
there were more than a million &LR; . November saw donation totals
approach 7 million. Now, people from about 175 countries click to
donate a million cups of food each day. Donations are tallied by
country at www.thehungersite.com/donationstodate.html.
</P>
<P>
   ``My favorite is the Vatican City,'' Breen said, scrolling down
the list. ``Usually I get two to six hits every day from the
Vatican City. I always imagine the pope sitting there clicking.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hunger Site's URL is &LR;   &LR; www.thehungersite.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
