 NEW SUPERCOMPUTER PACKS POWERFUL PUNCH  &HT;     By STAN BUNGER and JAN BOYD 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Like who-knows-how-many other information system
managers in Silicon Valley, Don Davis is busy planning a new
computer installation.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike anyone else, Davis is putting together a new installation
that will fill a building and come with an electrical substation
capable of supplying enough power for a small town.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is in charge of a facility being completed at Lawrence
Livermore National Laboratory in Livermore, Calif. That facility,
part of the Energy Department's Accelerated Supercomputer
Initiative, will house Lawrence Livermore's new ASCI White
supercomputer, due to be delivered by next summer.
</P>
<P>
   The supercomputer's future home is a vast room large enough to
hold two full-size basketball courts. An enormous air-conditioning
system keeps the place chilled to 61 degrees Fahrenheit. The
electrical substation, capable of providing enough power for 11,000
homes, hums outside.
</P>
<P>
   Workers a &QL;  NVWn
</P>
</TEXT>
