<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARTOON-VENTURE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 COMIC BOOK POKES FUN AT VENTURE CAPITALISTS  &HT;     By CARRIE KIRBY 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ There's nothing funnier than pitching your
life's work to a callous executive who has the power to turn your
startup into the Next Big Thing _ or steal your idea and hand it to
someone else.
</P>
<P>
   Have trouble seeing the humor in venture capital?
</P>
<P>
   A Silicon Valley venture capitalist and his wife, an
illustrator, manage to squeeze a few laughs out of the subject in
their comic book, ``The VC _ The Surreal World of Silicon Valley
Venture Capital.''
</P>
<P>
   The book collects 33 comic strips that Robert von Goeben and
Kathryn Siegler created for their Web site, &LR;   &LR; www.thevc.com.
</P>
<P>
   One scenario has a venture capitalist determining a company's
fate by consulting a Magic 8 Ball. Another shows a hopeful CEO
getting shot down between slides one and two of his PowerPoint
presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Von Goeben was a partner in a VC firm in Saratoga, Calif.,
Redleaf Venture Management, when he began writing the strips in
1997. He's currently working on a new capital project and taking a
break from writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hunt for money in Silicon Valley is a world of its own,''
von Goeben said. People in that world recognize the truisms in the
comic immediately, while outsiders sometimes just don't get it, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strip started as a joke with some people I know, but then
it just exploded.'' Soon Upside magazine began running it. Since
then, he's had whole boardrooms break into applause when he's
identified as the author of ``The VC.''
</P>
<P>
   Von Goeben and Siegler plan to create more strips for their Web
site in early 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-19-99 2349EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
