<DOCNO> NYT19991219.0278 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-19 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3891 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-BOMB-PLOT-SPI &LR;      12-19 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMB-PLOT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECURITY TIGHTENED ALONG U.S.-CANADIAN BORDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. Customs Service tightened security Sunday along a
Canadian border that an expert on terrorism says has been porous
for years.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed Ressam, arrested by Customs agents as he allegedly tried
to smuggle explosives into Port Angeles last week, wasn't the first
suspected terrorist to be caught crossing from Canada into the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   And he probably won't be the last.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons are two-fold:
</P>
<P>
   Canada's lax laws have made it a magnet for extremist groups.
</P>
<P>
   And members of those organizations have had little trouble
crossing one of the longest and friendliest borders in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last couple of years, it's happened more and more
frequently,'' Vincent Cannistraro, former counter-terrorism chief
for the CIA, told the Post-Intelligencer Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 and 1997, for example, authorities arrested Gazi Ibrahim
Abu Mezer three times for trying to cross the border from British
Columbia into Washington. Mezer was later charged with plotting to
bomb New York subways.
</P>
<P>
   Ressam's arrest, coupled with fears that he may have had
accomplices who remain free, prompted the Customs Service to
announce Sunday that it will add 150 agents at the Canadian border
and work them longer hours to beef up security.
</P>
<P>
   But there's been no indication yet of an increase in the number
of field agents who patrol the unguarded territory between the
ports of entry, said Keith Olson, president of the National Border
Patrol Council Local 2913, which represents about 200 agents in
Washington, Oregon, Idaho and Western Montana.
</P>
<P>
   The Customs Service is responsible for those coming into the
U.S. at formal entry points while the Border Patrol has primary
responsibility for the vast boundary stretches in between.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still don't have 24-hour coverage and we still don't have
any more people,'' Olson said Sunday. ``If they're tightening up
the border, I don't see it, and I work there.''
</P>
<P>
   The stretches in between ports of entry are notorious for being
easy to cross, he said. ``If this guy (Ressam) had driven in at 2
(in the morning,) there would've been no one there to catch him. I
guess he didn't do his homework.''
</P>
<P>
   Tightening the borders now is like closing the gate after the
horse is already out, he said. ``Whoever is here is here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Border Patrol has about 33 agents in the field patrolling
the stretch from the Pacific beaches to the Cascades and only 289
agents along the entire U.S.-Canada border, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The southern boundary between the U.S. and Mexico has about
8,200 Border Patrol agents.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials haven't been overly concerned about the Canadian
border until recently because most terrorist threats were perceived
to be aimed outside the United States, Cannistraro said.
</P>
<P>
   But the chance arrest of Ressam last Tuesday has altered that
perception, he said. Ressam was arrested after Customs officials
found bomb-making materials in his car when he tried to cross by
ferry from Victoria, B.C., to Port Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pure luck, the unravelling of this in Port Angeles,''
Cannistraro said. ``Now that this has happened, they're worried.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and Canadian law enforcement mounted a massive manhunt
Sunday for a man who had been staying with Ressam outside Vancouver
in the weeks before his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Ressam reportedly had two ferry ticket stubs in his possession
when he was stopped crossing into Port Angeles, suggesting a
companion may have walked off the boat.
</P>
<P>
   Ressam lived in Montreal before flying to Vancouver a month ago.
Newsweek, citing unnamed Canadian police sources, reported that
Ressam lived for a time there with Said Atmani, who was extradited
from Canada to France in connection with the 1995 Paris subway
bombing that killed four people and injured 86. The bombing was
attributed to the Algerian radical Armed Islamic Group.
</P>
<P>
   Cannistraro said Ressam also has suspected ties to Osama bin
Laden, the man U.S. officials believe heads a terrorist network
involved in the bombings of U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, police in Montreal searched a van belonging to
Ressam for signs of explosives, said Cpl. Leo Monbourquette, a
spokesman for the Royal Canadian Mounted Police.
</P>
<P>
   Cannistraro said Canada has become a magnet for terrorist
operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``A number of terrorist groups find Canada a benign area in
terms of fund-raising, organizing and presence,'' he said.
``Terrorist groups naturally gravitate to Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Canadian intelligence officers, there are at least
50 known terrorist groups in Canada, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has strict laws against fund-raising by
terrorist groups or front groups for terrorist organizations, he
said. In contrast, Canadian laws are more lax.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian intelligence is concerned about the terrorist presence,
he said. ``But the Royal Canadian Mounted Police is limited in what
it can do,'' he said. ``Until they break the law, (authorities)
can't move against them.''
</P>
<P>
   The capture of Ressam, however, has catalyzed an increase in
security along the U.S.-Canadian border.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, 150 additional customs agents were being moved into
position at remote ports of entry along the U.S.-Canadian border,
said U.S. Customs spokesman Bill Anthony in Washington, D.C. In
addition, agents were allowed to work 12 and 13 hour days and were
joined by employees reassigned from desk jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we need to do is look at as many suspicious vehicles as
possible,'' Anthony said.
</P>
<P>
   Agents expected most travellers to be cooperative because of
publicity surrounding Ressam's arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Crossing the border into the United States wasn't a problem at
the Blaine crossing Sunday night. The wait was only about an hour,
normal for the holiday season, a Customs Service spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   P-I Reporter Jack Hopkins contributed to this report. It also
includes material from the Associated Press.
</P>
</TEXT>
